<HEADLINE>
HARRY USHER, 61, TOP AIDE FOR THE PROFITABLE 1984 OLYMPICS
</HEADLINE>
  By FRANK LITSKY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Harry Usher, who as the right-hand man to Peter Ueberroth helped
to make the 1984 Los Angeles Olympic Games by far the most
successful financially, died Thursday in Secaucus, N.J. He was 61.
</P>
<P>
   His family said he apparently suffered a heart attack at the
AmeriSuites in Secaucus, where he was staying during a business
trip as a corporate consultant.
</P>
<P>
   A spokeswoman for Meadowlands Hospital said he was pronounced
dead at the hospital's emergency room. He underwent open-heart
surgery in 1975 and 1985.
</P>
<P>
   From 1964 to 1979, Usher was a lawyer specializing in
entertainment law in Los Angeles and in Beverly Hills. When
Ueberroth became head of the Los Angeles Olympic Organizing
Committee, he chose Usher, who had done legal work for him, as
second in command.
</P>
<P>
   That was a troubled time for the Olympics. In 1972 at the Munich
Games, Arab terrorists murdered Israeli athletes. In 1976 the
Montreal Games ended with a $1 billion deficit. In 1980 the United
States and other nations boycotted the Moscow Games.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles city officials, fearing a huge deficit, refused to
guarantee the financial stability of the 1984 Games. Ueberroth and
Usher recruited the U.S. Olympic Committee as co-guarantor of the
first privately financed Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a national and international level there was a feeling that
this could be the last hurrah of the Olympics,'' Usher once
recalled. ``On a local level there was continuous doubting and
debate whether the Games could be sustained without public money.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead of losing money, as the Olympics traditionally had,
these Olympics produced a profit of more than $225 million. The
money was divided among the U.S. Olympic Committee, amateur sports
in Southern California and America's individual sports federations.
</P>
<P>
   Anita de Frantz of Los Angeles, a vice president of the
International Olympic Committee, described Usher's role as an
``extraordinary contribution to the Olympic movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Usher was a hands-on leader. No expense of $1,000 or more could
be paid without his approval, and for a time he had to approve
every outgoing letter. Once, he got on an elevator at the
committee's offices and saw stacked boxes of computers. If they
could be left there, he reasoned, the committee had too many
computers. So he issued an order: no more computer purchases.
</P>
<P>
   The IOC awarded him the Silver Olympic Order. He was also
honored by the governments of France and Sweden.
</P>
<P>
   Harry Lester Usher was born March 6, 1939, in Jersey City. In
1961 he received a bachelor's degree from Brown University, where
he was Phi Beta Kappa. In 1964 he received a law degree from
Stanford, where he was editor of the law review.
</P>
<P>
   After the Olympics, he became the second and last commissioner
of the United States Football League, a short-lived rival to the
established NFL. The new league was so short of money that one
team, the Los Angeles Express, put its 28 cheerleaders on
indefinite leave to save $980 a week.
</P>
<P>
   Usher explained his commissioner's job by saying, ``I am not
here to rearrange the deck chairs on the Titanic, but I'm here to
take this ship forward.''
</P>
<P>
   But soon after his league had won a $1.32 billion suit against
the NFL but was awarded only $1 (trebled to $3 under antitrust
laws), it died.
</P>
<P>
   From 1961 to 1990, he was married to the former Jo Misselhorn,
now the alumni director of Kenyon College in Ohio. In 1991 he
married the former Jane Ellison, the dean of the Annenberg School
of Communications at the University of Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   He is survived by his wife; four children from his first
marriage, Lindsay Clark, Timothy Usher and Jennifer Usher, all of
San Francisco, and Katie Usher of Seattle; and two sons by his
second marriage, Samuel and Jackson Usher of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   When Ueberroth learned of Usher's death, he said: ``He had
boundless energy. He was a comrade and a partner of mine in a
historic endeavor of the city of Los Angeles. He will be a sorely
missed pal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
