<SLUG> BC-GLF-LPGA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVIES FEELS COZY WITH TWO-SHOT LEAD 
</HEADLINE>
   By CLIFTON BROWN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILMINGTON, Del. _ Shortly after arriving at DuPont Country Club
this week, Laura Davies felt good about her chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I walked in the locker room, and I hear all the whining
about it's long and it's tough, I just love it,'' Davies said.
``They get a tough course, it's a major championship, and there's a
lot of whining that goes on. They like the shorter, easier courses.
I like the longer, tougher courses.''
</P>
<P>
   And after the second round Friday, Davies also likes her chances
to win another McDonald's LPGA Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Ending her day with three consecutive birdies and shooting a
5-under 66, Davies was 6-under (136) for the tournament. She held a
two-stroke lead over Wendy Ward.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, who shot a 69, was 4- under for the tournament, while Jan
Stephenson, who also shot 69, was tied for third place at 3-under
with Stefania Croce, who shot 67. Karrie Webb, trying to win her
third consecutive major, was even par (142), six strokes behind
Davies after a second-round 70.
</P>
<P>
   It is easy to understand why Davies has won three times at
DuPont _ in 1993, before the event was a major, and at major
championships in 1994 and 1996. Driving the ball is her strength,
and the layout at DuPont, which gives her an opportunity to cut
loose off the tee, plays into her hands.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the courses we play all year, this is the only one that
genuinely makes it a real advantage to the long hitters,'' Davies
said. ``That's why I love it so much, because I can get out there
and have some fun with the driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Having fun is rarely a problem for Davies, who at age 36 remains
one of the tour's most jovial players. She has won four majors and
18 LPGA tournaments, yet she leaves her game at the course, and
admits she does not like to practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always said, `If I can't see the range, I won't go to
the range,''' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's domination of the LPGA Tour for the last 18 months has
forced Davies to reassess her ways. Davies did not win an LPGA Tour
event last year, and now she spends time at the range.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been dedicated to anything, but I'm certainly
practicing a bit more,'' Davies said. ``If I want to be better, and
I want to win on a consistent basis, I've got to practice that
little bit more.''
</P>
<P>
   It paid off Friday. Davies made six birdies and only one bogey,
and she nearly made a hole in one at the par-3 No. 17, hitting an
8-iron shot from 156 yards that stopped just inches from the cup
for an easy tap-in birdie.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could hear the crowd getting louder and louder, and I really
thought it was going in,'' Davies said.
</P>
<P>
   The three players closest to Davies are facing a difficult
challenge, particularly on this course and in a major championship.
Ward has never won a major. Croce, a 30-year-old player from Italy,
has never won a tournament. And Stephenson, who is 48, has not won
a tournament since 1987, when she was one of the tour's best
players.
</P>
<P>
   ``This course suits Laura to a tee,'' said Stephenson, who has
rebuilt her career and her swing after injuring her hand in 1990.
``If I hit in the rough, I have to chip out. Laura can power her
way through.''
</P>
<P>
   So Davies entered the weekend feeling confident about her game,
and comfortable in her surroundings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't say I come expecting to win,'' Davies said. ``But I
fancy my chances every time we come here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
