<HEADLINE>
RENOWNED FRENCH JOURNALIST MICHEL DROIT, 77, DIES 
</HEADLINE>
   By ERIC PACE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Michel Droit, a man of letters and a journalist who was a member
of the Academie Francaise, died on Thursday in La
Celle-Saint-Cloud, a suburb of Paris. He was 77.
</P>
<P>
   Droit's writing, which included more than 20 novels and other
books during half a century, was rich as well as prolific.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known literary works included his 1964 novel, ``Le
Retour'' (``The Return''), which won a Grand Prix of the Academie
Francaise. The novel recounts the difficult return to France by
former French settlers in Algeria who had been ejected after
Algeria gained its independence.
</P>
<P>
   Another well-known work is ``L'Homme du Destin: Charles de
Gaulle'' (``Man of Destiny: Charles de Gaulle''), a five-volume
biography published in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   But Droit was better known among his compatriots for having been
the sole interviewer of de Gaulle in the three television
interviews that the general granted during his lifetime. They were
held while he was president of France, in 1965, 1968 and 1969.
</P>
<P>
   Droit also did other work in television, radio and print
journalism, and his political views were outspokenly conservative.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980, Droit was elected to the Academie Francaise, whose 40
members are often called ``the immortals.''
</P>
<P>
   Droit, whose father was an artist, was born in Vincennes,
outside Paris. He studied at the prestigious Ecole Libre des
Sciences Politiques, but he dropped out to join the French
Resistance against the German occupation during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   He went on to be a radio correspondent covering French army
units in that war, and he was on hand for de Gaulle's arrival at
the Arc de Triomphe in Paris.
</P>
<P>
   In later years, Droit was editor in chief at the French state
television organization and served as editor in chief of the
literary weekly Figaro Litteraire for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   He also held posts at the conservative newspaper Le Figaro for
20 years. When he was elected to the Academie Francaise, Le Figaro
declared that it took courage ``for him to openly call himself
reactionary, a partisan of order and of virtue.''
</P>
<P>
   He was made an officer of the Legion of Honor and received other
French military and civilian honors.
</P>
<P>
   He married Janine Bazin in 1947, and they had a daughter,
Corinne, and a son, Eric.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
