<SLUG> BC-WIGS-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ESCAPEE'S RELATIVES FORCED
 TO `DRESS UP`
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 BY CRAIG HARRIS 
 c.2000 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Phoenix) - Two female relatives of a jail escapee were forced
to put on wigs, fake noses, glasses and extra makeup in a Maricopa
County Sher iff's Office investigation into how convicted murderer
Tasha Wolf got out.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly why remains unclear.
</P>
<P>
   But the court-ordered dress-up ses sion earlier this week for
Betsy Brewer, Wolf's mother, and Wolf's sister failed to produce
damaging evidence, said Richard Gierloff, the family's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Gierloff, who declined to identify the sister, said the session
``pushed the limits'' of routine investigative meth ods.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Brewer women were eliminated as suspects,'' Gierloff said.
``It was obvious they (investigators) didn't get what they were
hoping to get.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Wolf was sen tenced to life in prison for
the 1995 shooting deaths of two drug dealers. She lured them to an
ambush, where they were tied up and injected with heroin before she
and accomplices killed them.
</P>
<P>
   In April, Wolf and cellmate Darlene August dressed as men and
escaped from the Estrella Jail for less than 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf's father, Paul Brewer, was arrested in May and was
suspected of providing wigs, clothing, money and a car to Wolf and
August.
</P>
<P>
   The father, who was acting as Wolf's private investigator until
the escape, has not been charged.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Dave Trombi wouldn't confirm or deny the dress-up session,
but said Paul Brewer still is an ''investigative lead'' in the
case.
</P>
<P>
   ''If he (Gierloff) wants to divulge that information to you or
be stupid to do that, he can,'' Trombi said. ''It is still an open
and ongoing investi gation.''
</P>
<P>
   Gierloff declined to elaborate on why the women were asked to
put on the disguises.
</P>
<P>
   ''I can't tell you why they put on the wigs. It was a legitimate
reason that I'm not taking issue with,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it does push the limits of a discovery device.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
