A3671 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-FIRINGS-HN     06-24 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-FIRINGS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros fire coaches McCraw, Ruhle; 
Spilman, Hooton named successors
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CARLTON THOMPSON
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ When a team is struggling, and firing the manager is
not a desirable alternative from a financial or public-relations
standpoint, the coaching staff is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Astros hitting coach Tom McCraw and pitching coach Vern Ruhle
found that out firsthand Friday when they were relieved of their
duties prior to the opener of a three-game series against the San
Francisco Giants.
</P>
<P>
   For all intents and purposes, McCraw and Ruhle are casualties _
some might say scapegoats _ of a disappointing season that has seen
the Astros go from three-time defending National League Central
champions to the team with the worst record in baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time a team falls dramatically short of its expectations,
it's time to examine what you can do to get back on track,''
general manager Gerry Hunsicker said. ``(Manager) Larry (Dierker)
and I talked about this, and we felt that with the new direction
we're taking, we might benefit from a fresh approach. It's too bad
that Vern and Mac are casualties in this, but in no way is this an
insinuation that they are the reason we are where we are.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Spilman replaced McCraw, and Burt Hooton takes over for
Ruhle. Spilman has been the Astros' minor-league field coordinator
for the past 2{ years, and Hooton was the pitching coach at Class
AA Round Rock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Vern and Mac did everything they could do to make us pitch and
hit better,'' said Dierker, who has two more years worth $1.5
million remaining on his contract. ``As a player, after being with
coaches for a while, you feel like you know everything they know
because they've told you everything they know. Sometimes (players)
tend to tune you out. They do that to me sometime.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, Hunsicker said Dierker's job was never in jeopardy
during the evaluation of the coaching staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I've said before, the manager's status has not and will not
be an issue this year,'' Hunsicker said. ``This is an isolated
incident. I don't anticipate any other (staff) changes.''
</P>
<P>
   If other moves are forthcoming, they likely will involve
players. Although the Astros don't figure to be major dealers at
the trading deadline, they could make a move.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're lucky they don't fire players,'' said righthander Jose
Lima, who fell to 1-11 with Friday's 10-3 loss to the Giants. ``If
they did, everyone in this room would be fired. I'd probably be the
first one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sad to see this happen, because Vern and Mac are both
great guys. Vern has been like a father to me, and Mac is one of
the greatest guys I've ever been around. I'm going to remember
those guys for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   McCraw and Ruhle had sterling track records during their tenures
with the Astros, which began when Dierker was hired prior to the
1997 season.
</P>
<P>
   During McCraw's tenure, the Astros set a franchise record for
runs in back-to-back years, scoring 777 in 1997 and 874 in 1998,
when they were second in the league in hitting. And under his
tutelage, young hitters such as Carl Everett and Richard Hidalgo
came into their own; Daryle Ward, Lance Berkman, Mitch Meluskey,
Julio Lugo and Glen Barker began to show signs of being legitimate
big-league batters.
</P>
<P>
   One day before his firing, McCraw said he was looking forward to
teaching the next generation of Astros. He won't get that
opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can walk away from this experience feeling like I did the
best I could,'' McCraw said. ``That's all you can do; do your best,
and let the chips fall where they may.''
</P>
<P>
   First baseman Jeff Bagwell and second baseman Craig Biggio
issued what were believed to be the first ``no comments'' of their
careers _ quite a statement in its own right. When the two players
who have been the team spokesmen on so many other issues declined
to address this one, it's obvious how they felt about the moves.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things were going, I knew something was going to
happen,'' McCraw said. ``You have to throw something out to the
public when things are going as poorly as they were going for us,
and the hitting and pitching coaches are the most visible
positions.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros' pitching staff ranked among the top three in the NL
during Ruhle's first three years on the job, and he helped Lima,
Darryl Kile, Shane Reynolds, Mike Hampton and Billy Wagner put
together career years.
</P>
<P>
   But entering Friday's game, the Astros ranked 14th in pitching
and 13th in hitting in the National League, prompting management to
pull out the pink slips.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate it,'' Wagner said. ``I really do. Vern and Mac are
great people, and they had a big impact on the success we've had
around here for the past three years. It's too bad that when the ax
falls, it has to take some good people with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Ruhle, who pitched for the Astros during the 1980s:
``Everyone is kind of surprised by it, including me. But I
understand the business side of it, and I thank the Astros for the
opportunity. I'll always consider myself a special part of the
Astros family.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a lot of success during my time here, and I feel like I
helped a lot of guys get better. Things are starting to come
around, but they were a little slow in coming around, maybe too
slow. Perhaps that's why I find myself in the situation I'm in
today.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
