<HEADER>
A3675 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RAC-ROZA-ROBATA-2TAKE     06-24 1174
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-ROZA-ROBATA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A FILLY CARRIES THE STORY OF A HOLOCAUST VICTIM 
</HEADLINE>
 
(Attn: Ark., Ind., Fla., Calif., Poland)   By JOE DRAPE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was a Vietnam veteran from Arkansas who was moved by the
story of a little-known heroine and victim of the Holocaust. So
Fletcher Clement decided that a racehorse should bear the name of
Roza Robota, a young Polish woman who was instrumental in a brief
uprising at Auschwitz.
</P>
<P>
   His idea, though unorthodox, was that he could help tell her
story, and in the simplest of ways, he has. The tale of the young
woman who bravely lost her life is retold each time the racehorse
Roza Robata runs, even if its heard only within racing circles.
</P>
<P>
   It will be told again Saturday at Belmont Park where Roza Robata
the racehorse _ though partly misspelled because of an
administrative error _ will make her 31st career start among a
field of six in the prestigious Grade I, $250,000 Hempstead
Handicap. The 5-year-old mare has won eight races, earned $583,430
in purses and, according to those who have been associated with
her, has displayed a remarkable energy and toughness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very hesitant and a little worried that I would offend
Jewish people by combining this horrific episode with horse
racing,'' said Clement, 57, a commercial real estate broker who
made the decision to name the horse after Robota. ``But I checked
around with some friends of mine who are Jewish, told them the
story and finally decided that it would be nice to honor this
courageous lady.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Berenbaum, former director of the Research Institute at
the U.S. Holocaust Memorial Museum in Washington, and currently a
distinguished visiting professor of Holocaust Studies at Richard
Stockton College in California, said Roza Robota is little known
outside scholarly circles. He acknowledged that some may be
offended by a horse carrying the name of a tragic figure from one
of the most horrific periods of world history.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be those who are offended,'' he said. ``I'm not.
It's an opportunity to use the name of a horse to tell a story that
is not well known about a person who should be remembered in the
annals of heroism.''
</P>
<P>
   Sara Bloomfield, director of the Holocaust Museum, said: ``It's
complicated. If the motive is to memorialize this young woman and
spread awareness about the Jewish resistance, which is not well
known among the public, it is very admirable. However, there may be
some survivors who might feel that connecting the Holocaust to a
racehorse, which represents how people spend leisure time, would be
a trivialization of an enormous tragedy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the middle of this unusual story is Clement, who for almost
30 years, has bought and raced horses. For even longer, he has
studied what has gone on in the world. He was a history major at
the University of Arkansas-Little Rock. He developed an interest in
the Holocaust after serving as a communications specialist in the
Army Special Forces from 1965-66 in Bu Dop near the Cambodia
border.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe as a veteran it gave me an affinity for people in
untenable positions,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the mid-1980s he came across a photograph of Roza Robota and
the story of her role in the Oct. 7, 1944, uprising by the Jewish
Sonderkommando of Auschwitz-Birkenau _ the all-male detail forced
to work in the death camps. For weeks leading up to the uprising,
Robota, along with three young other women, smuggled gunpowder in
small amounts out of a munitions plant they were assigned to as
prisoners.
</P>
<P>
   The uprising ended badly, although one crematorium was
destroyed. Several hundred prisoners escaped, all of whom were
caught and killed by German forces the same day, Bloomfield said.
Later that day, Bloomfield said, an additional 200 prisoners were
executed by the Germans.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a significant act of resistance,'' Berenbaum said. ``It
was not a decision to live but a decision on how to die. It gave
the victims a personal death in the impersonal process of
killings.''
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, on Oct. 10, Robota was arrested with the other
women. She was beaten and tortured, and then on Jan. 6, 1945,
Robota, Regina Safirsztain, Ella Gartner, and Esther Wajcblum were
hanged _ just 12 days before the Germans abandoned the camp as
their war effort began to crumble.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not only in the deed was she brave, but so were her last
words,'' Berenbaum said. ``She said, `Be strong, have courage,' as
the trap doors opened.''
</P>
<P>
   The story haunted Clement, especially after he visited Auschwitz
in the mid-1990s. In April 1997, he attended the Ocala Breeders
sale in Florida in the hopes of adding to his small stable. A
self-described ``bottom fisher,'' Clement is in the majority of
horse buyers who enter the bidding process long after the
wealthiest owners, with their private jets and deep pockets, have
abandoned the sales ring.
</P>
<P>
   After failing to land a colt he fancied when the bidding reached
a too- rich $20,000, Clement became captivated by a spirited,
dark-brown 2-year-old filly. She was already named Firey May Day,
but there was something about the way she held her head up. He
bought her for $12,000 and thought hard about changing her name to
Roza Robota. He didn't take the decision lightly.
</P>
<P>
   The Jockey Club, which registers the names of thoroughbreds,
allows a name change if a horse has not yet raced, as was the case
with Roza Robota. What's in an actual name is reviewed by the
organization, which approved 40,853 names in 1999 alone. The rules
for naming a horse range from a maximum of 18 characters including
punctuation, for example, to outlawing notorious names, and
requiring written permission from famous living people.
</P>
<P>
   It is not unusual to find horses with names that are linked to
real people or real events. Among the recent Triple Crown
competitors, there was Hugh Hefner, named for the Playboy Magazine
founder, and Impeachment, whose name was derived from the colt's
sire, Deputy Minister and his dam, Misconduct, although the horse's
owner, Cot Campbell, acknowledged the name had special resonance
due to the proceeding the U.S. Congress took against President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Six years ago, a horse named Irgun was a strong contender for
the Kentucky Derby until being sidelined with a sore foot. Irgun
was named after the Jewish underground group that fought the
British and the Arabs a half century ago in what is now Israel. And
26 years ago, a horse named Chris Evert _ after the tennis star _
was the best 3-year-old filly in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Some owners treat the naming of horses as a game and try to get
racy or nonsensical names with personal significance past the
organization. Mike Pegram, owner of 1998 Kentucky Derby winner Real
Quiet, named his champion filly Silverbulletday after the brand of
beer he prefers.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 71 percent of the people get their first preference with
names,'' said Buddy Bishop, The Jockey Club registrar. ``We are
very careful. But you always can get a name nobody knows.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   It's likely that no one at The Jockey Club recognized the name
Roza Robota. Clement says he believes he turned the name in with
the correct spelling and it came back ``Robata.'' If not, he will
accept blame for the mistake. While campaigning the horse in her
campaigns as a 2- and 3-year-old, Clement told the story as often
as he could.
</P>
<P>
   Roza Robata did well for Clement, earning more than $100,000 and
winning the Grade 3 Honeybee Stakes in Arkansas. After that race,
Clement put her up for auction as a brood mare at Keeneland in
Lexington, Ky. Roza Robata was bought for $150,000 by Ron McKee who
thought she had more races left before being relegated to breeding.
Last spring, after she won the Fairway Fun Stales at Turfway Park,
McKee heard from a friend and sometime partner named Jimmy Iselin.
It was Iselin who was aware of the life of the real Roza Robota. He
told McKee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was fascinating,'' said McKee, an Indianapolis businessman.
``Everyone I tell is intrigued.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Clement and McKee say that Roza Robata is the best race
horse they have ever owned. They also feel compelled to pass on the
tale of the woman the mare is named for. Even though it's a horse,
involved in a sport in which sentiment often takes a back seat to
the cold calculations of betting, Clement says he believes the
story of a brave young woman is being passed on, and that her
memory is being honored.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a footnote in the Holocaust annals,'' Clement said.
``She shouldn't be.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
