<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 00:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3688 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFC     06-24 0804
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-CALIFORNIA-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOV. DAVIS THREATENS VETO IF BUDGET LACKS TAX CUTS
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
 &LR;   &LR;  SACRAMENTO _ Gov. Gray Davis renewed his threat Friday to veto
a $3.6 billion cut in vehicle license fees unless lawmakers send
him nearly $100 million in tax cuts sought by businesses.
<P>
   The Assembly pledged to do what Davis wants but the leader of
the state Senate said he wasn't inclined to approve the tax cuts in
the form Davis wants.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor has not been in contact with me on this issue,''
said Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San Francisco. ``But
vetoing the license fee thing would only make Republicans upset. I
don't think Democrats would be too worked up about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ending a week-long stalemate, lawmakers sent Davis a $95 billion
spending plan Thursday for the fiscal year that begins July 1.
</P>
<P>
   Besides sharp increases in public school spending, the budget
includes a cut of 32.5 percent in the annual fees California's 27
million owners of motorcycles, trailers, trucks and cars.
</P>
<P>
   Counting previous cuts in license fees of 35 percent, vehicle
owners _ starting next year _ will pay 67.5 percent less in fees
than they did in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   It was that tax cut which crumbled Assembly GOP opposition to
the budget.
</P>
<P>
   But Davis said Friday that tax cut is in jeopardy unless
lawmakers approve tax breaks he wants in the form Davis initially
proposed them.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a threat some Democrats find too frightening.
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats would be happier if the license fee reduction
didn't drain $3.5 billion from state coffers because that would
allow for more spending on social programs.
</P>
<P>
   Davis' threat is ''like the scene in `Blazing Saddles' where the
sheriff puts a gun to his (own) head,'' said one Democratic
lawmaker who asked for anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor claims the tax cuts he wants benefit the
high tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   He said Friday those businesses should be rewarded because their
success helped fuel the state's $12.3 billion cash windfall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe strongly in building on our strengths,'' Davis said.
</P>
<P>
   Burton takes a different view.
</P>
<P>
   ``You give people business tax cuts to spur economic activity in
down times. The economy is so good now _ we're making so many
millionaires and billionaires _ I don't know how much more
encouragement they need,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, only a few of the tax cuts Davis wants help high tech
companies.
</P>
<P>
   One research and development credit primarily helps aerospace.
Another tax break is aimed at Central Valley manufacturers. Another
is a $100 million one-time credit to persons who donate land to the
state.
</P>
<P>
   Another gives a $500 credit to persons who care for seniors at
home.
</P>
<P>
   Three of the tax cuts do help high tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Business lobbyists argue the tax breaks are needed to keep
California competitive with other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you have development in Austin? Why do you have Silicon
Alley outside Boston? Why do you have the Research Triangle in
North Carolina? Because those states are providing economic
incentives and a better educated workforce,'' said Chris Micheli, a
lobbyist representing business backing some of Davis' cuts.
</P>
<P>
   Of the high tech tax cuts, one would help employees whose
graduate school tuition is paid by their company, which often
happens in high tech firms.
</P>
<P>
   The bill would exempt the first $5,250 of the tuition from the
worker's taxes.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wants the tax cut to apply to all employees, regardless of
salary.
</P>
<P>
   Burton limited the tax cut to employees earning $50,000 or less
a year and said the tax cut would expire after five years.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wants the state's main research and development credit,
which allows business to subtract those costs from tax liability,
to climb from 12 percent to 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Burton wants to hold it to 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Another tax credit Davis wants would allow companies to carry
forward 65 percent of the losses from previous years to offset
revenue when the company turns a profit.
</P>
<P>
   Burton lowered that to 60 percent of losses. Lawmakers have
already sent that tax cut to Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the governor's own estimates, his idea would cost the state
$198 million ten years from now,'' Burton said.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Assembly Republican leader Scott Baugh of
Huntington beach, said the Assembly planned to ``put the governor's
tax relief package out of our house'' on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are always happy to provide more tax relief,''
said Jamie Fisfis, Baugh's press secretary.
</P>
<P>
   Any action the Assembly takes is subject to Senate approval.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll look at each proposal on its individual merits,'' Burton
said. ``If the license fee gets vetoed we can always turn around
and give working families with kids a tax break instead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
