<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 00:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3689 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT &LR;      06-24 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-PIRATES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG INNING GIVES JONES MORE THAN HE NEEDS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The choice was obvious but not easy. Bobby J. Jones
had seven years in the major leagues and the pride that goes with
it. But the Mets' right-hander was pitching poorly, and because of
off-days in the schedule, the plan was to skip him for two turns
through the rotation. The Mets wanted Jones to go to Triple-A
Norfolk for a while, to stay sharp and, just maybe, rediscover
something. Jones had enough major league service time to veto the
demotion, but he accepted it and is glad he did.
</P>
<P>
   Building off two starts in the minors in which he tinkered with
his delivery and fortified his curveball, Jones returned Friday
night and pitched eight strong innings, leading the Mets to a 12-2
victory over the Pittsburgh Pirates at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets scored nine runs in the third inning, one shy of the
highest single-inning total in franchise history. But Jones hardly
needed that much support. He allowed five hits and one run, walking
two and striking out eight. Those were better numbers than he
posted at Norfolk (10 innings, 15 hits, seven earned runs), but
numbers did not matter there.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have an opportunity to work on things without having that
much pressure on you,'' Jones said of his stay in the minors. ``I
think that I needed that, to go down there and just be able to work
on things.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones does not throw hard, and his assortment of pitches is
considered below average. But he has been able to master that stuff
well enough to have made an All-Star team and to have started three
times on opening day. At Norfolk, he threw more fastballs than
usual, searching to rediscover his command of the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   He also adjusted his delivery. Jones had altered it in spring
training, pumping his hands together in front of his body in an
effort to get the ball out of his glove quicker. At Norfolk, he
found a way to remove the ball on time while keeping his hands at
chest level, and he noticed he was getting better downward movement
on his fastball.
</P>
<P>
   He also worked to improve his curveball, and the combination
devastated the Pirates. In his last start for the Mets, a 13-5 loss
at Yankee Stadium on June 10, the Yankees swung and missed at only
two of Jones' first 47 pitches. Friday night, he got better results
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates' leadoff hitter, Warren Morris, struck out swinging
on a high fastball. Jason Kendall was next, and he swung through an
outside fastball _ 87 mph on the Mets' radar gun, which manager
Bobby Valentine believes is probably the slowest in the National
League _ for strike three.
</P>
<P>
   Wil Cordero then swung and missed at two curveballs before
popping out on a fastball for the third out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first batter, every pitch was crisp,'' Valentine said.
``You can't really tell what you're going to get _ things change in
a hurry in our game _ but the first inning was the perfect inning.
He threw crisp pitch after crisp pitch, right where Mike was
sitting.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Mets' nine-run third put them ahead by 10-1, Jones
told catcher Mike Piazza that he wanted to continue using all his
pitches, to pitch as if the score was 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had something to prove tonight,'' Jones said. ``I had to
stay with my game plan.''
</P>
<P>
   He stayed with it, but the first batter of the fourth, Cordero,
stroked a double down the left-field line. Jones escaped the inning
scoreless, getting two fly outs and fanning Aramis Ramirez,
squelching a big inning before it could start.
</P>
<P>
   Besides his victory over Arizona on May 19 and an abbreviated
April start in which he strained a calf muscle, Jones had allowed
at least three runs in an inning in all of his starts.
</P>
<P>
   His focus never wavered, Valentine said. Jones is not expressive
when he pitches, and people can mistake that for nonchalance. But
Valentine said he observed a ``determined competitor'' Friday
night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people may think that he doesn't care,'' Valentine said.
``He cares as much as anybody that there is.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets supported Jones (2-3) with a run on a bases-loaded balk
in the second, but the Pirates tied the score, 1-1, in the third.
That was the last time the game was close.
</P>
<P>
   With two runners on and one out in the third, the Pirates rookie
starter Bronson Arroyo went up and in with a fastball to Piazza,
who turned on it and looped it into the left-field bleachers for a
three-run homer. The Mets had a 4-1 lead, Piazza had his 21st home
run (and third in his last three games), and a rout was on.
</P>
<P>
   With two men on, Jay Payton's bouncer took a bad hop and ruined
the Pirates' chances of an inning-ending double play. One run
scored, and three batters later, Melvin Mora drove in three runs
with a double.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates helped out with two errors in the third, and by the
time Piazza fanned to end the inning, the Mets had scored nine runs
in an inning for just the fifth time in their history. The Mets
have scored more runs in an inning only once, when they posted a
10-run sixth on June 12, 1979, against Cincinnati.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
