<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 00:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3693 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a BC-SUBWAY-LOSANGELES-SFC     06-24 1525
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUBWAY-LOSANGELES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A.'S PUBLIC TRANSIT DREAM STALLS IN OPENING OF LAST LEG OF RED 
 LINE
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CARL NOLTE 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The final leg of the Los Angeles subway system
opens for business Saturday offering a dream ride _ from the San
Fernando Valley to downtown L.A. in only 30 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   But this is the end of the line for subways in Southern
California. The new Red Line subway turned out to be the most
beautiful, cleanest, most expensive and least productive subway
system ever built in the United States, a kind of gorgeous failure.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles subway is an eye-opener in more ways than one.
The trains are clean and fast. The fares are low (only $1.35 each
way). The subway runs on the honor system; there are no fare gates.
</P>
<P>
   There are also no graffiti. In three days of riding at all hours
this week, only one scrawl was found, put on car 546 by someone
named Joey.
</P>
<P>
   The stations themselves are works of art: The station at the
famous corner of Hollywood and Vine has a ceiling made of film
reels, benches that resemble low-rider cars and pillars that look
like palm trees. At the Hollywood and Western station, the walls
glitter with multicolored tiles. There is a light show with cars,
trucks and trains at one entrance to Union Station.
</P>
<P>
   There will be a new shopping-dining complex above the Hollywood
/Highland station, complete with a theater where the Academy Awards
will be staged. The main Hollywood stations celebrate showbiz; the
new North Hollywood station features images of the Gabrileano
Indians, the missions of the Spanish period, the ranchos of the
Mexican times, Amelia Earhart, and the old Big Red Cars of the old
Pacific Electric Railroad.
</P>
<P>
   The stations and trains are busy, but not crowded; there's
always a seat. ``I ride it every day,'' said Patrick Moran, a
deputy district attorney. ``I like it. I wish it went farther.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great,'' said John Campbell, a visitor from Lake
Elsinore, who was riding for the first time. ``It's the best
E-Ticket ride I've ever been on. It's wonderful. I am impressed and
surprised.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Los Angeles subway is also a cautionary tale complete
with unrealistic expectations, cost overruns, scandals,
mismanagement, political battles and even a methane explosion
during construction.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, it is clear that the three new stations opening
today will be the last. With the new stations, the subway will be
17.4 miles long and cost $4.7 billion, or $270 million a mile.
</P>
<P>
   When construction began 15 years ago, subway backers said the
system would ease congestion on the freeways and be the center of a
network of lines running to the San Fernando Valley, to the ocean
at Santa Monica, to East L.A. The Red Line subway, they said, would
carry 300,000 passengers a day by 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the Red Line has 59,750 one-way riders a day. The North
Hollywood extensions opening today are expected to bring the
ridership up to 100,000 daily, only a third of projections. This
compares with a weekday ridership of 1.16 million on the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority's bus system.
</P>
<P>
   This is the automobile capital of the world _ there are more
than 7 million cars in the Los Angeles basin, probably the only
place in the world where there are more cars than licensed drivers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the huge expenditure of money on transit, neither the
subway nor the bus system has lured passengers away from the
freeway in significant numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, over the past 15 years, public-transit use in the Los
Angeles basin has declined by 25 percent, both in market share and
in absolute numbers. In terms of traffic, said John Cox, who
monitors freeway congestion at  &UR; traffic.tann.net,  &LR; the subway ``is
lost in the noise.''
</P>
<P>
   The L.A. situation is much different from in the Bay Area, where
BART carries 327,000 riders daily _ up by 10 percent in a year and
up by 22 percent over the past 15 years. In addition, the San
Francisco Muni Metro rail lines carry about 130,000 more. The
Muni's Mission Street bus lines alone carry 63,000 daily riders _
or nearly 4,000 more than the L.A. subway.
</P>
<P>
   These numbers and the huge cost have helped erode support for
the L.A. subway.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, who served two years as Metropolitan
Transit Authority chairman, will be on hand to open the stations
today, but like other L.A. political figures, has given up on more
subways. ``I wish we had never started the whole thing,'' he said
once. ``Fixed rail is not the answer to the transportation needs of
our city.''
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles County Supervisor Zev Yaroslavsky, who represents
the district served by the new line, once was a big subway
supporter. But the problems and the cost overruns changed his mind,
and he led the 1998 fight to approve Proposition A, which banned
use of transit sales tax money to plan or build more subways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even if you believe subway is right, if you can't afford it,
what's the point?'' he said. ``We can't sustain this. Who are we
trying to kid?''
</P>
<P>
   There was no organized opposition and the measure passed by an
overwhelming margin, effectively clipping the wings of the subway
builders. Plans to extend the subway west to Santa Monica and to
the east side were scrapped. Saturday's ceremonies mark the
beginning of a new service and the end of the line.
</P>
<P>
   The rail network has been pared back. Besides the Red Line
subway, MTA operates the Blue-Line to Long Beach with light rail
trains similar to those in San Jose or Sacramento and the Green
Line from Norwalk to Redondo Beach.
</P>
<P>
   Only the Long Beach line has met expectations. It carries 60,000
riders a day. The Green Line, which runs down the middle of the
Century Freeway, has 20,000 riders _ about a third of the
forecasts.
</P>
<P>
   Where rail transit flunked, said Mark Pisano, executive director
of the Southern California Association of Governments, was at the
bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   He said his agency, which represents county governments,
evaluated rail systems in terms of effectiveness. ``They didn't
perform well,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the association figures show fully allocated costs
for the Red Line subway come out to $1.15 per passenger mile, which
means a 17.4-mile ride from Union Station to North Hollywood would
cost $20.01 to provide. The full fare is $1.35.
</P>
<P>
   There are no subway extensions in the region's transportation
plan. Instead, plans call for improved and faster bus service,
special truck lanes on freeways, better technology for drivers,
toll roads, and perhaps even magnetic levitation trains, provided
they are privately financed.
</P>
<P>
   But the big costs only wounded the subway. What killed it was
politics and a series of embarrassing mistakes. There were huge
cost overruns. Construction problems produced a giant sinkhole on
Hollywood Boulevard, and even some of the stars on Hollywood's Walk
of Fame were swallowed up.
</P>
<P>
   Workers building the line on Wilshire Boulevard produced a spark
that set off methane gas under a Ross Dress for Less store. The
resulting explosion injured 21 people.
</P>
<P>
   Another time, work had to be stopped when construction crews ran
into a series of ancient fossils. On yet another occasion, a
Metropolitan Transportation Authority consultant was convicted of
bribing an MTA official. There were three deaths in construction
accidents.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the Bus Riders Union sued the MTA claiming that the
agency had diverted money needed for bus improvements into rail.
They called the subway and two other rail operations ``racist
transit.''
</P>
<P>
   This in a city where 80 percent of the transit riders earn less
than $20,000 a year, and 66 percent of the riders are nonwhite.
</P>
<P>
   All of this was live and in color on L.A. television, which is
famously short on news and long on entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It drew a lot of media attention,'' said Keith Killough, the
transportation authority's deputy executive officer for planning.
``Some of it overblown. It eroded political and public support.''
</P>
<P>
   Killough and others in the system are proud of what was built.
The job was huge: Tunnels were dug 900 feet deep under the Santa
Monica Mountains, and workers moved enough dirt to fill the Rose
Bowl 31/2 times. The project used enough steel to build 90,000
cars, enough concrete to build a sidewalk from Los Angeles to
Boston and enough waterproof plastic liner to make 550,000
umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a grand project,'' Killough says.
</P>
<P>
   Southern California will grow by 7 million people and 4 million
jobs in 20 years, according to the association of governments'
estimates. That's the equivalent of adding two cities the size of
Chicago to the area.
</P>
<P>
   And then, said Killough, ``people will forget all the travails
we had to get here, and they will marvel at the result.''
</P>
<P>
   Killough expects people to take to the North Hollywood line,
which runs under the crowded Cahuenga Pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``All we ask is that you should try it,'' he said. ``See what
you think, and then let us know if we should do more.''
</P>
<P>
   He does not believe this is the end of the line for subways.
``It is only a brief moratorium,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0015 </DOCNO>
