<HEADER>
A3699 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-COMPUTERS-B0MBAY-TEX     06-24 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COMPUTERS-B0MBAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAG AND ... IT'S JUST A DRAG
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am in dire need of your perspicacity. My
current system is disgusting (a Pentium II with Windows 98 Second
Edition). The clock will lose a full day in about two weeks. Also,
when you click the mouse pointer on something, there is a delay,
and when I type, there is a delay before the letters show up. I
call the hardware manufacturer, and he blames the software or the
operating system. I call the software company, and they blame the
hardware or the OS. I have never been able to talk to a real person
at Microsoft, so I am unsure who they'd blame.
</P>
<P>
   _ Slow Motion
</P>
<P>
   DEAR SLOW: There are no real people at Microsoft. I mean, have
you ever actually seen anyone who works there, other than Big Bill
or Steve Ballmer? Or maybe the're all just hiding in their
windowless little offices, eating aerosol cheese and sardines,
hoping nobody asks them why their products are so full of bugs.
</P>
<P>
   One thing I really hate about trying to run down a problem with
no clear solution is trying to get a straight answer out of a
support technician. I wish they'd just say they don't have a clue
instead of pointing a finger at somebody else. And before you say
it, yes, I've done the same thing when I've wanted to get rid of a
particularly annoying user and get back to playing Unreal
Tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, since I know I'll get the run-around from three or four
different help desks, I generally start looking for the answer
myself somewhere out there on the Internet. Try the Knowledge Base
at Microsoft (support.microsoft.com) first, although ``knowledge''
is a bit of a stretch. Maybe ``Stuff We Figured Out For Whiny
Users'' didn't sound so hot to the Marketing Department.
</P>
<P>
   Most software and hardware companies have similar collections of
fixes and suggestions on their Web sites. Just look for ``support''
links.
</P>
<P>
   The best places to find an answer, however, are news groups,
where you post a message and hopefully get an answer. When the
Internet was more text-based, these groups were fabulous places for
finding people with similar interests and problems, software,
little-known tips and, of course, dirty pictures. New Internet
users often pass the groups by, probably because the dirty pictures
are easier to see using a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising the groups, I learned that you're not the only one out
there losing time and putting up with a jerky mouse and keyboard.
Most PC clocks are about as accurate as my SATs, plus a flaky
battery will exacerbate the problem. But there's something else
afoot here, a conspiracy of major proportions. OK, maybe not a
conspiracy and maybe not major, but let me point a few fingers
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Many people report the slowdowns happen after installing Win98
Second Edition or Microsoft's Y2K patches. Others complain that it
all started after installing Norton AntiVirus 5.0 with
Auto-Protect, which runs all the time. And even Microsoft says that
your system can slow down when running stuff like a virus checker
in the background. No definitive answer, but there are a few clues.
</P>
<P>
   Some programs just don't play well with Win98, so turn off your
virus checker and see if things speed up. No? Try this: Shut down
everything else that's going on behind the scenes. If you hit
Control-Alt-Delete, you'll get a dialogue box that lets you end
individual tasks. You can safely knock out everything but Explorer
and Systray. If that doesn't work, go back to the Microsoft support
site and look for document Q259161 for some other suggestions.
</P>
<P>
   (Dr. Emilio Bombay says his editors are to blame for any
misinformation or outright lies that may appear in his columns.
Write him at drbombay(at)star-telegram.com (snail-mail: Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101). Fax: (817)
390-7257. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World
Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0049EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 00:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3700 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2NDL     06-24 0917
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE RELEASES TRANSCRIPT OF INTERVIEW WITH FUND-RAISING
INVESTIGATOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Tenn., Calif., N.C.)   (CORRECTS to ``Air Force 2'' in 5th graf; SUBS 19th graf to
clarify)  
(EDS: Includes GORE-NYT, budgeted earlier; see also GORE-CONRAD,
GORE-ASSESS) 
(ART ADV: Photo NYT2 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID JOHNSTON and DON VAN NATTA Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a caustic exchange with a senior Justice
Department prosecutor two months ago, Vice President Al Gore denied
being told by aides that a 1996 luncheon at a Buddhist temple was a
fund-raising event, according to a transcript of the interview that
the vice president's lawyers released Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sure as hell don't recall having _ I sure as hell did not
have any conversations with anyone saying this is a fund-raising
event,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's angry denial was contained in a 123-page transcript of a
four-hour interview in which the head of the Justice Department's
campaign finance unit questioned Gore at the vice presidential
mansion about his fund-raising activities prior to the 1996
election.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president disclosed the interview transcript Friday
afternoon, scrambling to blunt the potential damage of the revived
Justice Department inquiry of his truthfulness in answering
questions about his efforts to raise money. Still, it risked
prolonging an issue that has dogged Gore's presidential campaign
and threatens to bring renewed com- parisons to the scandals of the
Clin- ton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always cooperated fully,'' Gore told reporters aboard
Air Force 2 Friday afternoon, as he flew from Denver to Palo Alto,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have admitted that I have made mistakes in fund raising,''
he said in the middle of a chaotic day in which he and his aides
sought to contain the latest problem to engulf his presidential
campaign. ``But I want the American people to know that I have
always told the truth on this matter. I have always cooperated
fully. And I want the entire transcript to be out there and I want
people to be able to judge it for themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Later, Gore said, ``I think the truth is my friend in this. The
truth, the full truth and nothing but the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   In the April interview, Gore was confronted with questions about
a wide array of campaign finance issues, posed by a clearly
skeptical and at times incredulous prosecutor, Robert Conrad , the
head of the campaign finance task force. Besides the Buddhist
temple luncheon, Gore was asked whether the White House coffees
were fund-raising events and, more recently, what he knew about
missing e-mail messages from his office.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's decision to release the transcript came one day after the
Justice Department confirmed that Conrad had recommended that
Attorney General Janet Reno appoint a special counsel to
investigate the truthfulness of Gore's statements about his
political fund raising.
</P>
<P>
   But the vice president also questioned the timing of the
disclosure of the new inquiry. ``Here we are four months before an
election that takes place every four years,'' Gore told reporters.
``You can read into that what you want to.''
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas Friday seized on the renewed
inquiry of Gore's fund-raising activities. ``I reiterate my call
for a new tone in Washington which is going to require a new
administration in Washington,'' Bush said. ``People are sick and
tired of all this stuff and the best way to start anew is with a
new administration.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore has clearly made the political calculation that the public
will view the transcript, filled with questions about events that
occurred as long ago as 1989, as old news.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have full confidence in the judgment of the American
people,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's answers during the April 18 interview at times appeared
to conflict with conclusions reached by a 1997 inquiry by a Senate
panel that investigated campaign finance inquiries. But Gore
dismissed its report as ``a highly partisan document.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Gore insisted that the 103 White House coffees
held in 1995 and 1996 with campaign donors were not ``fund-raising
tools'' used to raise money for the Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   The Senate panel, led by Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., found in
1997 that supporters who had attended the coffee events between
November 1995 and October 1996 contributed a total of $7.7 million
within one month of having attended the coffees.
</P>
<P>
   During the questioning, Gore recalled that he had remembered
``only one that I attended briefly.'' But the Senate panel found
that he had hosted 23 coffees and attended eight with President
Clinton. Confronted with the contradictory information about the
coffees, Gore said, ``That seems inaccurate to me.''
</P>
<P>
   As a legal matter,the apparent conflicts with Gore's statements
may fall short of sufficient grounds to show that Gore illegally
perjured himself, a law enforcement official said Friday. That is
one reason, the officials said, Reno has, so far, shown no sign
that she is prepared to refer the case to an outside prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   Reno, after searing internal battles in 1997 and 1998, refused
to seek an independent counsel to investigate Gore's fund-raising
efforts over the objections of some of her senior advisers.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
