at Microsoft (support.microsoft.com) first, although ``knowledge''
is a bit of a stretch. Maybe ``Stuff We Figured Out For Whiny
Users'' didn't sound so hot to the Marketing Department.
</P>
<P>
   Most software and hardware companies have similar collections of
fixes and suggestions on their Web sites. Just look for ``support''
links.
</P>
<P>
   The best places to find an answer, however, are news groups,
where you post a message and hopefully get an answer. When the
Internet was more text-based, these groups were fabulous places for
finding people with similar interests and problems, software,
little-known tips and, of course, dirty pictures. New Internet
users often pass the groups by, probably because the dirty pictures
are easier to see using a browser.
</P>
<P>
   Cruising the groups, I learned that you're not the only one out
there losing time and putting up with a jerky mouse and keyboard.
Most PC clocks are about as accurate as my SATs, plus a flaky
battery will exacerbate the problem. But there's something else
afoot here, a conspiracy of major proportions. OK, maybe not a
conspiracy and maybe not major, but let me point a few fingers
anyway.
</P>
<P>
   Many people report the slowdowns happen after installing Win98
Second Edition or Microsoft's Y2K patches. Others complain that it
all started after installing Norton AntiVirus 5.0 with
