<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 00:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3703 &Cx1f; tta-z
u w BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2NDL     06-24 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FUNDRAISING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: senior advisers. 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Still, Conrad is not alone in his recommendation to refer the
case to a special prosecutor, the officials said Friday. FBI
Director Louis Freeh also favors a special counsel and has long
urged Reno to do so.
</P>
<P>
   During the interview with Gore, Conrad led the questioning,
assisted by two FBI agents. Conrad devoted a majority of the
four-hour interview to Gore's understanding of the true purpose of
the Buddhist temple event, a subject that Gore had not been asked
about in his four previous interviews with federal investigators
from the campaign finance unit.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad repeatedly showed Gore numerous memos _ all of which had
been made public years ago _ from aides that suggested that it was
known that the event was intended to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``You were aware in late February, were you not, that there was
a goal of raising $108 million by the DNC?'' Conrad asked,
referring to Democratic National Committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' the vice president answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then a couple of months later there is a DNC-sponsored event
at the temple and it didn't raise any fund-raising issues in your
mind?'' Conrad went on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did not know this was a fund-raiser,'' Gore answered.
</P>
<P>
   But later in the interview, Gore inadvertently referred to the
temple event as a ``fund-raiser.'' The vice president's personal
lawyer, James F. Neal, quickly advised Gore that he had misspoken.
</P>
<P>
   Neal told the vice president, ``I thought you said previously
you didn't, you still don't know whether it was a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore then replied, ``Well, that's right. That is more accurate.
Let me, let me amend that. That was first time it was alleged to
be, to have been a fund-raiser.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hsi Lai event, held on April 29, 1996 in Hacienda Heights,
Calif., was one of the most embarrassing episodes of the 1996
campaign finance scandal. The event was organized by Maria Hsia, a
longtime friend and political ally of the vice president who had
collected money before the event from monks and nuns, some of whom
had taken vows of poverty.
</P>
<P>
   As a tax exempt religious institution, the temple was not
allowed to serve as a venue for political fund raising or itself to
make political donations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was asked repeatedly in late 1996 and 1997 about his
knowledge of whether the event was a fund-raiser, and according to
Conrad responded with differing statements.
</P>
<P>
   Hsia was convicted in March for hiding $109,000 in illegal
contributions and making false statements to federal regulators
about the temple luncheon. She is awaiting sentencing.
</P>
<P>
   Gore insisted that he did not learn that the luncheon was used
to raise money until several months after it had occurred. In
between, he said in numerous interviews with the press that he
understood the luncheon was a ``community outreach event.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no solicitation of money,'' Gore said. ``I did not
see any money or checks change hands. I never heard it discussed.
Nor do I believe it took place, incidentally.''
</P>
<P>
   He told Conrad, ``Perhaps you know that some money changed hands
there. But to this day, I don't think any did.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday at the Justice Department, Reno acknowledged that
prosecutors had embarked on a renewed investigation of Gore's
statements under oath about his political fund-raising practices
during the 1996 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking at her weekly news conference, Reno said that she would
ignore the inflamed partisan passions surrounding the election year
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most important thing in any investigation, particularly in
this time of year, is that we conduct an investigation the right
way, not in the headlines, not with pressure from people who may
have differing views but just do it right _ methodically,
carefully, without commenting on it _ and get it done as quickly as
possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats sought to shift the spotlight to the background and
possible motives of Conrad, the head of the Justice Department's
campaign finance task force who made the special counsel
recommendation late last week.
</P>
<P>
   In August 1996, while working as a federal prosecutor in
Charlotte, N.C., Conrad contributed $250 to Sen. Jesse Helms,
R-N.C., Federal Election Commission reports show. Democrats said
the contribution raised questions about his political motives in
his inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews Friday, several senior Justice Department
officials defended Conrad's impartiality and said there was no
basis to believe that his legal judgments were politically
motivated.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
