<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3706 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-LAKERS-LAPD-LADN     06-24 1074
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LAKERS-LAPD-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAPD'S RESPONSE TO RAMPAGE WENT AGAINST GAME PLAN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE CARNEY AND LISA VAN PROYEN 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ LAPD officers failed to move swiftly when violence
erupted after the Lakers won the NBA title, despite their own
confidential plan calling an immediate show of overwhelming force
if there was trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The confidential LAPD plan, dated June 5 and obtained Friday by
the Los Angeles Daily News, noted that there was a high potential
for violence and that lawlessness should be dealt with quickly and
effectively to avoid an escalation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The early moments of the civil disorder are critical,''
according to the department's Lakers Victory Operations Plan 2000.
``The disorder should be contained to the smallest possible
geographical area and participants isolated from the public.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, officers held back while the mob - ostensibly
celebrating the team's first championship in 12 years - menaced
fans walking or driving away from Staples Center, vandalized and
looted area businesses and set several vehicles ablaze, including
two vacant police cruisers.
</P>
<P>
   Motorcycle officers escorting a limousine retreated after the
crowd swarmed the vehicle, which managed to escape.
</P>
<P>
   LAPD officials declined to comment specifically on the plan but
defended their overall handling of the incident.
</P>
<P>
   But rank-and-file officers criticized the department for failing
to adhere to the plan, saying supervisors ordered them to wait
before making arrests at Staples Center, even though they wanted to
move in as the mob became more violent and began to spread.
</P>
<P>
   ``The plan said `move in quickly.' The orders said `stand back
and wait,''' said Ted Hunt, president of the Police Protective
League, the officers' union. ``It's incredibly frustrating and
embarrassing to officers that are handcuffed by their management.
With crowd control you take swift and appropriate action. You don't
step back and wait-and-see. They already tried that and it failed
eight years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   LAPD spokesman Cmdr. David Kalish said that after the crowd got
out of control Monday night, about 300 extra officers had to be
called in from around the city to back up the 300 assigned to the
Staples Center area. He said it took ``some time'' deploy the
officers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was thought that would be a sufficient number of
personnel,'' Kalish said. ``That's something we'll look at. Through
the game there were absolutely no problems.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the department didn't want be heavy-handed with people
simply celebrating, and didn't want to throw officers into a
situation where they were far outnumbered.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan's office said the police did ``a fine
job'' Monday night, but had not seen the Lakers Victory Operations
Plan and would not question Chief Bernard C. Parks about why it
wasn't followed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor would not presume to second-guess the police chief
and his officers while they are out on the street making decisions.
We're not about to do any Monday-morning quarterbacking,'' said
Deputy Mayor Manuel Valencia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mayor was briefed extensively by the police chief, the
fire chief and the head of the DOT (Department of Transportation),
so basically, we're fine. We have already said we're going to be
getting from the police chief recommendations for how we can
improve and make sure we do a better job in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Police officials said Monday night that they had expected only
good-natured celebrations, and didn't have enough officers at
Staples Center to handle the crowd of more than 10,000 that massed
outside the arena during and after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``We certainly planned for a crowd. But we're not mind readers
and we had no experience with this type of thing,'' said the LAPD
incident commander at Staples Center, Capt. Stuart Maislin, in an
interview Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Operations Plan noted the potential for trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is concern for potential spontaneous celebrations in the
streets and civil disturbance from overzealous Lakers fans,'' it
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Experience from past disorders ... dictates that uniformed
officers should be deployed to the field as soon as possible to
deter criminal behavior and to present an overwhelming show of
force.''
</P>
<P>
   The history in other cities could have been a guide, as well.
Riots featuring vandalism, car burnings and other mayhem have
become a grim tradition in the wake of team championships, such as
after victories by the Denver Broncos in 1997, the Chicago Bulls in
1991, 1992, 1993 and 1996, the Detroit Pistons in 1990 and the
Montreal Canadiens in 1986 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Maislin did not return messages Friday, but a source within the
department said plans like the one for the Lakers are seen merely
as guidelines, and that it is ultimately up to the commanders at
the scene to make tactical decisions.
</P>
<P>
   The Operations Plan report, drawn up in anticipation of a Lakers
victory and ensuing spontaneous street celebration, said police
commanders ``must rapidly deploy forces and use equipment that will
quickly demonstrate the Department's unwavering determination to
restore order. The arrest of violators and the repeated dispersal
of unlawful groups will demoralize the crowd's will to resist
lawful police orders.''
</P>
<P>
   Officers made 11 arrests Monday night, but a dozen people were
hurt in the unrest and numerous businesses and vehicles were
damaged or destroyed within several blocks around Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this type of crowd you don't want to be provocative and
create a problem,'' Kalish said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't perfect and unfortunately we did have some
vandalism. However, at the end of the day, the Lakers won, there
were no serious injuries, no deaths, and the vast, vast amount of
people at the event had a great time.''
</P>
<P>
   In a training manual from the International Association of
Chiefs of Police, the organization held up the LAPD response to the
Rodney King verdict in 1992 as an example of how not to handle
crowd control.
</P>
<P>
   ``Immediate action is required in order to protect lives and
property. Containment is one of the most important initial measures
that officers can take in efforts to defuse and disband a riotous
of potentially riotous situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the crowd is not dispersed and order restored, arson and
wholesale destruction and violence often follows.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
