<P>
   ISRAEL-ARMY (Jerusalem) _ Near the ancient caves of Bet Guvrin
in Israel, there is a secret Palestinian village on a hill. It
consists of about 15 houses and a mosque and is for Israelis only.
The village is a simulation, a three-dimensional stage set that the
Israeli army uses to train its troops in occupation techniques,
riot control and all-out battle. It is populated by soldiers
playing the roles of what an army official called ``the enemy'':
Palestinian stone throwers and police officers, even journalists
and housewives. For the Israeli soldiers trained there, the
experience can be dizzying. By Deborah Sontag. 1,300 words.
</P>
<P>
   BANGLADESH-ACID (Gosarigaon, Bangladesh) _ More than 100
Bangladeshi women a year are victims of attacks by men, usually
spurned suitors, who throw acid in their faces. No one is sure why
this crime occurs here at such a high pace, for this nation on the
Indian subcontinent is not so different from many others in its
poverty or its culture or its treatment of women. And in a
male-dominated society, the victims rarely find justice. By Barry
Bearak.
