<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 01:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3710 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-KOREA-N     06-24 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-KOREA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOREA, AN EMBRACE THAT SHOOK THE WORLD 
</HEADLINE>
   By STEVEN R. WEISMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday marks the 50th anniversary of the start of the Korean
War. As all schoolchildren in North Korea know, the war began when
South Korea invaded its peaceful neighbor to the north. Since then
the government in Seoul has remained enslaved to a clique of
generals, spies and capitalists who are puppets of the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Old attitudes die hard, as is obvious from the twisted
propaganda along these lines that keeps flowing from Pyongyang even
after the extraordinary meeting between leaders of the North and
South last week. A visitor who met with President Kim Dae-Jung in
Seoul after the meeting says that despite all the euphoria in his
country, the South Korean president cautions that it will take
decades, perhaps generations, to achieve reunification.
</P>
<P>
   Still, anyone following recent events on the Korean Peninsula
cannot help but find them amazing.
</P>
<P>
   On one side is President Kim of South Korea, a former dissident
once rescued from a ship _ where he was about to be tossed
overboard wrapped in heavy chains by government goons _ only after
intervention by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On the other is Kim Jong Il of the North, often described as a
murderous megalomaniac surrounded by concubines. Among other
things, in the course of his despotic career he is said to have
ordered the blowing up of a civilian airliner, a bombing attack on
the South Korean Cabinet and the kidnapping of a movie star and
director who were forced to help build up the North Korean film
industry.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder that The Economist features the oddly coiffed and
reclusive Kim on its cover with the caption ``Greetings,
Earthlings.''
</P>
<P>
   The handful of Western visitors who have been in North Korea all
liken it to another planet. When I was in Pyongyang in 1991,
revolutionary slogans were everywhere, and loudspeakers at
construction sites exhorted workers with picks and shovels to toil
for the glory of the state. The 105-story hotel then under
construction, proudly described as the tallest hotel in the world,
was already sagging visibly. It still has not opened. Everyone I
met recited slogans about North Korea as paradise on earth. Some
admitted to meat shortages, but not to the truth of reports of
starvation in the countryside.
</P>
<P>
   Even if reconciliation remains a distant dream, the significance
of the two Kims meeting is tremendous. It shakes the equation in
East Asia and could even alter the political scene in the United
States. For one thing, the meeting puts South Korea in an
unaccustomed place _ the driver's seat of the policies being worked
out to deal with the danger posed by the North.
</P>
<P>
   For years the United States has taken the lead in negotiating
with North Korea, offering a combination of threats and incentives
to get it to stop building nuclear weapons. Now after negotiating a
deal on nuclear and missile restraint with Pyongyang, the Clinton
administration must defend its approach against charges of naivete
by hawkish Republicans, including advisers to Gov. George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of the two Korean leaders is unlikely to soften
their criticism. Indeed, some Republicans talk of ``taking out''
the North Korean nuclear installations. But they overlook the
reality that, aside from the difficulty of destroying facilities
hundreds of feet below ground, any such attempt would lead to the
destruction of Seoul with a barrage of mortar, artillery and poison
gas counterattacks.
</P>
<P>
   In years past, the United States has served as a brake on
confrontation-minded generals in Seoul. Today, with hawkish
Americans calling for a tough stance toward North Korea and plans
for an antimissile defense system, South Korea may be the one
arguing for military restraint and political engagement.
</P>
<P>
   In regional terms, the irony is that for all the yearning for
reunification of the Korean Peninsula, almost no one close to the
situation wants it to happen anytime soon. The South Koreans fear
that a rapid absorption of the North will wreck their economy in
the way Germany was weakened when it was reunified a decade ago.
Russia, China and Japan _ which for centuries jockeyed for
supremacy on the peninsula _ are hardly enthusiastic today about
the possibility of a newly powerful rival in the neighborhood. Many
U.S. experts have no such concerns but nonetheless fear the day _
regarded by some experts as inevitable _ that Koreans ask for the
United States to withdraw its troops.
</P>
<P>
   Why has North Korea decided to reach out to the people it still
regards as implacable foes? The answers lie in the overwhelming
economic incentives and in apparent pressure from China to defuse
the situation in hopes of speeding the withdrawal of the American
presence. President Kim of South Korea has also done a masterly job
of assuring the North that he really does not want to absorb it or
destroy its system.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, it appears that the unpredictable Kim of the North may
be looking for legitimacy. Few doubt that North Korea remains
capable of a clandestine nuclear program, missile exports or other
dangerous behavior. Yet the North may be willing to keep its
aggressive impulses in check in return for help from its wary
adversaries. As for South Korea, for now it has taken the lead, and
the rest of the world will have to respond. Who knows? The latest
in North Korean movies may soon be on their way to the outside
world.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
