<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GAGNE'S RETURN WILL REQUIRE TOUGH CHOICES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ When the Los Angeles Dodgers sent right-hander Eric
Gagne to the minor leagues 11 days ago, it was a decision manager
Davey Johnson wrestled with terribly.
</P>
<P>
   But one thing Johnson knows is he wants Gagne back and starting
with the Dodgers. How to achieve that continues to be debated.
</P>
<P>
   The obvious choices, barring injury, are to bump Orel Hershiser
or Carlos Perez from the rotation, which is why the Dodgers brass
are eager to see Hershiser pitch today against St. Louis. They want
to see improvement from him.
</P>
<P>
   And the solution could be as simple as putting either Hershiser
or Perez in the bullpen, or as complicated as releasing or trading
one of them, though Hershiser has a no-trade clause and team
officials believe it would take a lot for him to waive that.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are different ways I thought we could give our club a
shot in the arm,'' Johnson said. ``There's a couple areas that
concern me right now. We need to get a good outing out of Orel, and
see where we're at after that. You have discussions about if he's
not making an improvement, where do we go?
</P>
<P>
   ``We (Johnson and assistant general manager Bill Geivett) talked
about the suspensions, and if you went to 12 pitchers, what would
that do? There's a lot of things going on. If (Todd) Hundley comes
back early next week, where does that put us? When is (baseball)
making the rulings (on the suspensions)? There's a lot of things to
kind of think about before you start changing the balance of the
ballclub. We'll know more in a day or so.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll know because Hundley's on a rehab assignment in
Albuquerque (he was 0 for 3 and caught seven innings Friday), and
because of Hershiser's start. The Dodgers said they were committed
to Gagne, who's making $205,000 this season. But they've elected to
go with Hershiser and Perez. Hershiser is making $2 million and
Perez is being paid $5 million this and guaranteed $7.5 million in
2001.
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser and Perez, currently in the fourth and fifth spots in
the rotation, are a combined 5-5 in 17 starts. Hershiser's ERA in
four starts is 9.37 and Perez's is 5.89 in 13 starts. Gagne was 1-4
with a with a 4.47 ERA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, we'll get something to build on with (Hershiser
today),'' said Johnson, who was then asked about Perez's dilemma
again. ``We've hashed that situation over and over and over, and
it's like a topic of discussion every day, when really what it
boils down to is what's the best thing for our ballclub, and (do
we) have the options if something else happens. Then, where do we
go?''
</P>
<P>
   Releasing Perez doesn't appear to be an option at this point,
and it's unlikely a team would take him in a trade unless the
Dodgers pick up a bundle of his contract. Also, the Dodgers lack
pitching depth at the minor-league level. Jamie Arnold and Mike
Judd aren't pitching well enough to merit consideration for a
recall from Albuquerque if Gagne was back.
</P>
<P>
   Though Gagne's struggled at times with his pitch count with the
Dodgers, the club doesn't want him wasting away in the minors. He
allowed three hits, struck out 11 and didn't walk a batter in eight
innings of Albuquerque's 2-0 shutout win against Nashville on
Thursday. Gagne's 3-0 with a 0.86 ERA in three minor-league starts.
He's allowed two earned runs on nine hits in 21 innings while
striking out 26 and walking three.
</P>
<P>
   Slumping bat, awesome glove: Since being recalled from
Albuquerque on May 31 and entering into a platoon situation with
Kevin Elster at shortstop, Alex Cora has played well defensively
but has slacked off offensively.
</P>
<P>
   Cora, who is batting .258, hit .297 in his first stint with the
Dodgers but he's 13 for 56 (.232) since returning. Cora also has
struck out 10 times, including his first three at-bats against the
Cardinals.
</P>
<P>
   However, he made two outstanding defensive plays. He got Craig
Paquette on a ground ball that glanced off third baseman Adrian
Beltre's glove in the fourth and nailed Paquette in the eighth on a
broken-bat slow roller.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
