<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3713 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE     06-24 0550
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CAMPAIGN-FINANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A CAMPAIGN FINANCE RUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, June 24:
</P>
<P>
   No one wants to come out against the public disclosure of
fat-cat donors to political ad campaigns. That would be too
embarrassing when the public is so disgusted with fund-raising
abuses. So House Republican leaders have done what must have seemed
like the next best thing. They want a disclosure requirement that
is so inequitable and destructive of First Amendment rights that it
cannot pass. Their scheme is to use this hopelessly defective
legislation as a tool to prevent a serious, even-handed disclosure
measure from getting a fair vote, even though it has broad
bipartisan support. Reformers must defy these leaders and stand up
for real reform this week.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the effort to stop a new breed of shadowy slush
funds, created by elected officials and interest groups under
Section 527 of the tax code, from raising and spending undisclosed
sums for ad campaigns in elections. These groups have sprung up
this year and, circumventing campaign disclosure laws, run
anonymous attack ads like the one that smeared Sen. John McCain
during the primaries. That ad turned out to be paid for by
supporters of Gov. George W. Bush, but others have spread across
the air waves with no one knowing who was paying for them.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Rep. Tom DeLay and other foes of campaign
fund-raising curbs have said that what is needed is more
disclosure, not more limits on the fund-raising itself. Now DeLay,
Dick Armey and Bill Archer, the chairman of the House Ways and
Means Committee, have come up with a disclosure bill that would
apply to all sorts of activities, not just those in an election
campaign. Moreover, the disclosure requirements for lobbying would
be absurdly punitive toward unions. A labor group lobbying on a
bill would have onerous disclosure requirements, whereas a
corporation lobbying on the same bill would not.
</P>
<P>
   This badly drawn bill is to be voted on in the House next week.
But an alternative is being prepared by several reformers of both
parties, including Rep. Christopher Shays, Michael Castle and
Martin Meehan and Sens. McCain, Joseph Lieberman, Russell Feingold
and Olympia Snowe. Republican leaders are suggesting they might not
allow the bipartisan alternative to the floor. Their mechanism
would be to offer a rule adopted by the Rules Committee, which is a
tool of the speaker, allowing only one bill to be voted on, up or
down _ the one that everyone knows has no chance of passing. This
tactic is reminiscent of Speaker Newt Gingrich at his worst, when
he tried and failed to stop a soft-money ban from being passed in
the House two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   There has not been any meaningful campaign finance reform passed
in Congress in many years. The battle has come down to something so
elementary as to be beyond dispute: ripping the curtain of secrecy
from fund-raising that the public thought it had outlawed back in
the dark Watergate days. Lawmakers in the House must demand a
chance to vote on real reform, not the sham bill that is being
force-fed them by DeLay and his colleagues. To miss this
opportunity will only deepen popular cynicism and make more
scandals inevitable.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0122EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 01:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3717 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-B     06-24 0904
