<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-BLUEJAYS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RED SOX COME UP LAME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL MADDEN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ This 5-4 loss by the Red Sox to the Blue Jays was
painful. Literally and figuratively.
</P>
<P>
   Literally, because Jose Offerman (knee) could not even play,
Nomar Garciaparra (leg) had to pull himself out of defensive duty,
and Trot Nixon (right hamstring) fell in a heap at first base
during a most-painful eighth inning for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   By game's end, there were enough ice packs and walking wounded
in the Boston locker room to suggest a football team in late
December rather than a baseball team in June.
</P>
<P>
   And the only bright light for the Red Sox was that Nixon's
injury might not be as serious as it looked. Manager Jimy Williams
hopefully suggested it was a ``cramp'' and Nixon described the
injury as his hamstring ``knotting up'' on him during a pivotal
play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't hear anything pop,'' said Nixon, who was able to limp
around the locker room afterward. ``I'll know more (today).''
</P>
<P>
   Figuratively, though, this loss was similar to so many painful
losses the Red Sox have suffered in the last month. Poor base
running (two runners thrown out) and the inability to come through
in the clutch once again doomed the team to yet another one-run
loss, its 14th in 20 such games.
</P>
<P>
   Boston's 6-14 record in one-run games is far and away the worst
in the league, the minus-8 differential much worse than Seattle's
minus-5 (5-10 in one-run games). Poor hitting and base running,
much more than poor pitching, have prevented the Red Sox from
winning the games title contenders must win.
</P>
<P>
   Not to mention poor luck. With the bases loaded and two out in
the eighth, Toronto closer Billy Koch unleashed a pitch to Jason
Varitek that bounced past catcher Alberto Castillo. It was headed
for the backstop and would have brought home Garciaparra with the
tying run. Instead, the ball bounced off the leg of home plate
umpire Dale Scott, ricocheted up the third base line, and
Garciaparra was forced to hold. Varitek ultimately popped out to
short left, ending the threat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We caught a great kick save from the umpire with a man on
third and that was the game,'' said delighted Blue Jays manager Jim
Fregosi, whose team leapfrogged over the Red Sox into first place.
Toronto had not been in first place since Opening Day. The win
marked the first time Toronto has been in first place (after April)
since 1993, when the Blue Jays won their second straight World
Series.
</P>
<P>
   But poor base running by the Red Sox' Jeff Frye earlier in that
eighth inning had short-circuited a chance for a huge inning.
Toronto starter Frank Castillo (4-5) suddenly lost everything with
one out after retiring 16 of 17 batters and 15 in a row. Enjoying a
5-2 lead, Castillo gave up back-to-back doubles to Darren Lewis and
Frye with one out.
</P>
<P>
   Nixon then hit a sharp grounder deep into the shortstop hole and
appeared to have an infield hit, even though shortstop Alex
Gonzalez fielded the ball. But Frye froze and then belatedly began
running toward third and was easily cut down by Gonzalez's throw to
third baseman Tony Batista.
</P>
<P>
   ``I made a mistake,'' said Frye, normally one of the Red Sox
with keen baseball instincts. ``I can't run into an out there. But
(Gonzalez) was right behind me, playing Trot to pull, and when Trot
hit the ball I froze. But then I remembered he was playing behind
me and I thought the ball was going to get through because he was
playing Trot to pull. (Gonzalez) must have gone 30 feet on that
play to get that ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still, I can't get thrown out there.''
</P>
<P>
   With all eyes on third base, watching Frye being tagged out, few
of the 28,198 fans at SkyDome noticed that Nixon was in a heap at
first base, his leg having given out on him a few feet from the
bag.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running there, trying to get down the line because I
thought he'd be throwing to first and my hamstring sort of knotted
up on me,'' said Nixon. ``I didn't feel anything pop and what I
felt mostly was that my whole leg knotted up.''
</P>
<P>
   After that doubly-painful play, the Red Sox still came back.
Garciaparra walked and Carl Everett followed with a double down the
right field line, scoring Curtis Pride, who was running for Nixon,
closing the Blue Jays' lead to 5-4. Brian Daubach worked a walked
off Koch to load the bases, but Varitek, after that would-be wild
pitch, could not come through.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had taken an early 2-0 lead on homers by Nixon (No.
8) in the first and Everett (No. 23) in the second off Castillo.
But John Wasdin (0-3) showcased his penchant for giving up homers
as Toronto, the American league's top homer-hitting team, hit three
blasts off him.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely wasn't the game I was looking for from me, the
game the team was looking for, or the game the city of Boston was
looking for,'' said Wasdin. ``I was very anxious out there. It was
disappointing.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays tied the game in the second on a homer by Brad
Fullmer and a two-out single by the meek-hitting Homer Bush (.188
at the time) that drove in Alberto Castillo. Toronto took a 4-2
lead in the third on a two-run homer by Raul Mondesi and scored its
fifth run in the fourth when Jose Cruz went deep.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought back,'' said Williams.
</P>
<P>
   But once again, they lost a game good teams cannot lose with
such regularity, a one-run game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
