<HEADLINE>
FIZER NOT SURE ABOUT CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SEAN KEARNS  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All-American Marcus Fizer, projected as a possible
Los Angeles Clippers selection in the NBA Draft is lukewarm about
playing for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers have the third overall pick in the June 28 draft.
Fizer, who left Iowa State after his junior season, was asked about
the possibility of playing for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't know,'' Fizer said by phone. ``I don't know
what it is about the Clippers. My agent has informed me about the
Clippers ... who knows, I might not go to them.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer, a 6-foot-8 forward, didn't get into specifics about what
his agent, Henry Thomas, had told him.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas, reached later, said that he gives all his clients basic
information about the teams that might draft them such as rosters,
free agents and the coaching situation.
</P>
<P>
   Fizer added that he had heard negative comments about the
Clippers from fellow draftees but didn't elaborate. When it came
down to playing for the Clippers, Fizer was noncommittal. He said
he wanted to hold off judgment until he had better information.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm really not going to voice that right now,'' said Fizer,
who was on his way to Orlando for a second workout with the Magic.
``I won't have any worries until I find out later.''
</P>
<P>
   Fizer did have positive feelings toward Elgin Baylor, Clippers
vice president of basketball operations. Fizer met Baylor when he
worked out for the Clippers at the NBA pre-draft camp in Chicago
earlier this month.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great guy,'' Fizer said. ``He was a great player when
he played in the pros. He's a guy who wants to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor, who gave his draft overview on a conference call Friday,
said Fizer had a good workout with the Clippers in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``We liked what we saw,'' Baylor said. ``Certainly if you talk
about an NBA body, he has that.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor added that Fizer has good ballhandling skills for a 6-8
player.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas said the Clippers are a team that could use his client.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't expressed any preference nor has he to any
particular franchise,'' Thomas said. ``He's going to be happy when
the day comes that he can hear his name called.''
</P>
<P>
   Thomas represented point guard Charles Smith who played for the
Clippers from 1998 until January 1999. Thomas said that the
dealings between the two sides were normal.
</P>
<P>
   Coaching update: Baylor backed off his earlier statements that
the Clippers would have a coach in place by the NBA Draft, meaning
the Clippers could be drafting without a coach for the second time
in three years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might not happen,'' Baylor said. ``It might happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Baylor added, ``I don't think a coach at this point in time
would have a lot of knowledge about the players (in the draft).''
</P>
<P>
   The only two announced candidates for the job are Clippers
assistant coach Dennis Johnson and Denver Nuggets assistant coach
John Lucas.
</P>
<P>
   Lucas, in Houston working out draftees and veterans in the
off-season, said he is interested in the position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a person who likes to see things come back,'' said Lucas,
who has been a head coach in Philadelphia and San Antonio. ``I
think they have a great nucleus in a city where they can have two
teams that can be successful.''
</P>
<P>
   Former Georgetown coach John Thompson, a friend of Baylor's
since childhood, is no longer a candidate for the Clippers job.
</P>
<P>
   Baylor said Johnson would be the coach of the Clippers team in
the Summer Pro League at the Long Beach State Pyramid. The Summer
Pro League begins July 8, which means a contract extension for
Johnson. His contract runs out at the end of this month.
</P>
<P>
   Miles and Alexander: The Clippers didn't work out Darius Miles,
the 6-foot-9 high schooler from St. Louis. But that, said Baylor,
does not rule him out of Clippers draft plans ... Baylor does not
plan to take Fresno State guard Courtney Alexander with the third
pick. Baylor said he would take Alexander if he had a deal to trade
down in the draft. So far, Baylor said he does not see any good
deals for the third spot.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
