<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-CHISOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN UNKNOWN LIFTS THE YANKS, BUT RIVERA LETS THEM DOWN 
</HEADLINE>
   By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ The New York Yankees were pummeled last week by the
Chicago White Sox at Yankee Stadium. The two-time defending World
Series champions lost four games in their backyard in emphatic
fashion and trudged around like shadows of their former selves.
They were also ornery about losing two games to the Boston Red Sox
this week and splitting a pivotal series they could have swept.
</P>
<P>
   All of their angst had been building, and the Yankees had to
turn to Ben Ford to help them find redemption against the team with
the best record in the American League.
</P>
<P>
   Ben Who? Ford is the 24-year-old rookie who has been a reliever
for all but two starts in his career. He was rushed to the major
leagues because of Orlando Hernandez's sprained right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   It was not Ford who failed the Yankees as he pitched effectively
into the seventh inning. It was Mariano Rivera who failed them.
Carlos Lee belted a leadoff homer in the ninth inning and Jose
Valentin had a two-out broken-bat single to deliver Herbert Perry
with the decisive run as the White Sox rallied for two runs in the
ninth to win, 4-3, beating the Yankees for the fifth straight game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, I was trying to do my job in the ninth,'' Rivera
said. ``I couldn't do it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees (36-32) dropped to third place in the AL East, one
game behind the first-place Blue Jays (40-34) and a half game
behind the Red Sox (37-32). After losing their third straight game,
the Yankees are as low as third for the first time since April 18,
1999.
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox slowly gained more fan support as 38,773 fans came
to Comiskey Park on a muggy, rainy night. They came to see if the
surging White Sox could stymie the Yankees again. Few came to watch
Ford.
</P>
<P>
   But he lasted into the seventh, Jeff Nelson rescued him by
wriggling through a bases-loaded, one-out jam and the Yankees used
run-scoring hits by Bernie Williams and Shane Spencer in the eighth
to take a 3-2 lead. Rivera stranded a runner in the eighth, but he
crumbled in the ninth and botched his third save in 19 chances. The
Yankees' closer mishandled four saves in 49 chances all of last
season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mo is human, I guess,'' manager Joe Torre said. ``We're
finding that out. We'll still take our chances with him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though the Yankees are pursuing offense and again showed
they need it because Paul O'Neill's homer was all they managed off
starter Jim Parque, Ford delighted them with his poise.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez will toss a ball on Saturday and could be placed on
the disabled list if he feels uncomfortable, which would probably
keep Ford in the rotation. For one night, Ford, who had the flu,
looked as if he belonged. But, for the fifth straight game, the
White Sox humbled the Yankees. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm upset about the loss,'' Ford said. ``It's hard to take,
but I'm happy with where I'm at.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
