<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHAW FAILS TO BAIL OUT DODGERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Through all his problems in the last month, Los
Angeles Dodgers closer Jeff Shaw figured one part of his struggles
were the baseball breaks going against him.
</P>
<P>
   Most of his saves were in one-run games, and broken bat singles
and defensive lapses didn't help.
</P>
<P>
   Mother Nature and the umpiring crew threw some more circumstance
Friday at Shaw, who blew his seventh save in 19 chances under some
very trying circumstances that raises more questions about how
he'll be used in the future. The game was delayed 22 minutes by
rain with two outs and a St. Louis runner on second in the 11th
inning.
</P>
<P>
   When play resumed, J.D. Drew singled in the game-tying run off
Shaw.
</P>
<P>
   But there was a repeat performance in the 12th as weather forced
a 19-minute delay before Craig Paquette hit a three-run homer off
Shaw to give the Cardinals a 9-6 win at a near-empty Busch Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had to run out after a rain delay to pitch again,
and to do it twice is something I've never seen,'' said Dodgers
reliever Mike Fetters, a closer for three years in Milwaukee. ``It
was a tough spot, there was no one available.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time (the game was delayed) I thought, with two
outs, all we need is one more pitch to get out of the inning and
the game is over. To call it like that, I thought it was a little
premature. It was already raining. Why couldn't it wait until that
batter was done?''
</P>
<P>
   When crew chief Rick Reed called the second rain delay, it came
with runners on first and second and one out and a 2-2 count on
Craig Paquette.
</P>
<P>
   But the strangeness of the evening began with a 1-1 count to
Drew in the 11th. That's when the heavy rains, along with some
thunder and lightning, came. It lasted but 10 minutes, but by the
time the tarp was removed and the field manicured, the delay was
twice that.
</P>
<P>
   Placido Polanco led off the 11th by slapping Shaw's first pitch
through the right side of the infield. He was sacrificed to second,
and Shaw got Edgar Renteria to fly out to right.
</P>
<P>
   But Drew singled to right to tie it 6-6 before being thrown out
by Shawn Green at second.
</P>
<P>
   ``We battled and came back and had the lead, and the rain came
and put a damper on it,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
``It's a tough situation for (Shaw). It's a tough situation with
(one) strike on (Drew), and he doesn't want to walk him. The rains
come and it takes a little out of him. Then, the second one comes,
and you could almost see it coming.''
</P>
<P>
   Shaw's last appearance came Wednesday in Houston when he failed
to record an out in a save situation, and Johnson said he would
have to monitor when to use Shaw. With a quartet of relievers
already used, Shaw was the choice after catcher Paul LoDuca's solo
homer in the top of the 11th gave the Dodgers a 6-5 lead.
</P>
<P>
   With lightning flashing around the stadium and thunder rolling
through it, Jim Edmonds led off the 12th with a double to left
field that bounced off Shawn Gilbert's glove as he jumped into the
wall. Mark McGwire was intentionally walked and pinch-hitter Eli
Marrero's botched sacrifice attempt allowed LoDuca to throw out
Edmonds at third.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the count 2-2 to Paquette, heavy rains hit again.
When the game resumed, Paquette hit the first pitch he saw from
Shaw (2-4) into the left-center-field bleachers for the win.
</P>
<P>
   LoDuca's homer capped a power surge of a night for the Dodgers
in which all of their runs came via the long ball. Gary Sheffield,
Adrian Beltre and LoDuca each hit solo homers and Green had a
three-run blast.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield's solo homer in the first was momentous. It extended
his hitting streak to a season-high 13, but it was also his 25th of
the season. That's the most homers for a Los Angeles Dodger before
the All-Star break. Mike Piazza's 24 in 1996 were the old mark.
Sheffield has five homers in his past four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of felt for (Shaw), but other than going with a
position player I don't think we had another option,'' said
reliever Matt Herges, who allowed a solo homer to Mark McGwire to
tie it in the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``To go out there twice is tough, but I have to commend Shaw for
acting like it was no big deal. He went out there and gave it his
best. I admire that in him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 0209EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
