<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 02:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3726 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-REWR     06-24 0748
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-TWINS-REWRITE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS WIN, BUT ETHERTON GETS ODD REWARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(OPTIONAL: Adds quotes, details) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ If all had gone smoothly for the Anaheim
Angels this season, they never would have needed to call up Seth
Etherton from the minor leagues. But it didn't, and they did.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries to the starting staff forced the Angels to put Etherton
in the starting rotation and he responded by going 3-1 in six
starts, including victories in his past three starts, capped by
Friday's 8-3 win over the Minnesota Twins before 30,254 at Edison
Field.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton's reward?
</P>
<P>
   A one-way ticket back to Edmonton.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hill, the Angels' opening-day starter, is ready to return to
the rotation and will start Wednesday in Etherton's spot. Etherton
was optioned to the Triple-A club after Friday's game because the
Angels needed to clear a spot on the roster for Kent Bottenfield,
tonight's starter.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton saved his best for last, throwing a season-high 6
innings and striking out a season-high six. He had only one bad
inning - the second - when he gave up five hits, including a
two-run homer by David Ortiz. A third run scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   But Etherton gave up only one other hit before being replaced by
reliever Mike Holtz with two out in the seventh inning. Only an
error by second baseman Adam Kennedy prevented Etherton from
finishing the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense gave thanks to Etherton with four home runs,
including two by Troy Glaus (Nos. 21 and 22). Tim Salmon (No. 17)
and Bengie Molina (No. 6) also homered in an 11-hit attack. Darin
Erstad had three hits, his major-league-leading 36th multi-hit
game.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Etherton was diplomatic about the club's
decision to send him out.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very positive,'' he said. ``A change needed to be made.
The veteran guys are coming back. They've been successful here too.
I don't think it's any shot at me. They need to be here.''
</P>
<P>
   In his six starts, Etherton is 3-1 with a 4.98 ERA. He pitched
at least five innings in every start and didn't allow more than
four runs in any of them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Seth came up here and certainly made the most of his
opportunity to show he can pitch in the big leagues,'' Angels
manager Mike Scioscia said. ``But you can only pick five starters.
We have high expectations of Ken Hill with the experience he
brings. But Seth definitely made a footprint here and you'll see
him back. What he did up here certainly was above any expectations
for a guy who has very limited minor-league experience.''
</P>
<P>
   After Etherton put the Angels in a 3-0 hole in the top of the
second inning, the Angels got the three runs back in the bottom of
the second when Kennedy tripled in two and Benji Gil drove in
Kennedy with a sacrifice fly. Salmon and Glaus each hit a solo
homer in the third, giving the Angels a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   In the fourth, the Angels made it 6-3 after back-to-back singles
by Erstad and Orlando Palmeiro, and an RBI groundout by Mo Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Etherton took it from there. After the second inning, the only
hit he allowed was a two-out double by Matt Lawton in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I can compete at this level,'' Etherton said. ``Each
timeout I was feeling like I was getting better. I just want to
build on that and keep going. Facing big-league hitters just builds
on your confidence because I haven't been hit hard in any of my
starts. I made adjustments when I needed to.'' The Angels' trio of
pitchers (Etherton, Brian Cooper and Jarrod Washburn) who started
the season in the minors but found themselves in the starting
rotation, are 6-0 in their past nine starts combined.
</P>
<P>
   ``All three of us have done an outstanding job,'' Etherton said.
``I'm sure it's very encouraging for the team and players and the
organization itself.''
</P>
<P>
   The win also marked a breakthrough of sorts for the Angels.
After losing the previous five times when they had a chance to go
four games over .500, they won on their sixth try Friday, improving
to 38-34. It's the first time they've been as many as four games
over .500 since the final day of the 1998 season when they were
85-77.
</P>
<P>
   It also was the Angels' fifth win in six games. And with three
more to go against the struggling Twins, the Angels have an
opportunity to make a move in the division race.
</P>
<P>
   Twins starter Jason Ryan (0-1) got the loss Friday in his
major-league debut.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
