<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3739 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ROGUE-STATES-REVIEW-N     06-24 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGUE-STATES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KINDER, GENTLER ROGUES' GALLERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; EDITORS: The following is a fictionalized account &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; DIPLOMATIC NEWS FROM NOWHERE &LR;
</P>
<P>
   PYONGYANG, North Korea _ In a dramatic shift of rhetoric, if not
policy, President Kim Jong Il announced today that North Korea
would no longer refer to the United States as ``the imperialist
aggressor.''
</P>
<P>
   After years of Cold War tensions and suspicion, he declared that
the United States would henceforth be known as a ``superpower of
concern.''
</P>
<P>
   Kim disclosed the change in North Korea's diplomatic lexicon in
an interview with the National Public Radio host Diane Rehm, who
asked if last month's remarkable summit between Kim and President
Kim Dae-jung of South Korea portended a warming of relations with
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Kim's aides, speaking on the condition of anonymity, said North
Korea was still ``concerned'' by American policies, namely the
construction of a $60 billion missile defense aimed at the North.
But they expressed hope that it would encourage the tentative
diplomatic contacts the Clinton administration has pursued in
recent years.
</P>
<P>
   North Korea's gesture came a week after Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright announced a similar shift in American diplomatic
language. On the same radio program, Albright disclosed that the
State Department had officially purged the phrase ``rogue states''
and would now call America's international gallery of rogues _
North Korea, Iran, Iraq, Libya and sometimes Cuba, Syria and the
Sudan _ by the admittedly clunky phrase ``states of concern.''
</P>
<P>
   It remains to be seen whether Albright's gesture will open a new
era of diplomacy, but already there have been signs of global
warming. In the days after her announcement, President Fidel Castro
of Cuba declared that he would stop regularly calling Americans
``Yanqui imperialistas.'' Instead, he said he would call the United
States ``the superpower whose Cold War mentality allows me to
justify a repressive regime.''
</P>
<P>
   Iran's moderate president, Mohammad Khatami, said the United
States was no longer officially ``the Great Satan,'' and the
official Iraqi news agency announced that it would stop calling
American and British warplanes that patrol the nation's skies
``enemy crows'' and instead refer to them as ``birds who have
deviated from their migratory paths.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, including some allies, seemed less inclined to tinker
with the language of diplomacy. France insisted it would continue
calling the United States a ``hyperpower.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Rogue states'' is not the first diplomatic moniker to fall out
of use, of course. The end of the Cold War spelled doom for a raft
of nasty-sounding labels like Iron Curtain, Evil Empire, Free World
and third world, nonaligned, pariah states and Red China.
</P>
<P>
   But Albright's move appeared to be the first deliberate effort
to change the diplomatic lexicon in pursuit of foreign policy
goals.
</P>
<P>
   James P. Rubin, the former spokesman for Albright, said the
categorization of problem countries as rogue states had initially
served as an effective way to make sense of the increasingly
complex geopolitics after the fall of the Soviet Union. Rogue
states were those that, in the American view, sponsored terrorism
or pursued weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
   But with some of those formerly rogue states taking steps to act
in good faith, it was important not to allow colorful language to
stand in the way of diplomatic progress.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the United States speaks, the world listens,'' Rubin
said. ``So it matters what language the United States uses.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1017EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0038 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0907 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-ROGUE-STATES-REVIEW-N     06-24 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROGUE-STATES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A KINDER, GENTLER ROGUES' GALLERY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By STEVEN LEE MYERS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
