<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3746 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-IRAN-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-24 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRAN-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN IRAN'S MORALITY PLAY, THE MORAL MAY BE UNITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By ELAINE SCIOLINO    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It's been years since the Clinton administration
called Iran an ``international outlaw,'' and now it has decided to
stop calling it a ``rogue state.'' People inside and outside the
administration were saying last week that dropping such labels
could open the way for Americans to think more realistically about
such countries. But these labels aren't the only problem with the
way the administration has been thinking about Iran.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the matter of K1 and K2.
</P>
<P>
   Those are the labels applied in some quarters of the American
government to the two leading figures in Iran, who are often
portrayed as the bad guy and the good guy in a winner-take-all
morality play.
</P>
<P>
   K1 is Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, the dour spiritual leader and most
powerful person in the country. He ritualistically rails against
Israel, rapprochement with the United States and the cultural
invasion of the West. He has the support of Iran's theocratic
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   K2 is Mohammad Khatami, a smiling, charming president who won
election in a landslide three years ago, supported by the younger
generation and women, and has called for a ``dialogue among
civilizations,'' even with the United States. He continues to enjoy
remarkable popular support despite his difficulty in implementing
promises to create a civil society governed by the rule of law.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, there are stark differences between the two men _ so
stark that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright told a
congressional committee last February, ``In some ways it looks as
though there are kind of two parallel governments that are going
on.''
</P>
<P>
   But that may miss the most intriguing point about Iranian
politics: It is anything but a zero-sum game.
</P>
<P>
   There is, instead, a remarkable degree of overlapping authority,
producing a system where people who deeply disagree and compete
fiercely for power also cooperate frequently to make the whole
system work.
</P>
<P>
   And what has emerged between K1 and K2 is an arrangement of
sorts; if this were France instead of an Islamic republic, it could
be called cohabitation.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their different roles under the constitution, different
styles and different constituencies, these two men are both
clerics, and only a few years apart. Both are men of ideas who
claim descent from Mohammed. And both are sworn to preserve the
Islamic republic.
</P>
<P>
   Most surprising to anyone with a one-dimensional view of Iran,
there is a lot of evidence that the two leaders know they need each
other if Iran's fluid political system is to function. Khamenei has
power on paper; Khatami has the support of the people. They don't
openly attack each other. And they seem to work well together, even
having hugged each other in public.
</P>
<P>
   Their peculiarly symbiotic relationship has been on display
repeatedly. After Khatami announced in 1998 that he wanted to break
down ``the wall of mistrust'' with the United States through
cultural exchanges, Khamenei disagreed. But while he branded the
United States ``the enemy of the Iranian nation,'' he referred to
Khatami as the ``respected president'' and dismissed their
differences as ``a tone of speech and difference of taste.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, after nationwide student demonstrations last summer
deteriorated into the worst unrest since Iran's 1979 revolution,
both men made it clear that their own differences were not part of
that struggle. Khamenei announced, ``I support the respected
president and the job he is doing 100 percent. And Khatami never
challenged the extraordinary powers of the spiritual leader,
however incompatible they may be with his vision of a more
democratic Iran.
</P>
<P>
   The president's loyalty was returned in kind four months ago,
after reformers swept the elections for Iran's Parliament and
conservatives who had been defeated tried to get the results in
Tehran annulled. Khamenei declared the election results valid and
stopped a recount, paving the way for the reformist-dominated
Parliament to be seated last month.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, the cooperation is not surprising, considering how big
a stake both men have in preserving civil order and how passionate
many Iranians have become about their politics. Student leaders had
threatened to mobilize massive street demonstrations if the
election results were annulled. In the last such demonstrations, a
year ago, two dozen leaders of the Revolutionary Guards raised the
specter of a military coup.
</P>
<P>
   Order is not the only tie that binds K1 and K2. The Khamenei and
Khatami families have been close, a relationship that was forged
when Khamenei, as a teen-age theology student in Mashad, became a
devoted disciple of Khatami's father, a beloved ayatollah.
</P>
<P>
   Khamenei has also discovered that the charm offensive of Khatami
has paid off and is struggling to change his own image. He has
taken to holding small seminars with young people, women, actors
and athletes. He sometimes appears on television strolling in
flower-filled gardens, as soft music plays in the background, even
though he once issued a ruling banning music lessons as immoral.
</P>
<P>
   But showing off his soft side does not mean that Khamenei has
transformed himself into an Islamic democrat. His blunt speech in
April charging that some reformist newspapers had become ``bases of
the enemy'' resulted in the shutdown of 18 reformist publications.
The battle was joined when one of the first acts of the new
Parliament was a call for an urgent review of the country's tough
press law and the reopening of the banned publications.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration is eager to see how far it can push
rapprochement with Iran in this open-ended political game before
President Clinton leaves office, even though Iran has not formally
responded to its offer of an official dialogue.
</P>
<P>
   Most recently, administration officials said, they were hoping
that a third country would invite Iran to a three-day Community of
Democracies Conference that opens today in Warsaw. After all,
countries that the administration considers less democratic in some
ways than Iran _ Kuwait, Egypt, Qatar and Jordan, for example _ are
expected to attend.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
