<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3748 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIE     06-24 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAWYERS LIVE TO FIGHT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c. 2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the state of Texas executed Gary Graham last week for the
1981 murder of a man outside a Houston supermarket, death-penalty
opponents pointed a spotlight on Graham's court-appointed trial
lawyer, whom they criticized for failing to mount anything near an
adequate defense. He barely investigated the case, they maintained,
and failed to alert the jury to two witnesses who said Graham was
not the killer and to ballistics evidence that could have
exonerated his client.
</P>
<P>
   While poor legal representation rarely leads to the overturning
of criminal convictions, a recent Columbia University study found
that two out of three death-penalty sentences were reversed on
appeal, and of those about 37 percent were the result of
incompetent lawyering. The study _ which examined appeals in all
capital cases from 1973, when the Supreme Court reinstated the
death penalty, to 1995 _ said those reversals were due to
``egregiously incompetent defense lawyers who didn't even look for
and demonstrably missed important evidence that the defendant was
innocent or did not deserve to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Graham's execution, Attorney General Janet Reno said,
``There are too many people in this country who do not have
competent counsel to represent them in capital cases.'' She added,
``Each state should develop a system that can ensure adequate
representation.''
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to criminal trial lawyers who don't mount
adequate defenses?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to experts, is rarely anything other than
being given more capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Bar Association Center for
Professional Responsibility, the guidelines are clear: Lawyers in
death-penalty cases must present a ``diligent'' and ``competent''
defense, with lawyers who have several years of experience handling
capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Fox, a Cornell University law professor and a former
chairman of the American Bar Association's Committee on Ethics and
Standards, said that such rules are rarely followed and that there
is a ``total disconnect between the standards that lawyers are
supposed to meet in capital cases and what they are actually
allowed to get away with.'' In those rare cases where disciplinary
boards find trial lawyers negligent in capital cases, sanctions
range from fines to disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Amendment not only guarantees criminal defendants the
right to counsel, but the right to effective counsel. Courts have
generally defined effective counsel as a lawyer whose ``material''
legal actions are reasonable and who does not make errors that
would have been likely to change the outcome of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox said many states, including Texas, do not have written
guidelines that outline the amount of experience court-appointed
capital-trial lawyers should have, or the efforts that they should
make.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often do not present a competent defense, they are often
not diligent, they often do not find witnesses or spend the time
and effort necessary to find evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, according to John Howley, a New York
appeals lawyer who has helped win reprieves in recent years for
three people sentenced to death in Alabama and Virginia, is pay.
</P>
<P>
   Few defense lawyers want to take capital cases, because they are
difficult to prosecute and the defendants are often indigent and
unable to pay their bills. This means judges must make appointments
from a small pool of lawyers, many of whom have poor records and
cannot find enough work on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, for example, court-appointed lawyers make $20 an
hour. In turn, a 1996 study by a group opposed to the death penalty
found that the court-appointed lawyers in Alabama spent an average
of three hours trying the penalty phase, in which judges and jurors
decide between life and death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's lawyer, Ronald Mock, spent less than a week
investigating his case and presented little evidence that supported
Graham's assertion that he was not guilty. Mock has contended that
he presented an adequate defense in the case of Graham and the
dozen or so other clients of his who have been sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, like New York, have attempted to deal with the
compensation issue by setting up capital defender agencies that
help shoulder the burden in such cases. The more pressing problem,
some legal experts said, is that incompetent lawyers are often
allowed _ and even encouraged, because they are less troublesome to
judges _ to try additional capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death penalty cases are some of the most difficult cases for a
lawyer to bring to trial, but there is no organized way to assure
adequate assistance of counsel in Texas and most states,'' Howley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox of Cornell said judges and lawyers do not really have to
follow the bar association's standards because the Supreme Court
ruled in 1984 that there was a high burden of proof in an appeal
that centers on inadequate legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the answer for clients who are misrepresented is
to file a civil malpractice suit against their counsel. But that's
little consolation for those whose lives are on the line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1041EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0051 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0924 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIE     06-24 0915
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEFENSE-LAWYERS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE LAWYERS LIVE TO FIGHT AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By JAYSON BLAIR    
 c. 2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the state of Texas executed Gary Graham last week for the
1981 murder of a man outside a Houston supermarket, death-penalty
opponents pointed a spotlight on Graham's court-appointed trial
lawyer, whom they criticized for failing to mount anything near an
adequate defense. He barely investigated the case, they maintained,
and failed to alert the jury to two witnesses who said Graham was
not the killer and to ballistics evidence that could have
exonerated his client.
</P>
<P>
   While poor legal representation rarely leads to the overturning
of criminal convictions, a recent Columbia University study found
that two out of three death-penalty sentences were reversed on
appeal, and of those about 37 percent were the result of
incompetent lawyering. The study _ which examined appeals in all
capital cases from 1973, when the Supreme Court reinstated the
death penalty, to 1995 _ said those reversals were due to
``egregiously incompetent defense lawyers who didn't even look for
and demonstrably missed important evidence that the defendant was
innocent or did not deserve to die.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Graham's execution, Attorney General Janet Reno said,
``There are too many people in this country who do not have
competent counsel to represent them in capital cases.'' She added,
``Each state should develop a system that can ensure adequate
representation.''
</P>
<P>
   But what happens to criminal trial lawyers who don't mount
adequate defenses?
</P>
<P>
   The answer, according to experts, is rarely anything other than
being given more capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   According to the American Bar Association Center for
Professional Responsibility, the guidelines are clear: Lawyers in
death-penalty cases must present a ``diligent'' and ``competent''
defense, with lawyers who have several years of experience handling
capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   But Larry Fox, a Cornell University law professor and a former
chairman of the American Bar Association's Committee on Ethics and
Standards, said that such rules are rarely followed and that there
is a ``total disconnect between the standards that lawyers are
supposed to meet in capital cases and what they are actually
allowed to get away with.'' In those rare cases where disciplinary
boards find trial lawyers negligent in capital cases, sanctions
range from fines to disbarment.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixth Amendment not only guarantees criminal defendants the
right to counsel, but the right to effective counsel. Courts have
generally defined effective counsel as a lawyer whose ``material''
legal actions are reasonable and who does not make errors that
would have been likely to change the outcome of a trial.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox said many states, including Texas, do not have written
guidelines that outline the amount of experience court-appointed
capital-trial lawyers should have, or the efforts that they should
make.
</P>
<P>
   ``They often do not present a competent defense, they are often
not diligent, they often do not find witnesses or spend the time
and effort necessary to find evidence,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, according to John Howley, a New York
appeals lawyer who has helped win reprieves in recent years for
three people sentenced to death in Alabama and Virginia, is pay.
</P>
<P>
   Few defense lawyers want to take capital cases, because they are
difficult to prosecute and the defendants are often indigent and
unable to pay their bills. This means judges must make appointments
from a small pool of lawyers, many of whom have poor records and
cannot find enough work on their own.
</P>
<P>
   In Alabama, for example, court-appointed lawyers make $20 an
hour. In turn, a 1996 study by a group opposed to the death penalty
found that the court-appointed lawyers in Alabama spent an average
of three hours trying the penalty phase, in which judges and jurors
decide between life and death sentences.
</P>
<P>
   Graham's lawyer, Ronald Mock, spent less than a week
investigating his case and presented little evidence that supported
Graham's assertion that he was not guilty. Mock has contended that
he presented an adequate defense in the case of Graham and the
dozen or so other clients of his who have been sentenced to die.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, like New York, have attempted to deal with the
compensation issue by setting up capital defender agencies that
help shoulder the burden in such cases. The more pressing problem,
some legal experts said, is that incompetent lawyers are often
allowed _ and even encouraged, because they are less troublesome to
judges _ to try additional capital cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Death penalty cases are some of the most difficult cases for a
lawyer to bring to trial, but there is no organized way to assure
adequate assistance of counsel in Texas and most states,'' Howley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fox of Cornell said judges and lawyers do not really have to
follow the bar association's standards because the Supreme Court
ruled in 1984 that there was a high burden of proof in an appeal
that centers on inadequate legal representation.
</P>
<P>
   In most cases, the answer for clients who are misrepresented is
to file a civil malpractice suit against their counsel. But that's
little consolation for those whose lives are on the line.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
