<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 10:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3749 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-ECON-NYT &LR;      06-24 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-ECON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SIX-YEAR CURSE THREATENS, BUT THIS TIME MEXICO IS BULLISH
</HEADLINE>
  By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Mexicans call it the six-year curse, that spell
that has come over the economy at the end of every recent
presidential term to make the currency plunge, interest rates soar
and people go broke.
</P>
<P>
   With elections approaching on July 2, Antonio Gonzalez Perez,
46, who has lived through all of Mexico's cyclical economic traumas
since he opened his curtain-making shop a quarter century ago, is
taking no chances. These days the sewing machine at his shop in a
workaday suburb of Mexico City is running late into the night so he
can salt away savings and be ready in case the hex strikes again.
</P>
<P>
   But despite the jitters of Mexicans like Gonzalez, economists
are surprisingly united that for once the economy is strong enough
to keep any disturbance caused by the handover of power from
becoming disaster.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, they say, is that President Ernesto Zedillo, an
economist, has spent the last three years reshaping the economy and
building armor, as he calls it, around Mexico's finances to shield
them from the kind of meltdown that almost sent the country into
default when he took office in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vulnerabilities are not there,'' said Jonathan Heath, a
Mexican economist who has written a book about the recurring crises
at the end of the president's single six-year term. ``There are
risks,'' Heath added, ``but they are within the context of the
normal risks of an economy.''
</P>
<P>
   In the past, the enormous concentration of power in the hands of
the almost kingly chief executive has made the hand-over
exceptionally perilous for Mexico. Since the mid-1970s, a
procession of presidents used that power to further their political
aims by overspending and running up the debt _ often behind the
veneer of what looked like a sound economy.
</P>
<P>
   Then, when it came time for the hand-off to a successor, those
fiscal weaknesses came abruptly to light, shattering investors'
confidence and sending the peso into a dive.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo, however, has had powerful incentives for wanting to
leave his successor a healthier country than the one he received
from President Carlos Salinas de Gortari.
</P>
<P>
   After a devaluation just weeks after his inauguration, Zedillo's
first year in office was a nightmare of stricken businesses, lost
jobs and paralyzed government programs. He has said that he knows
only too well that the economic gains Mexicans make while he is
president can be wiped out in a flash after he leaves.
</P>
<P>
   Salinas' fate also served as a cautionary example. Mexicans were
so outraged by the mess he left, he had to leave the country in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo's determination to achieve a smooth finish will be just
as great if an opposition candidate wins the presidency, as could
happen for the first time in a Mexican election. A president who is
not from Zedillo's Institutional Revolutionary Party, which has
controlled Mexico for seven decades, would be even more inclined to
blame his predecessor for any economic shocks in the transition.
</P>
<P>
   ``A total overhaul'' is how Abel Beltran del Rio, president of
the consulting firm Ciemex-Wefa, describes Zedillo's changes. ``The
edifice was rebuilt so that it can get through the earthquakes
without the crumbling as it did in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1994, in the final months under Salinas, Mexico had
short-term debts of $40 billion and foreign reserves of $12
billion. Today Mexico has $32 billion in reserves and its
short-term debt is insignificant. Salinas kept the reserves under
wraps most of the time. Zedillo opened things up, so that the vital
economic indicators are on view every day. Under Salinas the peso
traded within fixed limits. Now the peso floats with the market, so
the government faces a less severe challenge in spending its
reserves to defend the currency.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo is on track to meet his goal of a budget deficit this
year of 1 percent of the gross domestic product. Reforms he
promoted have given the central bank authorities leverage to say no
to government officials who want to fiddle with the money supply.
As a result, Mexico's stubborn inflation has been slowly sliding
down toward the official target of under 10 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   Buoyed by the North American Free Trade Agreement, foreigners
will probably make more than $10 billion in long-lasting
investments in factories and businesses this year. The economy
steamed forward by 7.9 percent in the first quarter, making some
analysts fret that it was actually expanding too fast.
</P>
<P>
   There are a few gray spots on the picture. The $100 billion bank
bailout remains a hot political issue and could take unexpected
turns. No one is quite sure how Mexico, now fastened at the hip to
the U.S. economy, will fare in a slowdown in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Zedillo has not been above stepping up federal spending to help
the campaign of Francisco Labastida Ochoa, his party's presidential
candidate. Public outlays jumped by 15.4 percent in the first
quarter, as the federal government laid hand on money budgeted for
the last half of the year and dipped into the windfall from soaring
oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``With oil prices running so high, Mexico should be running a
surplus, and it's not,'' said Walter Molano, head of research at
BCP Securities. ``They're spending money based on a volatile
revenue source when they should be saving for the time when prices
drop.''
</P>
<P>
   But the real surprise came from the elections. Polls show that
Labastida is tied with Vicente Fox Quesada, a right-of-center
opposition candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party has begun a campaign to sway voters, and the
opposition is warning that the election may not be clean. Protests
may well follow the vote.
</P>
<P>
   The sparring has already created some turbulence in the economy.
On June 8, when Labastida accused Fox of planning to create
``chaos'' if the opposition candidate lost, the peso dipped from
9.5 to the dollar to over 10. It has since recovered slightly but
continues to waver.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez, the curtain-maker, sees other signs of uneasiness. His
suppliers are telling him that the imported toile he uses is out of
stock. ``It's speculation,'' he said. ``They're waiting to sell
until after the election because they know the price is going up.''
Nonetheless, seasoned Mexico watchers remain sanguine.
</P>
<P>
   Luis Rubio, the head of Cidac, a political economics research
institution, said, ``This time Mexico could have a political crisis
without an economic one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1046EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
