<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 11:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3755 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v AM-NYT-BUDGET &LR;      06-24 1702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, June 25:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA (Phnom Penh, Cambodia) _ After three decades of
conflict, a new era of peace and political stability is taking root
here in one of the world's most tormented nations. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-ECON (Seoul, South Korea) _ With the easing of economic
sanctions against North Korea by the Clinton administration last
week, U.S. corporations based here are beginning to assess business
opportunities in a country that has been out of bounds for five
decades. By Jane Perlez.
</P>
<P>
   KENYA-CRISES (Nairobi, Kenya) _ Nearly three quarters of Kenyans
will be affected in one way or another by the severe drought that
is choking the region, the government estimates. The Tana River,
where the nation's five hydroelectric dams are located, is low. So
the government has imposed strict power rationing: Factories get
power every other day. Water rationing starts soon. But even before
the dry weather, the economy was strangling from years of
corruption and poor management. The phones and roads are barely
usable. Students are rioting. There is turmoil among the coffee and
tea growers. Tourists, afraid of runaway crime, are staying away.
Through it all, President Daniel arap Moi and his government have
declined to accept any blame, though Kenya is so corrupt that the
World Bank and International Monetary Fund cut off aid three years
ago. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   KOREAN-WAR-ANNIVERSARY (Seoul, South Korea) _ The South Korean
government's decision to tone down the war anniversary celebrations
has brought angry denouncements from veterans, and it has also
touched off a heated national debate over the significance of the
Korean War and just how far the South should go to appease the
North. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Bogota, Colombia) _ Minister of Defense Luis
Fernando Ramirez hails it as ``a new beginning.'' But Washington's
decision to escalate its involvement in the Colombian government's
struggle against drugs and the armed groups that increasingly
control their production also means the United States will now be
facing new risks here as it begins working closely with some new
faces. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ECON (Mexico City) _ Mexicans call it the six-year curse,
that spell that has come over the economy at the end of every
recent presidential term to make the currency plunge, interest
rates soar and people go broke. But despite the jitters, economists
are surprisingly united that for once the economy is strong enough
to keep any disturbance caused by the handover of power from
becoming disaster. The reason, they say, is that President Ernesto
Zedillo, an economist himself, has spent the last three years
reshaping the economy and building armor, as he calls it, around
Mexico's finances to shield them from the kind of meltdown that
almost sent the country into default when he took office in 1994.
By Julia Preston.
</P>
<P>
   MONACO-MONEY-LAUNDERING (Paris) _ In a scathing 400-page report,
the French parliament said that the tiny principality of Monaco _ a
famous refuge for wealthy tax dodgers _ was also an ideal place to
launder money. It accused Monaco of having deliberately put in
place lax banking laws _ including a guarantee of anonymity _ to
attract wealthy depositors no matter who they were. By Suzanne
Daley.
</P>
<P>
   PEOPLE-TRAFFICKING (United Nations) _ Trafficking in people is
now the fastest-growing business of organized crime, and it is
being run by new, barely understood networks that have sidelined
traditional criminal syndicates, the top anti-crime official at the
United Nations said last week. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-ELECTION (Harare, Zimbabwe) _ The ruling party faces
its toughest challenge in 20 years since independence in
parliamentary elections after a campaign in which President Robert
Mugabe has been accused of fomenting political violence. By Henri
E. Cauvin.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-PRICES (Undated) _ Internet retailers are in big
trouble. Stock prices have collapsed, venture capital has dried up
and the public markets have closed their doors to those who cannot
demonstrate how they will be profitable soon. To please testy
investors, dot.coms are trying numerous tactics _ including
employee layoffs, rethinking their entire business and raising
advertising and association fees. But because many Internet product
prices were once set beneath cost to lure new customers, the
easiest and most obvious step has been to bring those prices back
to the real world. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   RACE-KIDS (Maplewood, N.J.) _ It happens everywhere, in the
confusions of adolescence and the yearning for identity, when the
most important thing in life is choosing a group and fitting in:
Black children and white children move into separate worlds.
Friendships ebb and end. But what is striking is that it happens
even here. In a nation of segregated schools, the South
Orange-Maplewood district is extraordinarily mixed. This is the
kind of place where people _ black and white _ talk a lot about the
virtues of diversity, where hundreds will turn out to discuss the
book ``Why Are All the Black Kids Sitting Together in the
Cafeteria?'' But even here, as if pulled by internal magnets, black
and white children begin to separate at sixth grade. These are
children who walked to school together, learned to read together,
slept over at each other's houses. But despite all the personal
history, all the community good will, race divides them as they
grow up. By Tamar Lewin.
</P>
<P>
   LA-GOVERNOR (Baton Rouge, La.) _ For a few high-flying months in
his first term, Mike Foster might have been the most popular
governor in America, riding a brief economic boom and his
Harley-Davidson Road King to unheard-of approval ratings in the
range of 70 percent to 80 percent. But the good years never seem to
last long in Louisiana. And when this year's state budget could not
be balanced without a sales tax increase on food, Mike Foster fell
back to earth, hard. And it is unclear whether the economy will
allow him to ascend again in the last three years of his second
term. By David Firestone.
</P>
<P>
   SANFRAN-DYING-ALONE (San Francisco) _ In San Francisco, more
people are dying alone, with no one to arrange their funerals,
settle their estates or mourn their passing. So far this year, 275
people in the city have died this way, said city officials,
compared with about 300 a year for the last decade. By Evelyn
Nieves.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-ASBESTOS (Cambridge, Mass.) _ The Environmental Protection
Agency is investigating whether the contamination of a children's
athletic field in a bustling neighborhood on the outskirts of this
city poses an immediate health risk. By Adrianne Appel.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   HISPANIC-VOTERS (Denver) _ For many Hispanic Americans,
especially those eager to vote in this year's presidential
election, Vice President Al Gore and his probable Republican
opponent, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, have turned the campaign
into a virtual love-fest. Describing themselves as the ``soccer
moms'' of the 2000 elections, Hispanic voters say they have never
been courted so aggressively by presidential candidates, giving
Hispanics electoral leverage they never had before. The amorous
turn, a more profound difference in Republican strategy than in
Democratic, evolves directly from demographic shifts: Hispanics are
now the fastest-growing bloc of ethnic voters. By Michael Janofsky.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ Farmers Get Help, and Back the
Helper; Bush Not so Welcome in Battleground State; Gas-Tax
Suspension Arouses Skepticism; Fearless McCain Attacks Finance Law.
By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DRUGS-LOBBIES (Washington) _ The struggle over prescription drug
benefits for the elderly, now center stage in the House, is not
simply between Democrats and Republicans, liberals and
conservatives. It has also driven a wedge between two of the
biggest, most influential lobbies in Washington: the Health
Insurance Association of America and the Pharmaceutical Research
and Manufacturers of America. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-DRUGS (Washington) _ President Clinton announced a
major change in his proposal for Medicare drug benefits Saturday,
making it much more generous to millions of elderly people and much
more costly to the federal government. The new proposal came four
days before the House of Representatives is scheduled to vote on a
Republican proposal to offer drug benefits, through private
insurance companies, to all 39 million people on Medicare. By
Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A corn-fed gasoline shortage. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MOVING LATER:  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS-BUDGET _ A rundown of sports stories will move by 1 p.m.
ET.
</P>
<P>
   AM-FRONTPAGE-NYT _ A description of the front page layout of the
first edition of The New York Times will move at 12 noon.
</P>
