</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELEBS-INTERVIEW-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE PERFECT CELEBRITY INTERVIEW 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By JOHN B. KENNEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month, a Swiss journalist was fired by a major
German newspaper when it was revealed that he fabricated intimate
interviews with Hollywood celebrities like Sharon Stone and Brad
Pitt. The journalist defended his work as ``conceptual art.''
</P>
<P>
   I first see (celebrity's name) getting out of a (foreign
convertible) at the (Mondrian/Four Seasons/Shutters). (He/she) is
(taller/shorter) than I had imagined, though, in fact, far more
(handsome/beautiful). (He/She) is dressed casually in (linen pants
and T-shirt/jeans and tube-top/sarong and baseball cap backward).
The doorman is trying too hard not to notice, but it is especially
difficult, as (the top four buttons of her blouse are undone/his
fly is down).
</P>
<P>
   I had spoken by phone with (his/her) agent and had suggested
that New York would be a perfect meeting place for our interview,
as (he/she) would be in town for a (premiere/awards dinner/court
appearance). Unfortunately, we were disconnected before we were
able to make firm plans. I flew to the Coast.
</P>
<P>
   You must be (not your name but close), (he/she) says with a
(grin/scowl) as we walk through the lobby to the patio. It's (your
name), actually, I say, but (he/she) doesn't seem to hear as
(he/she) is (making a call on a cellphone/ordering a drink).
</P>
<P>
   We are seated in a corner of the patio and only now does the
star of the biggest box-office weekend in almost (number of weeks)
remove (his/her) sunglasses, only to reveal (an eye patch/a black
eye/another pair of sunglasses).
</P>
<P>
   I'm hesitant to mention (the surgery/the infamous fight/how
ridiculous he/she looks) but feel compelled to do so. (What's the
prognosis?/Are the nuns pressing charges?/Do you realize how silly
you look?).
</P>
<P>
   (He/she) pauses and looks away, out over the Hollywood Hills. It
is a look eerily reminiscent of (his/her) work in (insert film or
TV show).
</P>
<P>
   (He/she) begins speaking while still gazing at the hills. ``Just
before (he/she) died, my (dad/mom/grandmother) told me a story
about what's really important in life: (friends/love/jam).''
(He/She) pauses. ``(He/She) died in my (arms/apartment/wood
chipper).''
</P>
<P>
   (He/She) turns suddenly to the waiter, who happens to be walking
by and says (I said no croutons! Are you deaf as well as
stupid?/The salmon is lovely, thank you).
</P>
<P>
   I'd heard of the (temper/unfailing politeness), of the (flashes
of anger/moments of near beatific kindness). (Abruptly/With
monk-like grace), (he/she) stands and (throws a chair/quietly hands
the maitre d' a $1,000 bill).
</P>
<P>
   (He/She) suggests a drive.
</P>
<P>
   We meander through the city and find ourselves on the Pacific
Coast highway heading north, the azure ocean sparkling on our left.
(He/She) is quiet for a time, then hits the stereo power button.
Dean Martin's ``You're Nobody Till Somebody Loves You'' comes
crooning out. ``Is that you?'' I ask, knowing that I'm (skating on
thin ice/on safe ground) as a result of the recent
(breakup/marriage to) a certain (blonde/brunette) (hunk/beauty) and
star of the fantastically successful (sitcom/movie).
</P>
<P>
   (He/She) pauses and takes a deep drag off a cigarette. I'd heard
a rumor that (he/she)) just (started/quit). ``No,'' (he/she) says.
``It's Dean Martin.'' I, of course, sense the sarcasm immediately.
</P>
<P>
   I ask what it's like to be (23/27/31/34/42) and (suddenly/back
on top again and) commanding ($12 million/$17 million/$20 million)
a film, building a house in (Montana/Peru), (engaged/newly single),
and have a new film coming out. ``Great,'' comes the reply. Again,
the cagey depths.
</P>
<P>
   ``May I get serious for a moment?'' I ask.
</P>
<P>
   ``What?'' (he/she) replies. The wind and the stereo are making
it difficult to speak.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rumors,'' I shout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tumors?''(he/she) screams back.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no. Ru-mors.'' (He/She) turns the volume down. ``I've
talked with people _ directors you've worked with, grips, gaffers,
craft services people _ and they all say the same thing: that
you're (a delight to work with/the Saddam Hussein of acting).''
</P>
<P>
   We turn (right/left) off the highway, (down/up) a long, winding
dirt road toward the (ocean/mountains). (He/She) is quiet for a
time, thinking. Then, ``Did you say something?'' I get it.
</P>
<P>
   We arrive at (his/a producer friend's/a director friend's)
(ranch/beach house), and sit for a moment in the car. The sun is
fading in the distance. The only sound is the (surf/cicadas).
</P>
<P>
   ``My guru once told my personal trainer something very
interesting. He said, `There is truth in all things. Unless there
isn't.'''
</P>
<P>
   True enough.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
