<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0060 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3757 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-REVI     06-24 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING BETTER (AND RISKIER) ELECTRONICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By AMY HARMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the recent string of electronic events: A virus that
becomes known as the love bug causes nearly $1 billion worth of
damages as it ravages computer systems across the world. The Office
of National Drug Control Policy admits that it may have violated
federal privacy guidelines by implanting software on the computers
of its Web site visitors that tracks their travels across the
Internet. Hackers seize control of Nike's corporate Web site to
announce that ``global justice is coming _ prepare now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the threats to privacy and security on the Internet
thrust their way into the public consciousness, Congress
overwhelmingly passes a bill that aims to turbo-charge electronic
commerce by giving electronic signatures the legal weight of paper
signatures _ without many provisions for security. Americans
continue to transfer their personal, political, financial and even
medical lives online, all the while trading horror stories about
identity theft and credit card scams.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a disconnect here?
</P>
<P>
   If so, it may be because people simply can't stop themselves
from using the Internet, spooked though they may be. They do not
fight the nearly universal tendency to equate technology with
progress. And at a time when the Internet is widely believed to be
driving the buoyant economy, the financial incentives to continue
on the current trajectory are huge.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it is simpler than that: the risk seems worth it. So
seductive is the technology that even its most strident critics
cannot imagine voluntarily going without e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, those who are most outspoken about the privacy
and security risks are no longer modern-day Luddites but computer
scientists _ some of them the architects of the global computer
network, which they have come to believe is insufficient to meet
the demands being placed on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If situation A is not working right, does it make sense to do
A times 10 using the same technology?'' asked Lauren Weinstein, a
veteran Internet engineer and co-founder of a group called People
for Internet Responsibility, which has issued a technical critique
of the electronic signature bill. ``That doesn't make any sense to
me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As reports of electronic breaches and privacy lapses roll in
with increasing frequency, it has become almost an article of faith
among computer security experts that the radical, global commitment
to research and installing safeguards that could make the Internet
more secure will not happen until a major catastrophe strikes. But
there is little doubt among them that such an effort will be made
some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net's going to go fumbling along until there's a massive
intrusion,'' said Dave Farber, an Internet pioneer and chief
technologist for the Federal Communications Commission. ``Then
everything will hit the fan. Congress is going to go ballistic, and
we're going to panic our way into doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, without much hope, ``It would be much nicer to start
talking about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The technological roots of the Internet's vulnerability are well
known. Conceived by the Defense Department as a decentralized
communications system that would continue to function even if
chunks of it were destroyed, the Internet is by its nature open and
interconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet was built in an age when we all knew each other,
we all trusted each other, we were talking about where to have
dinner and what silver futures to buy,'' said Farber, speaking of
the scientists who built it. ``Now we've moved it into an
environment where the country counts on it. And it's very hard to
retrofit security.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with a network that is expanding so rapidly. Even as
software designers and security experts scramble to fix problems
that they know about, dozens of new software applications are
released and hundreds of thousands of new users log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity for things to go wrong is always increasing,''
said Robert Morris, an assistant professor of computer science at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who is perhaps better
known as the creator of the first Internet worm, which crippled the
network in 1988. ``More people are also going after things. But
it's not clear who's going to win, the people who write software
with bugs or the people trying to fix the bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many technologists believe that the Internet could be made
considerably more secure. Cars, they note, used to be a lot less
safe than they are now. That was before a combination of consumer
pressure, governmental regulation and manufacturers' designs came
up with seat belts and air bags and anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the network extensively,'' said Peter Neumann, a
computer security expert with SRI International. ``I also know it
can be brought down by anybody, anywhere in the world, in about 30
minutes. One of the things we need to do is educate the populace,
so that they can take precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   Risk assessment has been a big topic lately on the online
discussion groups at eBay, the Internet auction site that has
suffered a spate of high-profile fraud attempts. Sandi Brady, 49,
of Franklin, N.J., echoed a widely held view: ``I struggle a little
bit with using my credit card on the Internet,'' she said. ``But
for every bad transaction, there's so many more good transactions.
I use common sense, I use caution, and that's no different than the
caution you take in life, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet proponents argue that the vulnerabilities of the
Internet are not any greater than those of the physical world _
just different. For instance, Paul Leuhr, who supervises the
Federal Trade Commission's Internet fraud program, calls consumers'
fears that someone will seize their credit card numbers as they
travel across the network a ``gross misperception.'' Although
credit card fraud on the Internet is thought to be slightly higher
than in real-world transactions, and the speed and reach of the
network can make its consequences far more serious, Leuhr said,
``almost always, fraud springs from the natural flaws in human
behavior,'' such as writing down passwords or leaving credit card
receipts in the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   But a relatively new realm of human behavior now encompasses
making policy and personal decisions about how to handle the
technology that is becoming so closely woven into everyday life.
And critics say greater attention to the vulnerabilities of the
computer network is an important part of that.
</P>
<P>
   A law that promises to eliminate costly paperwork and to speed
transactions like purchasing home mortgages or paying taxes sounds
great, for instance. But with no standards for ensuring the
security of such documents, it could merely create a lot of
confusion and litigation. Under the current law, it seems that a
simple e-mail signature could qualify as binding. What happens when
one party says a contract is changed after it is signed? What
happens when a family paying bills online drops its Internet
account?
</P>
<P>
   But Margot Saunders, an attorney at the National Consumer Law
Center, said the real problem for critics of the new law is that
``these are all what-ifs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not intuitive because we're not seeing these problems out
there and reporting back,'' she added. ``We're just guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that in turn may help explain why it is so hard to confront
the virtual impossibility of privacy and security on the Internet,
or find the will to adjust behavior accordingly. It dovetails with
the way people have for decades grappled with technological risk.
Because it is harder to comprehend _ particularly with information
technology, which is itself is so intangible _ it seems easier to
dismiss the potential to do damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same as getting your face smashed through the
windshield,'' said David Mindell, a historian of technology at MIT.
``It's a lot less clear what your risks are when you're on the
Internet or moving your life management over to Internet. And it's
very hard for people to change their behavior based on poorly
defined risks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1121EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0061 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 11:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0942 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-REVI     06-24 1404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-PRIVACY-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIVING BETTER (AND RISKIER) ELECTRONICALLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 By AMY HARMON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Consider the recent string of electronic events: A virus that
becomes known as the love bug causes nearly $1 billion worth of
damages as it ravages computer systems across the world. The Office
of National Drug Control Policy admits that it may have violated
federal privacy guidelines by implanting software on the computers
of its Web site visitors that tracks their travels across the
Internet. Hackers seize control of Nike's corporate Web site to
announce that ``global justice is coming _ prepare now.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet even as the threats to privacy and security on the Internet
thrust their way into the public consciousness, Congress
overwhelmingly passes a bill that aims to turbo-charge electronic
commerce by giving electronic signatures the legal weight of paper
signatures _ without many provisions for security. Americans
continue to transfer their personal, political, financial and even
medical lives online, all the while trading horror stories about
identity theft and credit card scams.
</P>
<P>
   Is there a disconnect here?
</P>
<P>
   If so, it may be because people simply can't stop themselves
from using the Internet, spooked though they may be. They do not
fight the nearly universal tendency to equate technology with
progress. And at a time when the Internet is widely believed to be
driving the buoyant economy, the financial incentives to continue
on the current trajectory are huge.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps it is simpler than that: the risk seems worth it. So
seductive is the technology that even its most strident critics
cannot imagine voluntarily going without e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, those who are most outspoken about the privacy
and security risks are no longer modern-day Luddites but computer
scientists _ some of them the architects of the global computer
network, which they have come to believe is insufficient to meet
the demands being placed on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``If situation A is not working right, does it make sense to do
A times 10 using the same technology?'' asked Lauren Weinstein, a
veteran Internet engineer and co-founder of a group called People
for Internet Responsibility, which has issued a technical critique
of the electronic signature bill. ``That doesn't make any sense to
me at all.''
</P>
<P>
   As reports of electronic breaches and privacy lapses roll in
with increasing frequency, it has become almost an article of faith
among computer security experts that the radical, global commitment
to research and installing safeguards that could make the Internet
more secure will not happen until a major catastrophe strikes. But
there is little doubt among them that such an effort will be made
some day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Net's going to go fumbling along until there's a massive
intrusion,'' said Dave Farber, an Internet pioneer and chief
technologist for the Federal Communications Commission. ``Then
everything will hit the fan. Congress is going to go ballistic, and
we're going to panic our way into doing something.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, without much hope, ``It would be much nicer to start
talking about it now.''
</P>
<P>
   The technological roots of the Internet's vulnerability are well
known. Conceived by the Defense Department as a decentralized
communications system that would continue to function even if
chunks of it were destroyed, the Internet is by its nature open and
interconnected.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet was built in an age when we all knew each other,
we all trusted each other, we were talking about where to have
dinner and what silver futures to buy,'' said Farber, speaking of
the scientists who built it. ``Now we've moved it into an
environment where the country counts on it. And it's very hard to
retrofit security.''
</P>
<P>
   Especially with a network that is expanding so rapidly. Even as
software designers and security experts scramble to fix problems
that they know about, dozens of new software applications are
released and hundreds of thousands of new users log on.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity for things to go wrong is always increasing,''
said Robert Morris, an assistant professor of computer science at
the Massachusetts Institute of Technology who is perhaps better
known as the creator of the first Internet worm, which crippled the
network in 1988. ``More people are also going after things. But
it's not clear who's going to win, the people who write software
with bugs or the people trying to fix the bugs.''
</P>
<P>
   Many technologists believe that the Internet could be made
considerably more secure. Cars, they note, used to be a lot less
safe than they are now. That was before a combination of consumer
pressure, governmental regulation and manufacturers' designs came
up with seat belts and air bags and anti-lock brakes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I use the network extensively,'' said Peter Neumann, a
computer security expert with SRI International. ``I also know it
can be brought down by anybody, anywhere in the world, in about 30
minutes. One of the things we need to do is educate the populace,
so that they can take precautions.''
</P>
<P>
   Risk assessment has been a big topic lately on the online
discussion groups at eBay, the Internet auction site that has
suffered a spate of high-profile fraud attempts. Sandi Brady, 49,
of Franklin, N.J., echoed a widely held view: ``I struggle a little
bit with using my credit card on the Internet,'' she said. ``But
for every bad transaction, there's so many more good transactions.
I use common sense, I use caution, and that's no different than the
caution you take in life, period.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet proponents argue that the vulnerabilities of the
Internet are not any greater than those of the physical world _
just different. For instance, Paul Leuhr, who supervises the
Federal Trade Commission's Internet fraud program, calls consumers'
fears that someone will seize their credit card numbers as they
travel across the network a ``gross misperception.'' Although
credit card fraud on the Internet is thought to be slightly higher
than in real-world transactions, and the speed and reach of the
network can make its consequences far more serious, Leuhr said,
``almost always, fraud springs from the natural flaws in human
behavior,'' such as writing down passwords or leaving credit card
receipts in the garbage.
</P>
<P>
   But a relatively new realm of human behavior now encompasses
making policy and personal decisions about how to handle the
technology that is becoming so closely woven into everyday life.
And critics say greater attention to the vulnerabilities of the
computer network is an important part of that.
</P>
<P>
   A law that promises to eliminate costly paperwork and to speed
transactions like purchasing home mortgages or paying taxes sounds
great, for instance. But with no standards for ensuring the
security of such documents, it could merely create a lot of
confusion and litigation. Under the current law, it seems that a
simple e-mail signature could qualify as binding. What happens when
one party says a contract is changed after it is signed? What
happens when a family paying bills online drops its Internet
account?
</P>
<P>
   But Margot Saunders, an attorney at the National Consumer Law
Center, said the real problem for critics of the new law is that
``these are all what-ifs.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not intuitive because we're not seeing these problems out
there and reporting back,'' she added. ``We're just guessing.''
</P>
<P>
   And that in turn may help explain why it is so hard to confront
the virtual impossibility of privacy and security on the Internet,
or find the will to adjust behavior accordingly. It dovetails with
the way people have for decades grappled with technological risk.
Because it is harder to comprehend _ particularly with information
technology, which is itself is so intangible _ it seems easier to
dismiss the potential to do damage.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the same as getting your face smashed through the
windshield,'' said David Mindell, a historian of technology at MIT.
``It's a lot less clear what your risks are when you're on the
Internet or moving your life management over to Internet. And it's
very hard for people to change their behavior based on poorly
defined risks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
