<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0062 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 11:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3758 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      06-24 1189
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
  
(The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44).). 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   (Week in Review summary of events in the headlines last week)
</P>
<P>
   For Microsoft, Quick Appeal and Slower Penalties
</P>
<P>
   The trial judge in the Microsoft antitrust case surprised
everyone by ordering a postponement of the conduct restrictions he
imposed just two weeks earlier until appeals are complete. In the
same order he certified the case for direct appeal to the Supreme
Court. Microsoft was jubilant; penalties that were to take effect
in September are now on hold for at least a year, maybe longer. But
some government officials say they believe Microsoft, freed from
scrutiny for a while, might continue the sort of behavior that got
the company in trouble to begin with, and help convince the appeals
courts to uphold the lower court's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Trying for a Trend in Asia
</P>
<P>
   The historic handshake between the leaders of the two Koreas a
week before inspired another Asian leader to reach out to a
longtime adversary. Chen Shui-bian, Taiwan's new president, invited
his Chinese counterpart, Jiang Zemin, to attend a similar
peacemaking summit. China was unmoved by Taiwan's overture.
</P>
<P>
   To Deal or Not to Deal
</P>
<P>
   With six months left in office and frustrated by the ability of
Slobodan Milosevic to keep his job, the Clinton administration is
exploring with America's allies suggestions that Yugoslavia's
president might leave office if he were given guarantees for his
safety and savings, despite his indictment on charges of war crimes
in Kosovo. Greece is doing the intermediary work. American
spokesmen denied any thought of a bargain, but senior American and
NATO officials said differently.
</P>
<P>
   Broadening Hate Protection
</P>
<P>
   The Senate passed a milestone _ though not necessarily a law _
when it adopted a hate crimes bill that listed sexual orientation,
along with race, religion, national origin and handicapped status,
as a protected category.
</P>
<P>
   The bipartisan vote, 57-42, was the first time either house of
Congress had moved to protect gay people on a roll call that could
have political consequences. The measure was strongly supported by
President Clinton, and its fate may depend on his willingness to
insist that House Republican leaders accept it before signing
spending bills that will let Congress go home.
</P>
<P>
   Escalating in Colombia
</P>
<P>
   The Senate approved nearly $1 billion in aid to Colombia, a
major escalation in America's commitment to help an important Latin
American ally combat drug trafficking and a guerrilla insurgency.
</P>
<P>
   The House has already approved the measure, a top priority of
the Clinton administration. Proponents said the aid, including
helicopters, would be used to train and equip three army battalions
for counter-drug operations. But critics warned that Washington was
plunging into an open-ended civil conflict that has cost thousands
of lives over nearly four decades.
</P>
<P>
   A Chance for Addicts
</P>
<P>
   New York state moved to expand pilot programs that had shown
some success in changing the lives of convicted drug addicts, by
offering every nonviolent addict the option of treatment instead of
jail. While all 50 states offer some form of court-mandated
treatment, New York will be the first to make it an integral part
of the system. The move is expected to move one-tenth of the
state's 95,000 inmates from behind bars and into treatment
programs, and save $500 million a year in prison, foster care and
mental health costs.
</P>
<P>
   A New Archbishop
</P>
<P>
   Edward M. Egan, the former bishop of Bridgeport, Conn., who was
credited with rescuing that diocese from bankruptcy and
replenishing its dwindling priesthood, was installed as the ninth
archbishop of New York, succeeding Cardinal John O'Connor. Egan is
a canon lawyer and classical pianist who is expected to adapt the
New York archdiocese to demographic changes and fiscal pressures by
closing or merging schools, parishes and perhaps hospitals _ all
steps his predecessor was loath to undertake.
</P>
<P>
   A Long-Awaited Truce
</P>
<P>
   After two years of high-intensity warfare, Ethiopia and Eritrea
_ once held out by Western nations as beacons of hope in Africa _
signed a cease-fire to be monitored by U.N. peacekeepers. Their war
was fought, on the surface, over who owned what along their common
border. But it was fueled as much by economic tensions and personal
grudges stemming from Eritrea's independence from Ethiopia in 1993.
The next step is a border commission, though that will not heal
tattered economies or relations.
</P>
<P>
   New Golf Records
</P>
<P>
   Tiger Woods did not just win the U.S. Open. He dominated. He won
by a record 15 strokes, even as he broke or equaled several other
records. Golf has never seen a player quite like Woods, who
combines tremendous athletic ability with a magnetism that attracts
people of all ages and backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   A Grim Trade
</P>
<P>
   The growing trade in people transported by criminal gangs from
their impoverished lands to Europe produced a grisly new statistic
when the bodies of 58 refugees from Fujian province in China were
discovered in the overheated and airless container of a Dutch truck
when it came ashore from a channel ferry at Dover, in southern
England. Two survivors were recovering in a Canterbury hospital.
The British police charged the driver, Perry Wacker, 32, of
Rotterdam, the Netherlands, with 58 counts of manslaughter.
</P>
<P>
   Signs of Water on Mars
</P>
<P>
   Mars used to have oceans and rivers, but they vanished more than
a billion years ago, the water evaporating and escaping into space.
Scientists believed that what little water remained was trapped in
the planet's frozen poles.
</P>
<P>
   Now, pictures taken by an orbiting American spacecraft suggest
there may be underground sources of water beneath the upper crust
that occasionally burst free and flow down crater walls. Scientists
think those may be ideal places to seek evidence of life.
</P>
<P>
   No Prayers, Please
</P>
<P>
   On religion, the Supreme Court often speaks with many voices in
a confusing tangle of opinions, so last week's ruling declaring
unconstitutional the practice of student-led prayer at public
school football games was notable for its clarity. Organized prayer
at a school-sponsored event _ even if ostensibly the private choice
of a student speaker _ amounts to an official endorsement of
religion that is inherently coercive of unwilling participants,
Justice John Paul Stevens said in the 6-3 decision.
</P>
<P>
   Inquiry on First Lady Ends
</P>
<P>
   Robert Ray, the independent counsel who succeeded Kenneth Starr,
announced he would seek no criminal charges against Hillary Rodham
Clinton in the firing of seven White House travel office employees
in 1993, but he said evidence indicated she had played a greater
role than she had portrayed in her testimony. He said she
``ultimately influenced'' the decision by expressing ``concerns''
to White House officials.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
