<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONACO-MONEY-LAUNDERING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRANCE ISSUES TOUGH REPORT ON MONACO AND ITS MONEY
</HEADLINE>
  By SUZANNE DALEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARIS _ The writer W. Somerset Maugham once described Monaco as
``a sunny spot for shady people.'' Last week, the French Parliament
offered a few more details.
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing 400-page report, the Parliament said that the tiny
principality _ a famous refuge for wealthy tax dodgers _ was also
an ideal place to launder money.
</P>
<P>
   It accused Monaco of having deliberately put in place lax
banking laws _ including a guarantee of anonymity _ to attract
wealthy depositors no matter who they were. And it said that the
monetary surveillance systems were so poor that even if Monaco
officials wanted to cooperate in international efforts to prevent
money laundering, they could not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monaco is one of the most hypocritical territories when it
comes to the fight against money laundering,'' said Arnaud
Montebourg, one of the Socialist members of Parliament who helped
to write the report. ``A loose system is not just tolerated there,
it was created on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   Even control systems that were in place are not functioning
properly, the report said. One French auditor described inspecting
more than 260 files that should have contained information about
the identity of depositors. He found that a quarter of them were
completely empty.
</P>
<P>
   The parliamentary report recommended that France review its
accords with Monaco, some of which date back hundreds of years.
Unless changes are made, the report said, France _ which provides
Monaco with top civil servants and supervises its lending agencies
_ is in danger of losing its own credibility in the fight against
money laundering.
</P>
<P>
   The report also questioned why France should continue to
contribute to the upkeep of the Mediterranean resort, especially
when the principality's main goal ``appeared to be to let some of
the wealthiest citizens in the world get away without paying
taxes.'' At the moment, France shares its sales tax proceeds with
Monaco, under a formula that most experts say favors Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   Money laundering and banking practices have been a hot topic in
Europe. France's report on Monaco came only a day after members of
the European Union reached an agreement in principle on sweeping
changes to bank secrecy laws, intended to bring cross-border
investment income within the net of tax authorities.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, all 15 European Union states will exchange
information on nonresident's savings. This is intended to prevent
tax evasion by people who place their investments in secret
accounts in another European Union member country, or elsewhere
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, however, faces some major hurdles. It is dependent on
the cooperation of the United States, Switzerland and such tax
havens as Monaco and Liechtenstein, another principality that has
come under heavy scrutiny by an official from neighboring Austria
who claims to have found evidence of money laundering. Austria
itself has drawn the ire of fellow European Union members for
insisting on maintaining a high degree of banking secrecy.
</P>
<P>
   Liechtenstein was among the 15 countries named by an
international task force last week as failing to cooperate with the
fight against the concealment of illegally earned funds. Other
countries on the list included Russia and Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Monaco had also been rumored to be on the blacklist, drawn up by
the 26-nation Finance Action Task Force on money laundering. But
instead it was placed on the second tier ``gray'' list.
</P>
<P>
   The French Parliament report found that much of Monaco's
surveillance system was woefully understaffed. The report also
pointed out only 37 ``declarations of suspicion'' on potentially
illegal transactions were filed in 1998, far less than in any other
European tax haven, and despite more than $44 billion on deposit.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the report said, Monaco had 10 times as many
bank accounts as residents and about 60 percent of the 340,000
accounts belonged to nonresidents. Only about 30,000 people live in
Monaco, which occupies a choice piece of Mediterranean coast not
quite as big as Central Park.
</P>
<P>
   Monaco remained silent on the report. It issued a statement
saying only that in time ``it would communicate the observations
and comments that it believed were necessary.''
</P>
<P>
   The principality has a complicated relationship with France,
which provides many of its top functionaries and magistrates.
Monaco also uses French francs.
</P>
<P>
   The French report said that Monaco risks destabilizing markets
through a lack of surveillance of its banking and financial
sectors, and could hardly succeed in joining the Euro zone unless
it mended its ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monaco must choose,'' the report said. ``It is up to it to
head for change.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
