<HEADER>
A3775 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: WHADDAYA MEAN YOU DON'T WANT TO PLAY HERE? 
</HEADLINE>
   By GEORGE VECSEY    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Ranting, apparently, is in style. Dennis Miller, the new man in
the booth for ``Monday Night Football,'' is known for his rants.
</P>
<P>
   If ABC wanted rants, they could have hired that homeless guy
near my office. All he wants is a quarter a rant.
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath, everybody is ranting about the sacrilege of
hiring a sarcastic comedian to do ``Monday Night Football.''
Apparently, this will defile the dignified memory of Howard, Giff
and Dandy Don, doing their Edward R. Murrow imitations.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, if ranting is in, let's give it a try:
</P>
<P>
   I'm sick of watching the fans and the news media being played
like cheap fiddles in this Sosa-Gonzalez dance. One day Sammy wants
to come to New York. The next day he isn't sure. One day Juan
doesn't want to come to Yankee Stadium. The next day he might
consider a few months to see if he likes it.
</P>
<P>
   What do you mean, Juan Gonzalez doesn't want to play in New
York? Is he nuts?
</P>
<P>
   It may only be a negotiating ploy that Gonzalez has suggested he
wants to play someplace quiet, but people are not going to forget
these sentiments. Doesn't he know what an honor it is to play in
Yankee Stadium?
</P>
<P>
   Just ask Wade Boggs. Just ask David Wells. Just ask Tim Raines.
Just ask Cecil Fielder. Just ask Chili Davis. Just ask Darryl and
Doc. Just ask Reggie Jackson, who sat in the Orioles' bus in 1976
and sang ``New York, New York'' and other such ditties, just to
tell his temporary teammates he was in a New York frame of mind.
Some ballplayers have imagination and some don't.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez may have gotten the wrong idea when he had to duck some
missiles from the barbarians in the right-field stands during the
three losing playoff series Texas had in Yankee Stadium in 1996,
'98 and '99.
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for the vile language and aerial warfare
conducted from the outer seats, but hasn't Gonzalez figured out
that the boos tend to stop when you put on the stripes? (Unless
you've got Whitson's Disease, that is.)
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he got discouraged from batting one for 12 and two for 11
in the past two playoffs against the Yankees, but he has to
remember the awesome feeling of hitting three homers in two games
in the Stadium in 1996 and going seven for 16 and driving in nine
runs. They could hardly get him out.
</P>
<P>
   Anybody with that kind of series and a minimal sense of
imagination would look around him and say, ``I could own this
place.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the guy is using New York for leverage, or else he has
got the pips. He doesn't like New York? Who does he think he is,
John Rocker?
</P>
<P>
   By the way, that gallant spitter into toll booths is coming to
town on Thursday. Somehow, Rocker has emerged as a symbol for
conservatives. Apparently, it's a freedom of speech issue.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody said he didn't have the right to be prejudiced against
whole swaths of the population. On the other hand, some of us have
the obligation to reply, ``Those are our relatives and our friends
and our neighbors you're talking about, young fellow.''
</P>
<P>
   Rocker's defenders should see the disgusted looks on the faces
of his Atlanta teammates, who are athletes, not ideologues. In
their pragmatism, they think he is a cancer.
</P>
<P>
   Now Rocker wants to indulge himself in a subway ride to Shea
Stadium. He'll cost New Yorkers thousands of dollars for security
by going out in public. Who does he think he is, a presidential
candidate?
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez has not made any anti-New York statements, but the
original word was that he did not want to play here. Isn't this the
same guy who said he wouldn't play in the All-Star Game if he
couldn't start? Didn't Steinbrenner check his dossier?
</P>
<P>
   Now the Gonzalez camp is floating out the suggestion that
Gonzalez wants rent-a-player status, coming to the Bronx and taking
a look around.
</P>
<P>
   That might work, except that first impressions are not always so
great. Mike Piazza had that deer-in-the-headlights look when he
landed in Shea Stadium. At first, the fans booed him, sensing, in
their cruelty, that he was stunned. Now they love the big gentle
lug.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Gonzalez might find love at first sight. He
could be like the vast majority of cool guys who have come to New
York in recent years and found it much more than doable. Derek
Jeter gets around. Darryl Hamilton fits in fine. Al Leiter's
looking at public schools in Manhattan for one of his kids. Public
schools! John Olerud rode the subway. So does Todd Zeile.
</P>
<P>
   Gonzalez would be a better fit for the Yankees than Sammy Sosa,
but on the other hand Sammy would light up the Bronx with his
smile.
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't Gonzalez know what a career move this could be? He has
never been to the World Series. Hasn't he seen what happens to even
a Jim Leyritz or a Chad Curtis or a Scott Brosius when they start
playing best-of-seven in late October?
</P>
<P>
   This guy doesn't get it. He doesn't deserve New York. Besides,
what the Yankees really need is pitching.
</P>
<P>
   That's it for the ranting. The ranter near my office told me
everything is the CIA's fault. The guy is a loon. Everybody knows
it's Nike's fault.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0075 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3776 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      06-24 1438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIPSYTE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: TAKING THE MEASURE OF A YOUNG TRACK STAR 
</HEADLINE>
   By ROBERT LIPSYTE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Khadijah Conda, sisterhood's child, is still one one-hundredth
of a second shy of qualifying for next month's Olympic
track-and-field trials in the 400-meter run. Her college coach, Pat
Connolly, wails, ``You can't even blink your eye that fast.''
</P>
<P>
   But both women know that smidgen of time may be the measure of a
life; at the world class, where all athletes are gifted and strong,
it is a competitor's will, not skill, that makes the difference
between winning and going home early. Even Conda is not sure if she
has the heart to run so hard she will collapse, retching and seeing
stars, then get up and shake it off so she can do it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of me can't quite let go of the dream,'' she said last
week without conviction.
</P>
<P>
   She is barely even talking the talk. Walking the walk came to a
dead stop last Sunday, when she quit in the middle of a race. That
was an unthinkable act to Willye White, the five-time Olympian who
sent Conda to the three-time Olympian, Connolly, her best friend,
for a year of running dangerously at Radford University in
Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still don't know if that girl is hungry enough, greedy
enough, to pay the price to be a champion,'' White said. ``Khadijah
hasn't shown the die-hardness, the killer instinct. She was called,
but she wasn't chosen.''
</P>
<P>
   The choosing is not quite over. Next Saturday, at a club meet in
Indianapolis, Conda could run the qualifying time of 52.45 seconds
and get a spot in the trials, which begin July 14 in Sacramento.
Her best time so far is 52.46. She is in physical shape to run
well, she said, but it took her most of last week to get her mind
on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to keep reminding myself this is something I want,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   The energy level in her voice rose as she talked about her
current internship with General Electric, which she finds
absorbing, and a plan to surprise a sorority sister this weekend by
attending her wedding. ``I had told her a long time ago I wouldn't
make it because I'd be in training.''
</P>
<P>
   Conda said she has been bedeviled with ``crazy thoughts.'' She
didn't want to disappoint White and Connolly. She felt she had some
responsibility to find the limits of her considerable talents. Yet
she wanted a life, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I gave up a year of my life,'' she said. ``I wouldn't change
that, but it was a hard year, the first Thanksgiving I didn't spend
with my family, the first Mother's Day I wasn't with my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, after Conda transferred from Purdue to run for
Connolly's Radford team, the three women thought they were a
sisterhood heading for this year's Olympics in Sydney. Conda had
the ``tools'' _ the leg speed, strength and stamina _ of an Olympic
champion. But she needed the kind of intensive, one-on-one coaching
that would build her confidence and ignite her competitive fire.
And Connolly and White needed to find out if Conda was really the
one.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches call it heart, but it is really a desperation to win.
Not all athletes care enough about winning to allow the quest to
dominate their lives. Nothing burns out coaches faster than an
unusually talented youngster who will not embrace pain and
sacrifice, who would rather play than pay the price to be the best.
</P>
<P>
   In their time, Connolly, 56, and White, 60, had been desperate
enough to pay the price. White sprinted out of a snake-infested
Mississippi cotton field to the 1956 Melbourne Games and eventually
won two silver medals. Connolly ran and long-jumped out of an
abusive California home to the 1960 Rome Olympics, where she and
White became teammates.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 40 years, the women have considered themselves
sisters, supporting each other through births, deaths, four
husbands and the tidal shifts in the sports world. The rise of
performance-enhancing chemicals and procedures drove both women out
of competition; neither wanted to take drugs or compete at a
disadvantage against those who did.
</P>
<P>
   After a long career coaching and mentoring young women for the
city of Chicago, White retired; she is involved now in Olympic
development. Connolly, who is married to the 1956 Olympic gold
medalist in the hammer throw, Harold Connolly, found her calling as
an elite coach, especially with Evelyn Ashford, winner of three
Olympic gold medals and the former world-record holder in the
women's 100 meters. Last year, Connolly took a job as head men's
and women's track-and-field coach at Radford.
</P>
<P>
   It was a hard year, building a new program with subpar
facilities. Most of her athletes regarded varsity sports as a
beauty and fitness regime. Her family was scattered; Harold was in
California, coaching their son, Adam, who had his own Olympic
hammer-throwing aspirations. Their daughter was in New York,
finishing at Columbia. And then there was Conda: smart, lovely,
athletically gifted, a young princess who, her sports mothers
thought, would put Radford on the map or break Connolly's heart.
</P>
<P>
   Conda, who turns 22 June 26, was raised in a strict Chicago
Muslim home. Her beloved late father was a sociology professor.
Educational achievement was emphasized; sports was a pastime,
tolerated so long as Khadijah did well in school. She accepted an
athletic scholarship to Purdue because she wanted to be an
engineer. She won Big 10 titles at Purdue but never competed in the
NCAA championships. Her progress was stalled. Conda and the Purdue
track coach had problems.
</P>
<P>
   White had followed Conda's athletic career since she was a
schoolgirl participant in the Willye B. White Foundation's annual
gala. White thought that Connolly could do for Conda what she had
done for Ashford. But Ashford had been hungry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have some hunger,'' Conda said last week as she talked
herself into competing in next weekend's Indianapolis race. ``But
I'm not sure. Is there a lacking in hunger, did it decrease? Is my
dream not as deep as I thought it was? I'm searching my soul.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly thinks such introspection, along with Conda leaving
Radford for Chicago to take the GE job and attend the wedding,
shows a lack of desire.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she really wanted to be an Olympian, she would be here
working out,'' she said. ``I'm sad. I taught her how to run. She
came here and she had never run below 54 seconds before. Maybe it's
me. Some coaches can coach fear, like Bobby Knight. I can't do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   In Chicago, White said: ``Pat's the one I'm worried about. She
gave the girl everything. I don't want her to think it had to do
with her coaching. I told Pat not to talk to the girl till she
comes back to school in September, let her marinate, maybe she'll
mature, have greater insights. And after what happened last Sunday,
I told Pat, `You can't coach guts.'''
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, at a college meet in Chapel Hill, N.C., Conda quit
in the middle of a race she was losing. She stopped and walked off
the course. For White and Connolly, it was a sacrilege.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to run hard, gut it out, fight to the death,'' White
said. ``You have to run faster than you are trained to run, you
have to hurt, you can't let anyone beat you.''
</P>
<P>
   Connolly said: ``I was so disappointed, all I could say to her
was, `Thank you for not insulting me and pretending you were
injured.' I really thought she was going to make it, run her heart
out and qualify and go to the Olympics as an alternate in the
relay, take home a gold and be inspired to train for 2004.''
</P>
<P>
   A few days after that race, Conda struggled to explain why she
had quit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the first time since I began competing at 9 that I
didn't finish a race,'' she said. ``Before I even ran, I was so
discouraged I had to force myself to a place I didn't feel I wanted
to be.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, I thought what I did was my way of telling myself to
walk away from all this, a perverted way of trying to take control
of my life. Afterwards I thought, this is not control, it's part of
battling with inner demons.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, I learned so much this year. I gained strength. I
improved so much as a runner'' _ she was named outstanding female
athlete at the Big South Indoors. ``Coach Connolly got me to the
NCAA championships. But when I ran my 52.46, I was sick for a day.
Do I want that?''
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last week, however, Conda's spirits had risen,
although she was not sure how much had to do with good feelings
about the GE job, the wedding festivities and her birthday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to Indianapolis,'' she said. ``I am trying to muster
it up, find out whether I have it or not, do or die.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1226EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
