<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3780 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT     06-24 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR INDIANA CRITIC, A GRACEFUL RETREAT 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a child growing up in Montreal, Murray Sperber could walk to
any one of three hockey rinks. He played the game, and naturally
engaged in his share of fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you wanted to play, if you wanted to win, you had to
fight,'' he said. ``But hockey fights are very ritualistic. It was
you and the other guy, and nobody ever jumped in.''
</P>
<P>
   Not in the way people have in Sperber's more unconventional
battle with Bob Knight, an enforcer with a posse.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is different,'' he said. ``This is sanity versus
insanity.''
</P>
<P>
   After 29 years as an English professor at Indiana University,
the past three spiced by his role as a rare faculty critic of the
volatile basketball coach, 59-year-old Murray Sperber will pack up
his family later this week and return to Montreal. After threats to
disrupt his fall classes and calls to his home threatened his life,
he is terming it a leave of absence, while conceding he may have
taught his last class on his beloved Bloomington campus.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, call it what you want, sabbatical or
surrender. Sperber prefers to consider himself what Russell Hanson,
the dean of arts and sciences, recently declared him _ a living
example of what he is preaching.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of Knight's favorite sayings is, `Last man standing
wins,''' Sperber said recently. ``I reject that. The fight I'm in
is the reform of college sports, and that is a long process. If
what's happened to me in any way encourages more college faculties
to get involved, then, who knows, maybe I'm winning.''
</P>
<P>
   An old antiwar and civil rights activist while doing graduate
work at the University of California-Berkeley, Sperber always
understood the consequences for confronting the establishment.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of my '60s activism probably did get channeled into
it,'' he said. ``But I have to laugh when these Knight supporters
look up my bio, see the Berkeley part of it, and then it's `Commie
this, Pinko that.' The truth is, there were so many people to the
left of me. I was a liberal then. I'm a liberal now.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine years on the same campus, the liberal never shook
hands with the General. They never met. Sperber tried to interview
Knight more than a decade ago for his book, ``College Sports
Inc.,'' which started him down this road. He never got past the
secretary, he said, which made him no different than most faculty
members.
</P>
<P>
   Sperber, in fact, once polled 45 instructors with 10 years or
more experience, and discovered that not one had been in the same
room with Knight, not counting the basketball arena.
</P>
<P>
   Had he deigned to break bread with a respected critic on his own
faculty, Knight might have actually learned something about Sperber
that he could respect. How Sperber and his wife, Aneta, struggled
to cope with having to bury a 6-year-old son more than a decade
ago. How they adopted two foster children, both girls, now 12 and
10. Knight would have discovered that Sperber played the game,
Knight's game. An inch over 6 feet, Sperber went from youth hockey
to high school basketball, to intramurals at Purdue and even played
some semipro ball while working on his Ph.D. in the south of
France.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, confronted with mounting evidence of his ill-tempered
handiwork after the Neil Reed hand-on-throat allegations surfaced,
instead chose to discredit Sperber as a critic and an author. On
what did he base his evaluations? Bob Hammel, a retired Bloomington
sports editor and longtime friend and flatterer, told him so.
</P>
<P>
   Knight, the tough guy who builds character, has made a career of
stomping out dissent, or just avoiding it altogether. Consider how
he let Myles Brand cover for him when the university president
announced the zero-tolerance policy last month. When he finally did
address the news media, Knight hand-picked the participants as if
he were choosing the members of his wedding party.
</P>
<P>
   For what it's worth, Sperber has never been afraid to debate any
rational Knight supporter, including university officials. Several
weeks ago, he walked into what looked like an ambush, on sports
talk radio with Mike Francesa and Chris Russo in New York. Francesa
seemed eager to put Sperber on the defensive, but, to his credit,
conducted a spirited but fair interview. He later agreed that
Sperber in no way came across as uninformed or unreasonable.
</P>
<P>
   Sperber has another book on the subject of big-time college
sports due out in September. Of course, he has heard that he is
exploiting Knight, as if he knew the Neil Reed story would break.
As if he has been calling newspapers after every Knight outburst
for 29 years.
</P>
<P>
   To the best of his recollection, it was not until 1997, when he
was first interviewed by anyone outside Bloomington. By this
spring, he was on all the national outlets, often identified as
``Murray Sperber, Knight critic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `After all my years of teaching, writing, putting off
family outings for students and school, I'm going to go to my grave
as Knight critic,''' he said. ``I have to tell you that was pretty
depressing.''
</P>
<P>
   The truth is his interest was the increasingly dysfunctional
college sports system long before he became the go-to guy on
Knight. Even then, just as at Berkeley, Sperber's bent was more
liberal than radical. He always credited Knight for ``running a
clean program in a corrupt sport.'' He just thought the cons had
finally come to outweigh the pros, that someone on the faculty
should stand up to say that ``sports should never overshadow the
academic functions of a university.''
</P>
<P>
   For now, Bob Knight stays at Indiana. Murray Sperber goes, a
living example of what he preached.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
