<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 12:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3781 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-LA-GOVERNOR-NYT &LR;      06-24 1161
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-GOVERNOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOUISIANA GOVERNOR'S UNUSUAL POPULARITY PLUMMETS AS ECONOMIC CRISIS
LOOMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID FIRESTONE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BATON ROUGE, La. _ For a few high-flying months in his first
term, Mike Foster might have been the most popular governor in
America, riding a brief economic boom and his Harley-Davidson Road
King to unheard-of approval ratings in the range of 70 percent to
80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the good years never seem to last long in Louisiana.
Inevitably, they are overtaken by an extreme statewide poverty
virtually unparalleled in the nation, along with an addiction to
oil revenues that frequently run dry. When this year's state budget
could not be balanced without a sales tax increase on food, Mike
Foster fell back to earth, hard. And it is unclear whether the
economy will allow him to ascend again in the last three years of
his second term.
</P>
<P>
   A poll released on Monday by Southern Media and Opinion Research
found that Foster now has an approval rating of 54.8 percent, which
many governors might consider a blessing. But in April, the same
poll gave him an approval rating of 69.4 percent, and in March
1999, his approval reached a high of 82 percent. Bernie Pinsonat,
who conducted the poll, said the governor's popularity has been in
a ``free fall'' since the budget crisis developed earlier this
year, after several years of surpluses.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, a gruff, wealthy Republican who often spends weekends at
his private duck-hunting camp, has never been popular among the
state's black residents, particularly after admitting that in 1995
he secretly bought the contributors list of David Duke, a former
Louisiana Ku Klux Klan wizard and state politician. But Foster has
always had a strong following among rural and suburban white
voters, and among business leaders. Both groups seem to be
deserting him now.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the darling of the business community during his first
term,'' said Pete deGravelles, chairman of the Greater Lafayette
Chamber of Commerce and a boyhood friend of Foster. ``But he really
shocked us after he was re-elected last year. All of a sudden he
was talking about a whole bunch of new business taxes. It was a
whole different tone, and a lot of people were disappointed.''
</P>
<P>
   Even legislators from his own party have criticized how the
governor handled what became a surprise fiscal emergency. Gathered
in the state's Capitol this week for an unusual special session to
complete the budget, several lawmakers said they wished Foster had
better informed the public about the state's economic condition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Frankly, he isn't exactly the great communicator,'' said state
Rep. Victor Stelly, a Republican from Lake Charles. ``We've had
governors like Edwin Edwards and Buddy Roemer who could charm the
socks off a billy goat, and he's not the charismatic type.''
</P>
<P>
   Foster, who says he has no political ambitions after he is
required to leave office in 2004, insisted that he is not concerned
about the falloff in popularity. ``That's what happens when you
have a budget crisis pop up on you,'' he said in an interview,
though he acknowledged that he could have done better in explaining
the state's teetering economy to the public.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've had a difficult time getting that across,'' he
said. ``After you have a few good years, people aren't prepared for
a downturn, they haven't had that much pain. There's a kind of
disconnect there that makes it very difficult to govern.''
</P>
<P>
   Louisiana is one of the few states that is having trouble
balancing its budget in a period of national prosperity, but its
economy and civic health have always followed a different course
than the rest of the nation, or even the South. It has the
second-highest poverty rate of any state, after much-smaller New
Mexico, and the gap between its wealthiest and poorest residents is
the nation's widest and is growing. This month it was ranked the
worst state for children by the Annie E. Casey Foundation, a
private, charitable organization based in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   And according to census data, Louisiana was the only Southern
state where more people moved out than moved in during the 1990s.
While 3.6 million Americans moved to the South, Louisiana
experienced a net migration loss of 140,000 people.
</P>
<P>
   Foster, like several of his predecessors, has tried to solve
some long-term problems by improving the state's educational
system. But he has found that his state does not have enough money
to bring teacher salaries into line even with the rest of the
South, a region that already trails the national average. The state
is one of the most lightly taxed in the country, collecting less
money per capita than all but five other states.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, state government relied on the oil and gas industry
as a reliable source of revenue that provided up to 40 percent of
the state budget as recently as the 1980s. But with the depletion
of the state's energy resources, oil is now supplying less than 10
percent of the budget, and the state is relying on gambling, a high
sales tax and a low income tax for most of its revenues.
</P>
<P>
   After the price of oil dropped precipitously last year, the
industry laid off nearly 13,000 people, which quickly rippled
through the economy and produced a sharp plunge in state revenues.
Loren Scott, an economics professor at Louisiana State University,
said the governor and the Legislature also engaged in some
questionable budgeting practices, such as using one-time revenues
from the national tobacco settlement for operating expenses.
</P>
<P>
   And so this year, faced with a budget deficit of nearly $400
million, the governor and the Legislature raised the state sales
tax on food and utilities by a penny to 4 cents on the dollar, cut
personal income tax deductions and increased taxes on telephone
calls and tobacco. Many Democratic legislators were furious that
business lobbyists prevented any new taxes on the oil and gas
industry or on casino gambling, and education advocates said the
package did little to improve the state's school system.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, though, the Legislature sent a proposed
constitutional amendment to voters that would lower the state's
dependence on the sales tax, while raising the income tax enough to
increase teacher salaries. Economists say such a change would
finally allow state revenues to grow with the economy, unlike the
current system in which more than half of revenues come from sales
taxes.
</P>
<P>
   But considering the mood the voters are in, few people expect
the amendment to pass in November. Foster acknowledges the
difficulty he faces in selling the tax package, hoping he still has
a reserve of popularity left from which to draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course we're undertaxed, but no one wants to hear that from
me,'' he said. ``I'm just going to have to tell people and not
worry about the consequences. We're in the worst of all worlds if I
have to start worrying about what my popularity is.''  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
