<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, June 25, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A weak area of low pressure moving into the eastern Great Lakes
and its associated fronts will trigger many showers and
thunderstorms Sunday. Thunderstorms and showers will develop early
in the Ohio Valley as a cold front impinges upon very warm and
humid air. Afternoon thunderstorms will also develop in the
northern and central Appalachians as a jet stream disturbance races
ahead of the same front.
</P>
<P>
   The East Coast will turn noticeably more humid as increasing
breezes from the southwest direct sticky air over the region.
Meanwhile, thunderstorms will develop at the Southeast coast as a
jet stream disturbance lingers over the Carolina Piedmont.
</P>
<P>
   Thunderstorms, some of which will be strong, will develop in the
central Plains as a front becomes stationary. The Pacific Northwest
states will be sunny and warm.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: ARIZONA MONSOON
</P>
<P>
   Monsoon is an Arabic word meaning seasonal wind. In the
Southwestern United States, the seasonal wind shift is often too
subtle to detect, so humidity is used to define the start of the
monsoon. The second earliest start of the monsoon was declared in
Phoenix last week with the first occurrence of three consecutive
days of high humidity. Each year in late June or the first half of
July the amount of moisture in the normally arid desert air nearly
triples. As a result, scattered afternoon thunderstorms become a
common feature during the desert monsoon.
</P>
</TEXT>
