<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 13:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3797 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-GLIDERS0625-COX     06-24 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLIDERS0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A powerless passion
 &HT;    By Jim DeBrosse
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNESVILLE, Ohio _ Five minutes after takeoff, when we reach
3,000 feet in a pristine sky, glider pilot Rich Carraway releases
the line from the tow plane and banks our two-seater sailplane
gently to the north _ free, as the poet said, of the surly bonds of
Earth.
</P>
<P>
   Silence.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing but the wind whispering around our clear plastic canopy.
We're in a peaceful bubble floating over a checkerboard of Warren
County farms and forests just a few miles east of Caesar Creek
Lake.
</P>
<P>
   Below us, turkey vultures circle lazily on the percolating air.
We are brothers, it seems, in the purity and ease of flight.
</P>
<P>
   Even for a shameless wuss like myself, who has a paralyzing fear
of heights, my 20-minute ride as a guest passenger with the Caesar
Creek Soaring Club was as gentle and agreeable as many of the
club's 200-plus members.
</P>
<P>
   Pilots who want a more exhilarating experience can catch a
thermal _ a rising column of air _ that can lift them into the
clouds and keep them swirling in the sky for hours.
</P>
<P>
   Soaring ``is probably one of the most addictive things you can
do,'' said club member Mark Statt, 45, of Cincinnati. Statt
developed his habit soon after retiring from the Army in 1994.
``It's the purest form of flight.''
</P>
<P>
   Soaring also offers a relatively easy way for many people, from
teen-agers to octogenarians, to make their fantasy of flying come
true. Caesar Creek club members range in age from 14 to 90.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always thought flying was a really cool thing, because my
dad has been a pilot for a long time. Gliding seemed the simplest
way for me to get some flight experience,'' said Katie Menchen, a
14-year-old Westchester resident who flew solo this spring for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Glider pilots can be licensed by age 16 _ two years younger than
airplane pilots.
</P>
<P>
   Caesar Creek Soaring Club prides itself on having one of the
lowest-priced and safest glider pilot training programs in the
country. The group's 20 instructors are all volunteers and
instruction is free. You must join the club, however, and will need
about 75 flights before qualifying for the pilot's exam.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1947 by a group of mostly Wright-Patterson Air Force
Base researchers, the club is situated on 146 acres of woods and
pasture near Waynesville that was once a dairy farm. The bucolic
setting now includes a landing strip, clubhouse (with showers, rest
rooms and a well-stocked refrigerator), campgrounds, hangars,
picnic shelters, fishing pond and observation deck. The club owns
eight gliders and three tow planes for members' use.
</P>
<P>
   Members keep flight costs well below those of individually owned
sailplanes by volunteering once a month as ground crew and
tow-plane pilots. About 50 members of the club are licensed pilots,
so there is no shortage of volunteers to fly the club's three Piper
Pawnee tow planes.
</P>
<P>
   Still, soaring is not the sport of paupers. The club's entry fee
is $400 _ an initial payment of $200 plus another $200 after the
first year for those who want to continue their membership.
(Members younger than 21 pay less.) In addition, adult members are
required to buy 12 shares of stock in the club at $100 a share over
a 10-year period.
</P>
<P>
   Membership dues range from $12 to $22 per month, depending on
how many shares of stock the member owns. The towing cost for
individual flights starts at $10.
</P>
<P>
   Neophytes who just want a taste of gliding can take a guest ride
that lasts 20 to 30 minutes for a one-time charge of $45 to $55.
</P>
<P>
   Glider pilots seem eternally youthful. Francis Bundy, who turns
90 in September, was an instructor at the club until late last year
when he suffered some minor health setbacks. In his 32 years of
soaring, he has flown more than 8,000 flights.
</P>
<P>
   Bundy, a physicist by training and a researcher for General
Electric who helped develop the first artificial diamonds, says he
still enjoys ``winning over gravity.''
</P>
<P>
   As a teen-ager, Bundy and his father were inspired to build
their own glider after watching hawks circling on the thermals near
their Westerville home in the 1920s.
</P>
<P>
   They built their own glider frame and tested it ``but then the
Great Crash of 1929 came and we couldn't afford to buy the fabric
and the rope,'' Bundy said. He had to wait another 23 years, until
after his education and his service in the war, to realize his
dream of soaring. He was 42 at the time.
</P>
<P>
   Bundy is among a group of about 20 retirees in the club who
gather at the Der Dutchman Restaurant in Waynesville every
Wednesday morning to eat breakfast, sip coffee and trade soaring
stories before heading over to the gliderport.
</P>
<P>
   Club members of all ages are divided over whether to keep the
organization small and elite or to grow it with new members.
</P>
<P>
   John Biernacki, 77, is among those members who feel strongly
that the sport must be popularized to survive against the
juggernaut of commercial and private plane aviation.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 600,000 or so licensed pilots in the country, only 15,000
are glider pilots. The Caesar Creek club alone accounts for about
150 of them.
</P>
<P>
   Expanding club membership and increasing public interest in the
sport ``means growing our own ability to participate,'' Biernacki
said. ``Right now we're being squeezed by the (expansion of the)
Cincinnati airport.''
</P>
<P>
   Club members can't fly much south of the gliderport without
violating the airport's airspace.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike European countries, where soaring is thriving, America
seems to be turning away from the source of its aviation roots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's almost becoming like a forgotten art,'' Statt said.
``It's a lot like sailing is to boating. You have to know how to
work the wind.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
