<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   GLIDERS _ Five minutes after takeoff, when we reach 3,000 feet
in a pristine sky, glider pilot Rich Carraway releases the line
from the tow plane and banks our two-seater sailplane gently to the
north _ free, as the poet said, of the surly bonds of earth.
Nothing but the wind whispering now around our clear plastic
canopy. We're in a peaceful bubble floating over a checkerboard of
Warren County farms and forests just a few miles east of Caesar
Creek Lake. Even for a shameless wuss like myself, who has a
paralyzing fear of heights, my 20-minute ride as a guest passenger
with the Caesar Creek Soaring Club was as gentle and agreeable as
many of the club's 200-plus members. (Dayton Daily News). 27. WITH
PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   HOWARD-FINSTER _ SUMMERVILLE, Ga. _ Word was out that the Rev.
Howard Finster, the godfather of saving souls, the hardest working
man in the folk art business, had been seriously sick. So the
faithful flocked to Paradise Garden, his wild 3-acre folk version
of the Garden of Eden, during last month's Howard Finster Fest, a
show and sale that offered a thoroughly mixed bag of 60 artists but
only one Howard. With the ailing 83-year-old artist recovering from
double pneumonia and congestive heart failure and battling
diabetes, many visitors worried it might be the last chance to see
Finster, get his autograph, hear one of his classic sermonettes.
And, some feared, it might be the final opportunity to visit
Paradise. (Pousner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 77. WITH PHOTOS
and LAYOUTS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   GEHRY-MUSICPROJECT _ SEATTLE _ Architect of the hour Frank Gehry
has projects all over the world. His latest since Bilbao is
something called Experience the Music project in Seattle, paid for
by Microsoft millionaire Paul Allen. Main story will wrap up
history and a review of the building. (Fox, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 36. MOVED.
</P>
