<HEADER>
A3820 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MASS-ASBESTOS-NYT &LR;      06-24 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-ASBESTOS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA TO ASSESS IF CONTAMINATED SPORTS FIELD IMPERILS HEALTH 
</HEADLINE>
   By ADRIANNE APPEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CAMBRIDGE, Mass. _ The Environmental Protection Agency is
investigating whether the contamination of a children's athletic
field in a bustling neighborhood on the outskirts of this city
poses an immediate health risk.
</P>
<P>
   The agency also plans to look into the risks of the
contamination at a nearby 27-acre site where W.R. Grace and Co.
employs 350 people at the headquarters of its construction products
division.
</P>
<P>
   More than two years ago, a consultant for a neighborhood
association here found concentrations of asbestos 6 inches or more
below the surface of the grassy athletic field. But athletic teams,
including a Little League squad sponsored by W.R. Grace, have
continued to play soccer and baseball on the field, which abuts a
bicycle path and a heavily traveled subway stop.
</P>
<P>
   City officials in Cambridge said they had allowed people to use
the field because tests found only trace amounts of asbestos. There
was no risk to health, they said, because the asbestos was buried
beneath a layer of topsoil.
</P>
<P>
   Grace, a maker of specialty chemicals and building materials,
has acknowledged that its property a few feet from the field is
contaminated with asbestos, chemicals and heavy metals. Grace says
the materials pose no danger, but it announced this month that it
was shelving plans to build a hotel and office complex on the site.
Grace said it would cooperate with federal and local efforts to
remove the pollutants.
</P>
<P>
   The land has a lengthy industrial history. It was owned for a
time by a company that was trying to develop a new type of brake
lining made with asbestos. That company was bought 46 years ago by
Grace, which then used the site for corporate offices, chemical
manufacturing and a laboratory that tested fireproofing materials
containing asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Ellen Stanton, a senior EPA official in New England, said
the agency would assess the level of pollution on the field and the
Grace property over the next few months to determine if there was
``an immediate threat to human health.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials say they think the contamination of the playing
field dates from the late 1970s, when the Massachusetts Bay
Transportation Authority extended a subway line through the Grace
property.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge allowed the transit authority to store equipment and
some contaminated soil, called ``acid sludge,'' on the playing
field, according to Robert Healy, Cambridge city manager, who was
deputy city manager and acting director of public health at the
time of the project.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, the transportation authority agreed to rebuild the
field using soil excavated during the subway project, Healy said.
He said it was known at the time that the dirt was laced with
chemicals and heavy metals. The authority, Healy said, agreed to
clean it to safe levels.
</P>
<P>
   City officials said they saw no reason at the time to demand
that the soil be checked for asbestos contamination. ``You don't
usually look for it unless it's suspected of being disposed,'' said
Stanton of the EPA. The waste was covered with 6 inches of topsoil,
which was planted with grass.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about the athletic field surfaced in the mid-1980s,
when Grace proposed building a hotel and office complex on its
property, stirring local opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Members of a neighborhood association said former Grace
employees had told them that the nearby offices had been used for
asbestos testing.
</P>
<P>
   Many in the neighborhood feared that construction would stir up
clouds of asbestos and other contaminants, and demanded testing of
both the Grace property and the field.
</P>
<P>
   Grace has said that its tests of the property found asbestos at
varying depths. The levels of asbestos in the samples varied, and
in one sample making up 12 percent of the soil's weight, Grace
said. The EPA considers a concentration of 1 percent to be a
potential threat.
</P>
<P>
   A consultant hired by the neighborhood group found patches of
asbestos 6 inches or more beneath the athletic field with
concentrations as much as 11 percent. The City of Cambridge's test
detected only trace amounts at the field but did find hazardous
levels of chemicals and heavy metals like lead and copper.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Lipson, Cambridge's director of public health, said the
findings created a dilemma for the city. Any effort to clean the
soil of the chemicals and heavy metals would stir up the asbestos,
which, Lipson said, does not threaten public health because it is
buried.
</P>
<P>
   William Corcoran, a spokesman for Grace, said the asbestos on
its property probably came from demolition of the several buildings
at the site that had asbestos insulation. ``There could have been
testing that went on,'' Corcoran said, referring to the laboratory
work at the site. ``But more likely it's from our buildings or
renovations.''
</P>
<P>
   Grace acknowledged to state officials two years ago that it had
occasionally tested asbestos products at the site in the 1960s and
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   Corcoran said the asbestos on the Grace property in Cambridge
posed no danger because it was covered by grass, plants or
pavement.
</P>
<P>
   And several company documents made public as a result of
environmental lawsuits note that vermiculite, a mineral that
contains asbestos, was sent to the ``Cambridge quality assurance
laboratory'' for analysis.
</P>
<P>
   Stanton said the EPA inquiry was part of a nationwide
examination of Grace's handling of asbestos, an ingredient of
fireproofing products it sold in the United States from the early
1960s until the mid-1980s.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's review of W.R. Grace operations was prompted by
disclosures late last year that a large number of company employees
had died of respiratory illnesses characteristic of exposure to
asbestos.
</P>
<P>
   Grace made insulation and other building products from
vermiculite, a mineral that often contains asbestos. The EPA is
investigating the illnesses and deaths of Grace workers who handled
vermiculite in mines and factories around the country. Asbestos is
known to cause lung and other cancers, and is considered dangerous
when airborne.
</P>
<P>
   Grace's decision to drop the hotel project has not assuaged the
fears in the neighborhood about the safety of the athletic field.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge officials have told Grace and the transit authority
that they may be held responsible for the cost of cleaning up the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big question is, why was a playing field used as a staging
area for toxic waste?'' said Joe Joseph, one of the organizers of
the group opposing the project.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1327EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0088 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 13:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3821 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-HONDATOWN0625-COX     06-24 1549
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HONDATOWN0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Big changes in small town, USA
 &HT;    By Marlon Manuel
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LINCOLN, Ala. _ Sharon Denson moved away from the smokestacks of
Birmingham and came here for peace and tranquillity. ``Small Town,
USA,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   No one locked their doors. For generations, local fortunes clung
to bales of cotton and a tiny railroad depot. Nearby Logan Martin
Lake made for good bass fishing and a serene view.
</P>
<P>
   By the time her husband retired from a nearby fire department,
Denson wanted to have a business established in the town of 4,000.
</P>
<P>
   She drew $12,600 from an equity line on her house nearly two
years ago to rent space and buy supplies at the vacant Dairyland
burger joint. The white brick building sits near the intersection
of U.S. 78 and Ala. 77 _ a couple of two-lane highways.
</P>
<P>
   At lunch, customers take up six orange vinyl chairs at the
counter and chow down on the $4.89 specials _ country-fried steak,
three vegetables, a drink and corn bread. Regulars wish she'd serve
fried green tomatoes more often. In her red NASCAR apron, Denson
greets almost everyone by name.
</P>
<P>
   Like many places in the rural South, jobs have been the only
thing missing from the country utopia. If they can find it, people
revel in $7-an-hour pay. The county's median household income is
$25,777 a year _ $1,580 less than the state average, according to
the U.S. Census.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, economic salvation rolled into town with front-wheel
drive and seating for seven. Auto giant Honda committed $440
million to turn farmland into a 1.7 million-square-foot factory to
build its Odyssey minivan, one of the hottest sellers in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Honda has pushed up its timetable and plans to start production
late next year. The company has received 17,000 applications for
1,500 jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Denson's parking lot marquee last May beckoned, ``HONDA THE
LINCOLN CAFE WELCOMES YOU.'' Denson's giddy customers talked about
getting $20-an-hour jobs with Honda.
</P>
<P>
   Today, however, the town is at a crossroads. Denson and others
are caught at the intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Progress, Lincoln is learning, comes with a bulldozer. In the
end, the urbanization of the small-town South costs more than
money. It can turn lifestyles upside down.
</P>
<P>
   A new bridge over a creek in town will take more than a year to
build, diverting locals from their accustomed paths.
</P>
<P>
   Farm property closer to the factory will be eaten up if a new
railroad line Honda wants installed is built to supplement the
existing one.
</P>
<P>
   The sign of the times has a decidedly sharper tongue more than a
year later. Denson's marquee now reads: THE STATE SAID 1000 FOR
CAFE WHAT DO U THINK!!
</P>
<P>
   To widen U.S. 78, the Lincoln Cafe will be demolished. The state
has offered Denson $1,000 for her business, which includes seven
tables, 24 chairs, a freezer, industrial range and a 6-foot-long
oak butcher block.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing I asked for was what I put into it,'' said
Denson, 46, a former assistant manager at Shoney's.
</P>
<P>
   Her landlord _ Mayor Lew Watson _ offered to move Denson to a
new location. But she balked at Watson's offer and the state buyout
because she wants to remain at the hub of town.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sharon Denson's actions are uncalled for,'' said Watson, mayor
for more than 20 years and up for re-election this fall. ``If she's
got a problem she can present her case to 12 men in a jury.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the chief landowners in town, Watson said he has had no
control over what state transportation officials have offered. A
real estate appraiser by trade, Watson figures land is worth
$82,000 an acre now. It was going for about $36,000 an acre or less
before Honda came.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all heard stories of big money to be paid when businesses
were relocated,'' Watson said. ``But I haven't heard of anybody
offered really big money.''
</P>
<P>
   Honda wants to be a good neighbor. After ground-breaking in
April, the company invited Lincoln residents to a picnic at the
Talladega Motor Speedway 15 minutes away. Honda served ribs and
chicken and put on a fireworks display.
</P>
<P>
   While much of the local criticism has been leveled at government
officials, some bile has spilled onto Honda, which plans to make
120,000 Odysseys in Lincoln by 2002.
</P>
<P>
   ``We understand that there is some inconvenience in the initial
stages, some interruption,'' said Jeffrey Smith, spokesman for
American Honda Motor Co. Inc. ``But we think the coincident
economic development will be a tide that lifts all boats in the
Lincoln area.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same intersection as the cafe, the Lincoln Pharmacy, a
gas station and Allred's garage also will be vanquished for the
wider highway. Down the road, a boat upholsterer needs to move. A
marina next to another expanding road is on the verge of closing
because its land will be eaten up. Same thing with a 7-year-old
bait and tackle shop that closed last July and sits idle with
$12,000 of goods inside.
</P>
<P>
   Now there are rumors Winn-Dixie is coming. Wal-Mart, too. Even
the town's first traffic light.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to be a metropolis,'' said Jeff Barnes, meat
manager at Lincoln's lone grocery store. ``It's not going to be a
small town anymore.'' Ask little Smyrna, Tenn., pumped up in the
1980s by Nissan. Once a sleepy Southern burg of 10,000 people
before the car factory, the town now has twice as many people and
tons more shops. Just outside Nashville, Smyrna was on a quick
growth path even before Nissan came to town. When industry cranked
up, it lopped off Smyrna's small-town roots.
</P>
<P>
   Nissan's pay nearly tripled the minimum wage and helped kill
cattle farming in Rutherford County. Randall Matlock, former
Rutherford County finance director, said growth has even spilled 20
miles southeast to Murfreesboro, where he's a CPA today.
</P>
<P>
   No question, Matlock said, the small-town feel has ``gone by the
wayside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Murfreesboro used to be what we would call a 15-minute town,
where you could get from one side to the other in 15 minutes,'' he
said. ``It takes us a good half-hour to get across it now. That
tells us right there we're right smack dab in the middle of being
an urban community. Smyrna itself, you could get anywhere in five
minutes back in those days before Nissan came in. Now with Nissan
being there, it's the true 15-minute town.''
</P>
<P>
   For the moment, Lincoln is a five-minute town.
</P>
<P>
   At Ron's BP, you can buy barbecue and crickets for a fishing
trip then drive to lunch at the cafe _ passing the coin laundry,
Dollar General Store, Town Hall and the post office all before a
country song ends on the radio.
</P>
<P>
   But that's disappearing in a New York minute.
</P>
<P>
   If dump trucks thundering down the highway don't tell you that,
the ominous right-of-way stakes with fluttering pink ribbons
should. Poking from the dirt in front of the Lincoln Cafe is a
stake that shows where the shoulder of a beefed-up U.S. 78 will
extend _ through the back door of the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Helen Hare, cook at the Lincoln Cafe, came here last year to
escape a boom in small-town Pell City 10 miles from Lincoln. A
month after Hare arrived, Honda announced it was coming, too. Now
Hare faces the prospect of filing for unemployment if Denson can't
find a new place.
</P>
<P>
   One of 13 brothers and sisters, Hare and her husband bought five
acres in Lincoln ``to keep people from moving in on us.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Five acres ain't all that big,'' Hare said between stirring
panfuls of brown gravy. ``You can still hear the neighbors
hollering at each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But Lincoln's expansion doesn't bother everybody. Ron Stickland
has run the Lincoln Pharmacy for two years. He moved from Gadsden,
where a good many workers let go by the Goodyear plant there figure
to be in the running for Honda's new jobs.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's exciting,'' said Strickland, a 30-year-old Auburn grad.
``It's going to be a busier place.''
</P>
<P>
   Strickland hasn't had an offer yet from the state Transportation
Department but his landlord is already building him a new place
next to the town's only supermarket back away from the highway.
He'll be moved by August.
</P>
<P>
   ``It'll be cleaner, nicer,'' Strickland said. Two buildings down
from the cafe, John Allred has run a garage since 1972. He hasn't
settled with the state yet, and he's not sure what he'll do _ but
he knows he's not going to buy another spot. ``You can't buy
property here,'' he said. ``It's too high.''
</P>
<P>
   Before excusing himself to stick his head under the hood of a
car, the 56-year-old mechanic lamented the changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be good to a certain extent,'' Allred said.
``But a city the size of Lincoln can't stand the growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Back in the cafe, at one end of the white Formica counter,
Denson has placed a 5-gallon jug and written in black marker,
``Help the state pay me for my business.'' Ones and fives line the
bottom of the clear bucket.
</P>
<P>
   Her husband has talked about opening an auto lot. ``I know how
to sell food,'' Denson said decidedly. ``I'm not selling cars.''
</P>
<P>
   Her cafe supplier jokes that she should buy 20 cases of napkins
with the $1,000 offered by the state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I order things every two weeks and I'm scared to now because I
don't know how long I'll be here,'' Denson said. ``It's just wait
and see.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
