<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 13:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3828 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-BESTWICK-RETIRES0625-     06-24 0826
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BESTWICK-RETIRES0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bestwick's specialty is nurturing successes
 &HT;    By Chip Towers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ It's half past six on a Monday evening and Dick
Bestwick is still in his office inside the University of Georgia's
McWhorter Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In itself, that would not seem so unusual. But, in this case,
Bestwick is just 10 days shy of retirement. If there ever was a
time to get to work late and leave early, this would be it.
</P>
<P>
   But leaving early never has been Bestwick's style. This, after
all, is a man who will have worked full time almost until his 70th
birthday, which is in August. Besides, there's still a lot of work
to be done. It's no small task to box up a half-century's worth of
memories.
</P>
<P>
   June 30th, Bestwick will end what has been a 52-year journey
within college athletics. It began when he left his hometown of
Grove City, Pa., to attend North Carolina on a football scholarship
in 1948, and it will end here in Athens as Georgia's senior
associate athletics director.
</P>
<P>
   In between were 16 stops as a coach or athletics administrator
and enough highs and lows to make a numerous other
responsibilities; he oversaw football, basketball and baseball and
was the point man on most of Vince Dooley's major hires. But the
core of his work was in tutoring student-athletes in successful
life strategies, something he continued long after giving up the
title of associate AD for academic and athletic standards.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know of no one more committed to serving the student-athlete
than Dick,'' Dooley said. ``When necessary, he pulls no punches in
counseling them when he feels they can do better. . . . He will be
sorely missed.''
</P>
<P>
   The son of a Pennsylvania millworker, Bestwick has always had a
soft spot for the underdog. Like any coach, he took pleasure in
seeing student-athletes achieve athletic greatness. But he took
even more in seeing the little-known reserve with poor academic
credentials earn his degree and land a good job after graduation.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta native Gene Toodle, who attended Georgia on a football
scholarship from 1993-97, is one of Bestwick's success stories.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's because of him I have everything I have,'' Toodle said.
``He believed in me when I didn't believe in myself. There was a
point in my athletic career that I was close to giving up. But
Coach Bestwick encouraged me to stick with it and excel at other
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Toodle ended up starting at linebacker his senior year in 1996
and was named a permanent team captain. He graduated in 1997 with a
degree in consumer science and now owns an office-supply business
in Norcross.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cringe when I think of how close I was to quitting,'' Toodle
said. ``Every college deserves a person like Coach Bestwick.
Georgia's going to miss him; I already do.''
</P>
<P>
   Other than Bestick's wife of 50 years, Phyllis, no one knows
Bestwick better than Dave Braine. The Georgia Tech AD, 12 years
Bestwick's junior, grew up next door to him in Grove City, Pa.
</P>
<P>
   Bestwick used to baby-sit Braine _ even changed his diapers _
and coached Braine all four years at Grove City High.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the part of my life he pin virtually every role he has
filled with the exception of the brief period he spent as athletics
director at South Carolina. It lasted less than two years and
resulted in him being hospitalized with stress-related health
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to solve all the problems at once, and there were
a lot of problems,'' Bestwick said. ``The president (Dr. Jim
Holderman) suggested that I see a physician and get something to
help me sleep. The next thing I know I'm taking 16 pills a day. A
short time later, I had lost 40 pounds, had internal bleeding and
was in the hospital for 10 days.''
</P>
<P>
   Bestwick ``asked to be relieved'' of his AD duties and served
South Carolina as system administrator for athletics for a short
while before Dooley lured him back to Georgia in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Bestwick has never really settled down, but he has spent more
time in the state of Georgia, 22 years, than he has anywhere else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been (at UGA) the longest of any the places I've worked,
and Georgia Tech the second-longest,'' Bestwick said, ``Both of
them have been blessings. My wife and family loved Atlanta, and we
love it here. I may be the only guy in Georgia who loves both
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   As for retirement, Bestwick enters into it grudgingly. He plans
to write a book based on the hundreds of letters he has received
from former players over the years, and he wants to play a lot of
golf and travel. But he believes he still has something to offer
college athletics and would consider consulting or part-time work.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some misgivings about (retirement) but my wife probably
has more,'' he said. ``I still enjoy young people as much as I ever
did. It's been a fascinating ride, very interesting.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
