   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs on
Sunday, June 24, and thereafter. For questions about stories,
contact Gerri Hoppe at the Daily News, (818) 713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   FARMERS-MARKETS (Los Angeles) _ Organic farmer Betty Kennedy has
watched with anger how corporate growers have infiltrated local
farmers markets in recent years. ``We can't compete with the big
rigs that roll into some of these markets and try to come across as
small farmers,'' said Kennedy. With farmers markets cropping up in
one community after another, state officials promise this year will
be different, and they're cracking down on violators. By Dominic
Berbeo and Orith Goldberg. (Will move in the ``a'' national and
``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   HILLARY-STARS (Los Angeles) _ The stars are coming out for
Hillary. The most recent Federal Elections Commission data on
campaign contributions show that Hillary Rodham Clinton, Democratic
candidate for a New York senate seat, has hijacked the celebrity
spotlight from Al Gore, her party's presidential candidate, and his
Republican challenger, George W. Bush. By Bill Hillburg. (Will move
in the ``a'' national and ``n'' California state news files.)
</P>
<P>
   LAUSD-REFORM (Los Angeles) _ On the eve of their departure from
Los Angeles Unified School District, interim Superintendend Ramon
Cortines and Chief Operating Officer Howard Miller detail their
accomplishments and unfulfilled promises when they were hired six
months ago. By David Baker. (Will move in the ``n'' California
state news file.)
</P>
