<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 14:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3867 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-HILLARY-STARS-1stLd-2     06-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-STARS-1stLd-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY LEADING IN STAR-BUCKS RACE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY BILL HILLBURG 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The stars are coming out for Hillary.
</P>
<P>
   The most recent Federal Election Commission data on campaign
contributions show that Hillary Rodham Clinton, Democratic
candidate to represent New York in the U.S. Senate, has hijacked
the celebrity spotlight from Al Gore, her party's presidential
candidate, and his Republican challenger, George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   The who's who of Tinseltown that backed President Clinton in
1992 and 1996 now appears to be allied with his better half. Name
your medium and most of its notables have bought into Hillary
Clinton's campaign, which has so far raked in $12.8 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hollywood people tend to attach themselves to somebody they
can identify with,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director of the
Center for Responsive Politics, a Washington watchdog group
specializing in campaign finance. ``They (the president and first
lady) just seem to connect with Hollywood types.''
</P>
<P>
   Her contributors include movie power couple Tom Cruise and
Nicole Kidman, former ``Wonder Woman'' star Lynda Carter, veteran
actor Paul Newman and rap artist Sean ``Puffy'' Combs.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's star power swamped her former foe, New York Mayor Rudy
Giuliani, who nevertheless bested her in fund raising with a total
of $19.3 million. But his very short star list included Charlton
Heston, currently the Moses of the National Rifle Association, and
``Walker, Texas Ranger'' actor Chuck Norris.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani dropped out of the race last month due to health
problems, he offered to return contributions and also asked that
donors shift their dollars to his successor, Rep. Rick Lazio,
R-N.Y. The most recent FEC records - which date to May 20 - do not
yet reflect the change in the GOP's New York Senate campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Hillary Clinton's galaxy of backers also outshines Gore, whose
limited array of stars includes Harrison Ford, who set the screen
standard for presidential heroics in ``Air Force One,'' as well as
Tom Hanks and Nicholas Cage.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's lineup is positively anemic: Pat Boone, the clean-cut
crooner, and Edward Kerr, a regular on TV's long-canceled
``SeaQuest.'' The actor who was arguably Bush's best-known
Hollywood donor, 1940s and '50s beefcake star Victor Mature, died
in August at age 86.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Hollywood crowd in general has always been more Democratic
than Republican,'' Makinson said. ``That's especially true for
actors and actresses. The moguls, on the other hand, vote their
business interests and support candidates or parties that back
their issues.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter who is celebrating on election night, Disney Chairman
Michael Eisner will likely be on the invitation list. Eisner has
covered all of his presidential bases, giving $1,000 each to Bush,
Gore and former candidates John McCain, Bill Bradley and Orrin
Hatch.
</P>
<P>
   Eisner's wife, Jane, whose FEC filing forms list her as a
Burbank homemaker and president of the couple's charitable Eisner
Foundation, also gave $1,000 each to Bush, McCain, Gore and
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Disney is a nonpartisan company. We support the democratic
process,'' Eisner said in a recent interview.
</P>
<P>
   The company also knows who its friends are, as evidenced by
Eisner's donation to Hatch, whose presidential campaign was among
the shortest of the GOP contenders.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Hatch, chairman of the Senate Judiciary Committee,
sponsored a bill that gave Disney a 20-year extension on its
treasured copyrights for Mickey Mouse, Pluto and Goofy. Hatch is
now the Senate's point man on efforts to stem piracy of
intellectual properties on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Bipartisan giving is also the rule for the Walt Disney
Productions Employees Political Action Committee, which has spread
$90,741 among Republicans and Democrats. The same goes for PACs run
by Universal Studios ($93,750) and the Motion Picture Association
of America ($51,286), Hollywood's premiere lobbying group.
</P>
<P>
   But some moguls have a partisan record. DreamWorks SKG partners
Steven Spielberg, Jeffrey Katzenberg and David Geffen gave all of
their individual and corporate contributions, totaling more than
$600,000, to Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Stars of the big screen greatly outnumber TV types on the
contributor rolls, with some notable exceptions. Ted Danson, one of
the tube's biggest spenders, chipped in $5,000 for Hillary Clinton.
Jerry Seinfeld gave $1,000 each to Bradley and Gore. Regis Philbin
also backed Bradley's failed effort. Kathie Lee Gifford, Philbin's
soon-to-depart morning co-host, supported Elizabeth Dole, an early
GOP presidential dropout.
</P>
<P>
   Within the ranks of screen and TV stars, Makinson noted that,
broadly speaking, ``gun-toting heroes like John Wayne have tended
to vote Republican. The rest vote Democratic.''
</P>
<P>
   But there are exceptions. Actor Warren Beatty, who briefly toyed
with the idea of making the quantum leap from fictional Sen. Jay W.
Bullworth to the White House, cast his lot with Green Party
candidate Ralph Nader.
</P>
<P>
   Also responding to a different drummer are singer Barry Manilow
and actor Christian Slater, who have contributed to the campaign of
Natural Law Party candidate John Hagelin.
</P>
<P>
   The local candidate getting the most buzz from Hollywood is
state Sen. Adam Schiff, D-Pasadena, who is locked in a high-stakes,
high-dollar House race with incumbent Rep. James Rogan, R-Pasadena.
</P>
<P>
   Schiff's take includes $1,000 each from DreamWorks' Spielberg,
Katzenberg and Geffen, and another grand from
singer-actress-director Barbra Streisand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't quite understand why there's so much star support for
Mr. Schiff,'' said Rogan's campaign manager, Jason Roe. ``(Rogan's)
been in their corner on every issue including copyright protections
and runaway production as a member of the House Judiciary
Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   Roe cites another Rogan role on the Judiciary panel as the cause
of his Hollywood problem - Rogan's highly visible position as a
leading prosecutor in last year's move to impeach Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an impeachment thing,'' Roe said. ``We didn't see this
kind of support for an opponent in 1998 when the congressman
defeated Barry Gordon, a former president of the Screen Actors
Guild.''
</P>
<P>
   The Schiff campaign had no comment.
</P>
<P>
   A notable no-show on Schiff's star-laden list is actor Steven
Hill, who plays Manhattan District Attorney Adam Schiff on NBC-TV's
``Law and Order.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogan remains far out in front of Schiff in the fund-raising
derby, having amassed $3.8 million to the challenger's $1.9
million. But the closest thing to a star on Rogan's long list of
contributors is William Hurt. Alas, Rogan's Hurt, a $1,000 donor,
is a successful Los Angeles investment banker and not the
heartthrob of the film ``Broadcast News.''
</P>
<P>
   Roe said that in recent weeks Rogan picked up a bit of star
backing, getting $1,000 from director Oliver Stone and winning $200
of game-show star Ben Stein's money. However, neither of those
contributions has yet appeared on reports filed with the FEC.
</P>
<P>
   (SECOND TAKE FOLLOWS)
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Howard Berman, D-Mission Hills, who has also worked to
protect Hollywood's output from copyright pirates, is backed by
three Oscar winners: actors Richard Dreyfuss and Michael Douglas
and director Spielberg.
</P>
<P>
   Fellow San Fernando Valley Democrat Brad Sherman, D-Woodland
Hills, has a short star list featuring actress Catherine Bach. The
Sherman Oaks resident made abbreviated cutoffs famous during her
stint as Daisy Duke on the 1970s TV series ``The Dukes of Hazard.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, former Eagles rocker Don Henley is the most
politically active music maker in Campaign 2000. He has shelled out
$17,500 to a variety of candidates, including Gore, Hillary
Clinton, Schiff and Rep. Lois Capps, D-Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   Hollywood's own man in the White House has so far kept his
checkbook shut. Actor Martin Sheen, who plays President Josiah
Bartlett on NBC's ``The West Wing,'' has made no contributions to
real-life politicians during the latest reporting period, according
to FEC records.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians and their star contributors
</P>
<P>
