<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 14:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3873 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-FARMERS-MARKETS-LADN     06-24 1046
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FARMERS-MARKETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIALS CRACK DOWN ON FARMERS MARKET ABUSERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ORITH GOLDBERG AND DOMINIC BERBEO 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Organic farmer Betty Kennedy has watched with
anger how corporate growers have infiltrated local farmers markets
in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't compete with the big rigs that roll into some of
these markets and try to come across as small farmers,'' said
Kennedy, co-owner of the Kennedys With Harvest Pride farm in
Fresno. ``It's not fair - and it shouldn't be that way.''
</P>
<P>
   With farmers markets popping up in one community after another,
state officials promise this summer will be different.
</P>
<P>
   A newly formed team of inspectors is hitting farmers markets to
make sure big-time farmers stay out and that produce is
California-grown by small growers. They also will look for
entrepreneurs trying to make a fast buck with store-bought produce.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're interested in having family-owned small farms at the
market,'' said Marion Kalb, market development specialist for the
Southland Farmers Market Association, which includes 60 markets in
the Los Angeles area. ``That's the whole idea of the market: to
provide an alternative to the commercial markets.''
</P>
<P>
   Lax enforcement in previous years has led to abuse, which
customers say they've noticed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The large produce growers use so much pesticide,'' said Debbie
Brier, a Northridge resident who was visiting the market after work
and picking out fresh produce. Her bags already were laden with
green vegetables. ``Here you feel like you're buying real food.
Plus, you get to try free samples.''
</P>
<P>
   Under rules enacted more than two decades ago, growers who sell
at state Certified Farmers Markets are exempt from state
regulations that apply to other food vendors. This waiver makes it
economical for them to do business.
</P>
<P>
   They may sell fruit and vegetables too small to be sold in
stores, need not package their products individually and may get
them to market any way they can. Without such exemptions, farmers
say, they couldn't make enough profit to stay in business.
</P>
<P>
   But in return, farmers promise to sell only food grown in
California and to staff the stalls themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Keeping the markets honest, however, has largely failed for lack
of money.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because the funding wasn't enough, the state could only allow
so much time to go toward enforcement,'' said Janice Price, program
supervisor overseeing farmers markets for the CDFA.
</P>
<P>
   In January, the Legislature passed a bill that now requires
every producer to pay a 60-cent-a-day fee to support inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The passage of Assembly Bill 593, authored by Virginia
Strom-Martin, D-Santa Rosa, is expected to provide $250,000 to
$350,000 for inspectors to visit the markets and ensure that
vendors are properly certified.
</P>
<P>
   ``People would go to Costco and buy fruits and sell them as
fresh from the farm,'' said Strom-Martin's chief of staff, Robyn
Boyer-Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   The 60-cent fee can either be absorbed by market operators or
passed on to their vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The fee is expected to fund a full-time supervisor and support
staffers who will provide direction, training and oversight of the
inspections conducted throughout the 58 counties offering farmers
markets. The 60-cent fee will not lead to more inspections in each
county, but the state's full-time supervisor will be expected to
follow up on investigations and provide better oversight for the
inspection programs, said Los Angeles County deputy agricultural
commissioner David Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles County, about 35 inspectors check each farmers
market at least twice a year.
</P>
<P>
   Inspectors issue more than 100 violations each year, according
to Kruger.
</P>
<P>
   Most often, abusers supplement their produce with store-bought
produce, a problem that can be difficult to spot, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The inspection process is made more difficult when producers
have multiple markets in multiple counties.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we suspect abuse in another county, I, as a county
employee, would call my peer in the adjoining county and ask for
assistance,'' Kruger said. ``But there is no guarantee it will be
timely or thorough.''
</P>
<P>
   Abusers may be fined and have their privilege to sell suspended
or revoked.
</P>
<P>
   Kalb said market operators have a responsibility to make sure
their vendors are properly certified and that their certificates
are placed at the point of sale.
</P>
<P>
   Those seeking certification are required to fill out an
application and list where they are growing their product.
Investigators go to the location where the foods are grown to
ensure that potential vendors are growing what they intend to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to get it done within a week,'' said deputy
agricultural commissioner Dennis Vinopal.
</P>
<P>
   Vendors who break the rules could lose permission to sell and be
fined up to $1,000, Vinopal said.
</P>
<P>
   At the newly opened farmers market at the Westfield Shoppingtown
Promenade, sellers said they don't mind the fee because it ensures
they have a place to sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good for everybody because then we will all be on the
same page,'' said 22-year-old Jeff Watkins, who has sold produce
and passion fruit at farmers markets for the past year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   Volumes of business people from nearby businesses packed the
market, brightening the day for Frankie Peterson, a vendor who
sells decorated dishes and chenille-decorated clothes at both the
Promenade and the Northridge Fashion Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so busy,'' he said. ``There were a lot of people during
the lunch break, which was really, really nice.''
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Valley, farmers markets continue to draw droves
of people seeking quality food at reasonable costs.
</P>
<P>
   The Northridge Farmers Market and Festival, in its second year,
draws large crowds during its hours from 5 p.m. to 9 p.m. in the
parking lot of the Northridge Fashion Center.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hoover, a carpenter from Northridge, says he can find a
better selection of fresh food there at good prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can actually talk to the people who grew the food,'' said
Hoover, 29, after purchasing dried fruit, sprouts and greens from a
stand. ``I try to eat all organic and try different things.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
