u p BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      06-24 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HELP FOR ARKANSAS FARMERS; BUSH IN KENTUCKY; SKEPTICISM IN INDIANA;
GOP BICKERING IN WASHINGTON
</HEADLINE>
  By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ARKANSAS: FARMERS GET HELP, AND BACK THE HELPER  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Arkansas' 4th Congressional District, covering the bottom third
of the state, was solidly Democratic until 1992. Then along came a
conservative Republican named Jay Dickey, and since then the
district has been solidly Dickey.
</P>
<P>
   Democrats have failed three times to come up with a challenger
strong enough to take him, in good part because he is a master
mender of fences back home, able to get votes from Democrats and
Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Democrats refuse to give up, and this year, with
Republicans holding only a six-seat edge in Congress, Democratic
leaders decided to go after Dickey, with the party nominating a
popular, well-financed state senator, Mike Ross, to take him on.
The Democratic leaders figured they had Dickey beaten after he
alienated the Arkansas Black Farmers and Agriculturalists
Association, a major political force in the district. One poll put
Ross ahead by 2 points.
</P>
<P>
   The farmers association had asked Dickey to get Congress
involved in settling a lawsuit in which association members claimed
the Agriculture Department had discriminated against them. He
replied that it would be next to impossible to rally any Republican
support for the association because it had signaled its intent to
endorse a Democrat in the district this year.
</P>
<P>
   To some Dickey detractors, that smacked of political extortion,
and they talked for a while of filing an ethics complaint. In the
meantime, Dickey reopened a dialogue with the association and began
pressuring federal farm officials to speed the flow of loans to its
members.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, the association threw its support to Dickey,
saying: ``Jay Dickey has not just talked about supporting
African-Americans and other minorities, he has done it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ross' take on that: ``It's unfortunate we have the kind of
congressman who has demanded political endorsements and campaign
contributions before he will help.''
</P>
<P>
   KENTUCKY: BUSH NOT SO WELCOME IN BATTLEGROUND STATE
</P>
<P>
   Kentucky is a battleground state this election year, and Gov.
Paul E. Patton, a Democrat, is worried. And irked.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas keeps showing up, raising money for
himself and the Kentucky and national Republican parties and
campaigning for himself and state and congressional Republican
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush says he intends to carry Kentucky. He is intent on helping
Kentucky Republicans win three hotly contested congressional races.
</P>
<P>
   And he is trying to help Republicans maintain their 20-18
majority in the Kentucky state Senate, a crucial majority because
going into next year's redistricting process, Patton will still be
sitting in the governor's chair, and Democrats almost certainly
will still be in control of the State House.
</P>
<P>
   So last weekend when Bush showed up in Kentucky for the third
time in five weeks _ he raised some $1.7 million while talking up
himself and other Republicans _ Patton groused ``enough already''
and accused him of using ``strong-arm tactics'' to wring money and
votes out of Kentuckians.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is unprecedented for a presidential candidate to
participate this way,'' Patton said. ``It just blows my mind.''
</P>
<P>
   The state Republican chairwoman, Ellen Williams, laughed and
called Patton's remarks ``wacky sour grapes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush was more pointed, sending the governor this message: ``I'm
coming. Get used to it. I'm going to come to your state as many
times as I feel like coming _ and win the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   INDIANA: GAS-TAX SUSPENSION AROUSES SKEPTICISM  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While many state and federal officials and investigators wring
their hands and wonder what to do about surging gas prices, Gov.
Frank O'Bannon of Indiana has acted.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, using an emergency provision in Indiana law,
O'Bannon, a Democrat, suspended the state's gas tax for two months,
a move that will cut up to 10 cents off the price of a gallon of
gasoline, now well over $2 in many places in Indiana and elsewhere
in the Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hoosiers can't afford to wait on federal and state
investigators to tell us why the Midwest is being hit so hard,''
O'Bannon said.
</P>
<P>
   At the pump, many drivers applauded the governor.
</P>
<P>
   But some Republican officials and legislators saw politics, not
just dollar signs, in O'Bannon's move, noting that he is up for
re-election and that he chose to announce the tax suspension
against the photogenic backdrop of a busy Indianapolis gas station.
They argued that the cut would unbalance the state budget and save
the average driver less than $2 per tank at the pump.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's politics, a political year,'' said state Sen. Lawrence
Borst of Greenwood, chairman of the Senate Finance Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The governor's campaign manager, Tom New, had a one word
response for that: ``Phooey.''
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON: FEARLESS MCCAIN ATTACKS FINANCE LAW
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., is still letting the chips fall where
they may.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, while urging a House committee to tighten regulations
on tax-exempt political groups, which do not have to tell who gives
them money or how they spend it, McCain likened their work to
``certain evils in our society,'' namely murder, rape and robbery.
</P>
<P>
   That was too much for House Majority Whip Tom DeLay, who has
close ties to a number of the groups and who disagrees strongly
with McCain on the need for an overhaul of campaign finance laws.
He struck back, unusually hard for a fellow Republican, asserting
that McCain was trying to curb free speech by demanding that the
groups name donors and detail the political activity their
donations support, like advertising.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have offended good Americans and you should apologize,''
DeLay declared. ``By employing emotionally overwrought rhetoric
that places Americans contributing to these groups on the same
level as evil criminals, you rashly condemn many citizens who are
simply pursuing their First Amendment right to join the debate.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain responded that DeLay seemed nervous about the possibility
that a campaign finance measure just might pass. As for whether he
would apologize, he recalled the answer the surrounded American
commander gave in the Battle of the Bulge in World War II when the
German commander demanded that he surrender: Nuts.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
