<HEADER>
A3895 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-AOL-MESSAGING-NYT &LR;      06-24 0884
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AOL-MESSAGING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAVID-AND-GOLIATH BATTLE IN CYBERSPACE
</HEADLINE>
  By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ From a cramped, three-room office near Wall Street
two weeks ago, four young programmers started a virtual duel with
America Online, the Internet behemoth.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, they had all been members of the Israeli
military's computer security unit. But now they were fighting for
their start-up company, Odigo Inc., and its instant-messaging
service.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, their David-and-Goliath battle to keep lines open to
the 140 million users of AOL's instant-message programs would reach
far beyond their corner of Silicon Alley. Even as AOL was
denouncing Odigo's programmers as hackers and criminals, AOL
announced its support for a worldwide standard for the technology.
</P>
<P>
   The fight started on a Saturday night two weeks ago, when Avner
Ronen, a founder and vice president of Odigo, received the call on
his cell phone _ fittingly enough, as he was walking up Third
Avenue to a 10:30 p.m. showing of ``Mission: Impossible 2.''
</P>
<P>
   America Online, Ronen was told, had just blocked the users of a
new version of Odigo's program, released on May 31, from sending
messages to or receiving messages from users of AOL Instant
Messenger and ICQ, the programs that account for 90 percent of all
instant-message users.
</P>
<P>
   Ronen, 24, quickly took the No. 5 train downtown to the
company's office at 11 Broadway.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were a bit surprised,'' he said of AOL's move, but not
worried.
</P>
<P>
   Instant messages travel over the Internet and quickly pop up on
users' screens, allowing instantaneous communication. But users of
the different instant-messaging programs have been unable to
communicate with each other _ not because it is technically
impossible, but because AOL has not allowed it. While more than 40
other software companies, including Odigo, offer such programs, for
more than a year AOL has blocked competitors from reaching its
users, citing privacy and security concerns.
</P>
<P>
   The competitors, most prominently Microsoft, have released
versions of their messaging programs that can communicate with
AOL's users, only to have the security team at the company's
headquarters in Dulles, Va., track the signals of competitors'
programs and block their users.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is as if AT&AMP;T said that you could not communicate with one
of its users from a Sprint line,'' said Ross Bagully, chief
executive of Tribal Voice Inc. of Denver, another instant-messaging
company.
</P>
<P>
   Enter Odigo. The company was founded in January 1999 in Israel,
but most of its 15 employees moved six months ago to Manhattan's
technology-rich Silicon Alley in search of their millions in the
Internet gold rush sweeping across America.
</P>
<P>
   Odigo, which provides its instant-messaging service free to
users and under contract to Internet providers like Prodigy,
StarMedia and Fortune City, found that its efforts to expand were
being stifled by AOL's dominance of the market.
</P>
<P>
   Simply put, Ronen said, users are reluctant to sign up for new
instant-messaging services if they cannot communicate with
colleagues, friends and family members who use AOL's two programs.
After unsuccessful efforts to talk to AOL, Ronen said, Odigo gave
up and released the new _ compatible _ version of its software in
late May.
</P>
<P>
   When AOL started blocking Odigo on June 10, Roee Vulkan, 26, a
software engineer who helped design the Israeli defense force's
internal intranet system, succeeded in creating a software patch
within hours that allowed Odigo users to circumvent AOL's security
measures. The company posted the software fix on its Web site.
</P>
<P>
   It was the opening salvo in what would become more than a week
of intense, day-to-day combat between the two companies, with Odigo
engineers coming up with solutions as soon as AOL experts had
blocked the previous ones.
</P>
<P>
   Barry M. Schuler, president of AOL's Interactive Services Group,
said his company was not concerned about losing business. Rather,
he said, it wants to prevent instant-messaging companies from
sending advertising, or selling the e-mail addresses of AOL users.
``All of a sudden you open a Pandora's box, where you kill a
product that everyone used to enjoy,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schuler said Odigo had ``illegally entered the AOL system'' by
attempting to make its software ``mimic an AOL signature.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is from a kid sitting with a computer in a garage
without his parents' permission,'' he said, ``or the engineering
team of a company that is backed by venture capital, hacking is the
same.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ronen said Odigo had done nothing illegal because its
programmers had not penetrated AOL's computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The cat-and-mouse game between AOL and Odigo would repeat itself
10 times, with AOL blocking Odigo's signature and the small company
altering its digital fingerprint to get around the firewall.
</P>
<P>
   On June 15, AOL released a document outlining its security and
privacy concerns about other companies' instant-messaging software
and laying out its support _ eventually _ for open communication in
the instant message medium.
</P>
<P>
   It was widely hailed as a victory for the little competitors.
But the victory was short-lived. About 15 minutes after releasing
the position paper, AOL again blocked Odigo's users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
