<HEADER>
A3904 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-BLUEJAYS-NYT &LR;      06-24 0893
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DELGADO AND WELLS HAVE BLUE JAYS SOARING HIGH 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBO-NOTEBOOK) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Considering that on successive days, the two recognized
contenders for the American League East championship lost games by
scores of 17-4 and 22-1, the fact that the Toronto Blue Jays, in
the space of six recent games, lost by scores of 16-3 and 18-6
should not rule them out as a third contender for that same title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We definitely have a chance,'' Carlos Delgado, the team's mass
weapon of opposing pitchers' destruction, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're for real. Absolutely,'' Gord Ash, the general manager,
proclaimed, then readily acknowledged that the Blue Jays have
benefited from the inconsistent performances of the Yankees and the
Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fooling ourselves,'' Ash added. ``The Yankees and
Red Sox have played probably more poorly than anyone anticipated
and given us a chance to contend. But given the circumstances, we
think we can compete with them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays began play Saturday in first place, half a game
ahead of the Red Sox, a game in front of the Yankees. The Blue Jays
had been four games from first before winning 12 of their last 17
games, including 2 of 3 games in each of five successive series.
When that stretch began, the other two teams were tied for first,
but then the Yankees won only 7 of 17 games and the Red Sox 8 of
18.
</P>
<P>
   If those expected contenders have been inconsistent, the Blue
Jays have been a contradiction. They have one of the best hitting
and highest-scoring teams in the league, but they have given up
more runs than they have scored. They have the pitcher with the
most victories in the major leagues, but their pitching staff has
allowed the most hits and has the league's third worst earned run
average.
</P>
<P>
   Delgado and David Wells are the primary reasons the Blue Jays
are in position to challenge the Yankees and the Red Sox, though
Delgado has had more help from other hitters than Wells has from
other pitchers. Delgado, who chose to remain in Toronto after his
good friend Shawn Green was traded to Los Angeles, is one of the
most fearsome hitters in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Entering Saturday's game, he led in home runs (25) and slugging
percentage (.714); he was second or tied for second in on-base
percentage (.469), runs scored (61), total bases (190), extra-base
hits (45) and walks (53); and he was fifth in hits (95), tied for
fifth in batting average (.357) and seventh in runs batted in (66).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very happy to come back,'' said Delgado, who could have
become a free agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``At some point in your career, you have some leverage. You have
to weigh your options. I don't think I sacrificed anything. If I
did, I'm happy with the way things have worked out.''
</P>
<P>
   Wells was not happy with his trade by the Yankees to Toronto
last year, but he has flourished there nonetheless. Following a
17-10 record last season, the portly portsider has run off a 12-2
record this season. His 3.55 earned run average is No. 2 in the AL
among pitchers with a name other than Pedro Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   But like the team, Wells has been a contradiction. He has
allowed the most hits in the league (126), but has countered the
potential effect of all those baserunners by having the best walk
ratio (1.2 per nine innings) with 14 walks in 1061/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Since the trade for Roger Clemens, Wells has compiled a 29-12
record, Clemens 18-16. ``He's having a great year,'' Ash said. ``I
think he's relishing the role, in his own unique way, of being the
leader of this group. He came out in spring training and said some
negative things about the club and the players.
</P>
<P>
   ``To his credit, 30 days later, he did an about-face after he
saw them compete. Ever since he's been the go-to guy. Probably the
most impressive thing about David this year is the number of times
he's been out there without his best stuff and he has battled and
kept us in the game.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wells is the only pitcher with a winning record in the Blue
Jays' starting rotation, which includes two young right-handers,
Chris Carpenter and Kelvim Escobar, and a journeyman pitcher, Frank
Castillo, but no steady fifth starter.
</P>
<P>
   The spot belonged to Roy Halladay, another young right-hander,
but an 11.97 ERA earned him a trip to the minor leagues after seven
starts. In his place, Lance Painter, Peter Munro and Clayton
Andrews have failed to make an improvement. Andrews was the starter
in the recent game the Blue Jays lost to Detroit, 16-3. A week
later Carpenter was the starter of an 18-6 loss to the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Ash said, games like that (earlier in the season the Blue
Jays lost successive games to Seattle, 17-6 and 19-7) can make him
crazy, but he added, ``It's the nature of the game at the moment.''
</P>
<P>
   With Raul Mondesi, acquired for Green in a swap of right
fielders; Shannon Stewart, Tony Batista and Brad Fullmer assisting
Delgado, the Blue Jays have done some pummeling of their own.
``Offensively, we're clearly right there with them,'' Ash said,
referring to the Yankees and the Red Sox. ``We're more balanced
than in recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ash also expressed the view that the division race would be
won by the team with the best pitching staff. ``We're all in
trouble,'' he said. ``It's the degree of trouble you're in.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1547EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
