<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUST ONE OF THOSE DAYS; PITCHING PROBLEMS IN ATLANTA; NO HELP FROM
REYNOSO; A RULEBOOK STRIKE ZONE? 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBA-BLUEJAYS) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the Yankees beat Pedro Martinez with a flurry of
bases-empty home runs last week, it was suggested that familiarity
might have done him in. That is, the Yankees were facing the
brilliant Boston pitcher for the third time in 24 days and perhaps
benefited from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   But the Cleveland Indians saw Cal Eldred three times in 28 days,
and the Chicago White Sox pitcher beat them every time. His third
start against the Indians, in fact, produced the best of Eldred's
three performances against them. He shut them out on six hits.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor could have made the difference in the outcomes
experienced by Martinez and Eldred. In Eldred's three games, the
White Sox scored a total of 19 runs; in the three Martinez pitched
against the Yankees, the Red Sox scored a total of three runs.
Eldred allowed six runs; Martinez gave up four and had an earned
run average in the three games that was just about a run lower than
Eldred's, 1.57 to 2.53.
</P>
<P>
   INFLATED ERA IN ATLANTA? &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's not bad enough that John Schuerholz, the Atlanta Braves
general manager, has spent the past six months dealing with the
fallout from the words that fall out every time John Rocker opens
his mouth. Now he has suffered culture shock. The Braves have
joined the rest of pitching humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' Schuerholz said. ``I looked at the
stats about two weeks ago. I looked at the earned run averages in
the American League and saw they were in the fives and sixes. Then
I looked at the National League and we're over four. It's so
foreign to me. But that is as true a reflection of our pitching
times as anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The Braves last had a season-ending team ERA that began with a
four in 1990. Leo Mazzone was named the team's pitching coach in
the middle of that season and quickly took steps to reduce the ERA.
From 1992 through last season, the Braves' pitching staff had
either the lowest or next-to-lowest ERA in the major leagues. Their
3.63 ERA was the lowest last season.
</P>
<P>
   They entered Saturday night's game at 4.15, the third lowest in
the majors but not low enough to suit Schuerholz. ``We're going to
try to fix it,'' he said, ``but when you see those stats, you say,
`how are we going to fix it?' I'd rather be writing about the
problem than trying to fix it.''
</P>
<P>
   NO HELP FROM REYNOSO  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Since the second day of their season, the Arizona Diamondbacks
have been out of first place in the National League West on only
two days, after their April 23 game against San Francisco and their
game last Sunday against the Rockies. Armando Reynoso was the
Diamondbacks' starting pitcher in both games, which were played on
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Reynoso pitched a total of two innings in the two games (he
faced only seven batters in the first one) and gave up 16 runs and
16 hits.
</P>
<P>
   A RULEBOOK STRIKE ZONE?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By instructing umpires to call the strike zone that is defined
in the rulebook, Major League Baseball could speed up the pace of
games, which has been one of its goals, and potentially reduce the
number of home runs and runs, which is not a goal. But Major League
Baseball apparently is not prepared to take such a drastic step.
</P>
<P>
   The upper limit of the rulebook strike zone is the midpoint
halfway between the top of the shoulders and the top of the uniform
pants. When that definition was enforced, that point was around the
letters on the uniform shirt. The lower limit is the hollow beneath
the kneecap.
</P>
<P>
   That zone, however, shrunk many seasons ago, and umpires now
basically use the knees to a point, by edict of the commissioner's
office, about 2 inches above the belt.
</P>
<P>
   At a negotiating session earlier this season in the talks for a
new labor agreement for the umpires, their representatives reacted
to comments they had seen from officials criticizing umpires for
not calling pitches correctly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Statements had been made in the papers that when we get an
agreement, umpires will call the rulebook strike zone,'' John
Hirschbeck, the union's president, said, relating a discussion at
the session. ``We said, `Wait a minute, if that's what you want,
we'll do that right now. Tell us, and we'll do it.' If they said,
`Call the rulebook strike zone,' I swear every major-league umpire
will go out and call armpits to knees.''
</P>
<P>
   Did officials leap at the chance to enlarge the strike zone?
``They said, `No, don't do that; we'll do this gradually,'''
Hirschbeck related.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
