<HEADLINE>
RESHAPING OF NETS MOVES INTO HIGH GEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-NOTEBOOK) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   From picking No. 1 to finding a coach, Rod Thorn begins
reshaping the New Jersey Nets in earnest this week. Though the NBA
draft on Wednesday remains a priority, the job of finding a
successor to Don Casey is apparently almost done.
</P>
<P>
   Byron Scott, a Sacramento Kings assistant, has been interviewed
by Thorn and appears to be the Nets' top choice.
</P>
<P>
   Scott is highly respected by Nets upper management, who view him
much in the mold of Orlando coach Doc Rivers: an even-keel person
with a solid playing career and the respect of his peers.
</P>
<P>
   Scott's coming to the Meadowlands is not guaranteed. Scott,
Magic Johnson's backcourt mate in the showtime years, is still in
the running for the Indiana job. But with Isiah Thomas and Rick
Carlisle waging campaigns to take over the Pacers, Scott may decide
to leave the Kings for the Nets before taking over for the retired
Larry Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn has been tight-lipped about the candidates and does not
expect to make a decision until next week. And the Nets could
easily go another direction, depending on circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Two of the other four candidates are Eddie Jordan, the respected
assistant on Casey's staff whom Stephon Marbury has endorsed, and
Tubby Smith, the University of Kentucky coach. Bob Huggins of the
University of Cincinnati and Mike Fratello have also been mentioned
in connection with the job.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Krzyzewski, the Duke University coach, was contacted by the
Nets but told them he was not interested in leaving the college
ranks.
</P>
<P>
   Thorn has other decisions to make. Kenyon Martin, the Cincinnati
forward considered the top pick until he broke his right leg in the
Conference USA tournament, finished his two-day visit with the Nets
on Friday. Because of the injury, Martin did not work out. But he
was examined closely by team doctors, and their evaluation would
not deter the Nets from taking him with the first pick.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1554EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0114 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3907 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      06-24 1067
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRAFT POSSIBILITIES; THE PACERS' CHOICE; AROUND THE LEAGUE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With BKN-NETS) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With Orlando and Chicago controlling the draft _ they hold five
of the top 13 picks and six of the first 24 _ the Nets are still
thinking about trading the No. 1 pick. But if they don't and decide
to select Cincinnati's Kenyon Martin, the rest of Wednesday's first
round will probably go like this:
</P>
<P>
   _ Vancouver likes Stromile Swift, the 6-foot-9-inch Louisiana
State forward who is the second-leading shot blocker in school
history, behind Shaquille O'Neal.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Clippers, who pick third, will most likely take Iowa
State's Marcus Fizer, who can score from anywhere and who should
blend in well with Lamar Odom.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Bulls, at No. 4, are contemplating trading some of their
multiple first-round picks. Jerry Krause is in need of more
veterans than youngsters. But they probably will not pass on Darius
Miles, this year's prep phenom from East St. Louis, Ill.
</P>
<P>
   _ That leaves Orlando at No. 5. Depending on what it does with
its three first-round selections, the Magic will most likely choose
between Texas center Chris Mihm or Florida's Mike Miller. If
Orlando takes Mihm, then the Atlanta Hawks will take Miller.
</P>
<P>
   Given the lack of an impact player, finding a sleeper late in
the first round is not impossible for a team like the Knicks, who
pick 22nd.
</P>
<P>
   But as more franchises build through free agency and as the
continued proliferation of early entry candidates dilutes the
talent pool, the draft continues to lose its luster.
</P>
<P>
   Hofstra's Speedy Claxton may be among the first point guards
taken. He impressed scouts at the draft camps and worked out with
the Knicks on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   It will be interesting to see where Ohio State's Scoonie Penn is
selected. Penn, a fifth-year senior who majored in sociology,
elected not to participate in the Chicago draft camp because he had
to take finals the same week. Penn was determined to get his degree
and passed up one of the main yardsticks for draft consideration.
</P>
<P>
   He reportedly also grew disenchanted with the performances of
some of his peers at the Phoenix draft camp, where his stock fell.
A 5-foot-11-inch point guard, Penn was moving the ball, setting
screens and playing help defense, and he apparently did not fit in
with the look-at-me crowd.
</P>
<P>
   But, really, who would want a guy who stayed in school and
played team ball? In this NBA?
</P>
<P>
   THE PACERS' CHOICE
</P>
<P>
   Donnie Walsh, the Indiana Pacers' president, met for three hours
Wednesday night with Rick Carlisle, a Pacers assistant, to assure
him that Walsh had not yet made Isiah Thomas an offer to become the
team's next coach.
</P>
<P>
   Carlisle assured Walsh that he still wanted the job and would go
on the offensive to make sure he received the proper consideration.
</P>
<P>
   That apparently meant having players over to his house and
telling them of his desire to work with them toward winning a
title, according to an Eastern Conference coach.
</P>
<P>
   ``With all the lobbying on both sides, it's getting ugly out
there,'' the coach said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
``Isiah thinks he has the job, Rick can't believe he's not being
more strongly considered and Donnie is really in a quandary,
wondering what to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Walsh has also met with players, and from their feedback it does
not appear the Pacers are leaning either way. It may come down to a
gut decision by Walsh.
</P>
<P>
   One Eastern Conference executive said Walsh had been receiving a
lot of anti-Isiah calls from NBA officials who do not want Thomas
to get the job. But Walsh received the same kind of feedback from
Boston when Bird was up for the job and hired him anyway.
</P>
<P>
   AROUND THE LEAGUE
</P>
<P>
   Grant Hill's days in Detroit are not over, but they may come to
an end soon. Hill, a free agent forward, has intimated to close
friends and family that he will most likely play in another city
next season, a person close to Hill said on condition of anonymity.
Barring an unlikely trade to New York, Hill is considering Chicago
and Orlando, both of which have salary-cap room to accommodate
Hill. And the notion that Hill will team up with Tim Duncan is
fading. Even if Duncan does not move to Orlando, Hill is not
particularly interested in playing in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   Free agents can begin negotiating with teams on July 1, but
cannot sign deals until Aug. 1. Some people are skeptical about how
much weight those dates actually carry. One Atlantic Division
official, for example, called the period a smoke screen. ``Tim
Duncan knows what he's going to do, Grant Hill knows what he wants
to do, and Tracy McGrady knows what he wants to do,'' the official
said. McGrady, the Toronto forward, is still leaning toward the
Magic or the Bulls unless the Raptors pull off a sign-and-trade
with another team.
</P>
<P>
   After all the TV studio candidates shamelessly threw their own
names around, the Knicks assistants Don Chaney and Brendan Malone
have finally been receiving interest for vacant jobs. Chaney
recently turned down the lead assistant position with Atlanta.
Malone was contacted by Washington to be the Wizards' top assistant
under Leonard Hamilton, but he chose not to pursue the job.
</P>
<P>
   A note on the Lakers' first title in 12 years: When Magic
Johnson was directing traffic in the 1980s, there was an aura about
the town and the team that could be felt when the old Forum was
buzzing, as if all the problems outside the arena did not exist.
Since 1988, Los Angeles has been beset with difficult times.
Whether it was Johnson telling the world he had contracted HIV in
1991, the fallout from Rodney King's arrest and the O.J. Simpson
trial, or the devastating fires and an earthquake, the city was
pelted the last decade with some kind of strife or tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1988, not a single pro sports team had won a title or
captured the imagination of the city like the Lakers of Shaq and
Kobe. A group of rioters on Monday night helped stall the healing
process, but at least it's beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not from L.A.,'' said Rick Fox, a Lakers forward, ``but in
watching a lot of times the turmoil the city has gone through, the
different riots and chaos, this would be a positive way to
celebrate. And you hope in that celebration everyone stays healthy
and safe. It would be something jubilant to pull the city
together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
