<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 15:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3908 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OUTDOORS-MAINE-NYT &LR;      06-24 0947
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTDOORS-MAINE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OUTDOORS: ANGLING ON THE RAPID RIVER 
</HEADLINE>
   By NELSON BRYANT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   As our 18-foot canoe, heavily laden with grub, clothing,
sleeping bags and fishing gear, moved up the Androscoggin River to
where it flows out of Lake Umbagog, a bald eagle regarded us from
his perch atop a tall, dead conifer and didn't bother to fly though
we passed within 50 yards.
</P>
<P>
   Umbagog, now within a federal wildlife refuge, is long, narrow
and shallow and covers 7,850 acres. Straddling the Maine-New
Hampshire border, it is the westernmost of the Rangeley lake chain
and about 30 miles southeast of Canada.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a decade, my companion Ruth Kirchmeier and I have
been making an annual hegira to the Rapid River, which flows into
Umbagog from Maine, in quest of wilderness, solitude, landlocked
salmon and trout. We begin by putting in at the public launching
area on the Androscoggin just above the power dam in Errol, N.H.;
from there, it's about two miles to Umbagog and approximately the
same distance across the lake to the Rapid River.
</P>
<P>
   For a few years, we tented at one of the remote campsites on the
Maine shore, but when Dick Celli of Lenox, Mass., told us that his
camp on the south side of the Rapid River's mouth was available for
rent, we acknowledged that we were getting a bit long in the tooth
to rough it in the bush. The moodiness of the lake, which is swept
by strong winds that build up rough water in the matter of minutes,
also persuaded us that while paddling was more fun and didn't
shatter the silence, an outboard was in order. So now our canoe is
propelled by a little two-horsepower, side-mounted Yamaha. If
conditions are ideal, the entire trip takes us a little more than
an hour each way.
</P>
<P>
   At the camp, we were pleased to find that Celli had kindled a
fire in the wood stove. Our crossing, in a stiff northerly wind
with the temperature in the low 50s, had been cold and wet.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of paper pinned to the wall near the dining room table
told the story of Dick's success on a fishing trip that he had made
up there in late May. Attached to it was a battered Black Ghost
streamer fly. The fly was large, about a No. 4, and unusually long,
and under it was written: ``Retired _ May 28, 2000 _ after having
taken 10 fish in 2{ hours _ including two 16-inch and one 19-inch
landlocked salmon. All fish were salmon.''
</P>
<P>
   These fish were caught at the outlet pool which is less than a
mile upstream from his camp and the end of the line for boat
fishermen. The Rapid River descends at a startling rate, and those
entering it from its lower end must walk upstream to fish other
pools and runs. Only fly fishing is allowed on the river downstream
to a clearly marked spot below the outlet pool called Cedar Stump.
</P>
<P>
   During that May trip, Dick also caught and released a brook
trout of about three pounds. The creel limit on the Rapid River is
one salmon a day at least 14 inches long, and all brook trout must
be released. The trout are wild fish, descendants of a race of
giant brookies whose numbers have been sadly depleted.
</P>
<P>
   The morning after Ruth and I arrived, Dick and I went to the
outlet pool boat at dawn. In two hours, he caught and released one
keeper salmon. I had no hits. The air temperature was in the high
40s and the water temperature about 54. It was frequently windy and
overcast _ with occasional rain _ during our entire stay at the
Rapid River, rarely exceeding 60 degrees at noon.
</P>
<P>
   One morning Ruth and I went ashore at the outlet pool and hiked
upstream to Smooth Ledge, where I hooked and and lost a large
salmon, released a 12-incher and then, using a Muddler Minnow,
caught and released a brook trout of about 16 inches. Returning to
the outlet pool, we found three wading anglers. A hatch of various
aquatic insects, including mayflies, was under way, and trout and
an occasional salmon were rising all about us.
</P>
<P>
   One of the wading anglers was on the opposite shore of the
stream fishing dry flies, and in less than an hour he caught and
released several trout and one keeper salmon. He was an
accomplished fly caster, and from time to time he would snatch one
of the hatching flies from the water or the air, examine it and
then dip into his fly box to tie on a new offering.
</P>
<P>
   Inspired in part by him, I switched to a small dry fly, a Royal
Wulff, and began catching trout, including a 15-incher. I then, in
rapid succession, caught two salmon just over 14 inches. I released
them both because I wanted a bigger one for supper. That proved to
be a bad decision. In the days that followed, I caught nearly a
dozen salmon but none was a keeper.
</P>
<P>
   On one of the evenings when we were anchored in the outlet pool,
Ruth yelled to me to turn around and watch a big cow moose wading
across the rapids 40 yards above us. It was Ruth's day for wildlife
sightings. That morning while on a solo hike behind the camp, she
had been ``attacked'' by a female grouse. A mother grouse with
chicks nearby will sometimes go through various antics, but this
was the first time I had ever heard of one actually pecking at a
hiker's legs.
</P>
<P>
   Wanting a meal of fresh fish, I took _ after 15 minutes of
casting with a Mickey Finn streamer fly on a sink-tip line _ a nice
smallmouth bass from the lake in front of the camp. Scaled, rolled
in a corn meal biscuit mix and pan-fried _ accompanied by rice
pilaf, the last of our French bread, freeze-dried peas and a
freeze-dried apple cobbler _ it was first rate. And the following
morning when we broke camp, Lake Umbagog was unusually peaceful: a
vast, undulating, gleaming expanse unruffled by even the slightest
breeze.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
