<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3909 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-BOOKS-READANDWHY0625-     06-24 0772
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOKS-READANDWHY0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    So you want to be a reader?
 &HT;    By Wendell Brock
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Too bad the Hugh Grant character in Woody Allen's
``Small Time Crooks'' couldn't give Harold Bloom's new book to
Tracey Ullman's daffy millionairess, who's trying to absorb a
lifetime's exposure to art and literature through osmosis and
shopping.
</P>
<P>
   ``How to Read and Why,'' by the author of the best-selling
``Shakespeare: The Invention of the Human,'' attempts to distill
the erudite professor's 40 years of university lecturing into a
kind of self-help manual for the general public. It's a brilliant
plan, really, to provide an easy-to-swallow literary pill for the
reader who's always yearned to know the likes of Austen, Dickens,
Proust and Mann but has never known where to start. With nothing
more than a pitcher of water, a comfortable chair and the
redoubtable Dr. Bloom in your lap, the arc of Western literature
can be yours in a single sitting.
</P>
<P>
   Wait. Just because that's how the book is being hyped doesn't
mean you must believe it. Bloom can be seductive. But instead of
automatically yielding to his personal, at times idiosyncratic,
sensibility, the reader must ultimately learn to trust his own
taste.
</P>
<P>
   The 69-year-old Bloom, who teaches at both Yale and New York
University, comes across as a combination of dotty grandfather and
endearing don _ kind of like the British critic John Bayley. He is
benign, eminently likable and possessed of the opinion that he is
the final arbiter of literary matters. Using Shakespeare as the
standard against which all else is measured, he puts forth a series
of practical lessons on the major forms: poetry, drama, the short
story and the novel.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why read?'' he asks. We read to know ourselves better and to
become engaged in a higher form of personal pleasure. ``There is a
reader's Sublime,'' Bloom writes, ``and it seems the only secular
transcendence we can ever attain, except for the more precarious
transcendence we call `falling in love.' ''
</P>
<P>
   This is so much pretty writing by a man who is clearly _ and
correctly _ convinced of the ennobling effects of literature. Bloom
is in love. And while he is on a chivalrous mission to save the
printed word from disappearing into cyberspace, he seems to have no
real grasp of who his audience is. His digressive, highfalutin
style is hardly going to win over a crowd hooked on the Internet
and ``Who Wants to Be a Millionaire.'' In fact, much of the time,
readers without some knowledge of the humanities aren't likely to
have a clue as to what he's talking about.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the chapters on the short story and the novel are a
testament to Bloom's timeless and impeccable taste. No one would
quibble with his selection of Chekhov, Hemingway and Borges as the
modern masters of the short tale. What's troublesome is his
struggle to shoehorn all stories into either the Chekhov-Hemingway
or Kafka-Borges mold. While he admirably includes the Italian
writers Tommaso Landolfi and Italo Calvino in his summary, he
barely mentions Joyce's ``Dubliners'' and entirely omits Katherine
Anne Porter, whose influence on the form is unquestionable.
</P>
<P>
   But these are quibbles and quirks.
</P>
<P>
   I wouldn't hesitate to recommend the sections on short fiction
and the European novel (from Cervantes to Thomas Mann) to young
readers. Someday, when I get around to rereading Borges or tackling
Henry James' more difficult novels, I will surely go back to see
what Bloom has to say. On the other hand, except for the commentary
on Walt Whitman and Emily Dickinson, I will probably never return
to his discussion of poetry. And I'm not sure this scholar has a
firm grasp of the American novel. A case in point: He cites
Nathanael West and Philip Roth as the bookends of 20th-century
Jewish fiction, overlooking Saul Bellow and Bernard Malamud. And he
calls Cormac McCarthy's ``Blood Meridian'' ``the strongest
imaginative work by any living American writer.'' I haven't read
it, but, by God, I will now.
</P>
<P>
   Readers looking for guidance on the classics would do better to
turn to Vladimir Nabokov's ``Lectures on Literature'' and
``Lectures on Russian Literature,'' in which the great writer
luxuriates in the architecture and details of some 19th- and
early-20th-century masterpieces. Both the Bloom and the Nabokov are
based on university lectures, and they cover much of the same
territory. But only Nabokov, born on Shakespeare's birthday, has
the capaciousness of spirit to turn his lectures into works of art.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
