<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 16:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3914 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-CHINA-SMUGGLE-DEATHS-     06-24 1655
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-SMUGGLE-DEATHS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMS OF NEW LIVES LED IMMIGRANTS ON FATAL JOURNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By INDIRA A.R. LAKSHMANAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   XIANZHI, China _ The smugglers promised a journey to prosperous
new lives in the West, in silk-lined cabins supplied with oxygen.
For the last leg, the illegal immigrants would ride a fast
catamaran to England. It would be like a vacation promoted in
glossy brochures for rich, urban Chinese.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the 60 men and women from rural China, who relatives
say were charged between $20,000 and $30,000 each for their illicit
passage, were found entombed in the back of an airtight,
unrefrigerated truck last week by customs inspectors in Dover,
England.
</P>
<P>
   Packed behind a wall of tomato crates, all but two of them
suffocated. Many of them had flown from Beijing to Eastern Europe,
traveled over land to the Netherlands and Belgium, and then were
crammed into the truck for the ferry trip to England.
</P>
<P>
   ``On June 6, he called his wife to say he was going to England,
but since then, we've had no news,'' said Mrs. Lin, a middle-aged
farmer in the Fujian Province village of Xianzhi, who believes her
son was one of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Her arms hugging her knees, Mrs. Lin choked on tears as she
explained why her son took such a risk.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house is breaking down,'' she said, motioning around her
dark, musty dwelling, with its concrete floor and molding walls.
``He was just a bricklayer, and he couldn't make enough money here
to renovate our house.''
</P>
<P>
   On the single dirt road that runs through this village, scrawny
chickens ran wild. Inside, dozens of modestly dressed residents
packed into the room to listen. ``Everyone in this village has to
go out, because we don't have enough money. The average income is
1,000 yuan ($120) a month,'' explained the missing man's aunt, her
arm wrapped around her grieving sister.
</P>
<P>
   The interview was cut short when authorities burst in and
ordered this journalist into an official vehicle headed for the
Changle City Propaganda Department. At least 10 other foreign
reporters, picked up in nearby villages, were also questioned and
told to leave the area. At least one British reporter, tracked by
police after he tried to contact alleged smugglers, was escorted
onto a flight back to Beijing.
</P>
<P>
   In a reflection of China's sensitivity to illegal emigration,
authorities went to every village that was home to a suspected
victim. They ordered local residents not to speak to ``suspicious
foreigners.'' Police were posted outside one man's home after he
told a reporter his son was missing. Another family changed its
story. Families can be punished for helping relatives flee.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the terrible risks, an estimated 100,000 Chinese pay to
be smuggled overseas to Western countries every year, according to
the US Immigration and Naturalization Service. Ten percent are
believed to find their way to the United States. Last year, the INS
caught 2,585 smuggled Chinese, more than double the number detained
in 1998, and four times the number in 1997. Some are deported,
while others apply for asylum. Most go undetected, and unknown
numbers perish en route.
</P>
<P>
   In January alone, more than 100 undocumented Chinese were found
crammed into containers at ports in Seattle and Vancouver, Canada,
including three who died on the way to Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Cashing in on people's dreams of a better life has become big
business; smugglers net $3 billion annually from Chinese passengers
alone, said Jean-Philippe Chauzy of the International Organization
for Migration.
</P>
<P>
   All of the victims in the Dover case are believed to be from
Fujian Province, in southeastern China. Numerous Fujian villages
have seen 10 percent of their residents depart each year. One has
been dubbed the ``widows' village,'' because almost every man of
working age has gone overseas to work. In another, locals say
four-fifths of their young people have left.
</P>
<P>
   The determination to emigrate seems paradoxical, since Fujian is
one of China's richest provinces. But its long coastline has eased
getaways, fueling a diaspora that dates back two centuries. Fujian
migrants built US railroads and mined gold in the 1800s,
established corporate empires in Southeast Asia, and started
businesses in Chinatowns around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In the last decade, economic reforms and China's opening to the
West have encouraged new forms of corruption and organized crime,
which prey on aspiring and gullible villagers who dream of getting
rich overseas _ especially in the United States, which is known
here as ``the golden mountain.''
</P>
<P>
   In almost every village for 100 miles here, small paddy fields
and decaying brick shacks are juxtaposed against ostentatious,
single-family homes, built with money sent back home. Decorated
with white tile, tinted windows, and flourishes such as rooftop
pavilions, these monuments to success abroad are often empty or
occupied only by elderly parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course it's because of the money'' that people leave, said
Mr. Lin, a 48-year-old farmer in Zhai Qian, a fishing village
eclipsed by a busy port in nearby Fuqing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Fujian is richer than other provinces, but we still don't
have enough money to build a house. Not even by the end of my life
could I afford a house like that,'' he said, pointing at a pink and
white, four-story tower crowned with a pink pagoda.
</P>
<P>
   With each new house that sprouts up, complete with flush toilets
and double-glazed windows, villagers who cannot afford such
luxuries say they feel like failures and cowards for not trying to
make their fortune overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Those who have gone are usually too ashamed to describe the
horrific conditions they endured during the journey. It may include
beatings and rape. Few ever admit to being forced into indentured
servitude at restaurants or sweatshops to pay off the $20,000 to
$50,000 cost of getting to Europe or the United States. Ten percent
of the price goes to local ``fixers,'' known as snakeheads, who
arrange the journey, according to a businessman familiar with the
process; the rest goes to Chinese criminal gangs overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the immigrants have landed in Boston's Chinatown, where
police in the mid-1990s discovered migrants kept as virtual slaves
until their smuggling debt was paid. Some women are forced into
prostitution, but tell relatives they are secretaries. No questions
are asked, because the money keeps flowing home.
</P>
<P>
   ``A guy in the next village went overseas and within a few
years, brought back 1 million yuan ($120,048) and built a six-story
house and used the rest to start a business. My husband made less
than $100 a month,'' said He Xiaohong of Changqi village, who
believes her 24-year-old husband is among those found in Dover.
``The snakehead told us the journey was safe, that he'd fly from
Shanghai to Beijing, and from Beijing direct to England.''
</P>
<P>
   The snakehead told them European customs was lax during the
month of June, so he should go now. Her husband was given a
Yugoslav passport, and took a train to Beijing and a flight to
Belgrade, according to Apple Daily, a Hong Kong newspaper. From
there, he went through Austria, Hungary, and countries she had
never heard of. When he called last month from Holland, his
passport, ID, and money had been seized by snakeheads. She has not
heard from him since.
</P>
<P>
   Clutching their baby and crying, He said that if her husband
comes back safely, ``I won't let him try again. After this tragedy,
I won't dream of money anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Another family in Changqi told Apple Daily that they last heard
from their son on June 14, when he called from Holland, en route to
England. Wailing hysterically, Chen Yuming, 57, said she and her
husband were against their son's illegal escape. ``We never
expected he'd be trapped in an iron box,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, authorities came, and Chen and her husband, Cao
Yigan, 63, changed their story, telling this reporter that no one
from their village ever had left.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, local authorities have tended to turn a blind eye
to human smuggling. Remittances from abroad have fed a building
boom and enriched the province, and the exodus has controlled
population growth.
</P>
<P>
   But the outflow has shamed Beijing. Each sensational smuggling
tragedy makes life in China seem so terrible that people are
willing to die to get out.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Fujian peasants have enough to eat and China's
policy limiting families to one child is loosely enforced in
villages, those who make it to the West are often coached by
smugglers to claim persecution for their political views or for not
adhering to the one-child policy.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the Federal Board of Immigration Appeals in the
United States reviewed 6,067 asylum applications from Chinese, of
which 929 were granted.
</P>
<P>
   Political persecution is widespread in China, but those targeted
are most often religious dissidents, democracy activists and labor
organizers who pose a threat to the Communist Party's grip on power
_ not farmers.
</P>
<P>
   Beijing has started to crack down on smuggling, last year
capturing 9,000 stowaways and 800 snakeheads, who were fined or
imprisoned. But many suspect that some corrupt customs agents help
the smugglers.
</P>
<P>
   The government is trying to educate people about the risks, with
graphic pictures of bodies of stowaways that washed ashore. In the
town of Qian Zhai, huge slogans painted on the walls scream the
warning: ``It's dangerous, illegal and hazardous to your health to
leave your country illegally!'' Another urges, ``Expose the
snakeheads and middlemen!''
</P>
<P>
   But people here pay little attention. ``Of course some people
know how dangerous it is, but everyone who has gone makes so much
money,'' said Xiao Yongwen, 25, a driver from Fuzhou. ``People just
build new houses and show off their money, and never mention how
hard it all was.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
