u a BC-NY-FLY-INVASION-NYT &LR;      06-24 0834
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-FLY-INVASION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHADES OF HITCHCOCK: FLY SWARMS PLAGUE RESIDENTS IN UPSTATE NEW
YORK 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: No byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NAPLES, N.Y. _ Will they return, or is the worst over?
</P>
<P>
   Will the buzzing black masses swarm around homes, settling on
screens and siding? Will they again slip through cracks around
windows or fly in doors, landing on food and brushing across the
faces of the sleeping? Will more barbecues be canceled, more garden
parties postponed?
</P>
<P>
   If only the people of Naples knew.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, millions of flies hatched and descended on about half
a dozen houses in town, three weeks after an area farmer spread 200
tons of chicken manure on a 20-acre field nearby. Some of the
residents fled to the homes of friends and relatives. The town's
health officer, noting the amount of dead flies around the houses,
declared a public health risk.
</P>
<P>
   Area residents banded together to pester county and state health
and environmental officials for help. Town officials fielded
inquiries from news organizations as far away as Japan.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of last week, after chemical spraying and the use of
lots of fly strips, traps and plain old fly swatters, the flies
were down to the kind of nuisance found in a stable. But some
residents of Naples, a town in the Finger Lakes region about 40
miles south of Rochester, were still digging out from under piles
of thousands of dead flies in closets, on front porches and in tool
sheds.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like a black cloud,'' said Ervin Paulsen, who lives
across County Road 36 from the field where the manure was spread.
He doused his house with insecticide. ``It was just like an Alfred
Hitchcock movie.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Fleischman, who lives next to the field, said, ``I'd get
home from work, and I'd have to get the hose and spray down the
door to get in the house.'' First, the odor of the manure, and then
the flies, kept her, her husband and their two daughters inside the
house for weeks. They stopped drinking their well water after all
four developed diarrhea. On Thursday, water testing confirmed the
presence of potentially dangerous E. coli bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one more nightmare after another,'' Fleischman said.
</P>
<P>
   Though their water had never been tested before, the area's
water superintendent said that it was not uncommon to find some E.
coli in well water.
</P>
<P>
   The beleaguered residents said they would go back to grilling
outdoors and enjoying their spectacular views of the Bristol Hills
if they knew that the fly infestation was over. Naples, a town of
2,830, is best known for its rural charm, vineyards and annual
Grape Festival. But right now, some people are still hunkering
down, scrubbing walls and sweeping floors.
</P>
<P>
   Phillip Kaufman, a veterinary entomologist at Cornell University
who consulted with the farmer, Mark Adams, said this type of
``giant fly explosion'' was reported only a few times each summer
across the country. ``They're very likely through the worst part,''
Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   But the town supervisor, Donald Leysath, said, ``If we continue
to get rain, I'm going to have a fly problem.''
</P>
<P>
   People who live a few miles down County Road 36 say they had a
similar fly problem last summer after Adams spread chicken manure
on an 80-acre field in the area.
</P>
<P>
   Adams is a member of the Naples Town Board and president of
Adams Hen House, the family farm, where he tends 105,000 laying
hens.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Adams spread the manure on his own fields as
fertilizer. But in the last few years, Adams _ who also happens to
be a member of the town's Board of Health, as well as president of
the New York Poultry Association _ began leasing acreage so he
could spread the manure more thinly to better protect the soil and
the water.
</P>
<P>
   Then the trouble began. Angry neighbors say Adams caused last
week's fly infestation by dumping manure filled with larvae that
hatch into flies, and by not plowing the manure under quickly
enough.
</P>
<P>
   Adams denies that the manure contained larvae.
</P>
<P>
   Kaufman said the flies had probably been attracted by the
manure's odor and had laid eggs before the plowing.
</P>
<P>
   Spreading manure is a common farm practice, and it rarely
results in such masses of flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a large number of variables and many unanswered
questions,'' Kaufman said.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he follows agricultural guidelines for applying
manure and for plowing the manure under within a few days. But he
concedes that frequent rains kept him from plowing under the recent
application of manure for more than two weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Adams said he is investigating alternatives to disposing of the
manure, such as composting and selling it as dried fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   The change would come none too soon for Denise Wheaton and
Charles Francis, who live near the field blamed for the fly
infestation. After spraying insecticide, their front porch was
littered with dead flies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been around farms all my life,'' Francis said. ``I've
never seen anything like this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
