<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3924 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-BUSH-POLL0625-COX     06-24 0711
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-POLL0625-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TBy Jamie Manfuso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Most Texas voters think Gov. George W. Bush has
done a good job in office. They're just not sure why.
</P>
<P>
   Despite overwhelming approval ratings, 63 percent of registered
voters in the state _ including 56 percent who support Bush's
campaign for president _ can't name a reform the governor has made,
according to The Scripps Howard Texas Poll released today.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor is saying that he's `A Reformer with Results,'
and it's interesting that Texans can't name a reform that he's
brought about in the state,'' said Texas Poll Director Ty Meighan.
``It's even more interesting because he's been out there talking
about it. Perhaps people haven't been paying attention at this
point.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the poll indicates state voters intend to vote for Bush
over Vice President Al Gore in the presidential election _ 57
percent to 24 percent. Two percent supported Ralph Nader and 1
percent favored Pat Buchanan. Twelve percent were undecided and 4
percent said they would vote for none of those candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's approval ratings as governor also remain high, at 73
percent. Twenty-three percent disapproved of his job performance
and 6 percent said they didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never seen job approval ratings as high as his ever,''
Meighan said. ``It's been unbelievable, and it's not a one time
shot.'' Approval ratings for Bush's predecessor, Democratic
Governor Ann Richards, peaked at 60 percent in Spring 1994 .
</P>
<P>
   Bush, who interjects Spanish into many of his speeches, has
wooed the Hispanic vote in past gubernatorial campaigns and in his
present run for the presidency. But 75 percent of Hispanics _ and
66 percent of African Americans _ couldn't name a reform brought
about by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign has done a great job with the photo ops and
sound bytes,'' said Texas Democratic Party Chairwoman Molly Beth
Malcolm in a prepared statement. ``He'd be a great candidate for
class favorite. But the job of president requires leadership _ not
just likability.''
</P>
<P>
   The results were less skewed among the state's Republican
voters, 52 percent of whom could not name a reform.
</P>
<P>
   Of those who named reforms made by Bush, 16 percent cited
education. Four percent named crime and 3 percent named property
tax as Bush's number-one reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush has always made education a number one priority,
and that is also the number one priority of Texans,'' said Bush
campaign spokesman Scott McClellan.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's changes in education, such as granting local
autonomy, ending social promotion and increasing teachers'
salaries, have not constituted a change in education great enough
to be called reforms, said presidential campaign expert Bruce
Buchanan, a professor of government at the University of Texas at
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush is not really a reformer as that term is truly
understood,'' Buchanan said. ``He's more of an incremental change
specialist.''
</P>
<P>
   While it's not unusual for the public to lack concrete knowledge
of politics and public policy, the poll results don't favor Bush's
slogan.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason the Bush group even went to that label was in
reaction to McCain in the primaries,'' Buchanan said, referring to
Sen. John McCain of Arizona, who campaigned against Bush for the
Republican Party nomination as a reformer of campaign finance, the
tax system and budgetary spending practices.
</P>
<P>
   Nineteen percent of Texas Democrats said they would vote for
Bush in the presidential election.
</P>
<P>
   The survey, a telephone interview of 1,000 adult Texans
conducted between May 22 and June 16, has an overall margin of
error of 3 percentage points. The poll also found that 56 percent
of Texas voters would cast their ballot for Republican Sen. Kay
Bailey Hutchinson. Democrat Gene Kelly received 21 percent support,
while 16 percent were undecided. Kelly has a slight lead leads over
Hutchinson among Hispanics and African Americans while Hutchinson
has a 40 percent edge over Kelly among Anglo voters.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
