<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-AIRCREWS-BAR-700&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME AWAY FROM HOME FOR AIRLINE CREWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SARAH KERSHAW   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Hans Krause was in the air, somewhere over Virginia,
when he heard about the pub. Another pilot, who flies for United,
told him there was a place in New York City where the beer was
cheap, the customers were airline and the bartender had a huge
collection of bras, hanging on a beam above the bottles of vodka
and whiskey.
</P>
<P>
   So the next time Krause, 32, a pilot for Trans States Airlines,
landed in New York, he dropped his things off at the crash pad in
Kew Gardens, Queens, that he shares with 13 other pilots and
wandered into Yer Man's Irish Pub on Metropolitan Avenue, main
street for people in the airline industry.
</P>
<P>
   Krause lives in Florida, but he spends three or four days a week
in New York. He is among the scores of flight attendants and pilots
who have apartments or second homes in Kew Gardens, which is close
to both La Guardia and Kennedy airports. The neighborhood is so
full of airline employees that residents call it ``Crew Gardens.''
</P>
<P>
   The other night Krause showed up at about 10 p.m. at Yer Man's
with a roommate, Dave Zook, who also flies for Trans States. It was
Wednesday, airline night at the pub. So anyone who flew _ and the
owner of Yer Man's, Jimmy O'Reilly, said he always knows who they
are _ got half-price drinks all night.
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd swelled with pilots and flight attendants, Krause
moved around the room, greeting friends from Delta, Continental,
United, American and TWA. Some he had known since he first showed
up at the pub four years ago, others he met just recently. But as
he worked his way around the room, they all seemed like his sisters
and brothers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a definite subculture,'' said Krause, on his third
beer. ``Being away from home so much, it feels like a family-type
environment.''
</P>
<P>
   Krause has spent his 30th birthday, a Thanksgiving and a
Christmas at Yer Man's, because his flying schedule made it
impossible for him to go home to Vero Beach, Fla., where he has a
wife and a 2-month-old baby.
</P>
<P>
   While Krause was mingling with his friends, the pilot who had
told him about Yer Man's in the first place called on his cell
phone from California and said he wished he were there.
</P>
<P>
   Krause said many of the pilots he knows have also got the Yer
Man's fever. On his briefcase is a sticker, from O'Reilly's
plentiful selection of Yer Man's paraphernalia, that says, ``Save
Water, Drink at Yer Man's.'' Krause said he has several times found
himself in an airline personnel lounge thousands of miles away and
noticed the stickers on other pilots' briefcases.
</P>
<P>
   In the six years since he opened the pub and introduced airline
night, O'Reilly, who is originally from Killarney, Ireland, has
become something of a father figure for airline personnel in the
neighborhood. (``Yer man,'' O'Reilly said, is slang in Ireland for
``what's-his-name.'') Almost as soon as he opened the place, he
noticed that Kew Gardens was a hub for airline people.
</P>
<P>
   ``You get to know the look,'' said O'Reilly. ``Their hair is all
nicely done and sometimes they come in here wearing summer clothes
in the winter.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly knew a good business opportunity when he saw one, but
he also thought that there was loneliness in the job and that the
pilots and flight attendants could use a place to go. Certainly
many of them might want to get away from their apartments, where
rooming with 10, 15 or 20 people is routine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought I could do something to help them out,'' O'Reilly
said. ``A lot of them are young, and so we watch them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Apking, 25, a flight attendant for Delta, was at Yer
Man's for the third time the other night, having heard about it
from another flight attendant. She has 15 roommates, living in
three bedrooms and a living room and sharing one and a half baths.
She works six days straight and then has six days off, so her
social life gets a little discombobulated, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, she had stopped in at Yer Man's and met a
pilot from JetBlue. The two agreed to meet the next night, airline
night, and they danced to live music and chatted at the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty cool,'' Apking said. ``Everyone's airline. There's
a certain comfort about that.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The pilot, Ralph Meyer, stays with 27 other pilots across the
street from the pub and has been going to Yer Man's for years.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice when we all get together,'' he said. ``The main
thing is we get to mix airlines.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Reilly knew three of the working crew members _ and several
others who were ``deadheading,'' or getting a ride but not working
_ on TWA Flight 800, which exploded over Long Island in July 1996,
killing all 230 aboard. Some of the pilots and flight attendants
who died in the crash had spent time at the pub, on airline night.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks after the crash, O'Reilly held a benefit at the pub,
featuring 18 bands and raising $6,500 for the children of airline
employees who died in the crash. In the back of the bar, a plaque
is propped against the wall, listing the names of the airline
employees who died. ``To the Crew of Flight 800,'' it says, ``From
all their friends at Yer Man's Irish Pub.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there's the bra collection. O'Reilly somewhat sheepishly
explained that he had a certain expertise in the bra-removal
department and that, if a woman was willing, he could unsnap and
remove a bra within 10 seconds, if it was under a short-sleeved
shirt. Looking up at the collection, hundreds of them dangling over
the bar _ lace, satin and cotton, ranging in size from A cups to
double D's _ O'Reilly said, ``If I had to estimate, I'd say about
60 percent of those came from flight attendants.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
