<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3926 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-CAR-NASCAR-SPOTTERS-2     06-24 1222
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-SPOTTERS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN NASCAR, THE DEALS ARE SHORT-LIVED, BUT THE MEMORIES LAST LONG
</HEADLINE>
  By SCOTT HULER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Every sport has its deals.
</P>
<P>
   In baseball, you want to make a deal, you go to spring training.
Football or hockey? Try draft day.
</P>
<P>
   But in Winston Cup racing, the deals go down where the guys go
up _ in the spotter's stand on top of the speedway grandstand.
During every race, every team sends a spotter to the roof; it's a
rule. And everyone knows he spends the race telling the driver what
he sees.
</P>
<P>
   Except the spotter has one more responsibility. He makes deals.
</P>
<P>
   Spotters make small deals throughout any race. They can promise
later cooperation if a lapped car will give way, or they can
explain why a lapped car will refuse to cooperate; perhaps it hopes
to regain its lap, or perhaps the driver remembers a race two years
previously when he didn't get the cooperation he asked for.
</P>
<P>
   If someone wants to get by a car, his spotter has to have
something to offer the passed car _ help later in the race, help
during another race. Sometimes it's as ineffable as a general
spirit of cooperation that can grow between two teams over years;
other times it's a promise to stick together until a certain point
in the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is no different than negotiating business contracts in a
boardroom,'' said Vic Maguire, spotter for the No. 10 car driven by
Johnny Benson. ``It's a give-and-take.''
</P>
<P>
   The spotters wheel and deal the most at the superspeedways at
Daytona, where the Pepsi 400 takes place on Saturday night, and
Talladega.
</P>
<P>
   At Talladega Superspeedway in Alabama, the real deals go down in
a couple of rows of rickety aluminum bleachers high atop the
grandstand at the start-finish line, almost in Turn 1. There, in a
cloud of gnats in the brutal Southern sun, squinting across the
2.66-mile track through haze so thick the spotters can barely
identify their own cars in Turn 3, twice-a-year spotters engage in
a kind of dealing that has parallels nowhere else in NASCAR _ or
any other sport.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Job 1 for a spotter is to keep his driver apprised of
where his competition is on the track _ when someone is coming up
behind him, when he can move up or down on the track. ``Clear
low!'' the spotter says into his radio, and the driver cuts down
into traffic, secure that he has a space. At most tracks the
spotter does little more than that eye-in-the-sky act, keeping his
driver safe and his $100,000 race car in one piece. Says Danny
Culler, who spots for the No. 3 car driven by Dale Earnhardt,
``It's kind of like being an air traffic controller for a race-car
driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Except at Talladega and Daytona.
</P>
<P>
   At those two superspeedways, where carburetor restrictor plates
limit engine output and smooth the field to a parity that renders
horsepower virtually inconsequential, the aerodynamic draft is the
key. In the draft, two or more cars running together outstrip even
the fastest car running alone. So without a dance partner, as they
say, you're sunk.
</P>
<P>
   Enter the spotter.
</P>
<P>
   If a crew chief is looking for a partner, he doesn't go running
up and down pit road. ``It's easier to do it through the spotter,''
Maguire said. ``The spotters are all in one place. I'm not more
than 30 feet away from a guy who might be a whole straightaway down
pit road.''
</P>
<P>
   So late in a race at Talladega, the spotters' stand can become a
cross between a boardroom and a bazaar. The only things at the
speedway moving faster than the spotters are the race cars
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Maguire offered a look into the spotter's life at Talladega
during the weekend of the Die Hard 500, which ran April 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``The necessity, in superspeedway racing, is to be in a
competitive position at the end of the race,'' Maguire said. ``If
you're in a tight draft, in the top five, you've got a chance to
win. So you have to create alliances that might not occur at short
tracks.''
</P>
<P>
   All during practice, drivers run just behind and just in front
of other cars. How does Benson's Pontiac handle behind a Ford? In
front of a Chevy? Are there particular cars it runs with well or
poorly? How does it do in a big draft? A small one? All those
elements will come into play when it's time to choose a friend on
race day.
</P>
<P>
   When this partnership of necessity is struck midrace, isn't it a
little bit like the Mets calling the Dodgers with a deal? Something
like: ``If you use your three weakest starters against the
Phillies, we'll throw everything we've got against the Giants''?
</P>
<P>
   Not quite, Maguire said. ``In the first place, baseball isn't
open to as many places.'' The driver Kenny Schrader agreed.
``Everything else, it's just two teams,'' he said. ``But when you
got 43 cars at once, you get a buddy and say, `Let's beat those 40
other guys first' _ then we'll lie to each other at the end.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, yes _ the lie. ``Really, the deals that are set are like a
fairy story,'' Benson said, shrugging and shaking his head. ``A lot
of people say, `Let's work together, let's make a deal,' but that
lasts a lap and a half.'' Bart Creasman, spotter for the No. 55 car
driven by Kenny Wallace, said it best: ``The real deal is there's
no deal.''
</P>
<P>
   So deals are being broken all race long, and yet there are
always more.
</P>
<P>
   Some spotters get reputations as dealmakers; some guys try to
rough their act up to drive harder bargains. ``It's WWF stuff going
on up there,'' Maguire said, laughing. And if some spotter is
combing the stand to make a deal, Creasman said: ``You can tell
your driver, `Hey, this guy's running up and down _ he ain't
watching his car. Jump on him.'''
</P>
<P>
   It truly is like a bazaar, where rational self-interest is
hardly the rule of the day. Benson gave the example of a group of
four or five cars drafting together not in the lead pack. ``That
pack of five needs to say, `We need to stay nose to tail,''' and
the spotters may not even need to get involved. ``That deal's going
to last,'' Benson said, ``at least until you get to the lead
pack.''
</P>
<P>
   Then things change. That draft may be the fastest draft on the
track _ if they stayed together, they would not only catch but pass
the lead cars. But as soon as that draft catches the leaders,
someone is going to decide he can run better behind the leaders _
or is going to make a deal with one of the leaders, and everything
breaks down in a hurry.
</P>
<P>
   The example that everyone in the garage still talks about
occurred in this season's Daytona 500 on Feb. 20. With only a few
laps remaining, Benson led the race, followed by Mark Martin (in
the No. 6 car), Dale Jarrett and Jeff Burton (in the No. 99 car).
Martin and Jarrett's teams brokered a deal for Martin and Jarrett
to pass Benson on the high side, sticking together until they were
by him. The spotters and teams had it all worked out.
</P>
<P>
   It lasted about a tenth of a second. Martin went high, Jarrett
moved to follow him _ and saw in his mirror that Burton, Martin's
teammate, was going low, which could have left Jarrett out in the
cold, behind both cars. ``He was committed to the 6 until the 99
changed his commitment,'' Benson said. ``And he had about
two-hundredths of a second to make his decision. That's how deals
work. And that's among teammates, let alone the rest of the
field.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett won that race; Martin, famous for sticking with his
deals, said, ``I got lied to.'' Jimmy Fennig, crew chief for
Martin, said at Talladega, ``We learned a lesson, and I guarantee
it won't happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   But it's not that deals are made in bad faith, said Stevie
Reeves, spotter for the No. 13 car driven by Robby Gordon, who
likens the promises teams make through their spotters to those made
by gamblers at a dice table. ``It's like saying, `I'm going to roll
a seven,''' Reeves said. ``You mean it, but you don't got no
control over that.''
</P>
<P>
   With a few laps remaining in the DieHard 500 at Talladega, which
was eventually won by Jeff Gordon, Martin led the race. But he ran
in the draft behind Jarrett, who was the last car on the lead lap.
The teams communicated through their spotters, Jarrett asking
Martin if he preferred him to move. Martin liked his position, and
only very late in the race did Jarrett make a gentlemanly shift
high to let the leaders by him.
</P>
<P>
   But don't expect that to make him best friends with Jimmy
Fennig.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never forget,'' he said of the Daytona 500. ``You never
forget.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
