<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORTGAGES-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MORTGAGE RATES EASE SOMEWHAT 
</HEADLINE>
  By EDWIN McDOWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Prospective home buyers surveying the mortgage market
have seen mortgage rates rise steadily if undramatically since last
June, prodded by Federal Reserve interest-rate increases. But in
recent weeks rates on the benchmark 30-year fixed-rate mortgage
have been easing somewhat. Adjustable-rate mortgages, meanwhile,
have been steadier.
</P>
<P>
   Largely because of the narrowness of the spread between rates
for fixed and adjustable mortgages, lending specialists say,
fixed-rate loans, which cannot change over the term of the
mortgage, have been gaining popularity.
</P>
<P>
   Weekly average rates for 30-year mortgages dropped from a high
for the year of 8.82 percent for the week ending May 19 to 8.37
percent for the week ending June 16. Last Wednesday, the rate was
8.33 percent. One-year adjustable-rate mortgages stood at 7.37
percent for the week ending May 19 and 7.38 percent the week ending
June 16, but rose to 7.55 percent on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   A major factor in the increases in the last year has been the
actions of the Federal Reserve, which has raised interest rates
1.75 percentage points since last June, raising the rate a quarter
point five times and a half point last month.
</P>
<P>
   In the first quarter of this year, adjustable-rate mortgages
accounted for 31 percent of all mortgages nationwide, compared with
12 percent in the same quarter in 1999. But midway through the
second quarter, the last period for which statistics are available,
they dropped to 29 percent, compared with 17 percent for the second
quarter of last year, and lenders say their percentage of the
mortgage market is continuing to fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our experience is that current applications for ARMs is down
from 32 percent to about 15 to 20 percent,'' said Luke Hayden, a
vice president of the Chase Manhattan Mortgage Corp.
</P>
<P>
   While fixed-rate mortgages remain constant throughout the length
of the loan, adjustable-rate mortgages carry a lower interest rate
initially and offer an array of choices. But after a set period of
time _ one year, three years, five years and even seven years are
typical _ the interest rate on adjustable-rate mortgages can rise,
pegged to a benchmark like the Federal Reserve rate, and can
typically increase by as much as 6 percentage points over the life
of the loan.
</P>
<P>
   These days, the refinancing market is moribund.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since the Fed started raising rates a year ago, refinancing
virtually disappeared since it's driven almost entirely by interest
rates,'' said Doug Duncan, the chief economist of the Mortgage
Bankers Association of America. ``At this moment, the share of
applications for refinancing is down to 12.45 percent, the lowest
in four or five years.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the most significant changes in the mortgage market in
recent years is that people wanting to know about mortgages are
flocking to the Internet. The most striking feature, perhaps, is
the availability of loans through scores of Web sites, sites that
offer interactive tools that allow prospective borrowers to play
out an infinite number of ``what if's'' involving a variety of
rates, down payments and types and terms of loans.
</P>
<P>
   But contrary to some expectations, few borrowers are actually
applying for loans over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Forrester Research in Cambridge, Mass., predicted last year that
online mortgage lending would soar more than fivefold from 1999 to
2003, to about $91 billion, or 10 percent of the total mortgage
market. But its most recent analysis, published in March, reported
that mortgage lenders ``worry about the lack of consumer acceptance
and the low close rates on applications to date.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent analysis of Internet mortgages by Kenneth A. Posner and
Michael D. Courtian of Morgan Stanley Dean Witter noted that while
recent surveys have found that more than 50 percent of people who
take out mortgages use the Web to research prices and terms, only 1
percent apply online.
</P>
<P>
   Prospective borrowers gather a lot of information on the Web,
Duncan said, ``but when it comes to actually filling out and
signing the documents, they realize it isn't a simple transaction
so they back away.''
</P>
<P>
   The main reason people looking for mortgages avoid online
brokers, the Morgan Stanley study said, is that they are wary of
putting their Social Security numbers, employment information,
income and assets online.
</P>
<P>
   Another stumbling block had been the refusal of some states to
accept electronic signatures as binding in online transactions,
including mortgages. But that obstacle was overcome when a bill
making e-signatures binding recently passed both houses of Congress
by lopsided margins. President Clinton is expected to sign the
measure, which is scheduled to take effect Oct. 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
