<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICAS-CUP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BILLIONAIRES ARE `RAISING THE BAR' FOR AMERICA'S CUP
</HEADLINE>
  By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In flush times and lean ones, the America's Cup has been a
historical lure to wealthy men eager to advance business or
personal agendas. In the early part of the last century, the Irish
merchant Sir Thomas Lipton employed numerous cup challenges to help
market tea bags. Later, the railroad tycoon Harold ``Mike''
Vanderbilt found cup racing to be a rigorous adjunct to the joys of
a Newport, R.I., summer.
</P>
<P>
   Although in more recent times well-heeled businessmen like Bill
Koch and Ted Turner have promulgated the notion that the cup is a
game for the financially gifted, other sailors with working-class
backgrounds, like Dennis Conner and Paul Cayard, have also proved
that campaigns can be started _ and a handsome individual salary
procured _ with a healthy input of corporate backing.
</P>
<P>
   But the days when a sponsored sailor can run a reasonably
successful effort for $12 million or even $32 million _ the budgets
for Conner's Stars &AMP; Stripes team and Cayard's America One squad in
the last cup _ now appear to be over.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Seattle cellular-phone billionaire Craig O. McCaw
announced the formation of his OneWorld Challenge for the 2002-2003
cup races. And racing personnel in the United States and New
Zealand have confirmed that Oracle's software founder, Larry
Ellison, whose personal fortune is a reported $47 billion, is
committed to a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in Europe, the cup newcomers Ernesto Bertarelli and
Pierre-Oliver Essig, from Switzerland, have joined the Prada
Challenge's Patrizio Bertelli in separate campaigns to bring the
cup to the continent. And while the announced cup budgets from this
group range from $50 million to $70 million, in an escalated war
for talent and technology, the thought of a $100 million America's
Cup campaign is no longer laughable.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dennis Conner calls these guys the Bees, for billionaires,''
said Bob Billingham, the general manager of America One. ``They've
changed the game. They're raising the bar.
</P>
<P>
   ``We fought hard to raise $20 million in corporate funding the
last time, and it's questionable if that was good value for our
sponsors,'' he said. ``To ask them to double or triple that amount
is unrealistic.''
</P>
<P>
   But if Billingham believes his team's business plan is no longer
competitively viable, he also feels the injection of fresh faces
and dollars could spark new interest. ``Whether you see these guys
as heroes or villains, the bottom line is that they're interesting
people going head to head,'' he said. ``It could give the cup a
whole new personality. And their funding will create technology
that advances the entire sport.''
</P>
<P>
   One cup rookie who plans to avoid the limelight is McCaw, who
skipped last week's luncheon at the Seattle Yacht Club, which his
team will represent, and who declined requests to be interviewed
for this story. For several weeks, McCaw's name has arisen as the
likely backer of a Seattle-based challenge that was intent on
raiding the back-to-back cup-winning Team New Zealand squad.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw has chosen the Australian cup veteran Peter Gilmour to
head his sailing team, has recruited the Kiwi yacht designer Laurie
Davidson to create his boats and has signed up two dozen of
Davidson's countrymen to race them and work on them. ``The reason
we built it around the Kiwis is that they were talented and
available,'' said Bob Ratliffe, a spokesman for McCaw.
</P>
<P>
   The initial roster of Kiwis, which include the grinders Andrew
Taylor and Craig Monk, is notable for its lack of marquee names.
The Kiwi superstars Russell Coutts and Brad Butterworth, have
already cast their fates with Bertarelli's Swiss group.
</P>
<P>
   McCaw has also enlisted the Seattle brothers Jonathan and
Charlie McKee, who will also represent the United States in the
49er dinghy class at the Olympic Games in Sydney, Australia. ``By
the time we're actually out there sailing, you'll see a much more
balanced team that I would guess would primarily consist of
Americans,'' Charlie McKee said. ``I'm excited about sailing with
the best team.''
</P>
<P>
   McKee also said he and his brother were intrigued by the
environmental mission of the syndicate. McCaw has proclaimed that
part of his motivation in mounting a challenge is to promote
environmental awareness of the world's oceans. ``Jonathan and I
have purposely stayed out of this arena before, and that was a
significant factor in our decision to join,'' Charlie McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhat lost in the shuffle surrounding McCaw's announcement is
the Seattle Challenge, a second local effort that represents the
Corinthian Yacht Club and is spearheaded by the 26-year-old boat
builder Russell Belden, who hopes to bankroll his $42 million
campaign with corporate funding. Belden's aim is to field an
all-American squad.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
