<SLUG> BC-CONN-POLICE-HEAD-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`OLD SCHOOL' JUDGE ADJUSTS TO RUNNING POLICE FORCE 
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL ZIELBAUER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIDDLETOWN, Conn. _ Arthur L. Spada, Connecticut's newly minted
state police commissioner, likes to talk about the lessons he
learned growing up in the ghetto. His parents, a bricklayer and a
seamstress, arrived from Sicily in 1923, and raised their children
on Front Street, on Hartford's hardscrabble east side in a house
without indoor plumbing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shined shoes at age 8 and 10,'' Spada recalled with proud
fondness, sitting in his tall new leather chair behind his enormous
new desk at state police headquarters. ``We were ditch-diggers at
16.''
</P>
<P>
   Before he left for Wesleyan University, where he studied history
and, at 5 feet 4, became a starting linebacker, Spada had also
worked four summers in Connecticut's tobacco fields, earning 35
cents an hour. ``You came home, your whole body was loaded with
nicotine,'' he said, brushing his hands over his arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``A day doesn't go by,'' he went on, leaning over the desk,
where two needle-sharp pencils poked out of a rainbow-striped
coffee mug, ``that I don't make a value judgment on whether
something is worth buying or investing based on the economics I
learned on Front Street.''
</P>
<P>
   Spada, 67, is what some of the younger state troopers might call
old-school. Until he retired to take his current job, Spada spent
the last 22 years as a Superior Court judge with no use for pagers,
cell phones, computers or, by his admission, stylish clothing.
``Judges are not fashion plates,'' he said, grimacing.
</P>
<P>
   Now all that is changing, and Spada _ he still gets called Judge
more than Commissioner _ is struggling to adapt, not only to the
new electronics (``They even gave me a laptop''), new suits (bought
at Filene's Basement) and his new gun (required), but also to a new
profession.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've gone from kind of a monastic culture, where you sat in a
courthouse chamber the size of my bathroom facility'' _ he jerked a
thumb at the private toilet next door to his office _ ``to a
culture involving people, contacts,'' he said. ``As a judge, when
you came into the courtroom, you had the first word and the last
word. Now you're working with 1,500 people. That is a cultural
shock that I'm still adjusting to. You just simply cannot work as a
Lone Ranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he has never been a police officer, Spada said it is
imperative to show his new employees that he is one of them. ``My
responsibility is to show them that if I don't have blue blood,''
he said, referring to the police kind of blue, ``I know what blue
blood is.''
</P>
<P>
   Having been on the job for two weeks, Spada has begun drafting
an agenda: to hire more troopers, including more nonwhite men and
women, and boost the pay that already ranks third highest of all
state police agencies; to complete the installation of a new
Motorola radio communications system; and to wire all patrol cars
with on-board computers.
</P>
<P>
   There is one more policy change to come under Spada: traffic
violations. The commissioner promised that troopers would soon
begin an all-out attack on Connecticut's increasingly crowded
highway traffic, ticketing speeders and tailgaters and bringing
what Spada twice referred to as ``rogue truckers'' to ``a
screeching halt.''
</P>
<P>
   With the General Assembly's approval, Spada would also like to
begin using video cameras that have already been installed along
Interstate 95, where the speed limit is 55 mph, to catch speeders.
</P>
<P>
   While Spada adjusts to being a member of the police force, he is
also adapting to other things, like the hour it takes to drive 20
miles north to Hartford each night, not because of traffic
congestion but because his chauffeured state police car is required
by law to pull over and assist any stranded or disabled vehicles
encountered on the state's highways.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very unusual, lucky day when we can get home without
any incidences,'' Spada said, toying with a pair of black
wrap-around sunglasses, a gift from his predecessor, Dr. Henry Lee.
</P>
<P>
   When word got out that Gov. John Rowland had offered the
commissioner's job to Spada _ best known as the grand jurist who
presided over the indictment of six police officers in 1994,
including one state trooper _ people immediately compared him with
Lee. An unusually popular state police commissioner who pioneered
the application of forensic science to police work, Lee left the
department after two years and remains a consultant to the
Connecticut State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The comparisons did not trouble Spada, who believes he will be
every bit the efficient administrator that Lee was. But if Lee
infused the agency with star power and a touch of high-tech elan,
Spada intends to improve it with elbow grease and a work ethic
learned in the tobacco fields _ all applied with the charm and
curiosity that have served Spada well over the years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   An avid reader of history, including five biographies of Abraham
Lincoln, Spada attracted the interest of a group of judges visiting
from Bosnia three years ago by displaying a detailed knowledge of
European history and discussing the peregrinations of the Visigoths
through southern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were extremely impressed,'' said Anthony Fisser, who
leads the Connecticut Judges Institute, a continuing education
program for state judges.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Blumenthal, Connecticut's attorney general, who first
met Spada nearly 20 years ago, said Spada was a deceptively simple
man. ``He's a much smarter and articulate person than your
impression might be on first meeting him,'' Blumenthal said. ``When
I met him, I remember thinking, `Gee, this guy is charming, but how
smart is he?' But he is razor sharp. He doesn't need to use
multisyllable words to show anybody how smart he is.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spada does not seem like a man whose life is dedicated only
to work. On warm weekends, he gardens; he cycles 25 miles every
Saturday and Sunday or plays golf at a public course, which, he
points out, costs only $6 a round. In the winter, he skis at
Butternut, a hill in Connecticut where lift tickets are $9.
</P>
<P>
   How long will he stay on the job? That depends on two things, he
said: He will stay as long as the governor wants him to, and as
long as his health holds out. Spada underwent quadruple bypass
surgery 18 years ago, and has had no complications since.
</P>
<P>
   ``Am I lucky? How long will it last?'' he asked, and he rapped
his knuckles on his big new wooden desk.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
