<SLUG> BC-NY-LEGISLATION-ASSESS-840&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NEW YORK LEGISLATURE CLOSES WITHOUT USUAL SQUABBLING 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD PEREZ-PENA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ For years, the pattern here was as reliable as
sunrise. Democrats and Republicans went at each other hammer and
tongs, hurling verbal bombs, delaying budgets for months, barely
speaking to each other, and tying unrelated issues together until
most of them collapsed in recriminations.
</P>
<P>
   Not this year. The legislative session that wound to a close
Friday had its bloody episodes, but they were Republican against
Republican and Democrat against Democrat, with remarkably little
partisan carping. And it ended with an extraordinary number of
agreements on big issues, making it not only the most amicable but
by far the most productive session since well before George Pataki
became governor five and a half years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a spectacular session for the people of this
state,'' a tired but beaming Pataki said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday morning, the Assembly and the Senate ended days of
squabbling over petty procedural issues and passed a hate-crimes
bill that the governor said he would sign.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few days, the Legislature and the governor struck
deals on the farthest-reaching package of gun controls anywhere in
the country, on a sweeping revision of sexual-assault laws, on a
new money-laundering law, on a broad package of school-safety
measures that includes fingerprinting and background checks of
school employees, on making doctors' malpractice records available
to the public, and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the mad rush to the finish, the lawmakers had set
down landmarks. In December they agreed to an ambitious plan to
provide health insurance to the working poor, paid for by doubling
the cigarette tax.
</P>
<P>
   This year New York became the first state in the country to
require fire-safety standards for cigarettes, the first to restrict
where companies can sell or trade the ``pollution credits'' they
earn and the second to phase out a gasoline additive that has
caused ground-water pollution. Another bill gives retired state
workers annual pension increases for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of these things that people have been fighting for and
dreaming for years would happen suddenly happened _ boom!'' said
Blair Horner, legislative director of the New York Public Interest
Research Group. ``It's incredible.''
</P>
<P>
   That list amounted to a string of victories for the governor, a
Republican, and for the Democratic majority in the Assembly and
their speaker, Sheldon Silver. For Pataki, the year's achievements
raised his national profile, enhanced his reputation as a social
moderate who is tough on crime, and attached him to several popular
issues as he considers whether to run for a third term in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   The Assembly Democrats gave ground on a few criminal-justice
areas, particularly sexual assault and school violence, but also
won passage of major measures on hate crimes, cigarette
flammability and pesticide notification that they had sought for
years.
</P>
<P>
   For the Republican majority in the Senate, it was a more mixed
result, and the verdict will not be known until the November
election.
</P>
<P>
   What most of the prominent bills passed this year have in common
is that they moved state policy significantly to the left _ much
further left than the Senate Republicans had been willing to go
before. Worried about their prospects in November, they have been
eager to shore up their standing with moderate voters, particularly
in the suburbs, and that has meant approving bills that made many
of them unhappy.
</P>
<P>
   Their internal struggle over that shift was laid bare early
Friday when the Senate Republicans, their hand forced by the
governor's push for gun control, finally voted on the matter after
struggling for months to establish their position. Of the 20
upstate Republicans, only the majority leader, Joseph Bruno, voted
for the bill, which they clearly wished had never come before them,
while the downstate Republicans voted, 16-1, in favor.
</P>
<P>
   The vote Friday morning on disclosing doctors' malpractice
records also had them deeply divided, 19 in favor and 17 against.
</P>
<P>
   Amicability between the parties was a theme this year. A month
ago, Silver could have criticized the governor for vetoing the
first version of the fire-safe cigarettes bill. Bruno and Pataki
could have berated Silver for resisting tougher penalties for sex
crimes. Silver could have taken after Bruno for dragging his feet
on gun control. But none of this happened.
</P>
<P>
   In previous years, they would all have taken those shots, and
the temptation must have been great this year. Bruno looked
vulnerable early in the year, when he was feuding with the
governor, and many Republicans believed Pataki was trying to foment
a coup against the Senate leader. Silver was perhaps even more
vulnerable last month, when the second-ranking Assembly Democrat,
Michael Bragman, the majority leader, tried to overthrow him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess we were all too busy shooting at our own people,''
said Assemblyman Steven Sanders, D-Manhattan. ``Just so many
bullets in the gun.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Everyone refrained from taking advantage of those weaknesses and
attacking across party lines. ``The opportunity was there to create
some partisan chaos, but I think that would have been at the
expense of getting principled changes at the end of the day,''
Pataki said in an interview. In trying to get his way, he said, he
must have an evolving sense of ``what's going to be most effective
at achieving the end result.''
</P>
<P>
   Heading into the 1996 and 1998 elections, the governor worked
hard to whittle down the Democratic majority in the Assembly, in
part by attacking and embarrassing them publicly over legislation.
But each time, the Democrats gained seats, and he may have
concluded that the strategy was pointless.
</P>
<P>
   Some Assembly Democrats say that the attempted coup in their
house may have contributed to this year's productivity. They argue
that Silver was forced to loosen his tight control over legislation
and, under pressure from the members, rely less on stalling as a
negotiating tactic. And Silver and many of his allies may have
felt, after surviving the coup, that they needed tangible
achievements to show their Assembly colleagues and the voters back
home.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a good year,'' said Sen. Kemp Hannon, R-Nassau
County. ``But it was hard getting here.''
</P>
</TEXT>
