<SLUG> BC-BALTIMORE-REAL-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: OLD BALTIMORE HIGH-RISE GETS A NEW LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLES BELFOURE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ When the elegant marble lobby and mosaic-tiled
corridors are restored in an $8 million renovation that is to be
completed next month, the Riviera apartment house will be the
fourth of five one-time luxury high-rises on what was once one of
this city's most prestigious streets to be rehabilitated in the
last six years.
</P>
<P>
   It will join the Emersonian, the Esplanade and Temple Gardens,
all of which have been refurbished in recent years. The
reconstruction has included replacing the floors of
rabbit-warren-like apartments to create more spacious units that
are closer to the buildings' original layouts.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera's developers have set market-rate rents for its
apartments, seeking affluent tenants for the inner-city location by
emphasizing such things as a new entrance to the building from a
fenced and gated parking lot and the equipping of all apartments
with a T-1 high-speed Internet connection.
</P>
<P>
   Traditionally a city of two- and three-story homes, Baltimore
built few large apartment houses before World War II, but these
four buildings on Druid Park Lake Drive overlooking the city's main
park and its reservoir were the finest of their kind from 1912 to
the early 1960s. Now after 35 years of decline, they are again
desirable places to live in.
</P>
<P>
   The six-story 92,000-square-foot Riviera was built in 1914. It
was vacant when it was foreclosed by the Department of Housing and
Urban Development in the mid-1990s. The building was acquired by
the Baltimore City Department of Housing and Community Development,
which issued a request for proposals for its reuse.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, the team of Pennrose Properties, a development firm
from Philadelphia, and Reservoir Hill Hope, a local nonprofit
developer, won the right to rehabilitate the Riviera. The project
was the first in Baltimore for Pennrose, a company that has
developed more than 5,000 units of multifamily housing, including
many historic properties, in Pennsylvania, New Jersey, Delaware and
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Renovations in the 1960s and 1970s had cut the apartments into a
warren of tiny units for subsidized housing, totally obliterating
most of the original apartment layouts. One of the few things left
from the 1914 design was a six-story-spiral fire-escape slide,
discovered behind a wall during demolition.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera originally had eight apartments per floor. It now
has nine units per floor: seven two-bedrooms of 1,200 to 1,600
square feet, and two one-bedrooms of about 700 square feet. All 54
units have either open porches or enclosed sun rooms with views of
the park or downtown Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   To redesign the apartments, the building had to be almost
gutted. But because it was a Baltimore city landmark and was
eligible for state and federal tax-credit equity for its historic
status, many elements were retained. The lobby, with walls of
marble and a coffered plaster ceiling, and the mosaic-tiled
corridor floors with their original plaster cove moldings were all
integrated into the new design, along with new lighting.
</P>
<P>
   As an additional condition for historic tax-credit status, four
apartments facing the park on the sixth floor and one apartment
each on floors one through five had to retain or duplicate original
interior detailing, like window trim, parquet flooring and
baseboards. The brick and stone Classical Revival exterior, along
with its sheet metal cornice, was restored.
</P>
<P>
   The Riviera's market-rate apartments are intended for
professionals who work in the city. Rents will be $560 to $800 for
the two-bedrooms and $600 for the one-bedrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The building is two miles northwest of the Inner Harbor, the
city's hottest rental market, where rents start at $800 for a
one-bedroom and $1,200 for a two-bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Riviera will have all the amenities of a high-scale
building,'' said Mark Dambly, vice president and a partner of
Pennrose. ``There'll be a business center in the basement that
offers Internet access, fax and copying machines, as well as a
fitness center.'' A new entrance at the rear of the building will
lead to a gated parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   A completely market-rate building tailored for professionals in
this location is unusual. The building abuts Reservoir Hill, a once
affluent neighborhood of elegant town houses that has been in
decline since the early 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the neighborhood are pleased that the units are not
subsidized. ``This is a sign that says that this community is worth
investing in,'' said Curtis Jones, the board president of Reservoir
Hill Hope and pastor of nearby Madison Avenue Presbyterian Church.
</P>
<P>
   Aside from the developer's own equity and the historic tax
credits, Pennrose received $5 million in loans from HUD and the
city of Baltimore.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   By the early 1990s, the Emersonian, the Esplanade and Temple
Gardens had suffered the same fate as the Riviera. When Maryland
decided to package all of them in a request for proposals in 1994,
the Emersonian and the Esplanade were in such a run-down condition
that the remaining tenants had to be moved to Temple Gardens.
</P>
<P>
   Roizman Development of Plymouth Meeting, Pa., and the Baltimore
Housing Partnership won the contract and called the project
Renaissance Plaza. Since the three buildings made up the
Eutaw-Madison Apartment House National Register District, they were
eligible for historic tax-credit equity.
</P>
<P>
   Like the Riviera, each building had interior features, like
distinctive lobbies and corridors, to preserve. ``Besides restoring
the exteriors, we established historic zones to be preserved,''
said Patricia Massey, who was project manager and director of the
Baltimore Housing Partnership and who now runs her own firm, Katia
Development.
</P>
<P>
   The oldest of the three, the nine-story Esplanade, built in
1912, was the first to be completed in 1994. Temple Gardens, at 14
stories the tallest building in Baltimore when it was built in
1926, came next in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   The last to be finished, in 1996, was the Emersonian, an
eight-story building constructed in 1915 by Isaac Emerson, the
creator of Bromo-Seltzer.
</P>
<P>
   With 84 of the 301 apartments at market-rate rents and the rest
either subsidized or with income restrictions, the three buildings
have had a 99 percent occupancy rate. The entire cost of
Renaissance Plaza was $20 million.
</P>
<P>
   The fifth apartment house, at 903 Druid Park Lake Drive _
adjacent to the Riviera _ is vacant. It is on the market for
$525,000.
</P>
<P>
   Until the early 1900s, Baltimore's wealthy lived in town houses
in the center city or in suburban villas at its outskirts.
Apartment living was considered lower-class until the first luxury
apartment house was built on Eutaw Place, an elite residential
district. Once the rich adopted this lifestyle, other apartment
buildings were erected, notably at Druid Park Lake Drive, which
intersects the entry to Eutaw Place.
</P>
<P>
   Still, high-rise apartment living (six stories or more by
Baltimore's definition) had limited appeal, and fewer than two
dozen were built before World War II. ``A lot of people said these
buildings should be demolished, but we re-established that living
along the lake was a glamorous thing,'' Massey said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
