<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-PROSECUTORS-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-PROSECUTORS RECONCILE THE TWO SIDES OF A CAREER
</HEADLINE>
  By JOSEPH P. FRIED   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For 16 years, Jonathan Frank was an assistant
district attorney in Brooklyn, prosecuting cases from the
little-known to the notorious, like the one in 1998 in which a man
was convicted of a triple murder and received the first death
sentence under New York State's current capital punishment law.
</P>
<P>
   Now Frank, 42, is in private practice at a law firm, dealing
with civil litigation and with criminal defense involving business
fraud. He wants nothing to do, he said, with defending anyone
charged with a violent crime. ``I've seen too much horror, tragedy,
pain and suffering from victims and their families,'' he said of
his days as a prosecutor, which ended last year.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is Bradley Simon, who was a federal prosecutor for 11
years before he began a one-man private practice in 1998. Simon,
44, sizes up potential clients more by character than criminal
category. He has no reservations about representing young people
whose ``immaturity and lack of judgment'' had led them into serious
crime, he said, but he has declined some cases involving career
criminals he considered ``beyond redemption.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank and Simon are known as ``double-digit crossovers,''
members of a relatively small fraternity of veteran prosecutors who
waited a decade _ sometimes more _ before they went into private
practice. Some, like Frank, shun entire classes of cases that were
part of their prosecution routine. Others, like Simon, base their
professional comfort levels on their perceptions of individual
defendants.
</P>
<P>
   Some find a criminal-defense practice just as challenging as
prosecution work, even uplifting. Others find the transition to
private practice a double-edged sword: they are their own bosses,
but they have to pay their own bills.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City, it is common for young law school graduates or
relative novices to seek experience by staffing the state
prosecution offices in the five boroughs and the federal
prosecution offices in Manhattan and Brooklyn, then move on or
return to private practice. The typical stint in the five district
attorney's offices and the two United States attorney's offices is
five to seven years.
</P>
<P>
   Those who wait longer to depart, lawyers and prosecutors said,
are more likely to have developed strong views about the cases or
clients they are willing to accept in private practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who's been a prosecutor for 15, 20 years may find it
difficult to defend people'' who have been charged with any kind of
crime, said Austin V. Campriello, a criminal-defense lawyer who is
chairman of the City Bar Association's criminal courts committee.
``It may be mentally hard to make that change.''
</P>
<P>
   Campriello was an assistant district attorney in Manhattan for
nine years, until 1980. Since then, he has represented an array of
criminal defendants, including one of the four men who were
convicted in the World Trade Center bombing in 1993, which killed
six people.
</P>
<P>
   But there is also abundant skepticism among lawyers that any
significant number in their ranks refuse cases or clients by
category, even among those who had been longtime prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not heard of people who turn away cases because they
had scruples after having done mob work, drug work, etc.,'' as
prosecutors, said Roger B. Adler, whose 25 years in private
practice followed five years in the Brooklyn district attorney's
office.
</P>
<P>
   Adler, a former chairman of the Brooklyn Bar Association's
federal courts committee, also said that competition for cases can
often define a lawyer's scruples. ``In the New York litigation
market, I think there is an undersupply of cases and an oversupply
of lawyers,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, one longtime federal prosecutor, Matthew E.
Fishbein, said that when he went into private practice three years
ago, he wrestled with whether to take certain cases.
</P>
<P>
   He said he had left prosecution _ after 12 years in the United
States attorney's offices in Brooklyn and Manhattan _ partly
because he felt ``ready to do something different.'' But he was not
certain whether ``something different'' should include representing
criminal defendants.
</P>
<P>
   ``With every firm I talked to, I made it very clear that I might
not want to do any criminal work,'' said Fishbein, who had risen
from prosecutor to chief assistant United States attorney, the No.
2 post, in Brooklyn, and also held that position in Manhattan. ``I
wasn't sure how I'd feel switching sides.''
</P>
<P>
   When he joined the Manhattan firm of Howard, Darby &AMP; Levin,
Fishbein said, he was immediately asked to take over the case of a
man charged with money laundering. When he found the man to be
basically ``a good and decent'' person, he said, ``I realized that
not only could I do the work, but it was something I would like
doing.''
</P>
<P>
   The man pleaded guilty, but that did not change Fishbein's
opinion of him. His case was ``the easiest transition I could have
ever imagined,'' said Fishbein, 46. Now with the New York office of
Covington &AMP; Burling, the Washington firm with which Howard, Darby &AMP;
Levin merged, Fishbein largely represents clients charged with
white-collar crimes like securities fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a prosecutor, I never saw the world in black and white,''
he said. ``A person may have committed a crime and has to pay the
consequences, but that's not necessarily the only thing that
defines a person.''
</P>
<P>
   Simon spoke of a similar approach. In his 11 years as a federal
prosecutor _ in Washington, on Long Island and in Brooklyn _ he
pursued defendants charged with drug trafficking. Now, in his
Manhattan solo practice, he handles a combination of criminal
defense and civil litigation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm more likely to take a case involving young people, even if
it's a serious crime, because immaturity and lack of judgment lead
them to get involved with people they should not, as opposed to
older people who have made a career of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He spoke of the different perspective he had gained in his
defense work, and how it enabled him to ``care very much'' about
some of those young clients. ``You find they have a capacity to
lead a productive life,'' he said, but instead they face the
possibility of many years in prison _ a prospect Simon finds
starker now than when he was working to send people there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was never in a federal prison while I was a prosecutor, but
now I'm sometimes there several times a week,'' he said of his
visits to clients. ``It's a big awakening.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Like Simon, Fishbein spoke of the rewards of working in the
public interest. Frank, now with the Manhattan office of Skadden,
Arps, Slate, Meagher &AMP; Flom, recalled his prosecution work as
meaningful, especially the homicide cases. ``It doesn't get any
more serious than taking someone's life,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But after 16 years in the Brooklyn district attorney's office,
where he had risen to executive assistant district attorney, ``I
had done everything, and a lot more than I expected, and it was
time to do something new.'' The financial needs of a family with
young children provided added incentives, said Frank, who was
earning $112,500 a year when he left a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Simon said building a practice has been challenging. ``You have
a lot of pressure to pay the bills, to build a practice,'' he said.
He added that after expenses, like rent on his Midtown Manhattan
office, ``my standard of living hasn't changed'' from that of his
later years as a prosecutor, when he earned about $100,000 a year.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Simon said, his automatic pilot forgets that he has
changed sides. Several times since the switch _ when putting his
name on the record at the start of a court proceeding _ he has
announced, ``Brad Simon for the government,'' prompting chuckles
from the judge and prosecutors and startled looks from his clients.
``Over 11 years, I must have said it thousands of times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Frank said he has no confusion about his old and new roles. At
Skadden, Arps, he said, ``I'm not going out to a crime scene at 4
in the morning and seeing a body riddled with bullets and people
crying.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
