<SLUG> BC-NY-BEETLES-INFEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TREES ARE DOOMED AS BEETLE STRIKES AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   By EUN LEE KOH   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Asian longhorned beetles, which have destroyed nearly
3,000 trees in New York City since their first appearance in the
Greenpoint section of Brooklyn four years ago, have invaded the
trees that line Luther Gulick Playground near the Williamsburg
Bridge, Parks Commissioner Henry Stern said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The infected trees _ at least six of the park's 34 Norway maples
_ will be removed beginning Monday, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beetles pose an enormous long-term danger to the city's
forests and to trees all along the Northeast,'' Stern said. ``All
of humanity is together in fighting this. This is biological
warfare and we are on the side of the trees.''
</P>
<P>
   If more trees are affected by the 2-inch-long, black-spotted
insects, he said, they too will be cut down; it is the only remedy
for a longhorned beetle infestation.
</P>
<P>
   The Parks Department learned of the infestation when inspectors
found pencil-sized holes made by the burrowing beetles in the
tree's trunks, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   The insects make such holes to bury their eggs. The larvae hatch
in the spring and tunnel into the trees, feeding on the wood and
destroying the tree.
</P>
<P>
   Because the beetles have no natural predators in the United
States, the only way to stop the spread of the insect is to chop
down infected trees, then chip and burn them to destroy both the
beetle and its eggs, Stern said.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Parks Department announced a major effort to fight
the longhorned beetle, with more than $10 million _ more than ever
before _ in city, state and federal money budgeted to inspect
trees, cut down those that show evidence of an infestation and
replace them with seedlings.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's worse than cancer,'' Stern said of the beetle invasion.
``You can't just cut out the infected areas, you have to kill the
entire tree to get rid of them. You have to sacrifice the tree to
save the forest.''
</P>
<P>
   The Parks Department suspects that the beetle, responsible for
the destruction of a huge expanse of forest in China, hitched a
ride to the United States on imported crates, landing at the docks
in Greenpoint.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Parks and Recreation first detected the
beetles in Greenpoint in 1996. Last August the insects invaded
Ruppert Playground, a park in Manhattan's Upper East Side, and 28
trees had to be destroyed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
