<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3942 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-LAZIO-SEC-NYT &LR;      06-24 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LAZIO-SEC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR SEC, QUESTION IS WHAT LAZIO KNEW 
</HEADLINE>
   By FLOYD NORRIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Securities and Exchange Commission, in deciding to
investigate whether Rep. Rick Lazio violated insider trading laws,
acted on the basis of information that suggested _ but hardly
proved _ that he might have known about a pending takeover that had
not been disclosed to the public.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the information that prompted the investigation was on
the public record for two years before the SEC acted, but it was
evidently not put together by anyone until Lazio, a Republican,
began running for the U.S. Senate from New York. Aides to Lazio
said last week that he had received a request for information from
the SEC staff early in the week.
</P>
<P>
   The details, in brief, are that when Lazio made what seems to
have been his first purchase of stock options ever _ securities
that essentially represent a bet that a stock will rise
significantly in a short period of time _ the company he bought the
options on was actively, but confidentially, looking for another
company to buy it out.
</P>
<P>
   To SEC investigators, that in itself would arouse suspicion. A
first-time options buyer who gets lucky enough to profit from a
takeover typically draws questions from the SEC on whether the
trader might have had a relationship with an insider privy to
confidential information.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, a relationship did exist. Top executives of the
company, the Quick &AMP; Reilly brokerage firm, were major contributors
to Lazio's campaigns. Some of them were also executives of the
Securities Industry Association, which actively lobbies the House
Subcommittee on Finance, on which Lazio serves, because it has
jurisdiction over many issues directly affecting the brokerage
business.
</P>
<P>
   Securities lawyers say that combination _ unusual trading
considering an investor's history and a connection to people with
inside information about an unannounced takeover _ would prompt an
investigation by the SEC in virtually any case of which it became
aware.
</P>
<P>
   But the relatively meager profits earned by Lazio _ $21,509
altogether, including his investments in other Quick &AMP; Reilly
securities _ meant that his trading was unlikely to have been
noticed by the SEC in its normal market monitoring, which relies
heavily on the stock and options exchanges for leads.
</P>
<P>
   The Quick &AMP; Reilly transaction, moreover, seems not to have
generated a large amount of suspicious trading in advance, making
it unlikely that either the Chicago Board Options Exchange or the
New York Stock Exchange, the primary markets for Quick &AMP; Reilly
options and shares, respectively, would have referred any
suspicious trading to the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio disclosed most, but not all, of his trades in Quick &AMP;
Reilly securities in a filing with Congress in the spring of 1998.
Disclosure of the additional trades, which was made after reporters
for The New York Times concluded that the original trading records
could not have been complete, did not appear to raise any new
questions about Lazio's trading activity.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio and officials of Quick &AMP; Reilly vigorously deny that he
was given any inside information. If the SEC finds no evidence that
he was, the inquiry will be dropped. That is what happens in many
such investigations.
</P>
<P>
   But the SEC staff has more investigative options than simply
asking Lazio and the Quick &AMP; Reilly people if he received inside
information. If the commissioners authorize subpoenas, the staff
can search phone records or interview anyone who might have made
other similarly timed investments in the firm.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio's first trade in Quick &AMP; Reilly securities came on Feb.
11, 1997, when he bought 300 shares for $11,665. Simultaneously, in
a trade he did not disclose on his congressional report but did
disclose this month, he sold options that gave the buyer the right
to buy those shares for a price slightly above what Lazio paid.
</P>
<P>
   Together, those transactions represented a very conservative
strategy that meant that if the stock did rise Lazio would earn a
small profit. If it fell, however, the $392 he got for selling the
options would cushion the loss.
</P>
<P>
   As it happened, the stock price rose only briefly, after Quick &AMP;
Reilly announced the stock split, and then declined. The options
expired without being exercised, and Lazio was left with 450 shares
of stock after the split took effect.
</P>
<P>
   On June 24, he bought another 50 shares of stock, paying $1,217.
That left his average cost per share for the 500 shares he then
owned at about $25. Including the commission he would have to pay,
he would have to get a price of about $25.50 per share to break
even. But the stock never got that high until July 31.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Friday, Aug. 1, with the stock price rising on
above-normal volume, and activity in the options markets up as
well, Lazio could have sold his stake and made a small profit.
Instead, he bought options that allowed him to buy 1,200 more
shares, at a price of $30, any time until Oct. 17. On the following
Monday, he bought options on 600 more shares in a trade that was
not disclosed on his congressional filing.
</P>
<P>
   On Aug. 11, word leaked to Bloomberg News that the company had
hired investment bankers to seek buyers, and the stock price
soared. Lazio waited a few weeks to cash in his options, and sold
his shares the following January, shortly before Fleet Financial
completed its acquisition of Quick &AMP; Reilly.
</P>
<P>
   He earned a profit of $13,643, or nearly 600 percent, on the
August options purchases, and a profit of $7,866 on his other
trades in Quick &AMP; Reilly securities. Overall, his profit came to
142 percent of the $15,183 he invested.
</P>
<P>
   Lazio has said he bought the options as a takeover speculation,
on the advice of someone he has declined to name. A review of
databases found no report in any newspaper or investment wire about
such speculation before he bought the options on Aug. 1, although
Dow Jones News Service carried a report a few hours after he made
his options investment.
</P>
<P>
   But rising volume in options did indicate that speculation was
growing by the time he made his investment.
</P>
<P>
   Buying options on the basis of a rumor is legal, unless the
buyer has learned from an insider that the rumor is true. But
insider trading cases have been prosecuted when people with
confidential information about a coming takeover simply advised
others that it was not a good time to sell.
</P>
<P>
   For the SEC, an independent agency that normally conducts its
investigation with little public attention until it files charges,
the Lazio case is already proving to be a difficult one. Although
the investigation had begun before the agency received a request
for an inquiry from H. Carl McCall, the New York state comptroller,
McCall's letter helped to create a political tone.
</P>
<P>
   McCall, an ally of Hillary Rodham Clinton, Lazio's Senate
opponent, sent the request on his own campaign stationery. Lazio
was quick to denounce the SEC inquiry as politically motivated.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the SEC is under considerable pressure to complete
its inquiry before the November election.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
