<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3943 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-GAY-GAMES-ART-NYT &LR;      06-24 1143
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GAY-GAMES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMPETITION AND CAMARADERIE FOR GAY ATHLETES
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo NYT 9 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By SOPHIA HOLLANDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Laura Moore was growing up, she dreamed of being an Olympic
figure skater. While living in East Africa, she read a book about a
poor, sickly child befriended by a star skater. The sickly girl
became the star.
</P>
<P>
   The reality was different. Shy and klutzy, incapable of catching
a ball, Moore failed gym 12 times. During kickball games she
switched teams every half-inning so she would not have to play, and
nobody complained because they didn't want her playing, either. She
graduated from high school with a special dispensation because she
did not have a single gym credit.
</P>
<P>
   So it came as a surprise when she later found herself through
sports, specifically in competitions among gay athletes.
</P>
<P>
   Moore realized she was gay at an early age, but by the time she
was 30 she found herself married and living in the suburbs,
desperately ill with a stress-related disease and hating everything
about her life. So, 12 years ago, she left her husband, moved to
New York City and signed up for an ice skating class.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1994 Gay Games in New York, she initiated a figure
skating meet _ overcoming skepticism from organizers that the event
would not flourish during the summer games _ and became part of the
first lesbian pairs team to compete. She and her partner won the
gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty exciting, to say the least,'' said Moore, who is
now 44. ``I finally felt like, OK, this is the life that I was
supposed to have. I know I'm never going to do a triple jump. I'm
never going to be in the Olympics. But I have done more with
skating and skating has done more for me than I could ever have
imagined. I totally feel for the first time in my life that I am
part of a community. I belong to a global gay sports community.''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is now the vice president of Team New York, an
organization that was reinvented in late 1997 to foster sports and
cultural events for gays and lesbians. Saturday, Team New York
sponsored three events as part of the second annual Team New York
Sports and Cultural Festival during Gay Pride Week: a two-mile
community challenge run in Central Park, the NYSwimillennium2000, a
14-event swim meet at Lehman College in the Bronx, and the Metro
Gay Wrestling Alliance Tournament and Open Mat Clinic at the
McBurney YMCA Annex in Manhattan. The run was expected to draw
about 1,000 people, the swim meet up to 200 entrants from four
countries. Team New York has existed since the first Gay Games in
San Francisco in 1982 and has sent athletes to all four quadrennial
games since. But the group disbanded after each Games and hurriedly
reorganized just before the next one. In 1997, an officer for the
1998 Gay Games in Amsterdam phoned Ruth Gursky _ an active
volunteer since the 1990 Vancouver Games _ and asked her to set up
a meeting to generate interest in New York. Gursky called everyone
she knew, took out two ads in community newspapers, reserved a room
and hoped for the best.
</P>
<P>
   One hundred and fifty people showed up.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``It showed all of us that there was a need to have an
organization, it was just a question of who was going to do it,''
said Gursky. ``I realized it was going to be me or nobody.''
</P>
<P>
   She recruited a treasurer and a co-president and started having
meetings. Team New York is now associated with groups that
participate in 20 sports, including square dancing, table tennis,
softball, volleyball and swimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many gay and lesbian people feel funny, feel awkward, feel
they're not being accepted on a regular team,'' said Gursky, who
also swims on a masters team. ``I think we can really make a
difference in people's lives.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Participation in gay and lesbian sports has increased steadily,
both in New York and worldwide. The 1982 San Francisco Gay Games
had 1,350 athletes and a budget of $125,000, while the '94 New York
Games had 11,000 athletes and a $6.5 million budget. Both numbers
are expected to be much higher for the 2002 Games in Sydney,
Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Blane Roberts, a former vice president of Front Runners, a gay
and lesbian running group, said the New York chapter had 431
members in 1996. Now there are 460. Directly after the Amsterdam
Games in '98, an average of five wrestlers showed up weekly at the
Metro Gay Wrestling Alliance; now the number has nearly tripled.
Last year, the open house for the International Gay Figure Skating
Union, co-founded by Moore, drew six people. This year there were
50.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've observed that a lot of gay and lesbian men or women were
either intimidated by athletics, didn't feel that they could
compete, were uncomfortable with the situation,'' said Mike
Colgrove, the vice president and coach of the Metro Gay Wrestling
Alliance. ``We get a lot of people who are interested but are
afraid to try it, not because of their ability but because of how
they might be perceived. I think this gives a lot of gay men and
lesbian women an opportunity to try things they might have been
afraid of before.''
</P>
<P>
   For others, the increasing visibility of the Gay Games made
competing in sports a welcome alternative to a social scene that
consisted mainly of bars and clubs. ``I knew very few gay people
and I was going to the bars,'' said Barbara Gurtov, 55, who bowls
in a gay and lesbian league at Chelsea Piers. ``And I got sick of
the bars because I'm not a bar person and in those days they didn't
have many functions and now they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Although friendship and support are the key components to many
of the gay and lesbian clubs, competition is also important, many
of the club leaders say.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a total comfort level,'' Stephen DeRose, treasurer of
Team New York and a two-time Gay Games gold medalist for
bodybuilding, said of gay competitions. ``You could be who you
wanted to be. Jump up and down and scream. Clap and not have to
worry, `He's going to think I'm gay.'''
</P>
<P>
   Moore is still astonished by her metamorphosis from unhappy,
uncoordinated homemaker to medal-winning figure skater immersed in
a loving and accepting community.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you had told me when I was a child that I would become a
competitive athlete and I was going to have a drawer full of medals
and I was going to do something that people the world over are
going to be interested in because no one's ever done it before, I
would have laughed in their faces,'' she said. ``There are now so
many opportunities to meet people and participate in activities
that are healthy and fun. I really believe that the gay sports
movement has changed a lot of people's lives.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1743EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
