<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3945 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-BEACHFRONT-REAL-2TAKE     06-24 0802
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEACHFRONT-REAL-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REAL ESTATE: OCEAN-FRONT HOUSING BENEFITS FROM BEACH RESTORATION 
</HEADLINE>
   By DIANA SHAMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST HAMPTON DUNES, N.Y. _ The 2.25-mile stretch of Dune Road
that runs the length of this village on a barrier beach facing the
Atlantic in southeastern Suffolk County has the air of a gold-rush
town.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of houses are either being built or rebuilt. The village
is rapidly regaining the 190 houses that were once lost or made
uninhabitable by three decades of severe beach erosion. A $17
million publicly financed beach rebuilding project, completed in
1997, stabilized and expanded the beach and restored its dunes,
leading to the current building boom.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Vegliante, the mayor of West Hampton Dunes, said that in
the last 12 months, 25 houses have been completed and 40 are under
construction. He said he expects another 35 houses to be finished
in the next year. Since the village began rebuilding in 1996, 200
certificates of occupancy, including those for new houses on
formerly vacant lots, have been issued, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The beach restoration has worked so well that a sand
replenishment project, originally scheduled for last year, has been
postponed until this fall.
</P>
<P>
   Other public officials are much less enthusiastic about the
project, but whatever the view, it's generally agreed that the
beach restoration has had an unexpected but positive side effect.
The piping plover, an endangered migratory bird that had all but
vanished from the area, has flourished since the beach was rebuilt.
Thirty-three breeding pairs and 72 fledglings were counted last
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe this to be a blueprint for successful coastal
management because what we have clearly proven is that what used to
be competing interests can come together and have a vested interest
that's common to everyone's needs and goals,'' said Vegliante, who
helped establish the 1.5-square-mile village in 1993. The
population is now about 550.
</P>
<P>
   ``Public access to the beaches can cohabitate with private
property rights,'' the mayor said. ``And something that no one
believed could be done, the creation and enhancement of
environmental habitat, is resulting in a piping plover population
that is greater than that of Connecticut, New Hampshire and Rhode
Island combined.''
</P>
<P>
   Sand erosion along this strip of barrier beach, which lies
between the Atlantic and Moriches Bay just east of Cupsogue Beach
County Park, began occurring after 1964 when the Army Corps of
Engineers constructed 15 groins, also known as jetties, east of
what is now the village's eastern boundary. The groins trapped
sand, keeping it from replenishing the western end of the beach.
Soon homeowners there were seeing houses undermined by water, and
storms swept many of them away.
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, all but 18 of the 160 ocean-front houses were lost, and
most of the village's total of 250 houses had been destroyed or
severely damaged. Dune Road, covered with sand, was impassable; the
county park was closed.
</P>
<P>
   A December 1992 storm made an opening between the Atlantic and
Moriches Bay just west of the last groin, creating an island. The
gap quickly widened to 3,000 feet, threatening the ecology of the
brackish Moriches Bay, covering 5,000 acres, by allowing in greater
amounts of salt water. Had the remaining barrier beach west of the
breach been eaten away, the heavily populated areas north of the
bay would have become much more vulnerable to flooding from storms.
</P>
<P>
   It cost $8.8 million to close the breach, a project federal,
state and local officials undertook late in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a lawsuit by owners who had lost their houses to
reach a settlement that led to the beach restoration project. The
first lawsuit, against Suffolk County, was filed in 1984 by
property owners who had formed the Barrier Beach Preservation
Association. The suit was later expanded to include the federal and
state governments. The homeowners contended that the erosion
project begun in 1964 _ and financed by all three governments _
caused the loss of their homes. Represented by John J. O'Connell, a
Manhattan lawyer, the owners sought $200 million in damages.
</P>
<P>
   In a 1994 settlement, the three defendants agreed to restore the
beach and dunes and to maintain them for 30 years by replenishing
any sand that might be lost to erosion. To allow public access to
the ocean and bay while protecting the dunes, 11 wooden walkways
were to be built, and so far, nine have been completed.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government is paying 70 percent of the restoration
costs, New York state is paying 21 percent and Suffolk County is
paying 9 percent. The total cost is estimated at $50 million _
about two-thirds the original estimate _ by the time the project
ends in 2027.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   David and Carol Zolondek have reconstructed their ocean-front
house.
</P>
<P>
   ``We built our house in 1980, it was washed away in 1993, and we
rebuilt in 1998,'' said Zolondek, who owns a textile export company
in Manhattan. ``When you watch the beach deteriorating, and houses
wash away, and your neighbors suffering, it's not pleasant because
it was such a nice community that we had,'' he said. ``And now to
see people rebuilding their houses and putting money into them, and
families with children coming back, it's a renewal.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the lawsuit settlement agreement, owners had to make some
concessions. For lots on the south side of Dune Road, the owners
had to agree to transfer to Suffolk County everything on the ocean
side of the new dunes . The dunes, although owned by the
individuals whose property they are on, were designated a
conservation area, and they can be crossed only by wooden walkways
that individual homeowners must build.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of ocean-front lots have only 50 feet, measured northward
from the dunes, within which to construct a house, because they
must allow for a 25-foot setback from Dune Road. In addition, all
houses must stand on stilts that are a minimum of 12 feet high.
Under the village building code the house itself cannot be higher
than 32 feet above the platform's lowest beam.
</P>
<P>
   Building is prohibited in parts of the bay side of Dune Road
between April 1 and Sept. 1, the nesting season of the piping
plover. Construction has to stop anywhere in the village if a nest
is discovered near the building site.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the restrictions, land prices have soared in the last
three years, and West Hampton Dunes, once characterized by modest
beach houses. A 60-foot wide ocean-front lot sold for $70,000 five
years ago, said Christopher Foglio, a sales agent with the Coldwell
Banker brokerage company in Westhampton. Now the same size lot is
selling for $400,000, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Legacy Development USA of Hauppauge, which has 21 houses either
completed or under construction, has sold all but four. Prices for
the unsold houses, two on the ocean, are $880,000 to $1.35 million.
Citi Habitats in Manhattan is the sales agent.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Heiberger, the president of Legacy, said that ocean-front
houses like the 2,900-square-foot traditional house, with five
bedrooms, four and a half baths and a guest suite, that he sold a
year ago for $883,000 are now fetching $1.3 million. The reason, he
said, is that people are gaining confidence that the beach is no
longer endangered.
</P>
<P>
   Heiberger said he became aware of building opportunities in West
Hampton Dunes after his son Andrew, who is president of Citi
Habitats, saw an ocean-front lot advertised for $175,000 at the end
of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came out here to take a look,'' Ed Heiberger said, ``and
said: `This is just beautiful. What's happening here?'''
</P>
<P>
   Legacy builds a mix of Victorian, Mediterranean and what it
calls Plantation and Island Beach houses. The $1.1 million
Mediterranean style house under construction on the ocean is fairly
typical: it has a pool, and three of the four bedrooms and a den
are on the first floor. The living areas and master bedroom are on
the second floor, which offers the best views.
</P>
<P>
   Another large builder active in the area is Island Estates of
Ronkonkoma. It has two houses under construction. A five-bedroom
ocean-front house on a 75-foot-wide lot with a pool is priced at
$1.250 million. The other on Moriches Bay on a 60-by-600-foot lot,
also with five bedrooms and a pool, is priced at $999,000. The
company has yet to build on 12 other lots it owns along Dune Road,
said Rudy Princi, one of the principals.
</P>
<P>
   While some public officials call West Hampton Dunes a success
story, others contend that the restoration was a waste of taxpayer
dollars and that a better settlement of the lawsuit could have been
reached. They say that public money should not have been used to
stabilize the beach so that private owners of ocean- front lots
could build, allowing erosion problems to start once again. These
critics contend that the lots should have been bought up and made
part of the public beach.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is now being debated anew as a similar beach
restoration project is being considered farther west, along the
32-mile length of Fire Island.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a supporter of the notion of a new dune and pumping sand
onto the beach and trying to stabilize the flow of sediment from
east to west, but not to build houses on it,'' said Stephen Jones,
Suffolk County's planning director. ``I feel terrible about what is
happening at West Hampton Dunes. To stabilize the shoreline and
then build houses on the beach is a real perversion of public
policy.''
</P>
<P>
   But others say it is only fair that if houses were lost because
of government action, then homeowners should be allowed to keep
their property and rebuild.
</P>
<P>
   Jane Ekstein, the executive director of Save Our Seashore, a
nonprofit group formed in 1992 to lobby for the preservation and
protection of coastal resources from Montauk to Coney Island,
pointed out that protecting the coastline safeguards the property,
businesses and well-being of the people living on the South Shore.
Millions benefit from the recreation that beaches provide, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not about creating building lots,'' she said. ``This
is about developing the common goal of saving a fabulous resource
and understanding that to do so, everyone must work together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
