<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-HKN-DRAFT-NYT &LR;      06-24 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DRAFT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLES DRAFT A GOALIE AND MAKE 2 BIG TRADES
</HEADLINE>
  By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CALGARY, Alberta _ Hoping to reverse a long slide into
irrelevance and buoyed by the financial promises of new ownership,
the New York Islanders moved aggressively, dramatically and with
high risk Saturday at the NHL entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   They made two major trades, losing two goalies, including the
highly touted Roberto Luongo. They acquired two young players from
Florida, both of them forwards. And they drafted two of the first
five players, including the first overall.
</P>
<P>
   That opening pick was historic: Rick DiPietro, a Maine native
from Boston University, became the first goalie ever chosen first
overall. Mike Milbury, the Islanders' general manager, strongly
suggested that the 18-year-old DiPietro, with one year of college
experience, will be the first-string goalie next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``As dangerous as this might be, maybe Mad Mike has something
going for him,'' Milbury said of his dealings. ``We have not made
the playoffs in far too long. We need to get there. It's a roll of
the dice a little bit.'' The Islanders last reached the playoffs in
1994.
</P>
<P>
   Milbury compared DiPietro to Tom Barrasso, who had a record of
26-12-3 for the Buffalo Sabres as an 18-year-old rookie in 1983-84.
DiPietro seemed willing to accept the challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel relieved the day is over and we made a little
history,'' DiPietro said. ``I was pleasantly surprised to hear my
name called. I'm just happy it was me, to tell you the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   Can he step into a major role in the NHL? ``I don't know,''
DiPietro said. ``I have never been to an NHL training camp. I feel
pretty confident. It's obviously very mind boggling.''
</P>
<P>
   Referring to the Islanders' decision to trade Luongo and draft
him, DiPietro said: ``Obviously, there's going to be a lot of
pressure. Roberto Luongo will probably end up being a franchise
goaltender with Florida. I enjoy the pressure.''
</P>
<P>
   With their second choice, fifth overall in the first round due
to a trade with Tampa, the Islanders selected Raffi Torres, a
stocky left wing from Canada who scored 43 goals with Brampton last
season in the Ontario junior league. Torres is the son of a father
born in Mexico and a mother born in Peru. He started playing hockey
on roller skates in his basement.
</P>
<P>
   Scott Gomez of the Devils won rookie of the year honors last
season as the league's first Hispanic star, and Torres was asked
about comparisons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gomez was a highlight player in his first year,'' Torres said.
``I'd like to follow in his footsteps. I'm so excited. It's crazy.
It's crazy! I can't even talk.''
</P>
<P>
   Milbury said he was not sure if Torres, 18, is ready for the
NHL, because there are questions about his skating. It will be
determined by how hard he works this summer, before training camp,
Milbury said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In trades, the Islanders sent Luongo, their top goalie prospect
until Saturday, to Florida along with center Olli Jokinen for
center Oleg Kvasha and right wing Mark Parrish. In order to choose
Torres with the fifth pick, originally a Tampa choice, they sent
goalie Kevin Weekes and Kristian Kudroc, a defensive prospect, to
the Lightning along with the second-round pick in the 2001 entry
draft. As part of the deal, the Islanders obtained Tampa's
fourth-round pick in the current draft, which will conclude Sunday,
and a seventh-round pick that was originally traded to Tampa in
March.
</P>
<P>
   DiPietro went 17-3-5 last season with a goals-against average of
2.44. He is 5 feet 11 inches, 185 pounds, and made the tournament
All-Star team when he played for the United States in the World
Junior tournament. He set a NCAA record with 77 saves in one game,
a 3-2 defeat in overtime.
</P>
<P>
   According to the NHL's Central Scouting service, DiPietro plays
with the style of Martin Brodeur, the veteran goalie of the Stanley
Cup champion Devils.
</P>
<P>
   ``Handles the puck extremely well,'' the report said. ``Is very
good at setting up the puck for his defensemen. A very good skater,
with excellent agility and balance. Uses his stick well to deflect
pucks away from the net. Has a very quick glove hand and uses his
blocker to angle shots into the corner very well.''
</P>
<P>
   The Devils, with seven picks among the first 76, chose David
Hale with the 22nd pick in the first round. Hale is a 6-1,
204-pound defenseman who grew up in Colorado and plays junior
hockey with Sioux City, Iowa, of the United States Hockey League.
</P>
<P>
   The Central Scouting report said of Hale: ``An intense,
punishing player who can intimidate opponents. Has an excellent
work ethic.''
</P>
<P>
   The first round was dominated by European prospects. The third
pick was Marian Gaborik, a left wing from Slovakia, chosen by the
expansion team in Minnesota. The fourth pick was Rostislav Klesla,
a defenseman from the Czech Republic who has been playing with
Brampton. Among other choices in the first round was Dany Heatley,
a Canadian forward from the University of Wisconsin, taken by
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Kvasha, obtained by the Islanders in the Florida trade, scored
five goals and had 20 assists last season in 78 games. He is a
Moscow native who stands 6-5 and weighs 216 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   Parrish, who also came from Florida, grew up in Minnesota and
like Kvasha has played two years with Florida. Parrish, 5-11 and
191 pounds, scored 26 goals and 18 assists in 81 games with the
Panthers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
