<P>
   (NYT11) LINCOLN, Ala. -- June 24, 2000 -- HONDA-TOWN-COX-2 --
Like many places in the rural South, jobs have been the only thing
missing from the country utopia in Lincoln, Ala. Last year,
economic salvation rolled into town with front-wheel drive and
seating for seven. Auto giant Honda committed $440 million to turn
farmland into a 1.7 million-square-foot factory to build its
Odyssey minivan, one of the hottest sellers in the country. The new
Honda plant under construction in Lincoln, Ala. (Louie Favorite/Cox
News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LINCOLN, Ala. -- June 24, 2000 -- HONDA-TOWN-COX-1 --
Last year, economic salvation rolled into the town of Lincoln, Ala.
in the form of front-wheel drive and seating for seven. Auto giant
Honda committed $440 million to turn farmland into a 1.7
million-square-foot factory. Progress, Lincoln is learning, comes
with a bulldozer. In the end, the urbanization of the small-town
South costs more than money. It can turn lifestyles upside down.
Sharon Denson, 46, outside her Lincoln Cafe, was offered $1000 by
the state to move her business in order to widen the road to four
lanes. ``The only thing I want is was what I put into my
business,'' says Denson. (Louie Favorite/Cox News Service Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- June 24, 2000 -- GAY-GAMES -- Participation
in gay and lesbian sports has increased steadily, both in New York
and worldwide. For many gay people, the increasing visibility of
the Gay Games made competing in sports a welcome alternative to a
social scene that consisted mainly of bars and clubs. ``Although
friendship and support are the key components to many of the gay
and lesbian clubs, competition is also important,'' says Stephen
DeRose, treasurer of Team New York and a two-time Gay Games gold
medalist for bodybuilding. (Ozier Muhammad/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- June 24, 2000 -- NY-LAW-ENFORCEMENT -- Across
New York City, in the drug holes and seedy side streets and shadowy
hot spots where crime incubates, the police department continues to
be seen as an aggressive force that has not retreated -- not one
small inch -- from its kitchen-sink strategy of attacking crime.
True or not, and police officials say it is not, people who live
and work in New York City's roughest neighborhoods seem largely in
agreement that they are victims of aggressive policing by the NYPD.
Paul Sparks, left, and Jose Fontanez, hanging out near the Port
Authority bus terminal in Manhattan, a rough spot of the city to
this day. (James Estrin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) CHICAGO -- June 24, 2000 -- LIPSYTE-COLUMN-2 -- An
internship with General Electric and a plan to surprise a sorority
sister by attending her wedding, are not what most people would
think of when thinking of an Olympic caliber athlete in training.
Yet for Khadijah Conda, 26, these matters are testing her will as
an athlete. Conda who has all of the ``tools'' -- the leg speed,
strength and stamina -- of an Olympic champion, recently has been
bedeviled with ``crazy thoughts.'' ``I have to keep reminding
myself this is something I want,'' she says. (Steve Kagan/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) CHICAGO -- June 24, 2000 -- LIPSYTE-COLUMN-1 -- At the
world class level in professional sports, where all athletes are
gifted and strong, it is a competitor's will, not skill, that makes
the difference between winning and going home early. Khadijah
Conda, 26, has world-class talent in the 400-meter run and still
has a chance at next month's Olympic track-and-field trials, but
she has seemed more interested recently in off-the-track events
including an internship and a friend's wedding. (Steve Kagan/The
New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NAIROBI, Kenya -- June 24, 2000 -- KENYA-CRISIS -- It is
indeed dark in Kenya these days, and not just because electricity
is in such short supply. Kenya, once among the most stable and
prosperous nations in Africa, is facing its worst-ever crisis. Even
before the drought hitting the region, the economy was strangling
from years of corruption and poor management. The phones and roads
are barely passable. Students are rioting. Tourists, afraid of
runaway crime, are staying away. Maggie Mukungu, a Nairobi
hairdresser, has been turning customers away, asking them to return
when the electricity is on. ``It's carelessness,'' she says of the
government. ``They don't know what they are doing.'' (Ian
Fisher/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SEOUL, South Korea -- KOREAN-WAR-ANNIVERSARY-4 -- South
Korean protestors, including students and human rights activists,
hurl eggs at a picture of an ``Uncle Sam'' hat, during a
demonstration outside the U.S. Eighth Army base in Seoul. The
demonstration was against the resumption of bombing drills by the
U.S. Air Force at Koon-Ni. Local residents and civic groups have
demanded the range be moved. The protests came on the eve of 50th
anniversary ceremonies to mark the start of the Korean War. (Chang.
W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) INCHON, South Korea -- June 24, 2000 --
KOREAN-WAR-ANNIVERSARY-3 -- Fifty years after North Korea attacked
the South as Koreans slept, Korean War veterans from the United
States and elsewhere gathered at former battlegrounds this week to
remember. Sgt. Sean Melanphy of the United States Marine Color
Guard during the 50th Anniversary of the Korean War Commemoration
ceremony at Freedom Park in Incheon, South Korea, where some 50
American Korean-War veterans participated this week. (Chang. W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) SEOUL, South Korea -- June 24, 2000 --
KOREAN-WAR-ANNIVERSARY-2 -- As North Korea has agreed to pursue
peace and reconciliation with the South after a half-century of
hostilities, the South Korean government has canceled all parades,
battle re-enactments and other commemorative war events that could
be offensive to the North. Kim Min Uk of the South Korean Navy
rested last week during a rehearsal for a ceremony at the Korean
War memorial in Seoul. The ceremony on Sunday is part of a
toned-down observance of the war's 50th anniversary. (Chang. W.
Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) INCHON, South Korea -- June 24, 2000 --
KOREAN-WAR-ANNIVERSARY-1 -- The recent decision by the South Korean
government to tone down the 50th anniversary celebrations
commemorating the Korean War has not only brought angry
denouncements from veterans, but it has also touched off a heated
national debate over the significance of the Korean War and how far
the South should go to appease the North. The debate comes as
hundreds of veterans, diplomats and officials from around the world
have arrive in Seoul to participate in commemoration events. U.S.
veterans at Freedom Park with a statue of Gen. Douglas MacArthur in
Inchon, South Korea. (Chang. W. Lee/The New York Times)
</P>
