<HEADER>
A3963 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-OLY-U.S.-WRESTLING-NY     06-24 0832
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-U.S.-WRESTLING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUTS IN COLLEGE PROGRAMS SEEN AS ENDANGERING FUTURE U.S. TEAM
GOALS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Hawaii, Ky., Mo.)   By LIZ ROBBINS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ At the U.S. Olympic trials here last week, Jim Scherr,
USA Wrestling's executive director, made a bold prediction. He said
the men's Greco-Roman and freestyle teams would make frequent
appearances on the podium in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this will be the best Olympic team we've ever
fielded,'' Scherr said in Reunion Arena Thursday night. ``We could
get three to four medals in Greco-Roman and eight medals in
freestyle.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, when the Greco-Roman and freestyle teams each carried
10 weight classes instead of the eight now required under
international rules, U.S. Greco-Roman wrestlers won three silver
medals and freestyle wrestlers won three golds, a silver and a
bronze.
</P>
<P>
   Scherr expressed his beliefs before the 16 wrestlers had even
qualified for the 2000 Olympic teams, a testament to the wealth of
candidates vying for the honor.
</P>
<P>
   But how long will his optimism carry? Wrestling is thriving at
both the international and grass-roots levels, and even receiving
energy from the success of girls' and women's wrestling. But the
crucial middle link is gradually corroding.
</P>
<P>
   College wrestling has become an endangered species in the last
28 years, with more than half the programs disappearing.
</P>
<P>
   There were 750 programs in 1972, the year that Title IX was
enacted; now there are barely 300 and falling at a steady rate as
universities cut nonrevenue wrestling programs to enforce equity
with women's sports.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a tremendous following for the sport, but we have an
artificial bottleneck at the collegiate level,'' Scherr said. ``As
far as USA Wrestling is concerned, dropping collegiate programs
could affect Olympic programs.''
</P>
<P>
   Scherr sees no immediate solution to persuading universities to
keep wrestling. Coincidentally, women's wrestling is beginning to
become popular, but even that may not be able to help the cause of
men's wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   ``If colleges start women's wrestling, it would make it more
difficult to drop men's wrestling, but it's not enough to save NCAA
wrestling,'' said Mike Duroe, the women's national coach, referring
to programs at NCAA schools. ``The issue, in my opinion, is that
wrestling is being used as a scapegoat. It's easy to drop wrestling
where it's not popular.''
</P>
<P>
   But wrestling is popular on the high school level. In 1999,
boys' high school participants were at an all-time high, at
235,973, making it the sixth most popular sport for boys. In 1999,
2,361 girls participated in high school wrestling, and two states _
Texas and Hawaii _ officially sanctioned girls' wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Three varsity teams compete at NAIA schools _ Minnesota Morris,
Cumberland (Ky.) College and Missouri Valley College. The latter
two programs began last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be progressive thinking,'' Gary Abbott, USA
Wrestling's director of communications, said. ``Women's wrestling
is just as exciting, just as athletic, as men's.'' He proposes that
women's college programs should wrestle in the spring and compete
under the international rules of freestyle (men wrestle freestyle
in college), so that women can be better prepared for world
competition.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time, the women's senior national team
won the world championships. Tricia Saunders, 34, whose husband,
Townsend, won a silver medal at the Atlanta Olympics in 1996,
captured her fourth world championship last year as the United
States took the title from perennial power Japan.
</P>
<P>
   Women compete in six weight classes, ranging from 101.25 to
165.25 pounds. Although the world championships for women first
took place in 1990, the United States has fielded and funded a
national team for only three years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with USA Wrestling said they anticipated women's
wrestling to be on the program for the 2004 Games in Athens.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are going to be paying a lot more attention to women's
wrestling in the next couple of years,'' Abbott predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Women's wrestling is not as accepted in this country as it is in
Japan, Canada and the Scandinavian countries. That could change
when women's wrestling will be included with men's wrestling next
year at the world championships.
</P>
<P>
   The Olympics serve as this year's wrestling world championships.
But in September 2001, Greco-Roman, freestyle and women's wrestling
will be on the same bill for the first time when the championships
come to New York City. Scherr is eager to show off the sport on
such a grand stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hope because of the success we've had this will have a
larger impact at the Games in Athens,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   At these Olympic trials, Scherr admitted his concern for the
sport's growth on the collegiate level, but preferred to focus on
Sydney, hoping that the wrestlers' success there will enable the
sport to become rooted outside its loyal community.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
