<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 18:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-RUN-ROMANIA-NYT &LR;      06-24 0966
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-ROMANIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROMANIA'S CHAMPION TRACK STAR GABRIELA SZABO AIMS FOR RECORD BEFORE
OLYMPICS 
</HEADLINE>
   By JERE LONGMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ She stands only 5 feet 2 inches and weighs 93
pounds, with short blond hair and glasses, and modesty that causes
her to lower her eyes when she greets a stranger.
</P>
<P>
   She is Gabriela Szabo of Romania, and at first glance she does
not seem to be the world's greatest female middle-distance runner
or the first woman ever to win $1 million in prize money in one
season on the European track circuit. She might never have run at
all if a teacher had not encouraged her at age 13 to enter a school
race in Bistrita, a town in Transylvania.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one runs in my family,'' Szabo said. ``My parents are fat.
My mother ran maybe 100 meters once and said, `OK, that's
enough.'''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo took the advice of her physical education teacher and
entered a cross-country race of 600 meters, the equivalent of one
and a half laps around a track. She won easily, and a coach from a
local sports club noticed that she was not even breathing hard at
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, you come tomorrow,'' said the coach from the club.
</P>
<P>
   It was a chance conversation that would take the unordered life
of a teen-ager and place it on a structured path to international
greatness. Three months later, Szabo finished second in a national
race of 600 meters for Romanian children. She later attended a
special high school for athletes, and with training, an efficient
shuffling stride and a blistering kick, she won a silver medal at
1,500 meters, the metric mile, at the 1996 Summer Olympics in
Atlanta. Last summer she won the world championship at 5,000
meters, or 3.1 miles, collected $1 million in prize money and was
named the international female track athlete of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Szabo had not lost a race since August 1998 as she entered the
1,500 meters Saturday at the Prefontaine Classic. At age 24, Szabo
is favored to win the 5,000 meters at the 2000 Summer Olympics in
Sydney, Australia, by which time she hopes to have broken the world
record of 14 minutes 28.09 seconds, held by Jiang Bo of China.
Szabo's best time is 14:31.48. She was favored to win the gold
medal in Atlanta, too, but she said she did not prepare correctly
for the heat and humidity, suffered from dehydration, and did not
even qualify for the final of the 5,000 meters.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was my fault,'' said Zsolt Gyongyossy, her coach.
</P>
<P>
   He is the same coach from the sports club who spotted Szabo as a
13-year-old and convinced her that she could be a runner. Szabo's
parents were split on the idea of an athletic career. Her father,
John, a carpenter of Hungarian ancestry, gave his consent, but her
mother, Livia, disapproved, wanting her daughter to concentrate on
her studies. Eventually, Szabo became rich and successful, with a
degree in physical education, and her coach became her husband.
</P>
<P>
   Nadia Comenici, the first Olympic gymnast ever to receive a
perfect score of 10, is still the most popular athlete in Romania,
Szabo insists. But Gaby, as she is known, is the most potent symbol
of current success and possibility in a country that continues to
struggle in its sluggish transition to a market economy a decade
after the fall of Nicolae Ceausescu and his Communist regime.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone loves Nadia, but that was a long time ago,''
Gyongyossy said. ``The younger generation, they are looking at Gaby
on television.''
</P>
<P>
   Last October, Szabo and Gyongyossy were married in Bucharest,
and as a measure of her popularity, the president of Romania, Emil
Constantinescu, attended. The prime minister sent roses, and the
reception was held in a villa that once belonged to Ceausescu.
</P>
<P>
   Romanian women have won three Olympic gold medal at the middle
distances: Doina Melinte at 800 meters in 1984, Maricica Puica at
3,000 meters in 1984 and Paula Ivan at 1,500 meters in 1988. But
the centralized system of identifying and developing athletes has
eroded since communism. There are more urgent uses for money than
sports. Where there were once 150 to 200 elite track and field
athletes in Romania, Szabo said, now there are six to 10.
</P>
<P>
   Many coaches have been unwilling or unable to succeed without
the safety net of the state, said Gyongyossy, who is 38.
</P>
<P>
   ``Old coaches, in middle age, they can't change,'' he said.
``They don't understand that a coach must also find sponsors and be
a marketing director.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo has invested in real estate in Romania, but she spends
most of her time out of the country, training at altitude in South
Africa during the winter, living on a farm and having little
contact with anyone other than her husband, her physical therapist
and her cook. In her spare times she reads the classics, Emile Zola
and Jane Austen. Her seclusion is purposeful, for she is fastidious
about training, running up to 120 miles a week, but also running 5
miles of speed work in succession, running sprints as short as 40
meters to 60 meters to polish her relentless kick.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has that sprinter's mentality, every time she wants to
win,'' Gyongyossy said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, anyone who runs fast in track draws suspicion of drug
use, and Romania has a history of positive tests for
performance-enhancing substances. Szabo insists she is clean and is
calling for blood testing at the Sydney Games. ``If the lab is
better, the sport will be cleaner,'' she said. ``It will be fair
for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Szabo has come far from that first school race, from an unknown
girl into an almost unbeatable woman. She runs now, she said, not
for money, but for permanence in the tidy ledgers of history.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I win the Olympics, then I will have everything,'' she
said. ``I would have all the medals. What else could I ask for but
good health?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 1824EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
