<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-WHITESOX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MENDOZA LENDS HIS ARM TO YANKEES' UNDERACHIEVING STARTING ROTATION
</HEADLINE>
  By JACK CURRY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ Ramiro Mendoza was not even supposed to be in the
starting rotation for the New York Yankees this season. The Yankees
had marquee names like David Cone, Roger Clemens, Orlando Hernandez
and Andy Pettitte and they wanted the fifth starter to be an
untested rookie named Ed Yarnall. As always, Mendoza was destined
to do the grunt work.
</P>
<P>
   But the season is almost half over, the Yankees rotation has
been plagued by injuries and underachievement and Mendoza, the
versatile pitcher, has evolved into the most consistent starter on
the team. Mendoza helped the Yankees finally stop the White Sox
Saturday, 12-8, winning his second-straight start during a stretch
of 10 games where the wobbly Yankees have won only three times.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Joe Torre has called Mendoza his pet because he has
constantly advised the Yankees against trading Mendoza. Torre's
pleas might be redundant now. With both Clemens and Hernandez
injured, Cone stuck on one victory and the rookie Ben Ford in the
rotation for at least one more start, Mendoza could be as valuable
to the Yankees as Jorge Posada.
</P>
<P>
   Do not laugh. Posada is in the midst of an All-Star season, but
Mendoza's pitching has been a salve. Mendoza silenced Chicago for
five innings, after the amazing White Sox had swatted the Yankees
in five consecutive games, dominating them like they have rarely
been dominated. But the Yankees punched back Saturday as Shane
Spencer drove in three runs and Tino Martinez and Paul O'Neill
knocked in two each.
</P>
<P>
   For a team that is still trying to acquire Juan Gonzalez to
bolster its offense, the eruption was nice. But Mendoza's crisp
pitching is what pushed the Yankees. Mendoza gave up three runs on
six hits and three walks while pitching into the sixth inning,
hardly overwhelming statistics. More importantly, the White Sox
managed one run in the first five innings as the Yankees built a
10-1 cushion. Mendoza left the game in the sixth with slight
stiffness in his right shoulder and it was unclear if it would have
an impact his next start, which would be distressing for the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the past two weeks the Yankees have desperately
needed a victory and Mendoza has produced each time. He relieved an
injured Clemens in the second inning on June 14 and worked 5 2/3
shutout innings in equaling Pedro Martinez and helping the Yankees
win, 3-1. After the Yankees had lost four straight, Mendoza pitched
competently in taming Boston, 22-1.
</P>
<P>
   Thirteen hours after Mariano Rivera botched a save opportunity
in a devastating 4-3 loss to the White Sox here on Friday, Mendoza
held Chicago to two runs before leaving with a 10-2 lead in the
sixth. With a 7-3 record, Mendoza is tied with Pettitte for the
most victories on the team.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the Yankees trudged into the clubhouse about two hours
before the start of Saturday's game, which is a lot later than they
would usually arrive. But the Yankees played on Friday night and
then had to be back at Comiskey Park for an early game so at least
15 of them showed up with barely enough time to pull on their
uniforms for batting practice.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees are tired of seeing the White Sox, who had defeated
them five times in the last eight days. When Jose Valentin's
broken-bat single off Rivera gave the White Sox a 4-3 victory on
Friday, the Yankees fell into third place for the first time since
April 18, 1999.
</P>
<P>
   It did not take long for the Yankees to show some perkiness
against Kip Wells. Derek Jeter grounded to the mound in the first,
but Wells threw wildly to first and Jeter smartly scooted all the
way to third base. With only one out, it was pivotal for Jeter to
grab the additional base. O'Neill singled in the first run.
</P>
<P>
   After Bernie Williams singled O'Neill to third, he followed with
a clever play. Martinez smacked a grounder to first and Paul
Konerko stepped on the base and threw to second. Williams got in a
rundown, which allowed O'Neill to score the second run. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
