<TEXT>
<P>
   NOTES - Kansas City Star budget offers for Sunday, June 25, 2000
</P>
<P>
   JOHN-EMAIL: A few months ago, a Kentucky woman looked at two
photos e-mailed to her by ``John'' and envisioned a hard-working
businessman and caring father from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Now she looks at the photos and searches her mind to recall any
conversation that might help authorities as they investigate John
Edward Robinson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Olathe man has been charged with five counts of
murder in the deaths of women whose bodies were found in barrels in
Linn County, Kan., and Cass County, Mo., and has been linked to
three women and a baby missing since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   By DAWN BORMANN in Kansas City. 1,000 words.
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-KOREA: Pusan, Ichon, Chosin Reservoir, MiG Alley, Pork
Chop Hill, Heartbreak Ridge, Panmunjon.
</P>
<P>
   All pieces of something called a ``police action.'' Just a few
of the names on that corner of the map called Korea, where the Cold
War once turned very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after our World War II victory marches, a dozen years
before we waded into Vietnam, the see-saw stalemate around the 38th
Parallel is sometimes called ``The Forgotten War.'' That is a
bitter legacy for those who fought and froze on icy mountain roads
or bled and died in reeking rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   Because today_50 years after the conflict began_the ones who
came home still cannot forget.
</P>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER in Kansas City. 2,500 words.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS OFFERINGS
</P>
<P>
   SPRINT-MERGER: While the vast majority of corporate mergers
filed last year will be approved, antitrust experts detect a chill
wind in the regulatory atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. and WorldCom Inc. are now caught in the cold,
offering to sell off Sprint's Internet and long distance operations
to assuage regulatory concerns that the merger would concentrate 80
percent of long distance traffic in the hands of two companies:
AT&AMP;T and the merged Sprint//WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   That comes after Sprint and WorldCom officials predicted the
merger would be blessed without the companies having to auction
anything substantial.
</P>
<P>
   By ERIC PALMER in Kansas City. 1,200 words.
</P>
