u i BC-ZIMBABWE-VOTE-2ND-LEA     06-24 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-VOTE-2ND-LEAD-WRITETHROUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE'S TACTIC OF INTIMIDATION SEEN TO BACKFIRE  
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects slug)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HWEDZA, Zimbabwe _ The grassland farming district of Hwedza,
about 90 miles southeast of the capital, was scorched by terrible
political violence over the past four months. Farmworkers were
forced to attend nightly ``reeducation'' rallies, where thugs of
the ruling party beat them and made them sing revolutionary war
songs. The opposition candidate for parliament fled the country,
and remains in hiding.
</P>
<P>
   But when the polls opened Saturday on Zimbabwe's most important
election since independence in 1980, Eric Chikukwa was one of
hundreds of people waiting in the early winter morning to vote.
``People aren't worried about who the candidates are. They just
want change,'' said the young Zimbabwean, casting a ballot for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   Facing its first serious challenge in 20 years, President Robert
Mugabe's party encouraged a widespread intimidation in the months
preceding this weekend's ballot, which ends Sunday. He lashed out
the white minority for sabotaging the economy. His backers raided
more than 1,000 commercial farms, destroying crops and pummeling
anyone they suspected of supporting the opposition. At least 30
people were killed.
</P>
<P>
   The violence, however, seems to have backfired. Rather than
hiding at home, people turned out in record numbers, eager, many
said, to register their frustration over economic decline and
government corruption. Five years ago, just 29 percent of voters
bothered to mark a ballot. Saturday, they waited for hours in long
lines outside polling stations across the country.
</P>
<P>
   Most expressed the hope that the ballot's arrival would mark an
end to the violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``At last,'' said Daniel Chininga, one of the first voters to
arrive at a polling station in Goromonzi, outside the capital,
Harare. ``We all wish the elections had been held sooner. Brother
to brother will be brother to brother again.''
</P>
<P>
   In a contest between an entrenched ruling class and the forces
of change, both sides seemed to understand the stakes. Farmers gave
their workers the day off Saturday, and organized transportation
for them in pickup trucks and three-ton flatbeds to and from the
polling stations. Government supporters rode in on buses or
tractor-pulled hay wagons. At most polling stations, the atmosphere
was cheery, though a quiet tension prevailed in districts like
Hwedza that were most shaken by the violence.
</P>
<P>
   International teams of election observers reported only
scattered organizational problems and incidents of intimidation.
That was surprising, they said, given the turbulent campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition said that at one polling station farm workers
were required to stand in line between rows of war veterans, the
pro-Mugabe group that orchestrated the invasions on white-owned
commercial farms. In other locations, it said, ruling party
supporters blocked people from voting.
</P>
<P>
   One white farmer told Reuters that he and voting family members
were yanked out of the line by war veterans saying, ``you will not
vote here. This is not your country. This is not a white man's
country.'' Others were blocked from voting by incomplete voter
registration lists.
</P>
<P>
   But ``overall, things are running smoothly,'' said Pierre
Schori, head of the European Union monitoring group. ``We have
received reports from the countryside. There have been four or five
incidents, mainly people being obstructed from reaching polling
stations, some threats and that type of thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 5 million people are registered to vote for the 120
elected seats in parliament. Mugabe himself is not up for
reelection until 2002. Election officials were due to count the
ballots through the night after the polling stations close Sunday
in order to announce the results Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Both sides claimed the large turnout was auspicious.
</P>
<P>
   Before casting his ballot Saturday, Mugabe said the enthusiastic
participation proved Zimbabwe's peaceful, democratic nature. ``I
hear the people are voting in their masses,'' he said. ``The
prophets of doom . . . their prophecies are doomed.''
</P>
<P>
   Opposition leader Morgan Tsvangirai was equally upbeat. ``This
is the day we move forward as a country, or backward into an
economic abyss,'' he said after marking his ballot. ``Hope is our
future.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts had said a large turnout favored the
opposition, which faced an uphill battle in Mugabe's rural
strongholds.
</P>
<P>
   Valentine Ziswa, an opposition candidate in the rural district
of Makoni North, 90 miles east of Harare, said his opponent could
win only by rigging the vote, a claim Tsvangirai has made. Ziswa
vowed a court challenge if defeated.
</P>
<P>
   Chenjerai Hunzvi, a ruling party candidate and the inflammatory
leader of the war veterans' farm invasions, vowed to take up arms
if the opposition wins. ``There is no other way of liberating
Zimbabwe other than armed struggle,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the morning, as sprinklers shot across the oat fields
on Nico van Rensburg's farm, two sisters bundled up an infant and
prepared to go to vote. Every night since March, they said, they
were rounded up by war veterans occupying an adjacent farm and
forced to hear lectures about Mugabe's greatness. They wouldn't say
how they planned to vote, but allowed they wanted change.
</P>
<P>
   In a rare moment of candor, ruling party candidate Aenaes
Chigwedere admitted that the government's use of intimidation
hadn't worked so well. ``Maybe it made people afraid to enter the
arena and campaign,'' he said. ``But as a strategy it was
counterproductive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
