r s BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-L     06-24 0672
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-BASEBALL-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANGELS' GLAUS _ HE'S NO MIKE SCHMIDT, YET
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Dave Hollins used to call him ``the
franchise.''
</P>
<P>
   Hollins was the Anaheim Angels' third baseman at the time, and a
young Troy Glaus was too talented for Hollins to ignore. He called
him the franchise, partly out of admiration, but mostly out of envy
and jealousy.
</P>
<P>
   Hollins, an aging, beat-up veteran, could only dream of being in
Glaus' shoes.
</P>
<P>
   That was in 1998. In 1999, Hollins was gone and Glaus was indeed
the Angels' every-day third baseman at age 22.
</P>
<P>
   After hitting 29 homers last season, much is expected of him
this season. And he is delivering. His 22 homers is tied for the
team lead with Mo Vaughn. He's hitting .314, a marked improvement
from last season's .240. He ranks among the American League's top
10 in nine offensive categories.
</P>
<P>
   A former shortstop, Glaus is Gold Glove material defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels know what they have in Glaus, and now the rest of the
world is learning about him. So much so, Sports Illustrated
compared Glaus to Hall of Fame third baseman Mike Schmidt. That's
heady company, and it's often unfair to compare a young player with
legendary players.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't bother Glaus.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's flattering to be compared to him, but it's just (the
reporter's) opinion,'' Glaus said. ``I'm not trying to be Mike
Schmidt, I'm just trying to be the best Troy Glaus I can be.''
</P>
<P>
   There seems to be no debate about Glaus' talent and potential.
Despite his size - he's 6-foot-5, 229 pounds - he has quick hands
and is agile at third, where he fields almost everything. He has
power - he hit a 457- foot homer off Randy Johnson this month - and
still has patience at the plate (he's sixth in the league in
walks).
</P>
<P>
   But in order to be a star-type player, it requires more than
just a pretty swing and a good glove. Does Glaus have that certain
something?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he has it,'' Angels coach Joe Maddon said. ``What he
has to come to grips with is, as he becomes more comfortable with
his role on the team, to understand the awesome potential he has. I
don't think he understands that yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes it's difficult to remember that Glaus is so young. But
he'll give reminders when he slams his helmet and throws his bat
after striking out. Or when he'll be short with reporters after a
tough loss, or even after a win.
</P>
<P>
   Glaus is careful to avoid talking about himself as much as
possible. Which is why the comparisons to Schmidt might have made
him uneasy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all about how you take what people say,'' Angels first
baseman Mo Vaughn said. ``Mike Schmidt was a bad cat, one of the
best ever to play the position. Does (Glaus) have the potential?
Yes, but he has to work at it. It's all about how you apply
yourself. The only thing he can do is keep doing what he's doing.''
</P>
<P>
   Glaus almost surely will make the All-Star team, which will go
against his ``team-first'' philosophy. He'll have to talk about
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be a great honor, but it's an individual accolade,
and I don't play for individual accolades,'' Glaus said. ``The only
accolade I play for is a World Series championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Maddon insists Glaus means what he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's not motivated by hitting .300, he's motivated to help us
win,'' he said. ``With Troy, peer acceptance is very important. If
his fellow players see him as a guy who has winning as a first
priority, that will do whatever it takes to win, he will be
well-liked, as would anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   It might seem a difficult task to stay grounded at such a young
age when the compliments are coming fast and furious, but Glaus
says it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is, because I've still got a lot of work to do,''
he said. ``I'd like to be that (Hall of Fame-type) player. All of
us would. If you want to be the best, you have to work. And if
you're lucky enough to get there, you have to work to stay there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
