<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ALNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENSIONS INCREASE, AS DOES LOSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. -- Like with many teams that get edgy when
things aren't going well, the defending AL West-champion Texas
Rangers and defending AL Central-champion Cleveland Indians are
getting a little hot under the collar.
</P>
<P>
   In Cleveland, tempers flared between players during a
``friendly'' card game when center fielder Kenny Lofton and rookie
DH/first baseman Russell Branyan had to be separated.
</P>
<P>
   Lofton said only, ``The disagreement's over.'' Branyan, who hit
two homers in his first game this season, is developing a
reputation as a cocky player. Said Branyan about the incident:
``It's just Kenny being Kenny.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there was second baseman Roberto Alomar's criticism of
manager Charlie Manuel. Alomar was hit in the head by a pitch from
Detroit's Willie Blair and became upset because Manuel did not
order retaliation from one of his pitchers, even though Alomar
admitted Blair hit him accidentally.
</P>
<P>
   Wonder what Chuck Finley thinks of all the in-house griping?
</P>
<P>
   And in Texas, after being swept in the three-game series against
the Rockies last week, Rangers manager Johnny Oates was asked how
he was feeling: ``Whatever's one degree below frustrated, I'm
feeling it now.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, however, is concerned his players aren't as upset as he
is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope there's some people in the clubhouse feeling that way,
too,'' he said. ``I don't think there's enough of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Is there apathy among the players?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no idea what Johnny's talking about,'' Rangers reliever
Tim Crabtree said. ``This team comes to the ballpark to play hard
every day. There isn't one player on this team who doesn't give 100
percent every day.''
</P>
<P>
   No September showdown: Add Blue Jays manager Jim Fregosi to the
list of those critical of the schedule.
</P>
<P>
   The Blue Jays have joined the Red Sox and Yankees in the AL East
race, but after this weekend, the Blue Jays and Red Sox won't play
each other again this season.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Angels manager Mike Scioscia talked about, when he
was a player, how the final month of the season was played against
division foes. Fregosi said it should still be that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I honestly believe can be accomplished,''
Fregosi said. ``Those are the classic games in baseball, the
confrontations between people contending within their own division
in the month of September. To me, that's what baseball is all
about.''
</P>
<P>
   Break up the Orioles: With the third-highest payroll in baseball
at $83.1 million and the team going nowhere, look for the Orioles
to unload some high-priced players before the July 31 deadline.
</P>
<P>
   Here's who might go, and where they might end up:
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Scott Erickson, Cleveland; shortstop Mike Bordick,
Arizona; outfielder B.J. Surhoff, Yankees, and catcher Charles
Johnson, St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher Mike Mussina would help anybody, but he will be a free
agent at the end of the season.
</P>
<P>
   AL best: So which division is the best in baseball? Would you
believe the AL West?
</P>
<P>
   Based on the combined records of each team in the respective
divisions, the AL West (through Friday) was 24 games over .500.
</P>
<P>
   Next best was the NL West (19 over), followed by the NL East (14
over), the AL Central (two under), the AL East (9 under) and,
finally, the woeful NL Central (46 under).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
