<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-TYSON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TYSON EARNS TKO OVER SAVARESE 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL PENNINGTON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland _ Normalcy seems to exit the boxing ring as
soon as Mike Tyson enters it these days.
</P>
<P>
   In another bizarre and brief fight Saturday night at Hampden
Park, Tyson knocked Lou Savarese down with his first punch and then
won on a technical knockout 38 seconds into the first round _ after
briefly decking Referee John Coyle, too.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson hit Savarese with a looping left hook just seconds into
the fight, his glove striking Savarese with a grazing punch to the
top of the head. Savarese fell onto his back with his legs tangled
beneath him. He rose at the count of 6 and stepped forward when
Coyle asked him to, but Savarese was clearly dazed.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson swarmed Savarese, wobbling him with another left hook
followed by several uppercuts that landed on Savarese's jaw. Coyle
at this point jumped between the fighters, apparently trying to
stop the bout and shouting for both to stop punching. But Coyle
could not get Tyson away from Savarese, and Tyson continued to
throw wild, furious punches.
</P>
<P>
   One of those punches, a looping attempt to throw a left hook
around Coyle, glanced off the referee and knocked him to the
canvas. Coyle did not appear to be hurt, and when he got up, he
separated the fighters. It was then that Coyle informed Savarese
that he had stopped the fight and awarded Tyson the victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Savarese wasn't throwing any punches back, and I could see his
eyes weren't focused on the task any longer,'' Coyle said. ``It
would have been unsafe for him to continue. I wasn't hurt when
Tyson kept punching.''
</P>
<P>
   By ignoring Coyle's orders, Tyson may be involved in another
postfight controversy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dedicate this fight to my friend Darryl Baum,'' Tyson, 33,
said in the ring afterward, referring to a friend who was murdered
in New York two weeks ago. ``I'm the best ever. I didn't really
train for this fight. I was too upset. I probably trained for only
two weeks. I wanted to rip his heart out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell Lennox I'm coming after him. He can't fight me; he has no
chance against me when I'm ready. I'm not ready right now because
I'm rusty. I need more training. So when I am ready, he'll be no
match for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's victory over Savarese keeps him on the path to a title
fight, although a match with Lennox Lewis, who holds two of the
three heavyweight championship belts, may be held up because of the
fighters' contractual television agreements. Lewis is aligned with
Home Box Office, while Tyson has a contract with Showtime.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson's next title fight may likely be for the World Boxing
Association title, which is vacant. Evander Holyfield and John Ruiz
fight for the WBA title in August.
</P>
<P>
   For Tyson (48-8, 42 knockouts), it was his third consecutive
victory since his losses to Holyfield. Last year, Tyson knocked out
Francois Botha and had a bout with Orlin Norris declared a no
contest after he hit Norris after the bell ending the first round.
In January, Tyson knocked out Julius Francis.
</P>
<P>
   For Savarese (39-4, 32 knockouts), it was his second successive
defeat. He was soundly beaten in a 10-round unanimous decision that
went to Michael Grant almost a year ago. Savarese, who will soon
turn 35, talked about retirement after that fight.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the Scottish crowd booed the fight's result. The crowd,
which appeared considerably smaller than the sellout of 51,000 that
had been predicted, cheered both Savarese and Tyson when they
entered the ring. Savarese seemed to be the favorite.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Frank Warren, the promoter of the fight, made his first
appearance in a week when he arrived ringside. Some in the British
press reported this week that Tyson had scuffled with Warren in a
dispute over money Tyson believes Warren owes him. Tyson denied
that he hit Warren, who wore a tuxedo and did not appear to be
injured. A London judge announced on Friday that he was withholding
a portion, valued at nearly $700,000, of the expected $8 million
purse Tyson was expected to receive.
</P>
<P>
   There were protesters outside Hampden Park before the fight,
though heavy rain seemed to subdue the scene considerably. Several
protesters held placards denouncing the decision of Jack Straw, the
home secretary in London, to allow Tyson into Britain since recent
changes in immigration laws would normally prohibit someone like
Tyson, who was convicted of rape in the United States, from being
granted a visa.
</P>
<P>
   The rain put a damper on the atmosphere at Hampden Park, the
Scottish national soccer stadium. Though it had stopped raining by
the time Tyson and Savarese entered the ring, the canvas may have
been slippery.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
