<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-JUDAH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JUDAH WINS TITLE DEFENSE 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GLASGOW, Scotland _ Brooklyn, N.Y.,'s Zab Judah made a
successful first defense of his International Boxing Federation
junior-welterweight championship Saturday night with a unanimous
decision over Junior Witter on the undercard of the Mike Tyson-Lou
Savarese fight in Glasgow's Hampden Park.
</P>
<P>
   It was an awkward fight for Judah, who improved his record to
23-0 as Witter rarely engaged in an extended exchange of punches.
Witter also kept switching between fighting right-handed and
left-handed, which also helped make him an elusive opponent. By the
middle rounds, however, Judah's consistent body punching slowed
Witter, and with 30 seconds left in the fifth round, Judah caught
Witter with a straight left hand that dazed Witter and sent his
mouthpiece skittering across the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Judah continued to be the more effective fighter from there,
throwing many more power punches than Witter. Witter also was
clowning in the ring, and generally seemed more intent on
frustrating Judah than being aggressive enough to win.
</P>
<P>
   Witter (15-1-2), from Bradford, England, was a late replacement
for Jason Roland, who withdrew for the fight two weeks ago because
of medical reasons.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 2036EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
