<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0162 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 20:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3997 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-FISHER-KOREA-3TAKES-K     06-24 2037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-KOREA-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF KOREAN WAR STILL STRONG 50 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES J. FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Pusan, Inchon, Chosin Reservoir, MiG Alley,
Pork Chop Hill, Heartbreak Ridge, Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
   All pieces of something called a police action. Just a few of
the names on that corner of the map called Korea, where the Cold
War once turned very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after our World War II victory marches, a dozen years
before we waded into Vietnam, the seesaw stalemate around the 38th
parallel is sometimes called ``The Forgotten War.'' That is a
bitter legacy for those who fought and froze on icy mountain roads
or bled and died in reeking rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   Because today _ 50 years after the conflict began _ the ones who
came home still cannot forget.
</P>
<P>
   So their recollections are not of the great themes of history,
of Western strategies for communist containment, of how civilian
authority asserted itself over the military or of how ``limited
war'' could become a military objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothered me most was the brainwashing,''
recalled Charles Kerr, living today near Bentonville, Ark. A pilot,
he was held by the Chinese in solitary confinement for a year.
``Night and day interrogations. And not being able to communicate
with my parents. They let me write a couple of letters, but they
never sent them. No Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories, instead, are of the confusion, the fear and the loss.
</P>
<P>
   With his right hand, fingers curled and thumb outstretched,
Chung Hyun Kim, 66, makes the motion of loading a clip in the
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   He emigrated from Korea in 1974 to join the 5,000-strong Kansas
City Korean-American community. He remembers South Korean soldiers
coming to his village when he was 16 years old, giving him an M-1
rifle and telling him that he and 500 other young men were members
of the 5th Republic of Korea (ROK) Army Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had to show me to load,'' he said. ``I remember the
clip. Eight bullets. But I don't know about M-1. They said, `You
take; you shoot.' You know how many of the 500 survive?''
</P>
<P>
   He holds up three fingers.
</P>
<P>
   And who could forget the sad-faced children in a ravaged land;
waves of screaming men in quilted uniforms coming in the night; the
individual acts of heroism; and, above all, the barbarism of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a candle the other day,'' recalled Ken Lunt, 68, the
mayor of Fort Scott, Kan. He was a Marine scout-sniper in 1952 and
1953. ``All of a sudden I remembered this kid who had been shot in
the throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The wound was mortal and the bleeding unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cold it formed into a stalagmite like you see in a
cave, except it was this dark red, dripping down and getting bigger
and bigger....That candle brought all that back.''
</P>
<P>
   No, these veterans cannot forget. Nor should we.
INVASION AND RETREAT
</P>
<P>
   The conflict ignited when 90,000 North Koreans swarmed across
the South Korean border along the 38th parallel, brushing aside
undermanned ROK units that had given their farm-boy soldiers leave
for the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations immediately called for the North Koreans to
withdraw. The United States rushed unprepared troops from
occupation duty in Japan. Armed conflict in that fifth year of
post-World War II peace had not seemed on the horizon, despite
growing tension between East and West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't ready,'' said John Williams of the 21st Infantry
Regiment of the 24th Division and now of Overland Park, Kan. ``The
whole Army wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was among those first troops into Korea, part of what
was called Task Force Smith, which met advancing North Korean
troops near Osan, south of Seoul. Some thought the U.S. Army just
showing up would make the enemy _ which called itself the Inmin Gun
_ turn tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rifles, carbines, machine guns and those 2.36 rocket
launchers,'' recalled Williams. ``The North Koreans had T-34 tanks,
recoilless rifles, artillery, you name it. Our little-bitty rocket
launchers we had just bounced off their tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting retreat was chaotic. Vehicles, weapons and wounded
were left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Korea was not going to be a walkover. Task Force Smith,
too, would be remembered. The January 2000 edition of Military
Review, the professional journal of the U.S. Army Command and
General Staff College, at Fort Leavenworth, contained these words
in an article about today's shrinking military: ``No more Task
Force Smiths.''
</P>
<P>
   The news most all that summer was almost all bad _ engagement,
retreat, and the shrinking perimeter around a southern port called
Pusan. And a phenomenon called straggling _ troops white, black and
Asian running away.
</P>
<P>
   The daily newspapers did most of the coverage; television news
then was 15 minutes a night. The datelines on the stories were
Masan, Pohang, Taejon (where a two-star Army general was captured),
Taegu and Suwon. The black-and- white photos showed images such as
an exhausted GI weeping in another's arms, dead Americans found
with their hands bound, and floods of Korean refugees in their
flowing white dress and small black hats.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict's toll on the Koreans was staggering. Kim lost six
brothers. Villages were leveled, families sundered and much of the
population seemed uprooted. Fleeing columns of refugees often were
strafed in that panicky first year. Both sides summarily executed
ideological opponents as well as captive soldiers, especially the
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different,'' said Fred Rice, a sergeant and machine
gunner in the 7th Cavalry Regiment of the lst Cavalry Division, who
now lives in Belton. ``You never could tell with the refugees. They
could have a burp gun under those robes. Most of us suspected that,
here and there, there were enemy soldiers in among them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rice thinks, there was no massacre of huddled civilians
under the bridge by 1st Cavalry troopers at No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't happen,'' he insists, despite the recent spate of
articles. ``Anybody who's been in the Army will tell you something
like that would have spread like wildfire. Soldiers talk. We would
have known.''
STRIKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   Even with war undeclared officially, a lot of young men signed
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the younger brothers of the guys who'd been in World
War II,'' said Bill Norris, a Korean veteran from Springfield, Ill.
``Nobody went off to Canada. I don't even remember anybody talking
about draft deferments. We didn't consider ourselves special.''
(MORE)
</P>
<P>
   U.S. firepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We slaughtered them,'' said Bill Norris, who was a tank
commander and recalled hundreds of Chinese and North Korean bodies
in their padded uniforms and ubiquitous tennis shoes piled up in
front of American lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't count them. They would keep coming, and we'd just
keep shooting and calling in artillery. What I remember is the
smell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't forget what a battlefield where men have died smells
like. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Capturing real estate was secondary to punishing the enemy army,
said the new 8th Army commander, Lt. Gen. Matthew B. Ridgway. By
this time the idea of uniting the two Koreas had been given up by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur, however, had not abandoned the goal. Ignoring the
administration, he called loudly for expanding the war by
unleashing Nationalist Chinese from Taiwan and bombing or
blockading China.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong war against the wrong communist power, concluded
President Truman. MacArthur was sacked April 11, prompting a howl
of indignation through much of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought of the politics or the big brass,'' said John
Hureado, a son of migrant workers, who grew up in Kansas City's
north end. In the Navy he became a 5-inch gun captain on the USS
Erben, a destroyer that gave fire support to troops ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there just to do a job....we were a bunch of kids.
Kids don't think about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler was another sailor, serving on the USS Mispillion,
an oiler that delivered aviation gas to combat ships. He likens
such duty to living in a time bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a buddy named Jack Davenport,'' he said. They played
football at Paseo High School and delivered The Star together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the war came, I said to Jack, `Let's join the Navy and
see the world.' He wouldn't. He wanted the Marines.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, 1951, near Songnae-Dong, Cpl. Davenport threw
himself on a grenade, giving his life for another Marine. He was
awarded the Medal of Honor.
TALKS, FINALLY
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the communist armies were pushed back over most of the
38th parallel, where the Korean Demilitarized Zone stands today.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage the U.N. forces had was air superiority. Although
the communists had more jet fighters (usually flown by Chinese or
Russians), the U.S. Air Force achieved at least a 7-to-1 kill ratio
in dogfights.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kerr, an F-86 pilot, ended up on the wrong side of that
ratio. He was on patrol in April 1952 along the Yalu River with a
green flight leader, when a MiG-15 was spotted below. The Sabres
dived on him, but the communist flier slammed on his air brakes,
causing the Americans to overshoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My flight leader didn't react fast enough. We just zipped on
by him. ... He got in behind me and hit me as soon as I started to
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The second lieutenant began 16 months of captivity, most of it
alone in a farmhouse room. He describes his relentless
interrogators as well-educated, even boastful of studying in the
United States. They wanted propaganda, especially phony confessions
about germ warfare. ``That was their biggie.''
</P>
<P>
   Although peace talks had started in July 1951, the war would
drag out for two more years. The Chinese used the first round of
negotiations as a breather to organize a new offensive. It was
blunted. The next round they used to dig deep into their
mountainous defense lines.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45 percent of American casualties came in this last phase
of the war. Charles Stollenwerk of Overland Park served as a
butcher at March Air Force Base in California:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting meat. But what I remember is the big C-124
Globemasters coming in from Korea, day in and day out, just full of
coffins. They were huge planes. They could carry lots of coffins.''
Uneasy peace
</P>
<P>
   The truce finally came in late July 1953.
</P>
<P>
   It had been held up largely over the issue of returning
communist prisoners. China wanted them all back; the U.N. wanted to
give them a choice. Finally the exchange was made.
</P>
<P>
   When Kerr, the emaciated flier, finally walked under the
``Welcome Home'' arch, one of his thoughts was of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   He had lived largely on meager rice rations until the last weeks
of captivity, when he got some bread and a little meat. ``Rice,
something I hated all my life, and boiled cabbage.'' Kerr chuckled
at the grim memory. ``I lost a few pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunt remembered wanting more than anything a hamburger and a
root beer. One day, however, he and some of his fellow Marines got
their hands on some oranges.
</P>
<P>
   They perched themselves above a road where trucks hauling
Chinese communists on their way to repatriation would have to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here came these trucks, loaded with communists who had
ripped off their clothes and used to their own blood to make red
flags. They were singing these Chinese communist songs and chanting
and shouting like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we blasted them. With oranges. Just pelted them ... Shut
'em up. You should have seen the looks on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul DeWitt of Independence was with the 555th Army Field
Artillery Battalion. In the last days it was overrun. Half its 600
men were killed or listed as missing. DeWitt's memory of that
always will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another recollection would stick, one bordering on the
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country around where we'd been fighting was shot to
pieces,'' said DeWitt. ``A wasteland. It looked as barren as the
moon. But right after the truce we found this gorgeous little
valley, all green, absolutely untouched by the war and just full of
pheasants. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one day there were signs in the valley saying stay out;
it was now an artillery range. And so it got shot to pieces, too.''
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ U.S. firepower.
</P>
<P>
   ``We slaughtered them,'' said Bill Norris, who was a tank
commander and recalled hundreds of Chinese and North Korean bodies
in their padded uniforms and ubiquitous tennis shoes piled up in
front of American lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``You couldn't count them. They would keep coming, and we'd just
keep shooting and calling in artillery. What I remember is the
smell.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't forget what a battlefield where men have died smells
like. Ever.''
</P>
<P>
   Capturing real estate was secondary to punishing the enemy army,
said the new 8th Army commander, Lt. Gen. Matthew B. Ridgway. By
this time the idea of uniting the two Koreas had been given up by
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur, however, had not abandoned the goal. Ignoring the
administration, he called loudly for expanding the war by
unleashing Nationalist Chinese from Taiwan and bombing or
blockading China.
</P>
<P>
   The wrong war against the wrong communist power, concluded
President Truman. MacArthur was sacked April 11, prompting a howl
of indignation through much of the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never thought of the politics or the big brass,'' said John
Hureado, a son of migrant workers, who grew up in Kansas City's
north end. In the Navy he became a 5-inch gun captain on the USS
Erben, a destroyer that gave fire support to troops ashore.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were there just to do a job....we were a bunch of kids.
Kids don't think about things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler was another sailor, serving on the USS Mispillion,
an oiler that delivered aviation gas to combat ships. He likens
such duty to living in a time bomb.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a buddy named Jack Davenport,'' he said. They played
football at Paseo High School and delivered The Star together.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the war came, I said to Jack, `Let's join the Navy and
see the world.' He wouldn't. He wanted the Marines.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sept. 21, 1951, near Songnae-Dong, Cpl. Davenport threw
himself on a grenade, giving his life for another Marine. He was
awarded the Medal of Honor.
TALKS, FINALLY
</P>
<P>
   Slowly the communist armies were pushed back over most of the
38th parallel, where the Korean Demilitarized Zone stands today.
</P>
<P>
   One advantage the U.N. forces had was air superiority. Although
the communists had more jet fighters (usually flown by Chinese or
Russians), the U.S. Air Force achieved at least a 7-to-1 kill ratio
in dogfights.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Kerr, an F-86 pilot, ended up on the wrong side of that
ratio. He was on patrol in April 1952 along the Yalu River with a
green flight leader, when a MiG-15 was spotted below. The Sabres
dived on him, but the communist flier slammed on his air brakes,
causing the Americans to overshoot.
</P>
<P>
   ``My flight leader didn't react fast enough. We just zipped on
by him. ... He got in behind me and hit me as soon as I started to
turn.''
</P>
<P>
   The second lieutenant began 16 months of captivity, most of it
alone in a farmhouse room. He describes his relentless
interrogators as well-educated, even boastful of studying in the
United States. They wanted propaganda, especially phony confessions
about germ warfare. ``That was their biggie.''
</P>
<P>
   Although peace talks had started in July 1951, the war would
drag out for two more years. The Chinese used the first round of
negotiations as a breather to organize a new offensive. It was
blunted. The next round they used to dig deep into their
mountainous defense lines.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 45 percent of American casualties came in this last phase
of the war. Charles Stollenwerk of Overland Park served as a
butcher at March Air Force Base in California:
</P>
<P>
   ``Cutting meat. But what I remember is the big C-124
Globemasters coming in from Korea, day in and day out, just full of
coffins. They were huge planes. They could carry lots of coffins.''
Uneasy peace
</P>
<P>
   The truce finally came in late July 1953.
</P>
<P>
   It had been held up largely over the issue of returning
communist prisoners. China wanted them all back; the U.N. wanted to
give them a choice. Finally the exchange was made.
</P>
<P>
   When Kerr, the emaciated flier, finally walked under the
``Welcome Home'' arch, one of his thoughts was of ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   He had lived largely on meager rice rations until the last weeks
of captivity, when he got some bread and a little meat. ``Rice,
something I hated all my life, and boiled cabbage.'' Kerr chuckled
at the grim memory. ``I lost a few pounds.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunt remembered wanting more than anything a hamburger and a
root beer. One day, however, he and some of his fellow Marines got
their hands on some oranges.
</P>
<P>
   They perched themselves above a road where trucks hauling
Chinese communists on their way to repatriation would have to pass.
</P>
<P>
   ``So here came these trucks, loaded with communists who had
ripped off their clothes and used to their own blood to make red
flags. They were singing these Chinese communist songs and chanting
and shouting like crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we blasted them. With oranges. Just pelted them ... Shut
'em up. You should have seen the looks on their faces.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul DeWitt of Independence was with the 555th Army Field
Artillery Battalion. In the last days it was overrun. Half its 600
men were killed or listed as missing. DeWitt's memory of that
always will remain.
</P>
<P>
   Yet another recollection would stick, one bordering on the
bizarre.
</P>
<P>
   ``The country around where we'd been fighting was shot to
pieces,'' said DeWitt. ``A wasteland. It looked as barren as the
moon. But right after the truce we found this gorgeous little
valley, all green, absolutely untouched by the war and just full of
pheasants. ...
</P>
<P>
   ``Then one day there were signs in the valley saying stay out;
it was now an artillery range. And so it got shot to pieces, too.''
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ ourselves special.''
</P>
<P>
   The reserves were called up, said J.O. Smith, a Marine in a 105
mm Marine howitzer battalion in Kansas City. ``They called us and
we went. Nobody was exactly happy. But that was the deal we'd
made.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, even early on, an odd disconnect existed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, there was news about Korea in the papers or if you watched
television, you'd see a little here and there,'' recalled Rose
Matthews of Mattoon, Ill. When her husband, Joe, was assigned to
the 2nd Division, she took their baby to live with her parents.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you never knew there was a war. I'd meet people on the
street, and they'd ask where my husband was. I'd say Korea, and
they'd look at me like I was crazy. Life went on the same. It
wasn't a thing like World War II, when everybody was focused all
the time on the war.''
</P>
<P>
   But everybody did focus, at least for a while, when the old
Pacific war hero, Gen. Douglas MacArthur, made his gamble _ the end
run around the invading forces. On Sept. 15, 1950, the 1st Marine
and 7th Army Divisions went ashore at Inchon and seized Seoul.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the 8th Army broke out of the Pusan perimeter
and joined the pursuit of the Inmin Gun.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Young Park, who was 17 then, remembers the North Koreans
retreating through her village 70 miles outside of Seoul. The
communists already had taken all the livestock in their push south,
and now they grabbed what food they could as they moved north
again. Adding insult, they urinated in the home's vat of pickled
cabbage that they couldn't take with them, the Kansas City woman
recalls.
</P>
<P>
   In a period of two weeks, a savage defensive war seemed to have
been transformed into a brilliant American victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we'd be home for Christmas,'' said Chester Addison,
part of the 8th Cavalry Regiment. TO THE YALU AND BACK AGAIN
</P>
<P>
   The United States made a fateful decision to go beyond the 38th
parallel and reunite the Koreas under President Syngman Rhee's
corrupt but pro-Western dictatorship.
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur brushed off concerns that the Red Chinese might decide
to keep the imperialist Americans from their borders.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went right up the west coast of Korea,'' said Nathan Riley,
a sergeant in the 19th Regiment of the 24th Infantry Division, who
lives in Belton.
</P>
<P>
   ``But there were little things that bothered you. We were having
trouble getting ammunition. And winter gear. It was getting really
cold, way below zero, and I was still wearing just a field jacket,
a shirt, a sweatshirt and my old leather combat boots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Back in the rear everybody seemed to have these big winter
parkas, shoe-pacs, wool sacks, everything to keep toasty. But not
at the front. They were grabbing them off before they got to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Riley remembers how two men would dig a foxhole and sit facing
each other, each man sitting on the other's feet to keep them warm.
</P>
<P>
   But that wasn't the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then the Chinese came out of everywhere, and we took off
south.''
</P>
<P>
   MacArthur's intelligence sections, looking for trucks in
roadbound columns, had missed hundreds of thousands of
``volunteers'' infiltrating into North Korea by night and on foot.
</P>
<P>
   From headquarters to the front line, the resulting collapse
would leave a black mark on the Army's reputation. In western Korea
the 8th Army was suddenly hearing bugles, whistles and the screams
of thousands of Chinese soldiers bursting through their lines,
panicking the U.S. troops.
</P>
<P>
   Addison was at Unsan, north of the communist capital, Pyongyang,
where his unit was all but wiped out. Although wounded four times,
he escaped.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the popping sound when they shot me. They weren't
very good shots, you know. It still bothers me a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   On the eastern side of the peninsula's mountain spine, the
Chinese encircled the Marines, as well as some of the 3rd and 7th
Army divisions, around the Chosin Reservoir.
</P>
<P>
   James Ramsey was in the 7th. Of the 3,200 men in his 32nd
Regiment and the 31st, just 385 survived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wounded in the hip, and we went out across the ice of
the reservoir to get away,'' said Ramsey, who lives in Westfield,
Ill. ``Behind me I could see our vehicles burning and the Chinese
shooting them up. They had wounded men in them.''
</P>
<P>
   Ramsey and a few others made it to Marine lines at Hagaru-ri,
where a puny airstrip had been ripped out of the frozen earth.
Loaded aboard a C-47 for evacuation, Ramsey could finally breathe
as the plane took off. Then it crashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right back where we'd come from,'' he said. ``The Marines came
out and got us, threw us on another plane, and that one made it. It
was not a good day.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marines broke out, bringing most of their dead, their
wounded, much of their equipment and vehicles, Army and ROK units
and a mass of refugees. They were evacuated from the port of
Hungnam by mid-December.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 4, 1950, Ensign Jesse L. Brown's F4U Corsair, flying
close air support for the Marines, was hit by ground fire.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, 24, the first African-American naval aviator, could not
make it to Hagaru-ri. His belly landing in the snow was rough.
Brown's three squadron mates, circling above, saw Brown slide his
canopy open, but he did not get out of the smoking plane.
</P>
<P>
   Lt. Thomas Hudner landed his Corsair nearby. Finding Brown's
legs were pinned under a hydraulic panel, he called for a
helicopter. Meanwhile, he comforted Brown, who was in severe pain,
and tried to put the fire out with snow.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter, however, was no help, and the light started to
fade. Brown was unconscious and probably dead. The area was
swarming with Chinese. Hudner had to get out.
</P>
<P>
   But the Navy _ in its own way _ gave Brown a Valkyrian tribute.
Soon four Corsairs flew overhead and cremated Brown and his Corsair
in a billow of napalm.
BLOODY STALEMATE
</P>
<P>
   Six Chinese offensives came in the first five months of 1951.
The battle line slipped far below Seoul once again.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese needed only 50 tons of supplies a day for one of
their divisions, compared with 610 for an American division, but
now even their supply lines were badly stretched.
</P>
<P>
   The allies reorganized and mounted unglamorous operations called
Ripper and Killer, Thunderbolt, Tomahawk and the battle of ``The No
Name Line,'' all using the superiority of U.S. firepower. (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
