<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ completely meaningless.''
</P>
<P>
   In remarks in February, trade commission Chairman Robert
Pitofsky cited the study, saying that the United States was in a
wave of mergers and that divestitures proposed to remedy
anti-competitive results had become more complex.
</P>
<P>
   ``One way to ensure that scale and scope economies are not
entirely lost is to prefer _ but not always insist upon _ the
divestiture of an ongoing business with staff, supplies and
customer relations intact, to divestiture of a package of selected
assets,'' Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that when the government accepted a certain kind of
restructuring, it led companies that later initiated similar deals
to expect the same treatment. But if the market has become more
concentrated, then maybe a similar deal is not acceptable.
</P>
<P>
   The government is not justified in repeating a mistake if an
earlier restructuring failed to provide adequate competition,
Pitofsky said.
</P>
<P>
   These are insights that could have some bearing on the Sprint
and WorldCom deal, experts said.
</P>
<P>
   When WorldCom and MCI merged in 1998, the merging companies
agreed to sell MCI's Internet business to Cable &AMP; Wireless Inc. for
$1.75 billion, along with the customer contracts, employees, assets
and services that would allow it to replace MCI as a competitor in
the market.
</P>
<P>
   Cable &AMP; Wireless later sued WorldCom, alleging that it failed to
transfer all its customers, customer information and personnel, and
failed to provide all the services and support to operate the
business. WorldCom settled the case in March for $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   Looking at the Sprint and WorldCom deal, Kovacic says he thinks
it was always a gamble.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the policy change is a more demanding look at mergers
and settlement proposals. At the same time, it is the old
phenomenon of deals getting stickier as the number of players drops
to a handful,'' Kovacic said. ``What regulators have always said
is: When you get down to a handful of players, you have to have a
very compelling reason for us to contemplate the next merger. The
burden increases and gets heavier and heavier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
