<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 20:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4001 &Cx1f; kan-z
r f BC-SPRINT-MERGER-2TAKES-     06-24 1103
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRINT-MERGER-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT REGULATORS GIVE MERGER DEALS A HIGHER DEGREE OF
SCRUTINY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ While the vast majority of corporate mergers
filed last year will be approved, antitrust experts detect a chill
wind in the regulatory atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint Corp. and WorldCom Inc. now are caught in the cold,
offering to sell off Sprint's Internet and long distance operations
to assuage regulatory concerns that the merger would concentrate 80
percent of long distance traffic in the hands of two companies:
AT&AMP;T and the merged Sprint//WorldCom.
</P>
<P>
   That comes after Sprint and WorldCom officials predicted the
merger would be blessed without the companies' having to auction
anything substantial.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint's board is expected to meet in the next few days to
evaluate the plan to sell the entire long distance division, a move
that would effectively dismantle Kansas City's largest employer and
alter the dynamics of the deal. The alternative is to scrap the
deal altogether and send Sprint Chief Executive William T. Esrey
looking for another partner.
</P>
<P>
   It is still uncertain whether senior officials at the Department
of Justice will accept WorldCom and Sprint's offer, or choose to
back their staff's recommendation to block the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The department is likely to weigh in with its decision whether
to fight the merger in court in the next few days, and it may be
coordinating its approach with European regulators, who are also
disposed to block the merger.
</P>
<P>
   The Sprint situation comes hard on the heels of a judge's
agreeing with federal regulators that computer software behemoth
Microsoft needed to be broken into two competing companies.
</P>
<P>
   Some believe regulators have been emboldened by their ability to
convince a judge that Microsoft acted in a predatory manner.
</P>
<P>
   ``Recent victories have given the agencies a real shot in the
arm,'' said Hillard Sterling, a partner with Gordon &AMP; Glickson, a
Chicago antitrust law firm. ``They are feeling confident and
aggressive in their antitrust endeavors.''
</P>
<P>
   But even more significant than the Microsoft case, many experts
agree, has been a Federal Trade Commission study released last
summer. It found that more than 25 percent of the divestitures the
commission required as a condition of approving mergers in the
early 1990s never produced competition, or not at the level
desired.
</P>
<P>
   The commission is not evaluating the Sprint//WorldCom deal,
which is being reviewed by the Justice Department, the Federal
Communications Commission and the European Commission. Experts,
however, said that all antitrust agencies had taken note of the
trade commission study.
</P>
<P>
   ``The truth is, in the past, divestitures have been a convenient
way for antitrust agencies and companies to resolve a merger
without a real confrontation,'' said John Kwoka, professor of
economics at George Washington University and a fellow at the
Kennedy School at Harvard. ``Where agencies were uncertain or
lacked resolve, they could declare victory when walking away from
the deal.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been a surge in mergers in recent years as
corporations embraced the notion that huge economies of scale are
needed to compete on a global scale.
</P>
<P>
   Last year there were 9,270 mergers announced, valued at almost
$1.5 trillion, according to Mergerstat, which tracks publicly
announced marriages. That was up 59 percent from the 5,841 mergers
announced in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the 4,700 mergers filed with the trade commission last
year involve complex divestitures _ selling off parts of the merged
businesses to satisfy concerns over diminishing competition. But
the study found that in a significant number of cases merging
companies made only token attempts to satisfy the concerns of
regulators.
</P>
<P>
   The trade commission study confirmed regulators' suspicions that
they must be more diligent if consumers are not going to suffer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goal is to get back to the state of competition that
existed before the merger,'' said Dan Ducore, assistant director in
the commission's Compliance Division, which conducted the study.
``This is not resulting in revolutionary changes in our approach,
but the study confirmed our assessments that we needed to be
particularly careful in structuring divestitures.''
</P>
<P>
   Regulators have not redefined what deals they would find
palatable, Kwoka said. But they have been able to cite the report
when they think companies are not doing enough to preserve
competition in their industries.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no broad, new guidelines that now make deals
unacceptable that once were acceptable. But there is a new emphasis
by the Federal Trade Commission and the Department of Justice,
since the report on divestiture remedies found they often failed to
restore competition,'' Kwoka said.
</P>
<P>
   The trade commission report found that companies agreeing to
divest some of their operations often looked for weak buyers they
expected to fail and then sometimes sabotaged them. Buyers were
more likely to succeed when they bought ongoing businesses rather
than selected assets.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers, even large sophisticated companies, often lacked enough
information about the assets they were buying to negotiate good
deals. Sometimes they did not realize that assets the merging
companies had not included in a sale were essential to succeeding
in a new business. Some buyers even accepted conditions that the
trade commission opposed rather than risk the chance that they
might not get the deal.
</P>
<P>
   The report said it was no surprise companies might not look for
the best competitors when divesting business. But the commission
staff had relied on buyers of assets to help determine what needed
to be sold and on what terms, the report said. It was a surprise to
find that buyers often did not know or would not help regulators
formulate the best plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Evidence of widespread mistakes by buyers of divested assets
has, however, changed how the staff examines proposed divestiture
orders and prospective buyers,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   The lesson regulators have learned is that they have to be more
careful in evaluating mergers and the solutions companies propose
to solve concentration issues, said William Kovacic, a law
professor at George Washington University law school in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they knew before the report was finished is that in many
cases the government is getting low value,'' Kovacic said. ``Many
of these settlements trumpeted as good solutions turned out to be
competitively meaningless.'' (MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
