<SLUG> BC-FISHER-KOREA-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEMORIES OF KOREAN WAR STILL STRONG 50 YEARS LATER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES J. FISHER  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Pusan, Inchon, Chosin Reservoir, MiG Alley,
Pork Chop Hill, Heartbreak Ridge, Panmunjom.
</P>
<P>
   All pieces of something called a police action. Just a few of
the names on that corner of the map called Korea, where the Cold
War once turned very hot.
</P>
<P>
   Five years after our World War II victory marches, a dozen years
before we waded into Vietnam, the seesaw stalemate around the 38th
parallel is sometimes called ``The Forgotten War.'' That is a
bitter legacy for those who fought and froze on icy mountain roads
or bled and died in reeking rice paddies.
</P>
<P>
   Because today _ 50 years after the conflict began _ the ones who
came home still cannot forget.
</P>
<P>
   So their recollections are not of the great themes of history,
of Western strategies for communist containment, of how civilian
authority asserted itself over the military or of how ``limited
war'' could become a military objective.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing that bothered me most was the brainwashing,''
recalled Charles Kerr, living today near Bentonville, Ark. A pilot,
he was held by the Chinese in solitary confinement for a year.
``Night and day interrogations. And not being able to communicate
with my parents. They let me write a couple of letters, but they
never sent them. No Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   Memories, instead, are of the confusion, the fear and the loss.
</P>
<P>
   With his right hand, fingers curled and thumb outstretched,
Chung Hyun Kim, 66, makes the motion of loading a clip in the
weapon.
</P>
<P>
   He emigrated from Korea in 1974 to join the 5,000-strong Kansas
City Korean-American community. He remembers South Korean soldiers
coming to his village when he was 16 years old, giving him an M-1
rifle and telling him that he and 500 other young men were members
of the 5th Republic of Korea (ROK) Army Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``Somebody had to show me to load,'' he said. ``I remember the
clip. Eight bullets. But I don't know about M-1. They said, `You
take; you shoot.' You know how many of the 500 survive?''
</P>
<P>
   He holds up three fingers.
</P>
<P>
   And who could forget the sad-faced children in a ravaged land;
waves of screaming men in quilted uniforms coming in the night; the
individual acts of heroism; and, above all, the barbarism of the
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw a candle the other day,'' recalled Ken Lunt, 68, the
mayor of Fort Scott, Kan. He was a Marine scout-sniper in 1952 and
1953. ``All of a sudden I remembered this kid who had been shot in
the throat.''
</P>
<P>
   The wound was mortal and the bleeding unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the cold it formed into a stalagmite like you see in a
cave, except it was this dark red, dripping down and getting bigger
and bigger....That candle brought all that back.''
</P>
<P>
   No, these veterans cannot forget. Nor should we.
INVASION AND RETREAT
</P>
<P>
   The conflict ignited when 90,000 North Koreans swarmed across
the South Korean border along the 38th parallel, brushing aside
undermanned ROK units that had given their farm-boy soldiers leave
for the harvest.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations immediately called for the North Koreans to
withdraw. The United States rushed unprepared troops from
occupation duty in Japan. Armed conflict in that fifth year of
post-World War II peace had not seemed on the horizon, despite
growing tension between East and West.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't ready,'' said John Williams of the 21st Infantry
Regiment of the 24th Division and now of Overland Park, Kan. ``The
whole Army wasn't ready.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams was among those first troops into Korea, part of what
was called Task Force Smith, which met advancing North Korean
troops near Osan, south of Seoul. Some thought the U.S. Army just
showing up would make the enemy _ which called itself the Inmin Gun
_ turn tail.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had rifles, carbines, machine guns and those 2.36 rocket
launchers,'' recalled Williams. ``The North Koreans had T-34 tanks,
recoilless rifles, artillery, you name it. Our little-bitty rocket
launchers we had just bounced off their tanks.''
</P>
<P>
   The resulting retreat was chaotic. Vehicles, weapons and wounded
were left behind.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly Korea was not going to be a walkover. Task Force Smith,
too, would be remembered. The January 2000 edition of Military
Review, the professional journal of the U.S. Army Command and
General Staff College, at Fort Leavenworth, contained these words
in an article about today's shrinking military: ``No more Task
Force Smiths.''
</P>
<P>
   The news most all that summer was almost all bad _ engagement,
retreat, and the shrinking perimeter around a southern port called
Pusan. And a phenomenon called straggling _ troops white, black and
Asian running away.
</P>
<P>
   The daily newspapers did most of the coverage; television news
then was 15 minutes a night. The datelines on the stories were
Masan, Pohang, Taejon (where a two-star Army general was captured),
Taegu and Suwon. The black-and- white photos showed images such as
an exhausted GI weeping in another's arms, dead Americans found
with their hands bound, and floods of Korean refugees in their
flowing white dress and small black hats.
</P>
<P>
   The conflict's toll on the Koreans was staggering. Kim lost six
brothers. Villages were leveled, families sundered and much of the
population seemed uprooted. Fleeing columns of refugees often were
strafed in that panicky first year. Both sides summarily executed
ideological opponents as well as captive soldiers, especially the
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different,'' said Fred Rice, a sergeant and machine
gunner in the 7th Cavalry Regiment of the lst Cavalry Division, who
now lives in Belton. ``You never could tell with the refugees. They
could have a burp gun under those robes. Most of us suspected that,
here and there, there were enemy soldiers in among them.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Rice thinks, there was no massacre of huddled civilians
under the bridge by 1st Cavalry troopers at No Gun Ri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Didn't happen,'' he insists, despite the recent spate of
articles. ``Anybody who's been in the Army will tell you something
like that would have spread like wildfire. Soldiers talk. We would
have known.''
STRIKING BACK
</P>
<P>
   Even with war undeclared officially, a lot of young men signed
up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were the younger brothers of the guys who'd been in World
War II,'' said Bill Norris, a Korean veteran from Springfield, Ill.
``Nobody went off to Canada. I don't even remember anybody talking
about draft deferments. We didn't consider ourselves special.''
(MORE)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
