<SLUG> BC-JOHN-EMAIL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KENTUCKY WOMAN RECALLS E-MAIL RELATIONSHIP WITH MURDER SUSPECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAWN BORMANN  
 c. 2000 Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ A few months ago a Kentucky woman looked at
two photos e-mailed to her by ``John'' and envisioned a
hard-working businessman and caring father from Kansas.
</P>
<P>
   Now she looks at the photos and searches her mind to recall any
conversation that might help authorities as they investigate John
Edward Robinson Sr.
</P>
<P>
   The 56-year-old Olathe, Kan., man has been charged with five
counts of murder in the deaths of women whose bodies were found in
barrels in Linn County, Kan., and Cass County. He also has been
linked to three women and a baby missing since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson also is accused of sexually attacking two women who
traveled to the area in the spring for sadomasochistic encounters
after meeting him on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   For three months, the Kentucky woman said, she corresponded with
John in an e-mail relationship that began on a
bondage-discipline-sadomasochism, or BDSM, personal ad Web site.
The woman, who uses the name ``Lauralei'' on the Internet, asked
that her real name not be used in this article, to protect her
family.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said they had spoken with several women who received
similar pictures of Robinson. They would not confirm that they had
interviewed Lauralei.
</P>
<P>
   Lauralei said their conversation was far removed from the
violence and manipulation of which Robinson has been accused. She
and John never met in person but formed a strong bond over the
Internet, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The e-mails and so on that he sent me and the things that we
talked about were so completely different,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   At the solitude of their computers, the two enjoyed conversation
about their families and their day-to-day lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I found him interesting,'' she said. ``We e-mailed daily for
some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Though still perplexed by the charges, her mind now races with
questions about the conversations they shared. He spoke of a young
college student who dressed in black attire: Was it Izabela
Lewicka, whose body was found in one of the barrels in Linn County?
He would fail to respond to some messages, explaining later that he
had gone to his farm: Was he meeting other women?
</P>
<P>
   Lauralei and John met when he answered her ad seeking someone
``that was over 45 years and somebody that was sure of themselves
and secure financially,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``In other words, I didn't want to have to support somebody,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   John knew she was a business owner but never asked her about
money, she said. The relationship was mostly platonic but did
involve some BDSM role playing, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Looking back, Lauralei said, the only red flag in her mind was
that he did not have an ad on the page where the two met. That,
however, seemed less important as they communicated.
</P>
<P>
   Her image of him _ drawn by John's words _ was of a loving
father who was divorced, a well-to-do businessman with a caring
heart who called to console her after her brother's death.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said that he was there, and I needed to lean on him. He was
supposed to be the strong one and...I should bring my problems to
him,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   That was early May, but for some reason, Lauralei said, she did
not respond. She said she appreciated his kind words, e-mail
letters and occasional phone calls but had no interest in pursuing
a cyberrelationship.
</P>
<P>
   He sent some more messages, but she did not answer them.
Eventually she deleted their three months of correspondence. She
did not give him much mind until June 11, when a detective from
Lenexa, Kan. _ a city she had never heard of _ called to ask why
her name appeared on Robinson's phone bill.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first time she had connected Robinson _ the man
charged with five killings in Kansas City _ with the man she knew
as John. It seemed unreal until the detective asked her whether she
had any pictures. She remembered the digital images of John, clad
in Western attire.
</P>
<P>
   The Lenexa detective told her that her description of the
pictures sounded the same as those he had sent to several other
women.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't until he told me about a picture, a photo, that
(Robinson) had sent to some of these other women that it dawned on
me who it was,'' she said. ``I just about dropped my teeth. I could
not believe it. It just really hit me.''
</P>
<P>
   She remembered John telling her about a young woman who packed
up her belongings and left a college ``back East'' to live in
Kansas City to carry on a BDSM relationship with him. When the
student arrived, he was embarrassed by her appearance, he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   ``She had the black lipstick, the piercing and this, that and
the other,'' Lauralei said. ``He was embarrassed of her, and when
they went out for dinner, he introduced her as a daughter of a
friend. According to him, he sent her back; he sent her away.
</P>
<P>
   ``She begged him to let her stay and said that she would learn
to do whatever he wanted her to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Lauralei read newspaper articles about Lewicka but said she
could not be sure she was the woman John was writing about.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities have said that Lewicka left Purdue University and
traveled to Kansas City because of her connection with Robinson.
Those who knew Lewicka in the Kansas City area said she dressed in
black apparel.
</P>
<P>
   Before she disappeared last fall, Lewicka told people that she
was married to an older man. In 1997 she applied for a marriage
license in Johnson County, Kan., with a John Anthony Robinson _ a
different middle name but the same birthdate as Robinson, who has
been married since 1964.
</P>
<P>
   The computer site where John and Lauralei met has since been
disabled. The Webmaster for the site did not return phone calls or
e-mails.
</P>
<P>
   Lauralei has tried to retrieve John's e-mails, but the attempts
were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   At least once in his messages, she said, John proposed that they
get together, but she had no desire to meet a stranger in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he always thought of me as being too strong-willed,''
she said. ``...I just really wasn't interested.''
</P>
</TEXT>
