<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore's social security plan favored over Bush
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Newsweek poll out Saturday found voters support both Democrat
Al Gore and Republican George Bush each 45 percent, but more voters
favor Gore's ideas for changes in the social security system. The
random telephone survey of 750 adults found that while most
surveyed were not familiar with each candidates' specific plans for
social security changes, more respondents favored the vice
president's plan, 67 percent, to 51 percent for Bush. Only 18
percent knew Gore wants to create a supplemental savings program,
with workers allowed to put up to $2,000 a year in tax-deductible
savings with matching government contributions based on income.
Just 34 percent knew Bush would allow workers to invest some of
their Social Security payroll taxes in the stock market. The poll
has a 4 percentage points margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH CAMP LOOKING FOR RECORDS ON GUARD SERVICE
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Bush's campaign workers have concluded that no documents
exist showing he reported for duty as ordered in Alabama with the
Texas Air National Guard in 1972, and are searching for people who
might have served with him to verify his story. Dan Bartlett, a
Bush campaign spokesman, said last week he reviewed 200 pages of
documents from the National Guard's records but could not find
evidence of Bush's service. Bush has said he served in Montgomery,
Ala., while working on the unsuccessful Senate campaign of former
Postmaster General Winton Blount. However, on Friday Bush said he
doesn't recall what jobs he did. ``I can't remember what I did, but
I wasn't flying because they didn't have the same airplanes. I
fulfilled my obligations,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON BRINGING IN BUCKS FOR DEMS
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton is proving to be his party's most successful
and tireless rainmaker who has brought in an estimated $4.2 million
for Democratic candidates and the party's national convention
during the last four days. Friday night, Clinton helped raise
$500,000 during a Los Angeles fund-raiser. Saturday he raised $1.5
million at the home of Republican Los Angeles Mayor Richard Riordan
before returning to the White House later Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   GOP ACCUSES KENTUCKY GOVERNOR OF `SOUR GRAPES'
</P>
<P>
   Democratic Kentucky Gov. Paul E. Patton says he has had enough
of Bush's campaigning in his state. ``Enough already,' Patton said
last weekend after Bush raised $1.7 million for his presidential
campaign and the GOP. Patton accused Bush of using ``strong-arm
tactics'' to get money from voters. ``This is unprecedented for a
presidential candidate to participate this way,'' said Patton who
wants to block Republicans from maintaining their 20-18 majority in
the Kentucky state senate. ``It just blows my mind.'' GOP state
chairwoman Ellen Williams replied that Patton is suffering from
``wacky sour grapes.'' Bush sent Patton a more pointed message:
``I'm coming. Get used to it. I'm going to come to your state as
many times as I feel like coming _ and win the vote.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
