<HEADLINE>
MARLINS NOT GOING `OUT OF BUSINESS'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. LOUIS _ Baseball's biggest problem: finding a way to keep
small-market teams in contention while not ticking off large-market
teams that don't want to share the pie.
</P>
<P>
   Fire sales at the trading deadline have become a yearly watch,
and the rich have become richer.
</P>
<P>
   Things appeared so bad financially in Florida that Marlins
officials discussed dealing not only players who were eligible for
free agency but those who would be eligible for salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   However, manager John Boles tried to defuse the potential
crises. He went as far as to gather the team before a game to tell
them the club, which is hanging around .500 and entered Saturday
36-38, is not going to be dismantled near the trading deadline.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any decision that general manager Dave Dombrowski makes will
be in the best interest of this organization from a player-only
standpoint, not financial,'' Boles said. ``We are not going to lose
players because they're arbitration eligible - period. We are in
the business of getting better, and the people who are saying these
things are wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins, struggling to make ends meet and in search of a new
stadium that can produce the kind of revenue they believe they need
to keep the team in South Florida, have eight players eligible for
arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Boles said Luis Castillo would be the Marlins' second baseman
next season and that Cliff Floyd, who's making $4.5 million this
season, won't be traded.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just emphasizing the point that we are not going to make
wholesale changes with these players,'' Boles said. ``I wish
everybody would comprehend that that's not us anymore. If we start
getting rid of players because they're arbitration eligible, we
might as well hang a shingle on the door that says `out of
business,' and we're not out of business. And I should know
something about this, being the manager.''
</P>
<P>
   Tough finish: Arizona might have to build a nice lead heading
into September if they're to win the National League West. Because
of weather and scheduling, the Diamondbacks will finish the season
with 27 games in 27 days. Six of those games are against the
Dodgers, eight are against San Francisco and four are with
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   It gets worse come Sept. 15, when the Diamondbacks will play 18
games in 17 days without having a day off.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the schedule came out, we knew that was going to be a
challenge,'' Arizona manager Buck Showalter said. ``Now even more
so. We've got to worry about June right now.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for help: One of the things that made Atlanta a playoff
team for the past decade is general manager John Schuerholz's
willingness to acquire a key player for the second half of the
season. With right-hander Kevin McGlinchy bothered by a stiff
shoulder, the Braves are putting feelers out for another starter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we can afford to wait,'' Schuerholz said. ``We do
enjoy a lead. If we were trying to close a gap on somebody, it
might be different.''
</P>
<P>
   Burned out on Valdes: It took the Chicago Cubs less than three
months to get tired of former Dodgers right-hander Ismael Valdes,
who is on the trade market as the Cubs look for prospects.
</P>
<P>
   Valdes is 1-1 with a 5.40 ERA in eight starts, and he's been
plagued with injuries. First, it was a sore shoulder that enabled
Kerry Wood to return more quickly than expected. Lately, Valdes has
been yanked from starts because of a blister problem, which
prompted Cubs general manager Ed Lynch to quip: ``He has very dry
skin.''
</P>
<P>
   Valdes is a free agent after the season, but the Cubs haven't
even talked about extending his contract. Meanwhile, Valdes has
told people close to him he wouldn't mind pitching in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   A must-see: There is a can't-miss moment that could take place
Thursday, as long as John Rocker's pitches don't continue to follow
the same path as his tongue.
</P>
<P>
   For all the punishment handed out by baseball and fans and shear
comeuppance from his continuous moronic and ignorant statements,
Rocker will get the ultimate punishment when Atlanta travels to New
York to face the Mets.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
