<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-DRAFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS PICK SMIRNOV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRANK WELCH  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   To Russia, with love. . . . And some high hopes and a little
finger-crossing thrown in, for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Ducks president and general manager Pierre Gauthier did
his NHL Entry Draft Day shopping in Calgary on Saturday. However,
the stock concerns, and, perhaps, the organization's future
check-writing duties, were squarely focused on eastern Europe.
</P>
<P>
   Gauthier and the Mighty Ducks selected 18-year-old Russian left
wing Alexei Smirnov with the 12th overall pick in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   A couple hours following Smirnov's selection, Gauthier traded
his third, fourth, and fifth-round picks to the Montreal Canadiens
in exchange for the Canadiens second-round selection (44th
overall). With that pick, Gauthier snagged Russian goalie Ilja
Bryzgalov, a 6-foot-3, 196-pound talent who recently turned 20.
</P>
<P>
   ``Down the line, these are both first-line players,'' Gauthier
said from Calgary. ``But both of these kids are young and need time
to develop.''
</P>
<P>
   The selection of Smirnov was predictable, yet risky.
</P>
<P>
   The upside most certainly is there with Smirnov, who possesses a
left- handed shot. He has size, strength, breakaway speed, vision,
and grit. Those reasons, and several others, are why Gauthier
selected him.
</P>
<P>
   ``What a great talent!'' Gauthier said. ``We're very happy and
very excited. When you look at this kid, you think he is ready to
play in the NHL. When he is on his game, he is the best (skill
player) of anyone in this draft. But he's young.''
</P>
<P>
   With the upside also comes a downside. And Smirnov has some
issues in the minds of scouts throughout the league.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say he has tons of ability,'' one scout told The
Hockey News recently. ``I don't know if there's another prospect
who has as much potential. But I wonder about his drive.''
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Smirnov was believed to be a legitimate Top 5
pick. However, subpar showings at the Five Nations Tournament in
February and at the Under-18 World Tournament in Switzerland left
once-drooling scouts shaking their heads.
</P>
<P>
   And those facts, the questions regarding Smirnov's work ethic,
appeared to enter into play on Draft Day, at least as far as one
team was concerned.
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago Blackhawks took Russian forwards Mikhail Yakubov
(10th overall) and Pavel Yorobiev (11th) just ahead of the Ducks'
first-round pick. And it should be noted that Blackhawks GM Mike
Smith is one of the league's best at spotting European talent,
especially those who come from Russia. Smith also took a timeout
before making his two back-to-back picks, apparently to ponder the
thought of selecting Smirnov.
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-3, 211-pound Smirnov, who speaks little English,
addressed that issue 30 minutes after being selected.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I didn't have the desire to play in the NHL,'' he said
through an interpeter, ``I wouldn't be here wearing a Mighty Ducks
jersey and talking to you on the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryzgalov enters the picture with an apparent clean slate.
</P>
<P>
   He is a big goalie, at 6-3, with quick reflexes, a good glove
hand, and he has a knack for challenging shooters. He is a very
calm and focused worker who has a stand-up style.
</P>
<P>
   ``We really wanted this kid,'' Gauthier said. ``When the scouts
saw him (in the Junior Worlds), the reports were he went
head-to-head with (No. 1 overall pick Rick) DiPietro (of the New
York Islanders).''
</P>
<P>
   Both Smirnov and Bryzgalov, Gauthier reminds, are still young
and in the developmental stages. Both are unlikely to see Anaheim
ice this season and, at present, Smirnov's timetable to the NHL
appears to be more lengthy.
</P>
<P>
   The first three rounds were completed in Calgary on Saturday,
with the Ducks, following their draft day deal with Montreal,
making just the two selections.
</P>
<P>
   Rounds four through nine will be completed today. Anaheim has a
fourth-round pick, two fifth-round picks, a sixth- and a
seventh-round pick today.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to try and hit a home run again,'' Gauthier said.
``We are going to try and steal more good players, so don't go and
call the cops.''
</P>
</TEXT>
