<HEADLINE>
FREE-SWINGING JONES HURT BY INCONSISTENCY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Jacque Jones' presence on the Minnesota Twins
roster creates a daily dilemma for manager Tom Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   At 25 years old, Jones, a former USC standout, has enough power
to bat cleanup, enough speed to bat leadoff and just enough
discipline at the plate to avoid being put on the next plane to
Triple-A Salt Lake City.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jacque's getting better,'' Kelly said, ``but he sometimes gets
a little out of whack and swings at some pitches trying to hit the
ball over the fence. Sometimes he tries to do a little bit too
much, instead of just trying to keep himself under control and
putting the ball in play with a line drive.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's just natural for a lot of young people who try to do a
little too much.''
</P>
<P>
   A look at the statistics confirms why Kelly discusses his center
fielder with equal parts enthusiasm and criticism. Jones, in his
first full year in the majors, went into Saturday's game against
the Anaheim Angels with a .314 batting average and a team-high 10
home runs, but in 239 at-bats, he had struck out 47 times compared
to only 11 walks.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, a 5-foot-10, 176-pound left-hander, stands far away from
the plate, near the outer edge of the batter's box, and keeps his
feet as far from each other as possible, but his batting stance
isn't a problem. Jones doesn't disagree with Kelly's assertion that
he might be trying too hard but shrugs off the idea that he needs
to be more disciplined at the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am what I am right now,'' said Jones, who has alternated
between the No. 1 and No. 9 spots in the lineup because of his
inconsistency. ``I'll become better, and maybe I'll fit into the
lineup better, but right now I'm a free swinger.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like to swing the bat, and I need to get to the point where
I'm aggressive but not over-aggressive.''
</P>
<P>
   Whatever growing pains Jones must deal with are not caused by a
lack of effort. Less than 15 minutes after his arrival Friday at
Edison Field, Jones grabbed a bat and rushed to the underground
batting cage.
</P>
<P>
   From there it was on to the field, where Jones waited
impatiently next to the cage for the group of players ahead of him
to finish, so he could jump in and start swinging.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a matter of working and learning, getting a lot of
at-bats,'' said Jones, who played for the Trojans from 1994-96.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Twins hope, Jones' hard work will make him a
more consistent hitter. The home run numbers won't be as prolific,
but neither will the strikeout numbers. The towering fly balls,
which now alternately land in the bleachers or in an outfielder's
glove, will more often turn into line-drive doubles or triples.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a lot to learn about this game,'' Kelly said, ``but
he's getting better every day. He has a lot of ability, he has a
live body, he's got enthusiasm to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets a little too brave about what he's doing, but he's
doing fine, and I wish I could trade places with him because he's
going to have a long career in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   One measure of Jones' improvement is that Kelly is now more
comfortable starting him against left-handers, even though Jones
hovers around the .250 mark against lefties. Since the Twins are a
young team, already long since out of playoff contention, Jones has
a chance to work out his problems at the highest level.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just experience, and I'm working on having a good at-bat
every time out, and not giving away at-bats,'' Jones said. ``By
now, I've seen all the pitching staffs we face, and I pretty much
know what they're going to try to do, so it's just a matter of me
making adjustments, and then things will be better.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
