<SLUG> BC-BBO-MODESTI-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME TO SIZE UP NEW BALLPARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Dear baseball fan, which of the following would
you rather watch?
</P>
<P>
   A) A late inning, one out, runners on first and second, batting
team trails by two. A drive to left-center. Left fielder is away at
the crack of the bat, angles over and back with the speed and grace
of a gazelle, dives at the edge of the warning track but just
misses a heroic catch. Ball long-hops the wall. Center fielder
alertly backs up his mate, plays the carom on a sprint, spins and
heaves a bull's-eye to the shortstop, the cutoff man. First runner
scores. Second responds to the third-base coach's gyrations
signaling ``go'' and storms toward the plate. Shortstop whirls,
makes the split-second calculation he can prevent the tying run,
and fires a one-hopper to the catcher, who braces for a
bone-cracking collision. Runner cleverly loops behind him and slaps
the plate with his outstretched left hand a moment before the tag
comes down on his shoulder. Catcher jumps to his feet in a cloud of
dust and throws to third too late to prevent the sliding batter
from putting the go-ahead run 90 feet away.
</P>
<P>
   B) Same situation, and a guy with forearms the size of a trophy
halibut socks the ball into the seats.
</P>
<P>
   Which of those would you find more exciting, more intriguing,
more !ital!baseball!off!? Sorry if this seems to be a leading
question.
</P>
<P>
   If you're like me, your answer is A). The people who run
baseball appear to think we prefer B).
</P>
<P>
   Just look at the ballparks they build.
</P>
<P>
   Up the freeway from San Diego came news this week that the
Padres' plans for a new downtown ballpark include a center-field
fence 396 feet from home plate. The club received permission from
the commissioner's office to shave 4 feet off what is supposed to
be regulation size for straight-away center in a major-league park.
</P>
<P>
   The fence itself will be as low as 4 feet tall in left field and
as high as 12 feet in another spot. It will be 7 feet tall around
most of the field - ``allowing for spectacular, leaping, home
run-robbing catches,'' Padres president Larry Lucchino declared.
``In the future, you may see some of baseball's most dramatic,
thrilling and fascinating plays occur in San Diego's little
ballpark.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so. The right-center-field alley is designed to go 411
feet, and straightaway right will be a healthy 382. But
straightaway left will be only 367 and there will be a ``Home Run
Porch'' in right. It sounds as if Lucchino's definitions of
``dramatic, thrilling and fascinating'' relies heavily on the long
ball.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is that if you wanted dramatic, thrilling and
fascinating, you'd build ballparks bigger, not smaller.
</P>
<P>
   I'm writing as somebody who doesn't mind baseball's scoring
explosion - a 10-9 game can be just as tense, often more so, than a
2-1 game - but gets tired of all the home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Everything else being equal, I'd rather see a batter rounding
second and trying for a triple than watch a ball flying over a
fence. A double or triple puts more skills of more players on
display and raises the drama for the next hitter. But while the
number of home runs was rocketing up in the 1990s, the number of
triples was stagnant, the league leaders' average (13.2 in the
American League, 14.0 in the National) reflecting a decline from
the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   We keep hearing that home runs have increased in part because
players are better athletes - taller, better fed, fitter, more
scientifically coached. Yet what has baseball done to encourage
players to show off not only their strength but also their legs,
gloves and arms?
</P>
<P>
   The Padres president's vision of ``spectacular, leaping, home
run-robbing catches'' above a 7-foot-tall fence is ridiculous.
</P>
<P>
   I can catch a ball above a 7-foot fence 367 feet from the plate.
(I can also dunk on a 7-foot basket, thank you.)
</P>
<P>
   Spectacular plays are the result of outfielders having to cover
a lot of ground and to make throws. Think of Willie Mays' catch off
Vic Wertz in the 1954 World Series, 450 feet from home plate at the
Polo Grounds, and Al Gionfriddo's catch off Joe DiMaggio in the
1947 Series, back- back-back-back-back in Yankee Stadium's old
461-foot left-center field.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't a call to bring back the Polo Grounds, or uproot the
Dodger Stadium bleachers and move the fences back 30 feet. It is a
wish that the next stadium architect would grasp the value of
keeping the ball in the park.
</P>
<P>
   Somebody gets it: The Detroit Tigers' Comerica Park goes 420
feet to dead center, 398 and 380 to the power alleys, and 345 and
330 down the lines. It's a refreshing change from the trend
reflected in this year's other new parks in San Francisco (307 from
the plate to the water down the right-field line) and Houston (362
to left-center). Detroit's is the second-roomiest outfield in the
major leagues.
</P>
<P>
   The roomiest belongs to the Colorado Rockies' Coors Field (347
and 350 down the lines, 415 to center). The bad news about Coors is
that although it was built that way to compensate for the light air
at mile-high elevation, it's the easiest place in the major leagues
to hit a home run.
</P>
<P>
   The good news about Coors Field is that the huge outfield also
makes it one of the easiest places to hit a triple, a double or,
for that matter, a single. Balls drop in. Balls shoot through the
gaps. Outfielders have to make plays. Batters have to run the
bases.
</P>
<P>
   Move it to sea level and Coors Field might be the greatest
ballpark of them all. Now, where can San Diego find a really big
moving van?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
