<HEADLINE>
KINGS GIVE FROLOV EARLY BIRTHDAY GIFT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the 20th overall pick in Saturday's NHL entry draft, the
Los Angeles Kings selected Russian left-winger Alexander Frolov,
who turns 18 today.
</P>
<P>
   Frolov played in 36 games last season with Yaroslav 2 of the
Russian Division 2 League and recorded 40 points (27-13  &QC;  40) and
30 penalty minutes. He also helped Russia
win a silver medal in this year's under-18 World Championships.
</P>
<P>
   In six games during that tournament, Frolov scored five goals.
He also had three goals in four games in the Five Nations
Tournament, a major international event.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alexander Frolov brings a little bit of everything to the
table,'' Kings general manager Dave Taylor said Saturday from
Calgary, site of the draft. ``He has very good size, he is a good
skater, and he has scoring ability when he gets in tight around the
net. He also has a good reach and sees the ice well. We really like
the complete package we see in Alexander.''
</P>
<P>
   Frolov was the first of three players chosen Saturday by the
Kings. The draft will resume today with the fourth through ninth
rounds.
</P>
<P>
   With their second pick and 54th overall, the Kings took
defenseman Andreas Lilja, 24, who played 49 games last season with
Malmo of the Swedish Elite League. At 6-foot-3, 215 pounds, Lilja
logged 88 penalty minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Their third selection was center Yanick Lehoux (86th overall).
Lehoux, 18, played 66 games for Baie-Comeau of the Quebec Major
Junior Hockey League. He recorded 31 goals and 92 points.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
