<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PREFONTAINE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JONES TAKES BIG LEAP AHEAD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KIRBY LEE  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUGENE, Ore. _ Marion Jones is quickly returning to her greatest
asset - speed - to improve her chances for an unprecedented five
gold medals in the Sydney Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the two-time defending world 100-meter champion
sailed to a season-best 22 feet, 10 inches to win the long jump,
her weakest event, in the Prefontaine Classic at the University of
Oregon on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, the Thousand Oaks High graduate won the 100 meters in a
wind-aided 10.93 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, 24, who hopes to compete in the 100, 200, long jump and
400 as well as the 1,600 relays in the Olympics, has struggled in
the long jump after switching the emphasis of her long-jump
training from speed to technique.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who jumped 23-11 two years ago, went only 20-7 in her
season opener in Osaka, Japan, in May. Competing on her home track
at North Carolina State last Saturday, Jones could manage only two
21-6 efforts to place second to training partner Chandra Sturrup of
the Bahamas at the Pontiac Grand Prix Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a lot more aggressive, and I went for it today,'' Jones
said. ``I think it is a step in the right direction. It was night
and day compared to here and Osaka. I had nothing to hold me back.
I had been thinking about technique and too many things going
through my head. Today, I just ran and jumped.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones opened the competition with her winning effort and jumped
21-11 and wind-aided marks of 21-9 and 21-11 on her second, third
and fourth attempts, respectively. Jones fouled on her last two
jumps. All of her jumps surpassed those of Shana Williams, who was
second at 21-8.
</P>
<P>
   ``The important thing is I popped off a good one,'' Jones said.
``It was not the best of the series, but I was excited I could come
back after the 100 and pop one off. I feel a lot better than I have
in the past on the runway. My speed without a doubt is there.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael Johnson and Maurice Greene did little to detract from
their upcoming duel in the 200 in next month's U.S. Olympic Trials
in Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, the defending Olympic 200 and 400 champion and world
record holder in both events, won the 400 in 43.92 for the world's
fastest time of the year. Greene, the world 100 record holder who
captured the 200 in the 1999 world championships in Johnson's
absence, sped to victory in the 200 in a wind-aided 19.93.
</P>
<P>
   World women's 5,000 champion Gabriela Szabo of Romania produced
a world-leading 4:00.73 to nip Suzy Favor Hamilton by
six-hundredths of a second after overcoming a 15-meter deficit off
the final turn in her first appearance in the U.S. since the 1996
Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Three-time world 100 hurdle champion and 1992 and 1996 Olympic
100 champion Gail Devers won the 100 hurdles in 12.64 for the
world's No. 2 mark to start her quest for her fourth Olympic team.
</P>
<P>
   It was Jones, however, who captured the most attention in the
100, debuting a full-length hooded ``Swift Suit'' that she will
wear in the Olympics. It is designed to improve performance by
aerodynamics and maintaining warm muscle temperature.
</P>
<P>
   While flashy, the Nike outfit did little Saturday to help Jones.
Jones called her start ``horrible'' and never found her rhythm.
However, Jones was never challenged by runner-up and former USC
standout Torri Edwards (11.09) or Peta-Gaye Dowdie of Louisiana
State and Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   ``My transition was not very good, but I am strong enough I can
pull it out in the end,'' Jones said. ``A 10.93 for me is a jog.
There are some things I need to correct. But I am a technician when
it comes to the 100, and I can put the race together when I have
to. I am much more excited about my jumping today. I am just
waiting for a meet where I can be happy with both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones will get only one more chance in the Golden Gala meet in
Rome in her final competition before the U.S. Olympic Trials.
Jones, who moved to fourth on the yearly, global long jump list
with her performance Saturday, will face world leader Fiona May of
Italy in the long jump and compete in the 100 in the June 30 Golden
League meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sure the Europeans will make a big deal of it,'' Jones
said. ``(May) has been jumping very far. I thrive on competition. I
just think I need more competitions under my belt against the best
and I'll be OK.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 2333EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
