<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MYRON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOSHUA MYRON, ZIONIST WHO FOUGHT THE TURKS, DIES AT 102 
</HEADLINE>
   By DOUGLAS MARTIN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Joshua Myron, one of the last of the camel-mounted
Zionist brigade that fought with Vladimir Jabotinsky against Turkey
in Palestine during World War I, died in Manhattan on June 8. He
was 102.
</P>
<P>
   With the outbreak of World War I, Jabotinsky, then a Russian
journalist, realized that the Ottoman Empire was likely to lose to
the British and that it would pay for the Zionist settlers in
Israel to back the winning side. He spread the idea of forming a
Jewish Brigade, sometimes called the Jewish Legion, to fight beside
the British.
</P>
<P>
   The British army unit, which recruited Jews from both the Middle
East and Europe, used camels to move from front to front, and Myron
rose to become company sergeant in charge of transport.
</P>
<P>
   The brigade is believed to have contributed significantly to the
British war effort, and Jabotinsky believed its aid was a major
factor in winning the Balfour Declaration of 1917, in which Britain
announced support for a Jewish national home in Palestine. ``Half
the Balfour Declaration belongs to the Legion,'' Jabotinsky wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Among the other members of the brigade was David Ben-Gurion,
later the first prime minister of Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Myron was born at Rishon Lezion, the first officially Zionist
settlement in Palestine, and devoted his life first to battling for
a Jewish homeland, then to supporting Israel after its
establishment in 1948. After emigrating to New York and becoming a
pharmacist, he remained active in raising arms and money for
Israel.
</P>
<P>
   Myron's father, Feivel Miransky, left Russia with a group of
pioneers called the Biluim to go to Palestine as one of the
founders of Rishon Lezion. Jews already lived in Palestine, but had
not banded together in settlements in support of the Zionist ideal.
</P>
<P>
   The settlement of Rishon and other Zionist towns was financed by
Baron Edmond de Rothschild, who established a large vineyard there.
Miransky set up a carriage service to link Rishon with Jaffa, which
became Tel Aviv. At the time, the trip took more than two hours on
a sandy, muddy road.
</P>
<P>
   Myron was born on Aug. 17, 1897, into a frontier existence. His
grandson Marc Lubin told of the time some of Myron's father's
horses were stolen when he was 16. He reported the theft to the
police and was told he was on his own. He ended up crossing the
Jordan River and taking his horses back.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Myron decided to move to the United States. He
immediately experienced what he regarded as a stinging insult and a
great inconvenience when the British refused to grant him traveling
papers, saying he was officially a Turkish subject. So, officially
at least, he arrived in America as a Turk.
</P>
<P>
   He had intended to study veterinary medicine at Columbia
University but the school was not accepting new students at that
time. He studied pharmacy at Albany College of Pharmacy. While
there, he married Sybil Berkowitz, who died in 1973. In the early
1930s, they returned to Palestine, where their daughter, Naomi
Scheurer, was born. She now lives in Manhattan; Myron is also
survived by three grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually, the Myrons moved to Suffern, N.Y. Myron commuted to
Manhattan, where he owned two Midtown pharmacies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 2335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000624.0187 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-06-24 23:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4202 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-SOUTHERN-RACE-NY     06-24 0987
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SOUTHERN-RACE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PORTRAITS OF SOUTHERN LIVES SHOW A RECORD OF PAIN AND PROGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editorial Observer)  
 By HOWELL RAINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For someone who knew the South during the days of de jure
segregation, The New York Times' series on race in America
describes a world of routine social interaction that could be
imagined only by rebels, visionaries and dreamers _ almost all of
them black _ from the vantage point of, say, Birmingham in 1957.
</P>
<P>
   As the series shows, the new multiracial society announced into
our national consciousness by the break-through victories of the
Southern civil rights movement is not free of economic and cultural
tensions, of mistrust and plain old prejudice. The series documents
that no part of America, North or South, East or West, has fully
created what U.S. Rep. John Lewis of Georgia calls ``the beloved
community.''
</P>
<P>
   It also shows that what was once viewed as a regional story told
in black and white is now national in scope and multi-ethnic in
content.
</P>
<P>
   All that said, I found that three articles set in my native
South stirred a desire to bear witness to the persistence of some
distinctly regional themes in this broad narrative about race in
America's new century. For example, it seemed especially
appropriate to me that the series began with Kevin Sack's story on
June 4 about an integrated Pentecostal congregation in suburban
Atlanta. Think of the historical convergence in that setting and
subject.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta was the spiritual capital of the Confederate South, the
intellectual home of the New South economic-development movement,
and the command center of the civil rights revolution and the black
preachers who led it. The centrality of the black church to racial
transformation in America can hardly be overstated. Martin Luther
King Jr. and his colleagues forged the stories of Moses and Jesus
into mighty social weapons. Nor can the failure of the white church
in the South be overstated. Its preachers stood in fearful silence.
Its congregants tried to ignore the inner voices insisting that
belief in the gospels allowed but one response to segregation.
While Sack's reporting found that the Assembly of God Tabernacle
may not have perfected the beloved community, its members' effort
to do so, within the twin shadows of Stone Mountain and Ebenezer
Baptist Church, seems to me apt and momentous.
</P>
<P>
   Ebenezer's most famous pastor, King, had a special genius for
defining the links between economic oppression and racial conflict.
His lessons in that regard came to mind when I read Charlie
LeDuff's article on June 16 about the black, white, Mexican and
Native-American work force at the Smithfield Packing Co.'s plant in
Tar Heel, N.C. For generations, Northern industrial corporations
treated the South as a colonial enterprise. They used black-white
tensions to keep out unions and fattened their profits through a
two-tiered wage system _ low pay for whites, lower still for
blacks. In comparison, tenant farmers enjoyed a kind of rough
parity. The crop-lien system kept blacks and whites equally
impoverished, although blacks could be hanged as well as starved.
</P>
<P>
   But whether in the factory or on the farm, Southern workers were
schooled to understand a brutal financial fact. If you will not
take this harsh, low-paying, dead-end job, some other hungry person
will.
</P>
<P>
   What is taking place in North Carolina shows that in the
Southern industrial environment, change does not always bring
progress. The tough-minded employer in Tar Heel is a Southern firm.
Mexican immigrants have replaced blacks and Appalachian whites as
the workers willing to take the lowest wages with the fewest
complaints. And according to LeDuff's reporting, there is still
truth to King's teaching that the competition among poor people for
grinding jobs brews frustrations that are expressed through racial
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   It is a far piece from Tar Heel to Natchitoches, La., where
Ginger Thompson reported on the effort to preserve Magnolia
Plantation. That article last Thursday reminded me of perhaps the
greatest scholarly lesson of the last half-century of race
relations in the Southern region and the country at large. That
lesson is simply that we may more accurately speak of American
``histories,'' rather than a single, monolithic American history.
From Colonial Williamsburg to Acadian Louisiana, most preservation
efforts have focused on the big house and celebrating the lives of
its inhabitants. At Williamsburg and later at Magnolia, a National
Park Service ranger named Carla Cowles worked to add the buildings
and human histories of the slave quarter to the story of the big
house.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson's article is too complex to summarize here, but the
resonant quote with which it ended lingers in recollection as a
comment on a broad swath of social experience. That experience has
consisted of remarkable levels of social integration in places like
the Atlanta church, new levels of intellectual honesty about the
past in Natchitoches and, less happily, a persistence of obdurate
patterns in Tar Heel and many other places as well. Betty Hertzog,
the 70-year-old owner of Magnolia Plantation, spoke of moving away
from a property that has been in her family for 200 years. She
would depart knowing, of course, that Magnolia Plantation will be
used to teach a version of Southern history far more complex than
that associated with the traditional plantation ``tours'' of
decades past.
</P>
<P>
   ``Used to be that it was hard to leave this old place,'' Hertzog
said. ``But now it's harder and harder to stay.''
</P>
<P>
   Something similar might be said about race relations in America
today. As The Times' series documents, those relations are full of
tension at both the philosophical and quotidian levels. But for
millions of Americans of all colors, staying in the old place was
not, in the end, a tolerable possibility.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-06-24-00 2344EDT &QL; 
